<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A'S SUCCESSFUL AT FINDING GEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's absolutely no secret that small-market franchises must be
creative if they are to try to compete with the big-spenders, who
readily dole out wads of cash to lure big-name free agents to their
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Need a solid outfielder capable of driving in 100 runs and
hitting 25 home runs? No problem if you're the Atlanta Braves.
Simply agree to pay  &UR; Brian Jordan $40 million for five years, and
he's yours. A first baseman comes on the market, and you need one.
If you're the Anaheim Angels, you shell out $80 million and voila!
 &UR; Mo Vaughn magically appears.
</P>
<P>
   But those scenarios are little more than a fantasy for the
majority of clubs. For some general managers, getting a date with
Selma Hayek might occur before they can spend that kind of cash.
</P>
<P>
   But out in Oakland, the Athletics have taken a different
approach to finding missing cogs. The Athletics have been among the
trendsetters when it comes to sifting through the six-year free
agent pale and finding hidden gems.
</P>
<P>
   Once a player has put in six professional seasons (even at the
minor league level), he is eligible to become a free agent. The A's
have definitely discovered very usable refuse that other
organizations had no use for.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland, whose $23 million payroll this season ranks 27th out of
30 clubs, was on the six-year free agent bandwagon well before most
others were as deeply involved in the practice. The A's have reaped
the benefits, finding such capable big leaguers as designated
hitter
 &UR; Geronimo Berroa, outfielder  &UR; Matt Stairs, third baseman  &UR; Olmedo
Saenz, shortstop  &UR; Rafael Bournigal, and pitchers  &UR; Billy Taylor,
 &UR; Gil Heredia,
 &UR; Mike Oquist and  &UR; Buddy Groom.
</P>
<P>
   It may sound more like a trash list of players, but ask around
the majors and few would not applaud the finds Oakland has made
while dredging through the list of six-year minor league free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   In Stairs, the A's found someone capable of hitting 26 home runs
and driving in 89 runs per season, which Stairs has averaged the
past two season. Already, he had 14 home runs and 42 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Berroa, no longer with the A's, averaged 28 home runs and 93
RBIs over a three-year span from 1995-'97. Taylor, the A's closer
who spent 14 seasons in the minors before making his big-league
debut at age 32 in 1994, saved 73 games the past three years and
already has 16 this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been our lifeblood,'' said General Manager  &UR; Billy Beane,
considered one of the brightest up-and-coming minds in the game.
``It's the only area where we can compete with other clubs, where
finances aren't the rule of thumb because we're all paying around
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes comes down to evaluation and opportunity. We think we
can evaluate with other people in the league. We definitely think
we've got a good group of scouts and baseball people and take pride
in that one area of finding the six-year minor leaguers. It's our
form of guerilla warfare.'' &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
One season after finishing in last place in their division, the
Diamondbacks find themselves in first place in the NL West. Only
five times in the history of the game has a club finished in last
place one season and first the next. Who are they? A hint, all five
accomplished the feat during the 1990s. &QL; 
A New York state of mind &QL; 
In a scene directly from ``X-Files,'' the two New York clubs seem
to have magically been transposed at some point.
</P>
<P>
   While the Yankees, known for decades as the Bronx Zoo, where
problems arise from virtually nothing, seem at peace with each
other and Boss  &UR; George Steinbrenner, the same cannot be said for
the club that plays across the Triboro Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have taken on the look of the Queens Asylum, where
anything can happen at any moment. It all started 10 days ago when
it was learned that Mets outfielders  &UR; Bobby Bonilla and  &UR; Brian
McRae were each placed on irrevocable waivers, meaning that if they
were claimed, the Mets would lose them for just the $20,000 waiver
price.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, three coaches were fired, including the innocent
bullpen coach,  &UR; Randy Niemann. Two days later, Manager  &UR; Bobby
Valentine goes on the Mets radio broadcast and blasts a pair of New
York baseball writers, accusing them of working together, a strong
no-no among competitors.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, Valentine tells Bonilla he was going to begin
using a four-man outfield rotation and that he was not one of the
four. Bonilla then made himself unavailable to pinch-hit the next
night.
</P>
<P>
   There was no rest the next day (we're now up to Wednesday if
you're trying to keep up) when Valentine and one of the reporters
got into a heated argument in the dugout before a game, loudly
calling each other liars.
</P>
<P>
   That same afternoon, Valentine and Bonilla started screaming at
each other in the dugout, with Valentine telling Bonilla he would
``rather have one of my coaches play the outfield,'' after Bonilla
volunteered for the duty. Bonilla refused to take batting practice
that day.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Valentine was ejected from Wednesday night's game but
managed to re-appear in the dugout wearing some cheesy disguise
that included a fake mustache, a fake hat and a hat. The NL
suspended him for two games and fined him $5,000 for that one.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, though, the Mets snapped an eight-game losing
streak and entered their weekend series against Boston riding a
four-game winning streak. Go figure. &QL; 
Soup's on &QL; 
His career didn't quite pan out the way he envisioned while with
the Diamondbacks, but former starter  &UR; Jeff Suppan seems to have
found a nice home in Kansas City, where his 3.32 ERA ranks
secondbest among Royals starters and sixth-best in the American
League.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan was bounced out of Boston, his original club, when the
Red Sox exposed him in the expansion draft. The Diamondbacks
selected Suppan with their second pick (the third overall) in
November 1997 and immediately placed him in their original
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most players today, you're going to be moving around,'' Suppan
said. ``As a young player, in your first organization, you think
you're going to be with them forever. But every step along the way
has helped me out, and I'm grateful these teams have given me an
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Suppan seemed to have trouble adjusting to life in the
National League, where fastball pitchers thrive and those who rely
mostly on breaking balls don't. Suppan won only once for Arizona
and eventually was shipped to Triple-A Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   Suppan may have a 3-4 record, but he has managed to cut down on
his walks significantly, issuing 21 in 78 innings. He has become a
dependable member of Kansas City's rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt like Soupy was my dark horse,'' Royals
Manager
 &UR; Tony Muser said. ``I liked him when we had him last year in
September. I felt he had good mound presence. I felt he had a good
arm.'' &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
The 1991 Atlanta Braves and Minnesota Twins began a trend that has
some purists' stomachs turning in all sorts of directions. Two
years later, in 1993, Philadelphia also turned the trick. The 1997
San Francisco Giants followed suit, and last year San Diego did the
same. Incidently, the Padres finished in first place in 1996, last
in '97, first in '98 and currently are last in '99. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; It's all about having fun, and that's what they doing in
 &UR; Cheeseville: With Miller Park set to open next spring in Milwaukee,
the Brewers discovered they will have about 300 obstructed-view
seats in the upper deck behind home plate because of the mechanical
pivot needed to open and close the roof. They will sell for $1 the
day of games and are called, ``Uecker Seats,'' honoring longtime
broadcaster
 &UR; Bob Uecker.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Further unmasking of Mr. Turn It On For The TV
 &UR; cameras: Now that  &UR; Pedro Martinez is 11-2 with a 2.16 ERA, let's
remember that it was  &UR; Tommy Lasorda who insisted to Dodgers
executives that Martinez never could be a successful starter in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Wilbur Wood.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; That's it! No more 90210 re-runs: Florida pitcher
 &UR; Alex Fernandez, who is limited to around 80 pitches per start while
he recovers from rotator cuff surgery, was so frustrated after his
last outing that he fired a weighted batting donut through one of
the four TVs in the Marlins clubhouse. Total bill: Around $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; And while you're at it, stop calling at dinner time
 &UR; every night: Not to be outdone, Oakland's  &UR; Kenny Rogers ripped out
a pair of phones out of the wall in the visitors clubhouse at 3Com
Park last week and did a little more damage on his way out. Total
bill: $1,700. To which Rogers said, ``I'll get my own estimate.'' &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
While Seattle's  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. and Tampa Bay's  &UR; Jose Canseco wage
a battle for the majors' home run lead, a more interesting race is
taking shape within Seattle's ranks, where Griffey had 23 home runs
entering the weekend series and pitcher  &UR; Jeff Fassero had allowed
23 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see San Diego owner
 &UR; John Moores in the Valley very soon. The 1998 National League
championship ring for current Diamondbacks center fielder  &UR; Steve
Finley is in Moores' possession, and he plans to personally deliver
it to Finley, a close friend. Moores will do the same for  &UR; Ken
Caminiti, now with Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Believing he was going to return to his 1997 ways,
 &UR; Willie Blair was tickled when he returned to Detroit over the
winter. He now has been banished from the rotation to long relief,
where he served up home runs to Pittsburgh's  &UR; Jose Guillen and
 &UR; Brant Brown in the same outing. The two had combined for one home
run in their previous 209 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   After 1,138 games in the American League without ever being
ejected, Texas right fielder  &UR; Juan Gonzalez was ejected for arguing
home plate umpire  &UR; Wally Bell's strike zone during an interleague
game last week. Bell is an NL umpire. It was Gonzalez's 21st
interleague game.
</P>
<P>
   Now that one-third of the season is behind us, let's re-examine
Houston's trade with Seattle last summer for  &UR; Randy Johnson.
Johnson is 8-2 for the Diamondbacks and looks like he has returned
to being the most dominant pitcher in the game. The duo of  &UR; Freddie
Garcia and  &UR; John Halama entered the weekend a combined 11-4. It
appears only Houston lost out on this deal.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 27 smallest crowds in the 339-game history of Coors
Field, 16 of them have been this season, and the Colorado Rockies
have 57 more home dates to be played. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
Cleveland, which never has been shy to sign pitchers who seem all
but done to help provide depth, is kicking around the idea of going
after  &UR; Tom Candiotti, who was designated for assignment by Oakland
last week. The Indians, though, will wait until Candiotti comes
cheaper, after the 10-day waiver period ends.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore, which is struggling worse than anyone in the majors,
is ready to listen to offers for starter  &UR; Scott Erickson, who was
1-8 entering the weekend. Count Philadelphia among the more
interested parties in this one. Money, however, might be an
obstacle. Erickson signed a five-year, $35 million deal over the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, with a sudden surplus in money since
 &UR; Jeff King's surprise retirement, may no longer be actively shopping
 &UR; Kevin Appier (although they will continue to listen to offers). In
addition, the Royals actually may be in the market for a first
baseman, preferably one with strong defensive skills.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego and Seattle talked last week about the possibility of
the Padres sending  &UR; Donne Wall or  &UR; Dan Micelli to the Mariners.
Seattle continues to look for bullpen help. San Diego is willing to
listen to an offer for at least one of the two middle relievers.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Detroit right-hander  &UR; Seth
 &UR; Greisinger, out all season because of an elbow injury, is leaning
toward finally accepting surgery to repair his problem. Greisinger,
who awed hitters last year, may decide by Monday. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandLookie, here: &UR; Steve Karsay has emerged as the Tribe's
best pitcher.  &QL; 
2. AtlantaEven with some problems, the Braves remain the class of
the NL.  &QL; 
3. TexasThe Power Rangers are hitting, but it's the pitching
carrying these boys.  &QL; 
4. Houston &UR; Jeff Bagwell in Chicago (AL and NL): Six HRs, 14 RBIs in
five games.  &QL; 
5. NY YankeesCame into the weekend with a losing record in their
previous 27 games.  &QL; 
6. BostonWatched its AL East lead evaporate as  &UR; Pedro Martinez got
hammered.  &QL; 
7. Chicago Cubs &UR; Rick Aguilera may get closer's money, but
 &UR; Terry &UR; Adams has the title.  &QL; 
8. ArizonaIf the D-Backs are going to be taken seriously, they must
fix the bullpen.  &QL; 
9. San FranciscoThe sleeping Giants just got back their best
player,  &UR; Barry Bonds. &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. BaltimoreFurther proof that throwing money at problems isn't a
cure-all.  &QL; 
29. MinnesotaTwins are 1-7 on Sundays. They're 20-30 the rest of
the week.  &QL; 
28. MontrealBeat up on former Expo  &UR; Pedro Martinez in the worst
way.  &QL; 
27. FloridaMarlins entered the weekend with a 17-15 record since
May 6.  &QL; 
26. Kansas CityIf only Royals hitters could face St. Louis'
pitching all the time.  &QL; 
25. Tampa Bay &UR; Wilson Alvarez ripped off his jersey and stomped on
it . . . in the dugout.  &QL; 
24. San DiegoPadres remain the only club without a three-game
winning streak.  &QL; 
23. MilwaukeeThe locals are calling for Manager  &UR; Phil Garner to be
dumped. He may be.  &QL; 
22. Toronto &UR; Jim Fregosi and  &UR; Carlos Delgado have a small feud going
over leadership. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Cincinnati Reds: The Reds' longest trip in 10 years resulted in a
9-3 record. While the four-city trip took them through Florida, a
then-struggling New York Mets club, Kansas City and Minnesota
shouldn't matter because victories still count. More amazing, the
Reds are doing their damage out of the bullpen. Starters are
averaging just under 5 innings per outing, the lowest mark in the
NL. The bullpen's 15 victories are tied for the most with Texas and
the Cubs. In their last 35 games entering the weekend series
against Cleveland, Reds relievers were a combined 12-0 with 10
saves in 12 chances. &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Los Angeles Dodgers: Our favorite whipping boys (although the
Orioles are a close second) continue to underachieve. ``This team
should not be a .500 ballclub,'' said injured shortstop  &UR; Mark
 &UR; Grudzielanek, who broke his right hand on June 1 when he punched a
wall out of frustration. ``On paper, I think we're one of the best
teams around, hands down.'' Of course, it takes action, not paper
to compete for a playoff spot and the Dodgers aren't very good at
holding up that end of the bargain. Manager  &UR; Davey Johnson has
managed to lift topsy-turvy clubs before, as evidenced with the
Mets and Orioles. Is he capable of doing it again? &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
The San Diego Padres called up infielder  &UR; David Newhan from their
Triple-A affiliate in Las Vegas last week. Upon his arrival, Newhan
was asked if he had any idea that he was going to be summoned.
``You read stuff in the papers, but you can't trust what those guys
write,'' he said. Newhan's father is  &UR; Ross Newhan, longtime
baseball columnist for the ``Los Angeles Times.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Pittsburgh's  &UR; Mike Williams was little more than a journeyman two
years ago. Now he has become one of the most reliable closers in
the majors. While he does not possess the 95 mph fastball that most
officials want for their closer, Williams does have a wicked slider
that paralyzes batters. ``I don't even really consider myself a
closer,'' Williams said. ``I just happen to be the guy who is being
asked to get some outs in the ninth inning. Fortunately,
(Manager) &UR; Gene Lamont keeps asking me to do the job and I keep
getting it done.'' Maybe so, but Williams, according to several
scouts, is the real thing. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at (602) 444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
