<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-METS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNCHLESS RED SOX TAKE IT ON THE CHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He struck out twice in a game for only the third time
this season, after striking out just seven times in his previous 23
games.
</P>
<P>
   He hit into a double play for just the fifth time this season.
And it was the first time in 1999 he's whiffed and hit into a
double play in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   By anyone's criteria, it was a lousy afternoon. By the exacting
standards Nomar Garciaparra has set for himself, it was a
five-alarm fire, a nationally televised exercise in futility that
mocked the promotional print ad the Fox Network ran before this 4-2
loss to &UR;  &LR; the Mets, one in which Garciaparra's face was superimposed
on the body of a prizefighter exchanging punches with Mets slugger
Mike Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, while Garciaparra and the rest of the struggling
Boston hitters (.211 average and 28 runs in 10 games this month)
offered little more than a baseball version of the rope-a-dope, the
Mets threw all the body punches in sending the Sox to their sixth
loss in seven games and seventh in their last nine. Solo home runs
by Benny ``And The Mets'' Agbayani and Robin Ventura off Sox
starter Pat Rapp and another by John Olerud off reliever Mark
Guthrie accounted for three of their runs.
</P>
<P>
   When Garciaparra falters, especially the day after he had just
one infield hit in six at-bats against the Mets, the inclination is
to search for a cause-and-effect explanation.
</P>
<P>
   Hurt? Nope, at least nothing beyond the aches that are part of
his daily routine, and certainly nothing as obvious as the strained
groin and bad knee with which John Valentin is trying to play.
</P>
<P>
   Tired? Wouldn't be surprised, manager Jimy Williams said, given
that (1) it takes an act of God to keep Garciaparra out of the
lineup, and (2) the Sox were back at the ballpark Saturday morning
about 10 hours after winning in 12 innings the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tired? Yeah, I'm tired, but it's part of the game,'' said
Garciaparra, who has just three hits in his last 17 at-bats, has
not homered in his last 11 games, and has just three RBIs in that
span.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never ask (for a day off). I don't make that decision. I
prepare myself day in and day out to play. It's my job to get ready
to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox didn't advance a runner to second base until the sixth
inning, and then only because Mets starter Al Leiter made a bad
throw on an easy force play.
</P>
<P>
   Only once all afternoon did they have more than one hit in an
inning. That was in the seventh, when Troy O'Leary had their only
extra-base hit, a double sandwiched between singles by Damon Buford
and Creighton Gubanich, and the Sox scored both of their runs to
draw within 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis then worked Leiter for a full-count walk, but Jason
Varitek, pinch hitting for Rapp, popped out weakly on a
``foshball,'' a pitch Leiter has only recently taken to throwing,
one he describes as a batting-practice fastball that throws
righthanded hitters off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman walked and stole second with Garciaparra at the
plate in the eighth, but Mets reliever Armando Benitez fanned
Garciaparra with a split-fingered fastball and Mike Stanley flied
to left.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud took Guthrie deep in the bottom of the inning to make it
4-2. O'Leary hit a broken-bat single with one out in the ninth, but
Mets closer John Franco, beaten by the Sox Friday, closed them out
for his 15th save.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra shook his head when asked if he were trying to do
too much in the absence of any sustained attack by the rest of the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struggling myself,'' he said. ``I'm just trying to get
some hits, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working on myself, battling myself to feel comfortable. I
hit a couple hard, but right at people. What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   A reshuffling of the lineup isn't likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to hit the pitcher eighth, I'm not going to do
that,'' said Williams, invoking the strategy employed on occasion
by Cardinals manager Tony La Russa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll just keep playing hard, and good things are going to
happen. We get pitching like that, we're going to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin, who beat Franco with a single Friday in the 12th but
has just one RBI in eight games, also suggested the Sox can't dwell
on their recent failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to have short memories,'' he said. ``That's the only
way to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
