<SLUG> BC-BB-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYPICAL NEW YORK NIGHTMARE FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gotham always has been tough on the Red Sox. Boston
baseball horrors in Yankee Stadium and Shea Stadium are part of
hardball lore, and this weekend the Sox have endured new pain and
torture.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen had a team party on Long Island Thursday and
sustained a five-stitch cut on his foot that put him back on the
disabled list. On Friday, ace closer Flash Gordon may have blown
out his pitching elbow on the Shea mound. Saturday, Boston's popgun
attack produced almost nothing in a 4-2 loss to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   In the losers' locker room Saturday afternoon, someone asked Sox
first baseman Mike Stanley if he needed anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tourniquet,'' said Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Bingo. Time to stop the bleeding.
</P>
<P>
   Let's try not to be negative. Take a look at the non-first-place
teams in the American League and it's easy to project the
pitching-propelled Red Sox ahead of Seattle, Chicago, Oakland,
Anaheim, and Toronto for the coveted wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   Having said that, it's also easy to see that the Sox need help.
This week of National League ball has seen them lose their
three-week grip on the top rung of the AL East. They have lost six
of seven and Sunday they'll trot out Mark Portugal, followed by Jin
Ho Cho Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The slow bleed has seen them lose Juan Pena, Saberhagen, and
Gordon (soon) to the disabled list. There is no way to minimize the
seriousness of the Gordon situation. If he has ripped his pitching
elbow, go ahead and make those plans for October. In the meantime,
Tim Wakefield is the new closer, which only further dents the
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Remember three and four weeks ago when the Sox seemed to have
too much pitching? Fans wondered, ``What are we gonna do with all
these starters? Maybe we should trade a couple for a power
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, right now, in the spirit of ``Spahn and Sain and two days
of rain,'' the Sox are looking at ``Pedro and Rose and . . . who
knows?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no such thing as too much pitching,'' said Sox
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``We're just fortunate that we're
15-16 deep. Every spring we tell them all that if they don't come
north as one of the first 11 pitchers, they'll have plenty of
chances during the season. And it always works out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the hitting, not the pitching, that is killing the Red
Sox. Saturday's lineup featured a five-through-nine murderers row
of Damon Buford, Troy O'Leary, Creighton Gubanich, Darren Lewis,
and Pat Rapp. The Sox have hit only 57 homers, which puts them 12th
in the American League. Make sure to bring those ``Mo Who?''
T-shirts to Fenway Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep swinging, keep playing,'' said manager Jimy Williams.
``What can I do? Hell, I couldn't hit when I played. I'm not going
to hit the pitcher eighth. We hit some balls good today that were
caught. If we keep playing like that, we're going to win some
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, a veteran of slumps past, said, ``That's the good thing
about Jimy. He keeps things positive. We need to stay as positive
as we can in light of what's going on. We just got our butts kicked
in Montreal, but he keeps us positive about the things that we're
doing right. For a while we were scoring runs and getting the big
hit with runners in scoring position. Now we're struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin and Darren Lewis are at .257. Trot Nixon is
hitting .226 and has 12 RBIs in 137 at-bats. Jason Varitek is at
.241. Jose Offerman has cooled off, and even Nomar Garciaparra (3
for 17) is suddenly struggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to score runs as it is,'' said Lewis, another
veteran. ``But now when we do hit the ball hard it seems like it's
going at someone or they're making spectacular plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimywocky must have been afraid to turn his guys loose on the
town Saturday night. The city that doesn't sleep is a madhouse this
weekend. The Knicks have taken over the Apple, and the manager of
the Mets appears to be losing his mind. (Come to think of it, when
Bobby ``Master of Disguise'' Valentine serves his two-game
suspension, how will we know he's not really in the dugout? Maybe
next time he'll put on blackface and pretend he's Mookie Wilson.)
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Mookie, here's one last nugget from New York. On
Thursday, the same day Saberhagen was walking on busted glass at a
team party, Bill Buckner and Mookie did a signing at the Roosevelt
Field Shopping Center in Garden City, N.Y. For $25 you could get
Bill and Mookie to sign a photo of the infamous grounder. The photo
is dubbed, ``The boot,'' and the newspaper ad touted this item as a
``Great Gift for Father's Day!''
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh. Blood on the floor of the Saberhagen mansion. Flash flown
home for an MRI. No power. A raft of disabled pitchers. And
baseball's apocalyptic error selling as a Father's Day item.
</P>
<P>
   Only in New York. Can we all please leave now?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
