<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANCES SLIM THAT ARMSTRONG WILL SLIP AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Everybody here has been talking about the
newest Patriot, a 295-pound left tackle. Pete Carroll talks about
him. Bobby Grier talks about him. Players talk about him. I don't
blame any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Some rotund tackles don't surprise you when they say, ``I'm an
offensive lineman.'' Well, you should see the new guy. He's got
that Muscle Magazine cover boy look about him. He was wearing a
T-shirt Saturday. His chest bulged out of the thing so much that
you swore there were steel drums hidden beneath his skin. The new
guy looks good.
</P>
<P>
   Foxboro Stadium is no different from most offices and schools in
the country: The new employee or student comes and the gossip
starts. Same here. The gossip _ not at all mean-spirited _ has been
about the new man's weight. How much has he lost?
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say 10, some say 25, some say 50,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What's the truth?
</P>
<P>
   ``Twelve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The man's name is Bruce Armstrong. He is 33 years old. He plays
left tackle, the NFL's Secret Service position. The quarterback is
the president and the left tackle, usually protecting his
blindside, has got to see what the QB doesn't. That's what the new
guy, Armstrong, will have to do this season when he protects Drew
Bledsoe and . . .
</P>
<P>
   What's that? You say Armstrong is not new? You haven't been
paying attention to the Patriots and their weekend minicamp. It's
not often that a photograph causes me to do a triple take, but
that's exactly what I did when I saw Armstrong in Saturday's Globe.
I stared at it for several seconds wondering, ``Is that really
him?'' And then I had to drive here to see the new guy for myself.
I'm not saying that he looked bad last year, but he certainly
didn't look like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always lifted weights like a football player,'' Armstrong
explained. So when he went home to Alpharetta, Ga., he decided to
change the plan that had worked for more than 10 years. ``I lifted
weights like I was a bodybuilder.''
</P>
<P>
   It obviously worked. That's why the gossip is in place.
Armstrong looks as if he had a makeover. One of the changes he made
as Armstrong The Bodybuilder was to increase the repetitions in his
weightlifting. It's the repetitions that bring about the muscle
tone. As for Armstrong The Football Player, last season was one in
which people said things about him that he has rarely heard in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Parcells once said that football is not cumbersome for
Armstrong because he ``gets it.'' He is one of the most intelligent
men on the team and has been one of its most eloquent spokesmen
since coming into the league in 1987. But last season there were
whispers that he looked old. There was talk that he needed to be
moved to the right side of the line to make room for a younger man.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the talk seemed to ignore the facts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played hurt last year,'' Carroll said. ``Remember? He had
that big, plastic cast on his leg. There was that whole controversy
in training camp on whether he should play or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong played with a stress fracture for all 16 games. He
also was bothered by a pulled groin. Because of his injuries and
the injuries to many of his teammates, is it fair to say that
Armstrong should be a regular attendee of Johnny Parker's offseason
strength and conditioning program? Armstrong says no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great relationship with Johnny Parker,'' he said. He
added, ``I know my body.'' He is a veteran who has been to the
Super Bowl and Pro Bowl. He has survived the days of Patriot chaos,
survived the days of Parcells, and is now going into his third
season with Carroll. He said no one had to tell him to lose weight
and tone his body; he just did it. You'd have to say he has good
timing. Here's why: He will be part of a unit that is now the
team's biggest question mark.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds strange to say about the Patriots' offense. It's
always been assumed that offense is the team's strength. But there
is a rookie center who may start in place of the departed Dave
Wohlabaugh. Robert Edwards is out for the year, so two backs who
weren't here last season _ Kevin Faulk and Lamont Warren _ will
compete for his vacated job. The offensive line coach took another
job. And before he did, Paul Boudreau found himself shuffling and
reshuffling the line to find a combination he liked. Terry Glenn is
injury-prone. And then there is Armstrong, a man who is coming off
a season in which he was called fat and slow.
</P>
<P>
   He is asked if the team, as constructed, can be one of the top
ones in the league. ``Oh yeah,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke those words, he began to walk in another direction.
You got the sense that there was a place Armstrong needed to be. He
walked and the questions kept coming, about the team's chances,
about what a good leader should be, about Parker and his program.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was a question about the specifics of his workout
in Georgia. Really, the queen of weight-loss infomercials, Susan
Powter, has nothing on Armstrong. If he can make such a noticeable
difference by losing 12 pounds, maybe he's the one who needs to be
teaching people about proper dieting and exercise. Did he also do
Tae Bo at home? What's his secret?
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he also changed his weightlifting technique. But
he didn't have time to get into specifics. ``I have to go in
here,'' he said, pointing to a door. It was the weight room.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
