</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS DISAPPOINTED, THEN DISAPPEARED 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So much for that Utah-Indiana final.
</P>
<P>
   One half of it fell a while back. The other went unceremoniously
in the early morning hours Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks exposed the Pacers for what they are _ a team bereft
of athleticism that relied on experience and precision to win. The
Knicks disrupted that routine and Indiana had no Plan B. In the
end, the Pacers had no answer for the acrobatics of Marcus Camby or
Latrell Sprewell and, in the series-closing game, were outshot,
33-9, at the free throw line by a team without a legitimate inside
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Frauds? Well, you can make a case for them failing to meet their
own lofty expectations. You can probably fault them for taking the
Knicks lightly _ what other reason for all those no-shows during
the series? _ and for buying into all those nice things written
about them. You can certainly fault them for inexcusable lapses,
such as Camby's giant keep-alive in Game 3 with three Pacers
standing by idly. (Sprewell did the same thing in Game 6, although
the Knicks didn't capitalize.) And did we mention that the Knicks
won three big jump balls in Game 6, including one when Chris Childs
got the tip over Dale Davis?
</P>
<P>
   It's almost as if the Pacers felt they were entitled to move on
simply because of who they were and what they had done. That
doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough. It hurts,'' said Antonio Davis. ``I think it's
tougher because we put so much pressure on ourselves to win. It's
like we beat ourselves, more than any opponent beat us. Hopefully,
we can learn from this and become a better team and better
players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers aren't the first favorite to get floored by a hot
team and won't be the last. But this one has to hurt a lot, much
more than last year, when they extended the Bulls to seven games.
They were the noble pretenders in that series, catching people by
surprise and shaped in the all-business image of their rookie
coach. They were the Munich '38 Pacers in this one.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird kept waiting for players to deliver and he's still
waiting. He has to take his share of the blame; why did he have to
wait at all? Why couldn't they deal with Camby; he's not the first
athletic big man they've faced and they have some big guys
themselves. You just didn't see that same, passioned, now-or-never
look the team had last year. But, then again, Bird wasn't the one
bricking all those open jumpers and not boxing out.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Miller was a monumental disappointment. He turned into
Todd Day in Game 6 after a vastly overrated 30-point effort in a
Game 5 loss. (Contrast that with the absolutely macho 32 delivered
by Allan Houston in winning Game 6.) He has to wonder how many more
opportunities he's going to get with this unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Miller said, ``because I definitely feel I
let our franchise down. Really, our state. They've been riding my
back as well. For me to come up so short in such a crucial time is
very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Rik Smits? Where was he for most of the series? Chris Mullin? He
had a great Game 4 but was nearly invisible in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   All through this season, the Pacers showed signs that they
weren't the same as last year. They were 10-10 in games decided by
4 or fewer points, with a third of their losses, 6 of 17, by 1
point. They supposedly had settled down and gotten their Second
Season faces on with sweeps of Milwaukee and Philadelphia, two
happy-to-be-here teams. Then they gave away Game 1 to the Knicks,
blew a 17-point lead in Game 2 before winning on two questionable
calls, and regurgitated a 14-point lead in losing Game 5 at home
after tying the series. They were awful in the fourth quarter, the
time when experienced, savvy, structured teams are supposed to
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers thought they had the right mix. They still think they
do. The players feel the better team lost. They're still in denial,
which is understandable. They have a whole summer to figure it out,
one that begins with them having to watch the Knicks and Spurs
battle for the crown they thought was custom-fitted for them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder what is going on with the Celtics and Ron
Mercer. This cannot be a money thing; the Celtics aren't the
Florida Marlins. When Rick Pitino talks about his ``budget,'' he
neglects to note that he's already far over it anyway. If he's so
concerned about money and Mercer, why was he so quick to re-sign
Walter McCarty for $2.8 million per year? There may be an honest
difference of opinion about what Mercer is worth, which would
hardly be an NBA first. That's what negotiations are all about. It
can't be about Mercer's viability as a contributor; he's a very
nice piece of the puzzle (to borrow a phrase from M.L. Carr). But
with the Celtics entertaining trade offers and Pitino saying he
can't get in touch with Mercer's agent, well, you can see where
this is all going. So can Tevester Scott, who represents Mercer.
``It's propaganda,'' he said. ``I've talked several times to
(Boston general manager) Chris Wallace. You start feeding the media
like that and I wonder, what's your reason?'' Scott is well aware
that he and No Limit, the agency handling Mercer, are making their
NBA debut and people are watching. He is aware of the rules that
prevent negotiations before July 1. That includes faxing contract
proposals. ``I don't know what they expect me to do,'' Scott said.
``I mean, how far can you go? Not very far. We're new and people
are waiting for us to slip up. I won't. I know the rules.''
Regarding Mercer, Scott said, ``Ron has no problem with the city of
Boston or the fans. (He never mentioned Pitino.) I have to go for
the best deal I can get. I can't base that on what the Celtics are
saying. The only thing Ron's worried about is if Boston is willing
to step up to the table. He wants the best situation for him.'' The
real fear among the Celtics has to be that Mercer will leave. As
Kevin McHale noted, that should only be a fear if there are three
teams lined up to pay him what the Celtics won't. That doesn't seem
to be the case, although Chicago GM Jerry Krause likes him a lot
and could have a hefty stash to spend next summer. But this is not
new; the Celtics have been discussing a Mercer trade for a while.
They can't move him alone because his salary is artificially small
(by NBA standards), which is why he's being coupled with Kenny
Anderson. It's really something. Two years ago, Pitino stood at a
podium at the FleetCenter and announced he had his backcourt of the
future. Chauncey Billups lasted five months. It doesn't seem as
though Mercer is going to stick around a whole lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy on his role: ``I'm just thankful that I'm part of
a team that's still playing. Whatever small part I play in it, I
take seriously, try to do the best job I can. Like I said before
about criticism, if you're paralyzed by thoughts that you may be
criticized for something, you will never be the risk-taker you need
to be as a coach and leader. Risk-taking is part of it. If it
doesn't work out, you accept responsibility for it not working
out.'' . . . Last Thursday was Fan Appreciation Day at the Delta
Center for Karl Malone. About 20,000 fans showed up to pay homage
to the Mailman as well as to get a tour of the Jazz locker room and
see Malone's five Harley-Davidsons on display. Malone signed only a
few autographs; he mostly mingled and schmoozed. He also brought
some of his classic car collection and memorabilia, including his
two MVP trophies . . . Speaking of the Jazz, owner Larry Miller
says it's his gut feeling that Malone, John Stockton, and Jeff
Hornacek will be back. They're all free agents, as is Shandon
Anderson, who is certain to draw attention. We may never know
whether this past season benefited anyone, but the Jazz had to be
viewed, in the end, as something out of the first half-hour of
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Including the playoffs, Utah lost 11 of
its last 21 games. It got almost nothing from Greg Ostertag in the
playoffs. Very early in Game 6 against Portland, Utah's last game,
coach Jerry Sloan turned to his staff and said, ``Karl is dead.''
Malone certainly didn't have it that night; he was 3 of 16 from the
field. Later, Sloan said this past season was the worst he's ever
experienced, which says a lot since he was fired in Chicago in 1982
. . . Tim Hardaway broke a silence of sorts after the Heat's
disappointing playoff collapse to the Knicks and told Ira Winderman
of the Fort Lauderdale Sun-Sentinel that there wasn't the usual
``togetherness'' on this year's squad. ``There wasn't that
camaraderie. Everybody was scared to talk to one another,'' he
said. ``I probably spoke too much and that's what probably got me
and Pat (Riley) off (track). I told him it was my fault. I
shouldn't have said those things . . . I had a bad season. I had a
bad year.'' Asked about being traded, Hardaway said, ``If a team
lets me go, like the Golden State Warriors did, it would be a big
mistake.'' He turns 33 Sept. 1 . . . In each of the last seven
seasons, Scottie Pippen was All-NBA on either the first, second, or
third team. This year, he managed a single vote, same as Smits. We
can already imagine the trade rumors sending him to the Lakers if
Phil Jackson takes over. (A re-signed Glen Rice and others?)
Meanwhile, all but five teams had at least one player receive a
vote for the All-NBA teams. Those five were the Celtics, Clippers,
Warriors, Bulls, and, if you can believe it, the Knicks. When was
the last time a team was in the Finals without having one player
get one mention for an all-pro team? . . . Shaquille O'Neal and the
triple-post offense? We may look forward to that with Jackson's
return. Jackson is understandably intrigued by the Lakers, but will
he be Big Chief Triangle again with the game's most dominating
low-post presence on his roster? ``It's a very hard offense to
learn,'' said the Pistons' Jud Buechler. ``You have to be patient
but it's worth it because everyone is involved, everyone touches
the ball, you feel like you're doing something. The rest of the NBA
is all standing around.'' Adds Chicago's Krause, ``You have to have
a high basketball IQ to play it.'' If he does anything with the
Lakers, Jackson would be bucking the trend of the last several
coaches to win NBA titles and move elsewhere. The only one who has
had much success is Riley. Chuck Daly had a couple playoff
appearances with New Jersey and Bill Fitch got the Rockets to the
Finals in 1986 . . . Shaq, meanwhile, was the runaway scoring
leader based on 48-minute projections. The self-proclaimed Superman
averaged 36.3 points, 5.1 more than Allen Iverson, the actual
scoring leader. The rebounding leader? None other than the Nuggets'
Danny Fortson, who projected a haul of 19.7 a game. No Celtic
placed in the top 10 in any of the significant categories. But
Antoine Walker was seventh in shots attempted, which comes as no
surprise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
