<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0006 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3394 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      06-13 2377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE WAS NO NEED TO REVISIT KATZENMOYER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In the old days, before computers, there
used to be an expression in the newspaper business. A street
reporter would scurry around town gathering facts, then call the
office and bellow in dramatic fashion from a pay phone, ``Give me
rewrite!''
</P>
<P>
   On the phone would come a desk editor who had a way with words
to take the facts and rewrite them, turning the reporter's
information into a story. This procedure usually was used when time
was of the essence and news was being broken.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, however, Sports Illustrated took the expression
literally. For purposes only the magazine's editors truly know
(although I have my suspicions), they chose to rewrite a year-old
story about the educational follies of Patriots No. 1 draft choice
Andy Katzenmoyer at Ohio State and try to sell it as ``news.''
</P>
<P>
   When they wrote about Katzenmoyer last fall, it was a story of
great impact, making obvious that Katzenmoyer's only connections to
Ohio State were at the football stadium and in the cafeteria. It
made obvious that his academic standing was a joke and he was to
play that fall only through the oddest of summer school work, a
class load that included ``golf'' and ``AIDS awareness'' for
credit; the final exam for the latter was putting a condom on a
piece of fruit without damaging either. If such courses are the aim
of a college education, perhaps we should close the colleges.
</P>
<P>
   SI's point was that Katzenmoyer should no more be occupying a
seat in a college classroom than a potted plant should. It was
hardly a revelation, however, since anyone who has paid any
attention to big-time college athletics understands that the
Katzenmoyers are becoming the rule in high-profile football and
basketball programs rather than the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was a valid story, showing how an All-America
linebacker could be kept alive for athletic purposes while making
little or no progress toward an academic degree. To their credit,
neither Katzenmoyer nor his family tried to argue that he was a
student-athlete. They all acknowledged he had gone to Ohio State to
play football and hopefully learn enough about his trade to earn a
place in the NFL, which he did this spring when the Patriots made
him the second of their two first-round selections. To that extent,
at least, his OSU ``education'' served him well.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what Katzenmoyer did to deserve a second story on the
same subject is difficult to fathom. The ``new'' SI story reveals
nothing new about his academic woes. It does not make new charges
of further educational fraud. It does not point to new classes in
which he was taken care of by Ohio State's alleged educators, only
old ones we already knew about. It does nothing but use Katzenmoyer
to get some cheap publicity _ the same thing, frankly, that Ohio
State did with him the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an effort to exonerate Katzenmoyer for his shameful
academic efforts. Clearly he did little or nothing to advance
himself off the football field. He has already paid a price for
that in bad publicity that he admits hurt him and his family and
for which he recognizes his own culpability. If his football career
is a failure, he will continue to pay for the decisions he made.
</P>
<P>
   But while the shame last year was Katzenmoyer's when SI wrote
the story, the shame this time is the magazine's. The supposed
``revelation'' that the university received at least two letters
last August complaining of the special treatment Katzenmoyer
received was the excuse to rewrite a story that had already made
headlines once.
</P>
<P>
   Prominent in those headlines was the name of Sports Illustrated,
a magazine that finds itself locked in a circulation battle with
the upstart ESPN Magazine _ much more of a battle than it
originally expected. If this is SI's response to that, shame on it.
</P>
<P>
   If it was simply an effort to racially balance a much larger
article about educational shenanigans at the University of
Minnesota involving a black basketball coach, black players, and a
white tutor who allegedly wrote papers for money to keep them
eligible, shame on SI as well.
</P>
<P>
   And if it was just a cheap shot, a second bite at the same
apple, shame on SI all the more.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer is far from the only college athlete to march
through his education in this way, and there's enough shame in that
to go around, including plenty for the media.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who tries to argue the Katzenmoyer story is the exception
simply doesn't know what's going on or has spent far less time than
I have trying to have conversations with some of these athletes
after they've allegedly spent 2-5 years at some of our biggest and
best universities. Too many of them would need the help of Lewis
and Clark to find the campus library.
</P>
<P>
   This is the main reason I have little interest any more in
big-time college sports. It is a cesspool of lies, deceit, and
corruption at least as deep as anything I've found in the seamy
world of prizefighting, which at least doesn't claim to be anything
more than a money-making enterprise. This is not meant to demean
the many student-athletes who really are both. It is just to point
out that too many of them are on the track team or the volleyball
squad while too many others in revenue-producing programs (read:
football and basketball) are like Katzenmoyer or his former
teammate, Damon Moore, who is quoted in the SI story as having had
a similar summer school experience to stay eligible before entering
the NFL this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Football is the only sport without a minor league system. To a
lesser extent, basketball suffers the same problem, and the
colleges have chosen to fill that vacuum. I venture to say that if
there were a true minor league NFL system, Katzenmoyer, Moore, and
a lot of other people would never have set foot on a college
campus.
</P>
<P>
   If it were possible to go from high school to the NFL, as some
unusually talented and physically advanced basketball players can
do, they'd do that as well. But no high school football player is
physically ready to be hit by Reggie White or Tony Boselli at 18.
</P>
<P>
   So they go to college and the fraud begins. To expose it is
fine, but the media turn a blind eye to the fraud each fall
Saturday and winter weekend when the Ohio States go out to play the
Minnesotas or the Florida States do battle with the Miamis.
</P>
<P>
   We in the media glorify what we know is a fraud upon academia
and the public and then, to purge our own guilt, from time to time
expose the fraud as if we are surprised. We do this for a few weeks
until some kid gets publicly flogged or some college ends up on
probation, and then business returns to normal.
</P>
<P>
   If that's what it takes for some editors to sleep at night, so
be it, but to nail Andy Katzenmoyer twice for the same offense
would be a 15-yard penalty on the football field. It's called
piling on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right now, agent Rocky Arceneaux has bigger things to worry
about than the contract status of his client Marshall Faulk with
the St. Louis Rams. It seems a condo owned by Arceneaux was
recently raided by St. Louis police, who claimed a high-priced
escort service was being run out of the place. When the police got
there, whom did they stumble upon but St. Louis Cardinals
outfielder Ray Lankford? And while they were casing the joint, in
walked 300-plus-pound Rams offensive tackle Orlando Pace, which
only goes to show that it can pay to sleep late. It was 5 a.m. when
Pace walked in, claiming to know nothing about the alleged
prostitution ring. Lankford claimed the same, and both were
released because of lack of evidence, but Lankford was found to be
in possession of the following: keys to the place, several packages
of condoms, lubricants, and an empty 50 mg bottle of Viagra. Two
men were arrested for running the operation, which came to the
police's attention after they took out a want ad in a weekly paper
seeking ``beautfiul young ladies as exotic dancers and lingerie
models who want to make a lot of money. Our clients are pro
athletes and corporate executives, so you must have class, be
talented and dependable.'' Right . . . The fact Pace obviously has
some discretionary income may explain why he did not do enough
workouts to earn a $50,000 bonus this offseason. ``An extra $50,000
to a guy like Pace is just a tax problem,'' said an NFC insider . .
. Here's what the NFL has become. Former Cleveland Browns defensive
backs Frank Minniefield and Hanford Dixon claimed they should get a
piece of the revived team's licensing revenue for the nickname
``Dawg Pound,'' which they coined for the rowdy end zone fans at
the old Municipal Stadium. But the NFL says it holds all the
licensing rights, even though it acknowledges that Minniefield and
Dixon came up with the idea. Whatever happened to intellectual
property, lowbrow as this type might be? According to the league,
once the term became associated with the Browns, the NFL owned it.
Since the NFL put a trademark on it, Dixon and Minniefield are out
of luck, but are you telling me the NFL couldn't throw the
ex-players who came up with the idea a nickel, a shirt, or
something? . . . Let's give Arizona general manager Bob Ferguson a
standing ovation. When Ferguson was told that young defensive
tackle Mark Smith would not attend a minicamp because of a contract
dispute, he said, ``He ought to look around and see what they're
paying at McDonald's.'' Smith and his agent, Gil Thompson, were
outraged, and Thompson said Smith wanted to be traded. Ferguson
wrote a letter of apology Monday and has since said his remarks
were ``unprofessional.'' Maybe so, but that doesn't mean they
weren't accurate. Like many teams, the Cardinals are having salary
cap problems. Despite being $1.5 million under the cap at the
moment, they have to unload another $3 million to cover their
rookie pool expenses. At the same time, Smith is demanding a
one-year, $1 million contract, refusing to sign the $325,000
minimum tender offer made to him as a third-year pro. Considering
that, Ferguson may have picked the wrong job. You have to know how
to make change at McDonald's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although he has twice said he is not mentally ready to come back
to pro football, quarterback Mark Rypien spoke with Chargers line
coach Joe Bugel last week and said he was leaving the door open.
Rypien sat out last season to spend time with his ailing son, but
Chargers GM Bobby Beathard hoped to bring him in to help struggling
Ryan Leaf. San Diego has Jim Harbaugh as the designated starter but
might take a flyer on Rypien as a veteran backup. Here's a quote
that sums up the Charger veterans' point of view on Leaf, who
missed the opening of last week's minicamp to play in a golf
tournament. ``Youth is one thing, ignorance is another,''
linebacker Lew Bush said. ``He's got to wake up. It's not funny. It
ain't no joke. This is our livelihood. You've got to be
professional about it and right now, up to this point, he hasn't
been.'' The thing that most bothers new Charger coach Mike Riley
and Beathard is that Leaf lied to them about his whereabouts last
month after he vanished for a week. Leaf claimed he was working
with a personal trainer in Orange County, Calif., but the trainer
said he hadn't seen Leaf in a year. Then he was told by the club to
tell the media the truth if asked about the incident because there
was a videotape of him telling a reporter he was working out with
the trainer. Instead, Leaf lied again, telling reporters there had
been a miscommunication between him and the club. Considering how
Leaf acted last year, considering how he played (2 TD passes and 15
interceptions), considering that he has been caught lying this year
to his coach, his teammates, his general manager, and the local
media, one can only wonder one thing. Who changes his diapers? . .
. The Patriots made a small move in their scouting staff, firing
Edwin Bailey, who covered the Southeast, and replacing him with
Jason Licht. Licht worked the past two seasons for National
Combine, one of two scouting services used by many NFL teams. He
was assigned to the Carolina Panthers . . . The Patriots are
bringing in ex-Ravens receiver Michael Jackson for a look this week
but they can't sign him unless they continue to cut veterans to
make salary cap room. Jackson led the NFL in TD receptions in 1996
with 14 but he has been hurt the past two years and was considered
damaged goods in Baltimore, so much so that the Ravens chose to
sign Webster Slaughter to a one-year, minimum-salary deal
($400,000). The 34-year-old Slaughter was out of the NFL in 1997
and spent much of last year languishing on the sidelines in San
Diego, where he caught only eight passes and broke his finger in
November . . . Pete Carroll continues to keep his eye on ex-Redskin
running back Terry Allen, but until Allen brings down his contract
demands a lot closer to the NFL minimum for a nine-year veteran
he'll remain unemployed. The real place New England should be
looking is Miami, which has 10 backs and one ball. No way they all
survive, and any one of the top half-dozen is better than anyone on
New England's present roster . . . Pro Bowl cornerback Ty Law
continues to work as hard as anyone on the Patriot roster. After
the final minicamp ends Tuesday, he will take a few days to rest
and then head for St. Louis to continue workouts with top Olympic
track coach Bob Kersee. Law, along with many other NFL players
including Jerome Bettis, has been working out with Kersee at the
UCLA track but a real measure of his commitment is to shift from LA
to St. Louis in late June . . . By the way, despite all of Willie
McGinest's offseason efforts to solve the hamstring problems that
have plagued him, he is not yet 100 percent and did only limited
work at the final minicamp. The belief is that he'll be healthy and
ready to go by training camp, but the Patriots do not want to risk
a reinjury now. The same did not apply to Terry Glenn, however.
``He's full go,'' Carroll said. ``We're all anxious to see how he
handles himself. This camp will be a good gauge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
