<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3395 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXINGNOTEBOOK-BO     06-13 1953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS NEW `LEAGUE' THE WAY TO MAKE A CLEAN BREAK 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The last thing boxing would seem to need right now is
another set of capital letters, but Pensacola, Fla., attorney Fred
Levin believes there is one set that might help clean up the
sport's image, and it's not ``FBI.'' It's ``WBL,'' as in World
Boxing League.
</P>
<P>
   Temporarily, at least, that is the name Levin has attached to an
idea he's been hatching for two years to try to bring some order
into the red light district of sports. Levin, who recently earned
$275 million as the lead attorney in Florida's case against the
tobacco industry that resulted in a $13 billion settlement,
stumbled upon his idea in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has spent the last half-decade or so advising Roy
Jones, who just happens to be the best pound-for-pound fighter in
the world. In the process, Levin had his eyes opened to a seamy
side of sport he never quite knew existed. Second, he read a book
called, ``The NASCAR Way,'' a tome about the marketing of the
fastest-growing professional sport in the country, auto racing.
</P>
<P>
   Those two experiences helped Levin see the light, and now he's
hoping a big-name sponsor and the world's top fighters will, too,
because if they do, they could make the WBC, WBA, WBO, WBU, IBF,
IBC, IBA, and their 119 ``world champions'' and phony rankings
obsolete. For that alone, Levin's plan deserves serious
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 10 years I been screwed up in this, I got an education
quick from Don King, Bob Arum, and the rest of 'em,'' Levin said.
``Then you start fooling with those sanctioning bodies and you
learn how it works. Nobody ever solicited a dime from me but it was
obvious what was going on. Roy would beat the hell out of a guy and
the next month the guy would be rated ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally signed a three-fight deal with Arum because we
could see you had to be connected. We did it to get to (then super
middleweight champion James) Toney. But it pissed me off. Roy could
afford to do it, but not every fighter is in the position of a Roy
Jones. I just started thinking there had to be a way to end the
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Levin joined forces with Dallas Mavericks
president-CEO Terdema Ussery, the ex-commissioner of the
Continental Basketball Association and ex-president of Nike Sports
Management. It was through Jones's affiliation with Nike that Levin
and Ussery began to talk about boxing's ills. It was a long
conversation that led to a simple solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're calling it the World Boxing League for now but it
wouldn't really be a league,'' Levin said. ``I've got some leading
sports figures and business people interested in being
stockholders, and what we want to do is get a commissioner who
everybody in boxing would respect as a person of integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the WBL would contract with someone like the Boxing
Writers Association to provide independent rankings. We'd have
nothing to do with them beyond paying for the service. There'd be
no interference from the WBL with the ratings service, not like it
is now where it's all done internally and who knows what goes on?
The writers or whoever send the ratings and we live with 'em.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we'd cut the divisions to 10-12 (from the present 17) and
we'd provide professional referees and officials who would be paid
by the WBL, not the promoters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most important, we'd charge no sanction fees to fighters. Roy
paid $400,000 in sanction fees and Reggie (Johnson) paid over
$100,000 (for last weekend's light heavyweight unification title
fight). For what? A plastic belt? They charge you extra for the
damn belt!
</P>
<P>
   ``Our model is NASCAR, which has private-sector sponsoring.
Other sports have gone to the same thing. What we're looking for is
one sponsor to put up around $3 million a year for several years
and they'd get the Pepsi World Champions or the Gillette World
Champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of its long history in boxing, Gillette is a natural.
It's a credible brand name that would distinguish its champions
from the rest. Roy, for example, would be the `Gillette light
heavyweight champion of the world.' They'd get the naming rights to
the belts and the peripheral marketing tools like the ring mat for
40 or 50 title fights a year. And boxing is an international
business so we're not just talking about brand exposure in the US.
It would be on worldwide television regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``With fewer champions associated with a major corporation and
an organization that doesn't charge sanction fees or get involved
in rankings, people would start to recognize boxing again for the
great sport it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin points out that Budweiser just paid $10 million to have
its logo on Dale Earnhardt's stock car for five years; it will be
plastered on any empty space Earnhardt can find because he already
has a multitude of other logos on his car and racing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In the WBL's case, there would be only one sponsor, at least
initially. That company would get the full benefit of what Levin
and Ussery believe would quickly become the recognized world
champions in a sport with more kings at the moment than the Roman
Empire had.
</P>
<P>
   But why would the fighters risk entering a new venture when
boxing's three crime families _ the World Boxing Council, World
Boxing Association, and International Boxing Federation _ still
wield so much power over their futures?
</P>
<P>
   Five more letters. M-O-N-E-Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd need the biggest champions to come with us,'' Levin
acknowledged. ``We'd need Roy and Lennox Lewis and Oscar (De La
Hoya). We'd need (Shane) Mosley and the other guys viewed by the
boxing media and the public as the true champions at the various
weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think the media would accept the idea almost immediately
because it's a better system than the one that's in place'' _ and
under investigation by the Federal government for selling ratings
and title shots. ``The public would accept it if it gave them one
true champion and the politicians would love it because they know
they can't legislate boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighters would go for it because they wouldn't have to pay
those sanction fees to fight for a championship. It wouldn't cost a
nickel to become a champion in this organization. There's no
negative to this thing other than finding a sponsor. The only
people who'd be against it are the promoters because they've been
making good livings manipulating the system for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin said the WBL's champions could fight for the titles of
other organizations, if they wanted, but if he and Ussery and their
partners can find the right sponsor and convince champions like
Jones to believe in them, he believes, before long there won't be
other titles to fight for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organizations will fall by the wayside,'' Levin said.
``You won't have all these champions. You'll have more TV fights
between top-rated guys fighting for a chance to get a shot at a
real title.''
</P>
<P>
   If Fred Levin has his way _ and, as the tobacco industry
learned, he usually does _ that title will come with a razor maker
or a soda can logo, and something else. It will come with some
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bad blood between Fernando Vargas and De La Hoya almost
spilled on a restaurant floor last week in Big Bear, Calif., where
Vargas is training for his July 17 fight with former IBF junior
middleweight champion Raul Marquez, an Olympic teammate and friend
of De La Hoya's. Big Bear is a small community with only two real
restaurants, so it was no surprise that both the new IBF 154-pound
champion and the old one ended up at Sandy's Sports Bar, three
tables apart, since both are training at Big Bear to prepare for
the altitude at Lake Tahoe. The two began exchanging cross words,
and when De La Hoya arrived to join Marquez for dinner, Vargas
accused De La Hoya of plotting against him with Marquez in hopes of
seeing Vargas lose before De La Hoya had to face him. When a long
line of autograph seekers began to form at De La Hoya's table,
several sources said, Vargas grew enraged and louder before finally
leaving. Last week, at a press conference in Los Angeles, Marquez
handed Vargas a De La Hoya T-shirt and Vargas threw it back,
snapping, ``Keep it! You'll need it to wipe the blood out of your
mouth!'' To say there's bad blood here would be an understatement .
. . After that incident, De La Hoya reaffirmed his decision to
never fight Vargas, who has taunted and criticized De La Hoya since
he was on the 1996 Olympic team and failed to follow De La Hoya's
1992 gold medal performance with one of his own. De La Hoya told
Arum he intends to fight Felix Trinidad Sept. 18 and then move up
to 154 pounds but not to chase Vargas. Rather, he plans to
challenge WBC champion Javier Castillejo before moving on to WBA
champion David Reid, himself a former Olympic gold medalist and
Vargas knocker . . . Reid's July challenger, Kevin Kelly of
Australia (not the one from Flushing, N.Y.), is of so little skill
and import that HBO has declined to televise the fight despite
holding a deal with Reid . . . Robert Alcazar, De La Hoya's
trainer, was quoted in El Mundo, a Spanish-language newspaper in
Puerto Rico, as saying his fighter now wanted double his agreed-to
$15 million purse to fight Trinidad. Fortunately, De La Hoya has
more sense about dollars and cents than Alcazar. He told Arum that
while he had several contractual issues about the pay-per-view
overages, the size of his guarantee is not a problem. The proof of
that is De La Hoya and Trinidad will launch a nine-city promotional
tour Monday in New York. They will then fly on separate planes to
Chicago Tuesday. Then it's on to Miami and San Juan Wednesday,
Houston and Dallas Thursday, Mexico City Friday, Universal Studios
in Los Angeles Friday, and a big finish at the Las Vegas Hilton
Theatre Saturday night, when they will join Latino pop idol Luis
Luis on stage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The decision by IBF junior lightweight champion Roberto Garcia
to pull out of his title fight last weekend against Derrick
``Smoke'' Gainer because he didn't like the makeup of the officials
was a smart one. Who but the most naive could blame him after he
saw judges from Florida (Gainer's home state) and Mississippi
(where Gainer has often fought) and none from California, his home
state? The champion turned his back on a $400,000 payday, the
largest of his career, and another $200,000 for a rematch within 90
days if he lost for the simple reason that he believed the rematch
was as guaranteed as last weekend's purse. HBO executive Kery Davis
was in the middle of the on-site negotiations and was justifiably
upset, arguing, ``I'm not naive, but if we go along with these kind
of things, we're saying our sport is corrupt. We're saying each guy
comes with his own judge and the third guy is responsible for
getting it right. I can't accept that.'' Perhaps not, but one
veteran boxing insider said, ``It looked like they were setting the
kid up. Maybe they weren't, but it looked that way.'' . . . Garcia
may still end up on HBO this fall vs. WBC champion Floyd Mayweather
. . . World Boxing Organization heavyweight champion Herbie Hide
was recently declared bankrupt in England because of his refusal to
pay some bills, and this is causing problems with how he is to be
paid for his June 26 title fight with 6-foot-7-inch Vitali
Klitschko. The biggest problem came when Hide told a British
reporter he had left 8,000 pounds next to a lamp in his room at his
training camp and when he returned the money was on fire. Soon, so
were British court officers, demanding to know where it came from.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0032EDT &QL; 
