<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0008 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      06-13 2108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS UNABLE TO ASSIST JANNEY 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ He had the personal trainer ready to whip him into
shape. This was going to be a big summer for Craig Janney. He was
looking at July 1, the day he'll become an unrestricted free agent,
as his chance to find a new place to play and secure his long-term
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, unfortunately, I've exhausted every opinion out
there,'' said the former Bruins center. ``It looks like I won't be
able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 31 years old, Janney a couple of weeks ago notified the
Islanders, his most recent port of call, that a troublesome blood
clot below his right knee would not allow him to continue his
career. Janney said last week that no fewer than five doctors
diagnosed critical vascular damage in the leg and an impaired valve
that relays blood back to his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not functional in a hockey sense,'' said Janney,
speaking by phone from Scottsdale, Ariz., where he lives with wife
Kim and the couple's 15-month-old daughter, Barrette. ``The clot's
not going away _ it might not ever go away _ and there's a chance
I'll have to stay on blood thinners the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Janney, the clot developed late in the season after
he took what he felt was a harmless slash during a team practice.
Following the workout, he boarded the club's flight for a long trip
to Calgary and, upon leaving the plane, realized his leg was stiff
and swollen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a lot of factors coming together,'' he said.
``There was the slash, the long flight . . . and I've never liked
flying much, so I just sat in my seat for hours, my leg bent the
whole time, and that didn't help. On top of everything else, it
turns out I've got some kind of blood disorder, too, some sort of
protein deficiency maybe I had for years and knew nothing about.''
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for that unfortunate confluence of factors,
agent Rich Scimone right now would be shopping Janney's stats
around a 28-team league hungry for talented playmakers. Now Janney
ponders life without the game that took him from the neighborhood
rinks in Connecticut, to Boston College, to the US Olympic team
('88), to the riches of the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Financially, I've done fairly well,'' said Janney. ``From that
standpoint, I'm fortunate, I don't have to rush out and do
something. All of this has happened so quickly, I've really had no
time to deal with it, never mind figure out what I'm going to do
from here. I'm just now trying to swallow it. I've had some offers
to do some things, mainly back East. A lot of my buddies back home
have gotten into finance, but to be honest, I don't know what I
want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was at his best, the sweet-passing Janney collected 106
points in 1992-93, his first full season with the Blues after being
dished to St. Louis with Stephane Quintal in the deal that brought
Adam Oates to Boston. Janney's game lacked grit, the key element
that kept him from being an elite player in the league, but his
soft hands and keen sense of timing made him a valuable piece to
any offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first years in Boston were highlights,'' recalled Janney.
``You go to the finals twice like that ('88, '90), it's so exciting
to be part of something so big. I only wish I had been a little
older, maybe I would have appreciated it more when it was
happening. I'll never forget that first year, Taz (Terry O'Reilly)
telling me and Bobby Joyce, `Hey, listen, you may think right now
that this is going to happen to you eight or nine times in your
career, but don't be so sure, it could be your only chance _ so you
better be ready to go.' He was so right. We got there twice, and I
never got close again.''
</P>
<P>
   In slightly more than 11 years, Janney helped four wingers
collect 50 goals in a season. Brett Hull, here in the finals with
Dallas, drilled in a bunch of Janney's patented soft feeds in St.
Louis. Brendan Shanahan, Keith Tkachuk, and Cam Neely also hammered
home his relays on their way to 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the pleasure of playing with some top goal scorers,''
Janney said. ``And a lot of guys can't say that they helped four
guys to 50 goals. I'm pretty proud of that.''
</P>
<P>
   On his worst days now, said Janney, he makes his way around with
what he describes as a ``club foot.'' Nearly any amount of exercise
causes his leg to swell and brings a loss of feeling in the limb.
He laughs about using a cart when he plays golf, hanging a ``Derek
Sanderson handicapped flag'' on the buggy as he makes the 18-hole
loop. He has to wear support hose, more apt to be worn by those 30
or 40 years his senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the swelling's bad, that part of my leg can get three to
five times bigger than normal,'' he said. ``All these doctors I
see, vascular guys, heart specialists, they see me and they laugh
because I'm so young. They say, `Wow, your veins are so great.' And
I say, `You know, I really don't want to hear that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Janney remains on Coumadin, the blood thinner, and
keeps his physical activity to a minimum. The clot doesn't
dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't budged in three months,'' he said, when asked if he
might try a comeback if the condition were to clear. ``The damage
has been done, to the vein and to the valve. I'd love to say
(there's a chance of coming back), but there's just no way.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janney's partner in trade, Quintal, will see a huge payday when
he becomes an unrestricted free agent July 1. Within the last two
weeks, the Canadiens offered The Q a deal worth $10 million over
four years. He turned it down. Don't be surprised if the Rangers
come up with the same money but only three years of servitude . . .
Ex-Hab Vinny Damphousse agreed to terms with the Sharks Friday.
He'll make $18 million over the next four seasons and the Sharks
can sign him for a fifth year (2003-04) for $5 million, an option
that kicks in automatically for Damphousse if he attains
predetermined point levels . . . Ex-Bruin Dave Reid, who drives a
vintage Volkswagen Beetle around the Big D, knew he was getting a
little grayer when his Dallas teammates edited out his selection of
dressing room music. ``I walked out of the room,'' said Reid,
``when they made me get rid of my Neil Diamond records.'' . . . He
shot down the suggestion when it first came up a couple of weeks
ago, but Stars general manager Bob Gainey would be a nice fit as
club president in Montreal, where Ron Corey has decided to step
down. Gainey's eldest daughter attends McGill University in
Montreal. Another daughter just finished high school in Texas. If
the Stars win the Cup, where's his challenge in Dallas? And right
now, for someone who likes challenges, they don't come much bigger
than the very ordinary Canadiens . . . Vancouver GM Brian Burke is
on record as wanting to take the talented Sedin twins, Daniel and
Henrik, in the June 26 amateur draft at Boston. The Canucks have
the No. 3 pick, which means, for starters, both Tampa Bay and
Atlanta would have to pass on the talented Swedish pair. Burke then
would have to deal with Chicago (at No. 4) or the Islanders (No. 5)
to pick up the extra selection. In short, it's possible, but a real
stretch. And it all goes off the boards if Patrik Stefan remains
available at No. 3. Burke also is on record as saying he'd take
Stefan ahead of the whole bunch. Or is that posturing just to
entice the Bolts to bite on someone other than a Sedin? . . . Rick
Dudley got his wish last week when the Senators released him as
their GM and he signed with Tampa as president. The sticking point
was compensation. Word around the league is that the Senators will
get $1 million from Tampa Bay and a second- or third-round draft
pick . . . Good guy Marshall Johnston was recently promoted to
assistant GM in Ottawa to replace Dudley. ``I know I'll be a better
manager than I was a player,'' said Johnston, who collected 66
points in seven NHL seasons . . . Ex-Ranger first-round pick Chris
Kontos (15th overall in '82) is now a TV sports anchor with a
Barrie, Ontario, station . . . Valeri Kamensky's free agent price
bumped up considerably with his strong showing for the Avalanche in
the playoffs (9 points in 10 games) upon recovering from a
fractured wrist. Once Theo Fleury arrived from Calgary, it was
thought to be a fait accompli that Kamensky would be out of
Colorado, the Avalanche not having the dough to sign everyone. But
Fleury flopped in the series with Dallas, leading to speculation
that Colorado might not choose to bring him back and instead use
some of the savings to rehire Kamensky. One or the other will be
gone, which will bring offers from the Rangers. And if Kamensky is
the one let go, look for the Panthers to make a bid. He summers in
Miami and would make an interesting fit on a line with countryman
Pavel Bure.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fans toting homemade signs have a field day with Sabres forward
Miroslav Satan's last name (the pronunciation is a less-devilish
Shuh-tan), to wit: ``Thank God for Satan'' and, one in New Jersey,
``Beat the Devil out of Satan.'' When he first entered the league
with the Oilers, it was suggested that Satan insert an H into his
name, but he passed on the idea . . . Jacques Demers, now with
Dudley as his new boss in Tampa, has three years remaining on his
deal as coach and GM of the Bolts. Dudley likely will bring in
Steve Ludzik from the Detroit Vipers (IHL) as the bench boss,
leaving Demers to focus solely on GM duties _ something that Demers
figured was a year down the road for him anyway. Ludzik was Sergei
Samsonov's coach for the year ('96-97) that Samsonov spent in the
IHL . . . When Islander GM Mike Milbury gets around to trading
Ziggy Palffy (and just forget the Rangers), the league wants to
review the deal (shades of baseball's Bowie Kuhn/Charlie Finley
days). League vice president Colin Campbell: ``Once it comes across
the table, we'll look at it.'' The Islanders have to get a player
or two in return, someone with talent who hasn't made the big
bucks. One alternative: The club that acquires Palffy also could
agree to pay the player that it sends to New York. For instance, if
the Blackhawks wanted Palffy badly enough, they could send Alexei
Zhamnov to New York and agree to pay his $3 million-plus salary,
effectively making Palffy an $8 million-a-year player (a price
level that doesn't make some clubs blink) . . . Word out of LA is
that the Kings have decided that neither Dave Lewis nor Ted Nolan
will be their next head coach. Still on the list of possibilities:
John Van Boxmeer, Andy Murray, and Dave King . . . Stars defenseman
Craig Ludwig has worn the same wide-body shin pads since his days
at the University of North Dakota (carbon dating has traced them to
the Bronze Era). In recent years he has received two letters from
the Hockey Hall of Fame, requesting that he donate them at the end
of his career. Ludwig's response each time: ``If you take my pads,
you've got to take me.'' He hasn't heard back. Ludwig is also a
serious offseason softball player, suiting up for the ``Sid
Grinker'' club in Milwaukee, where he handles third base duties.
His specialty: home runs and knocking down sizzling shots at the
hot corner . . . The Flyers gave assistant GM John Blackwell the
heave-ho last week after seven years. There wasn't enough work for
three men to do, said GM Bob Clarke, who also has Paul Holmgren in
the front office. Word along Broad Street is that the Flyers want
to enhance Holmgren's role with the club, perhaps preventing him
from bolting to the Minnesota Wild . . . NHL clubs turn in their
protected lists 48 hours after the completion of the final Stanley
Cup game. If the Sabres-Stars series goes to the limit (Game 7 is
June 22), the lists would be turned in June 24 _ only one day prior
to the Atlanta Thrashers expansion draft. Talk about a one-timer .
. . Ron Low called it quits as head coach in Edmonton when Oiler
boss Glen Sather made him an offer he had to refuse: one-year
extension with no raise ($450,000 in Canadian funds). Low walked.
Kevin Lowe is the heir apparent _ provided he'll take the lowball
$450,000. Meanwhile, Low is one of three who have interviewed for
the Thrashers job, along with Don Hay and Curt Fraser. Contrary to
reports out of Toronto, Mike Keenan is not under consideration for
the Atlanta coaching job . . . Sabres forward Michael Peca is
finalizing a deal for ``Peca's Pickles'' here in hockey-mad Western
New York. You've got a terminal case of pennant fever if you still
have a loaf of Big Yaz bread tucked away in the family freezer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
