<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT PINEHURST, NO. 2 IS NO. 1 ATTRACTION 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 99th US Open begins Thursday at the storied No. 2
course at Pinehurst in the sandhills of North Carolina, one of the
game's true jewels. There is a history of classic golf at the
course, including the North &AMP; South Amateur and a couple of PGA
Tour Championships in the early years of this decade. The United
States won the Ryder Cup there in 1951, and Jack Nicklaus won the
North &AMP; South Amateur there in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   There are deep Bay State roots in the course; it may be even
more steeped in Boston than The Country Club in Brookline, where
the Ryder Cup will be contested this September. James Walker Tufts,
who bought the property before the turn of the century, was born in
Charlestown in 1835. The Tufts family is woven into the course, the
resort, and the sandhills.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Ross, a native of Dornoch, Scotland, who took over as
golf professional at Oakley CC in Watertown in 1899 and created Bay
State courses such as Salem, Winchester, Oak Hill, and Brae Burn,
became professional at Pinehurst in 1900 and completed the
construction of the second 18 holes later in the decade. Pinehurst
No. 2 is one of his architectural monuments.
</P>
<P>
   It has never been a venue for the US Open, and its time is long
overdue.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Andrade, who grew up in Bristol, R.I., and went to Wake
Forest, has seen a lot of Pinehurst. Andrade, who did not qualify
for this year's US Open, won the North &AMP; South Amateur at the No. 2
course in 1986 and made it to the semifinals the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played it quite a bit,'' said Andrade. ``In college I
played it all the time. We used to go down there a lot. We played
the ACC Tournament there once and we played the PGA Tour
Championship there. I went there about a month ago to check out all
the changes they've made.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be very, very hard. It's going to be
very difficult. It's going to be very different. It's really not
going to give you that US Open feel, because there's hardly going
to be any rough around the greens the way they're going to set it
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are all egg-shaped. I think they're a little more
raised, a little more sloped than they used to be. I think,
depending on wind and weather and firmness, I would take even par
right now to win. I think even par is going to win the
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the top players bypassed Memphis this week, including US
Open defender Lee Janzen, who is looking for a title to go with the
ones he won at Baltusrol in 1993 and last year at San Francisco's
Olympic Club. He played four straight weeks, up to the Memorial at
Muirfield Village last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was certainly trying to aim my game to be at its peak by the
end of this tournament, so I could go home and practice and
hopefully be ready for the US Open,'' said Janzen at the Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Janzen feels his game is on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's probably slightly better than last year,'' he
said. ``I probably have more confidence in my game now than I did a
year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does the US Open seem to be his tournament?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I have the right answer,'' he said. ``I like
playing strategy, always playing the smart shot. I think I control
the distance of my irons very well, which I think is very crucial
in the US Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens are very hard. I hit the ball pretty high and spin
the ball a lot. I'm able to land the ball very close to where I
think you need to land it on each green and make it stop.
Fortunately, I putted very well both times, too. They weren't the
best putting weeks I've ever had, but they were certainly very
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a guy has to know how far he's hitting each club at a
course like Pinehurst, and I think it helps to spin the ball. Guys
that hit the ball high and soft will have a better chance at
Pinehurst to get the ball near the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tiger Woods won the Memorial, he said he would take the
week off to prepare for the US Open. He also won in Germany, so
this would make it three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing is, my game is starting to come around,'' said
Woods. ``No doubt about that. I'm starting to understand how to
play golf a little better than I had before. That's definitely the
thing you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I will continue to learn how to play this game until
the day I die. It always changes. That's one of the great things
about it. You will always learn how to better manage yourself
around golf courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been able to soak up all the mishaps I've had in my life
and applied it each and every time and made it better.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, who is the world's No. 1-ranked player, has never
even seen Pinehurst No. 2 but planned to be there this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is it's going to be shaved around the greens,''
said Duval, who is expected to play despite burning his hand on a
teapot Friday. ``You know when you go to the US Open you have to
hit it on the fairway and you need to hit it on the green. That's
what I'm going to try to do. I'll figure out a way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   This should be a special US Open. There may be eight courses at
the Pinehurst resort, but there is only one No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Hines of West Roxbury, who has been involved with Jack
Nicklaus in every phase of the Golden Bear's business operations,
teamed up with son Steve Nicklaus to buy Executive Sports
International. It does global marketing and promotion of golf
tournaments, including the 2001 US Senior Open at Salem CC, and
even the proposed new hockey rink and athletic facility at Boston
University. But the major project at the moment is the creation of
the Jack Nicklaus Museum on the campus of Ohio State. ``We have a
bid into Boston University, and we're in on the early stages with
Villanova,'' said Hines. ``The one at Villanova is for basketball,
and the one at Boston University is for hockey. We're waiting to
hear from them. We've had a couple of trips to meet with them.
We're doing the 2001 Seniors at Salem, and we're also doing the
hospitality for BankBoston at the Ryder Cup.'' ESI just opened an
office in Beverly because of all of the Boston trade. ``We have
over 40 tournaments,'' said Hines. ``We do three weeks in a row in
Japan, and we help bring in an international field. We usually
bring in about a dozen for each tournament.'' Hines started out in
resort management, then went to the hotel business, to consulting
for Jack Nicklaus Design, to Golden Bear Corp., to desiging
clubhouses and hiring club managers and golf pros. ``He hired me in
1988 full time at Muirfield Village and I started doing special
events for him,'' said Hines, who also oversees the Golden Bear
Tour, a minitour on which Duval's father, Bob, tuned up for the PGA
Senior Tour. ``We have 17 events, and it just kicked off in Florida
for the fourth year,'' said Hines. ``It's been a huge success.'' .
. . Mike Weir, a native of Sarnia, Ontario, who hits the ball from
the left side, said at the Memorial he wrote to Nicklaus when he
was 11, asking for golf advice. He was stunned to get a reply. ``I
saw that it had his signature on it and I was thrilled,'' said
Weir. ``I still have it at home, framed.'' Weir played his way into
the Memorial and finished 66_285 for joint 24th . . . George
Strode, who will retire as executive sports editor of the Columbus
Dispatch this year, covered his 94th round of the Memorial _ every
round since its inception, including the early ones for the
Associated Press. He has dignified the tournament with his presence
. . . Nicklaus was impressed by young Spaniard Sergio Garcia after
a practice round. Nicklaus is 59, Garcia 19. ``I had no idea how
good a player he was,'' said Nicklaus. ``I knew he was going to be
good, but he's a little bit better than I thought. It's his
composure, and the general makeup of his whole game. He's long.
He's very accurate. He's got a marvelous short game. He's well
beyond his years.'' Will Garcia be a captain's pick for the
European side in the Ryder Cup in September? ``They'd be crazy not
to pick him,'' said Nicklaus . . . Curtis Strange, who won the 1988
US Open at The Country Club and defended successfully at Oak Hill
the next year, made a sustained run at the Memorial. ``I'm a little
surprised at some of the putts I've made,'' said Strange, who
spends more time in the broadcast booth these days. ``To do well
out here, though, you have to eat, sleep, and prepare. If you
don't, I don't think you can do your very best. I can't do it
anymore. I can only play between 15 and 16 tournaments, and for me
that's not enough to be competitive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
