<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3398 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      06-13 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO VIP TREATMENT FOR VET
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the interest of fairness, we must assume the worst about
Robert Deheer, a 77-year-old war hero.
</P>
<P>
   In order to give the benefit of the doubt to representatives of
the Veterans Affairs Department, we should take for granted that
Deheer is a stubborn, argumentative, even abusive man.
</P>
<P>
   Or worse.
</P>
<P>
   We should presume he's physically threatening, at least as much
as a man can be at his age and with his infirmities, which require
him to park his car in handicapped spots.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where the trouble began.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, Deheer decided to drive to the Carl T. Hayden
Veterans Affairs Medical Center in Phoenix to have his hearing aids
adjusted. It's a problem that goes back to World War II, when
Deheer found himself a little too close to shell concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to the VA and like always the lot is almost all full,''
he said. ``So I drive around and around and can't find a
handicapped spot near the building. Nothing close enough for me to
walk to comfortably. Then I spot these two parking places close to
the building marked `VIP.' ''
</P>
<P>
   According to Deheer, he was approached by a security officer
with the VA when he tried to pull into one of the spots. (I'm told
the spaces were reserved that day for federal inspectors.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to her, `Who are the VIPs?' '' Deheer said, ``And she
told me, `Not you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No one from the VA would speak directly about what happened
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, because his trial has not occurred, we have to
wait until due process has happened until we can make any
comment,'' said hospital spokeswoman Paula Pedene. &QL; 
NOT EVEN FOR A MINUTE
</P>
<P>
   Three security officers eventually were involved. Deheer said he
asked if he could park in one of the VIP spots just for a minute in
order to use the rest room, then promised to move on.
</P>
<P>
   He said he was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   While not speaking directly to Deheer's claims, Pedene said the
hospital has a policy of accommodating anyone in such distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't understand what the big deal was,'' Deheer said.
``So, yeah, I was arguing with them. Then I said forget it. I got
back in my car and was going to drive away when two guards came
over and said they were arresting me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was handcuffed and placed in a security van. Deheer said he
could no longer control his bladder and urinated on himself. He
said he was taken to a holding cell and handcuffed to a bench,
where he waited for 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Guards issued him two citations, one for $20 for failing to
comply with an officer's request, the other a $50 charge of
disorderly conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way I will ever pay either fine,'' Deheer said.
``I have never been arrested for anything in my life, until this. I
can't believe it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Deheer contacted attorney Michael Rooney, who requested a
hearing on the charges before a federal magistrate. It's scheduled
for July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sickened by what happened to Bob Deheer,'' Rooney said.
``This is a man who nearly lost his life fighting for his country,
and this is how we're going to treat him?'' &QL; 
DIFFICULT FOR GUARDS
</P>
<P>
   It must be difficult for security guards who find themselves
confronted by someone making a scene, perhaps jamming up a parking
lot. But even if, for safety's sake, they decided to haul away
Deheer, why charge him?
</P>
<P>
   Why not just calm him down and send him on his way? Or better
yet, why not let him park in one of the reserved spots and avoid
the whole mess?
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deheer was a machine-gunner in France. During an enemy
assault in the fall of 1944, another gunner abandoned his weapon
and Deheer took over and helped fight off the attack. He eventually
was awarded the Bronze Star and the Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   If that doesn't make someone a VIP, what does? &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
