<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (For use by New York Times News
 Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following Arizona Republic story has been added for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, June 13. If you
have any questions, please contact the Repub lic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MCCAIN-MOTHER _ Like her son, Roberta McCain possesses a sly,
self-deprecating sense of humor and the toughness that comes from
years of seeing loved ones placed in harm's way in military action.
But unlike the Arizona senator, his mom, shuns the public eye. By
JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3405 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCAIN-MOTHER-AZR &LR;      06-13 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-MOTHER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR'S MOM KEEPS `JOHNNY' IN LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He's introduced around town as ``Senator'' or ``Mr.
Chairman'' or ``The Honorable John McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   His mom still calls him `'Johnny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She keeps me on the straight and narrow,'' says McCain, a
candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   Who else but Roberta McCain, 87, could have scolded the
white-haired Arizona Republican, a former Vietnam War POW and
winner of the Silver Star for bravery, for cursing at the guards in
the Hanoi prison camps where he was held from October 1967 until
March 1973? She learned about the profanity in a magazine article
years later, but was still fired up about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I'm coming over there and wash your mouth out with
soap,' '' John recently told a National Press Club audience that
included his mother. ``I said, `But, Mom, these were very bad
guys.' And she said, `That's no excuse. I never taught you to use
such language under any circumstances.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like her son, Roberta McCain possesses a sly, self-deprecating
sense of humor and the toughness that comes from years of seeing
loved ones placed in harm's way in military action. But unlike the
Arizona senator, his mom, a striking woman, shuns the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   Owing to her camera shyness, she has rarely, if ever, told the
story in public about the day in 1967 when the phone rang in London
and a naval aviator said two U.S. planes had been shot down.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, apparently, was John's.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta McCain and her husband, Jack, were getting dressed for a
party at the Iranian embassy. He was commander in chief of U.S.
naval forces in Europe. He had just been elevated to the rank of
full admiral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Carol (McCain's first wife) and said, `I think he's
been shot down. What do you think?' She said, `I think the same
thing,' '' Roberta said.
</P>
<P>
   She found out the next day that John had ejected from the plane,
parachuted into a Hanoi lake, and was a prisoner of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine that that was good news? It all depends where
you're standing, I guess. For 12 to 16 hours, we just assumed he
was dead.'' &QL; 
PREPARED FOR TRAGEDY
</P>
<P>
   She said she never was in denial about what was unfolding,
accepting each piece of news for what it was, and helped by her
faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had seen people who wouldn't accept reality. That just leads
to unhappiness. I'm pragmatic, I guess,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, she said, she had always been prepared for the
eventuality of tragedy. ``My husband chose his profession, and my
son chose his profession. I take the view that you stand up and be
counted for what you believe in.'' And she said she believed in the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   She declined to tell her story on the A&AMP;E television network,
which invited her to be interviewed for a 60-minute biography of
John McCain, 62. She also turned down an invitation to appear in a
``60 Minutes'' profile of her son, or to have her picture taken
especially for this article.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time a picture of me looks like somebody they dug
up who'd been down in the grave for seven days, and the worst of it
is, it looks exactly like me,'' she said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   But, with no cameras in sight, she relaxes. Sometimes, she calls
visitors ``honey.'' Even the ``Arizona Republic'' reporter who
interviewed her finds himself invited over for tea. &QL; 
SHE'S NOT FOOLED
</P>
<P>
   At the National Press Club speech in May, she cracked up
reporters by chiding the senator for turning down the wrong
corridor after his address was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``No wonder he got shot down (in Vietnam),'' she quipped at the
time. `'He can't even find his way to the elevators.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the remark later, she laughs and says: ```See, my
children don't have me fooled.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Roberta Wright grew up in Los Angeles and attended
finishing school with her sister, who is her identical twin.
Roberta later lived in Washington, London and New York City, where
her husband served as military adviser to the U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations in the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The library in her Washington, D.C., apartment contains ``stacks
and stacks'' of memorabilia, including photos of her husband posing
with Presidents Nixon and Johnson and other chief executives. Last
week, she said, she asked former President Ford at a luncheon to
sign an old photo featuring himself and Jack McCain, and he gladly
complied.
</P>
<P>
   She also enjoyed telling how she christened a ship in 1952 named
for her father-in-law, John Sidney McCain, who was also an admiral
and with whom she was close.
</P>
<P>
   ``She always had another story that was more interesting than
the one I was looking for,'' said Mark Salter, John McCain's chief
of staff. He and the senator recently completed a book, ``Faith of
My Fathers,'' that focuses on the McCain family's military history.
It is due out in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just run the tape recorder and let her talk. We got all
sorts of great anecdotes. She's got a very good eye,'' Salter
said. &QL; 
PRESIDENTIAL CREDENTIALS
</P>
<P>
   Her husband died on a plane returning from Europe in 1981; they
had been married 48 years and had three children, including John.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta believes her son's background _ his military record and
a career in the U.S. House and Senate _ provides him the
credentials to be president. He is the chairman of the Senate
Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say that every mother, when the baby is born, assumes
their baby is going to be president. I never had thought about it,
but the more I do think about it, I think Johnny is the best
qualified,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She follows politics on C-SPAN and in the newspapers, and says
she keeps an open mind. ``I try to educate myself on both sides of
a subject in politics. And without anybody else telling me what to
do, I try to arrive at an intelligent conclusion,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But usually I'm wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   She won't be making many campaign appearances. She said she is
too thin-skinned to be a politician, and too reticent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever heard that expression, `a yellow-bellied
coward?' You're talking to one,'' she said. &QL; 
HER OWN AGENDA
</P>
<P>
   But there is another reason, too, why she'll stay on the
sidelines during the campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   Like her son _ and this may be the most profound similarity
between the two _ Roberta McCain is fiercely independent. Her
agenda is her own.
</P>
<P>
   She plays bridge, cooks, sews. And she travels all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   She goes to Turkey and Jordan and India. She travels so much
that she keeps a car in Europe, staying for months at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody can count on me for anything because I love traveling.
When you're as old as I am, you'd better make hay while the sun
shines. Time's a wastin'.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0059EDT &QL; 
