r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-TEX     06-13 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS OVERCOME INJURIES, SABRES, 2-1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The Stars might have pulled the wool over the
NHL world Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   They certainly buffaloed the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Modanogate _ the Mike Modano injury saga _ turned into a Trojan
horse of sorts for the Stars as Modano played brilliantly with a
left wrist that still might or might not be broken and the Stars
bludgeoned the Sabres in a 2-1 game that wasn't as close as the
score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   The victory in Game 3 of the Stanley Cup Finals gives the Stars
a 2-1 edge in the best-of-seven series. It also returns home-ice
advantage to the Stars and takes away the playoff mystique of
Marine Midland Arena, where the Sabres were 7-0 heading into
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to go down 2-1 in this building, knowing their
history in the playoffs here is so strong that would have given
them huge momentum,'' said winger Dave Reid, who assisted on both
Stars goals. ``It was something we talked about, and really we
focused on putting all our effort out there tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars did, overcoming Modano's sore wrist, an early groin
injury to winger Brett Hull and a hard-charging Sabres team that
coach Lindy Ruff said ``played a bad hockey game.'' In taking the
victory, the Stars outshot the Sabres, 29-12, forced 25 giveaways
and blocked 19 shots.
</P>
<P>
   While the Sabres hemmed and hawed about how to check Modano _
who came out as a left wing to start the game then quickly moved
back to center on the top line _ Joe Nieuwendyk and linemates Dave
Reid and Jamie Langenbrunner controlled the game, scored two goals
and delivered he knockout punch the Stars needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were great, and they've been great,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``What people don't realize is that the lightest
person on that line is 195 pounds (Langenbrunner). They're a big
line that doesn't mind paying the price and fighting for their
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk scored his 10th and 11th of the playoffs, leading the
NHL. Langenbrunner is second in NHL playoff goal scoring with 10.
Nieuwendyk tied an NHL record (set by Joe Sakic of the Colorado
Avalanche in 1996) with his sixth game-winning goal of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it was a huge performance to take the pressure off of
Modano, who himself came up with a huge game, playing almost 19
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have both lines going, that's when we're incredibly
hard to check'' said Reid. ``Check last year's playoffs, if you
know what I mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Nieuwendyk was lost for the playoffs in the first
game with a knee injury. The Stars eventually couldn't score enough
to beat the Detroit Red Wings. Saturday night, they outlasted red
hot Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek by throwing both lines at him all
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres scored first on Stu Barnes goal at the 7:51 mark of
the second period. But the Stars bounced back when Langenbrunner
put together a tremendous shift of forechecking and Nieuwendyk was
able to bat in his own rebound at the 15:33 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams went into the third period tied and Nieuwendyk
scored the game-winner at the 9:35 mark when Langenbrunner lifted a
perfect pass from behind the net into the slot and Nieuwendyk
lifted a wrist shot over Hasek, who had hit the ice expecting a low
shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a goal-scorer's goal,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   And, for all intents, it ended a game in which the Stars
overcame eight penalties. The Sabres went 0-for-8 in the game with
the man advantage, including a power play in the final two minutes
for the second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Carbonneau, Mike Keane, Modano, Jere Lehtinen and a host of
defensemen were exceptional on the penalty kill. But, as Hitchcock
said, every player was exceptional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our best game of the playoffs, I mean everybody came
out and really, really gave a superior effort,'' Hitchcock said.
``In that third period, we just wanted it bad, we wanted to get a
win here.''
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the Stars give the Sabres their first consecutive
defeats in the playoffs and put them down in a series for the first
time in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first chunk of adversity we are going to have to
face,'' Ruff said. ``They gave us a darn good lesson there.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
