<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-ASTROS-HNS     06-13 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
A previous engagement kept Astros owner Drayton McLane Jr. from
taking his customary seat behind home plate Saturday night. But
before McLane left the Astrodome on Friday night, he asked Jose
Lima to get him a win.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``No problem, boss,'' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   When you're pitching as well as Lima, nothing seems to be a
problem. The emerging staff ace withstood an early deficit long
enough for the offense to rescue him in a 3-2 victory over the San
Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Lima struck out a season-high 10 batters and allowed six hits in
eight innings. The crowd of 39,893 saluted Lima with a standing
ovation as he left the mound at the start of the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly his house for the night, as evidenced by signs
bearing messages such as ``Cy Lima'' and ``Lima Time.'' But after
throwing a season-high 132 pitches, Lima's time had run out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Billy time,'' Lima said.
</P>
<P>
   As in closer Billy Wagner, who struck out two of the four
batters he faced for his second save in two nights and his 16th of
the season. But as good as Wagner was, he knew the night belonged
to Lima, who joined Boston's Pedro Martinez as the only 11-game
winners in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Lima pitched a heck of a game,'' said Wagner, who hasn't
allowed a run in his past 9 innings. ``To be honest, I hate
watching him pitch when he does his antics, but I've talked to guys
like Barry Bonds, and they understand that he's having fun. I
wouldn't do it, but he's having fun and he's backing it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima was the beneficiary of another rock-solid defensive
performance by the Astros _ particularly second baseman Craig
Biggio and shortstop Ricky Gutierrez, both of whom made late bids
for ESPN's Sunday night Plays of the Week.
</P>
<P>
   But Lima's best supporter was catcher Paul Bako, who broke a 2-2
tie with a home run off former Astro Donne Wall in the seventh
inning. It was Bako's first home run in an Astros uniform and his
first since Sept. 5, 1998, when he was playing for Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who improved to 11-8 in one-run games, have won 10
of their last 12 at the Astrodome and eight of their last 11
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to credit my teammates,'' said Lima, who has held
opponents to a .193 batting average over his last six starts.
``They played great defense behind me, and they scored enough runs
for us to win. I want everyone to know this game was for Drayton.
He's been going through a lot, and I want him to know that I'm
behind him 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was just as strongly behind Lima.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those fans were unbelievable,'' he said. ``Getting that
standing ovation was the best feeling ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima breezed through the first four batters of the game but
worked himself into a jam after allowing a single and a walk with
one out in the second inning. A wild pitch gave the Padres runners
at second and third with two outs, but Lima struck out third
baseman George Arias to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   After he struck out Arias, Lima did his now-famous slide step
before heading toward the dugout. Arias appeared to mutter
something to Lima, but that was the extent of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the things he does rub a lot of guys the wrong way,''
said Padres right fielder Tony Gwynn, who was activated from the
disabled list before the game. ``But I think he just does that to
keep himself focused. He's 11-2; he must be doing something
right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres broke through in the third when Eric Owens started a
two-out rally with a double to left. Gwynn singled Owens home and
scored easily on a double by Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of their key players are out, but they still have a good
club,'' Lima said of the Padres. ``After I gave up the those two
runs, I knew I couldn't just give up. I knew if I could hang in
there, the guys would score some runs for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo started the comeback with a towering home run to
left field to lead off the fifth. It was Hidalgo's 12th home run,
ranking him second to Jeff Bagwell (20) among the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, Bagwell doubled off reliever Will Cunnane
and scored on Carl Everett's two-out triple to left-center field.
Everett leads the Astros with a .426 batting average with runners
in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy being up there with runners in scoring position,''
said Everett, who has been battling cold symptoms. ``I think that's
how you should be judged. If you're driving in runs in those
situations, you're doing a good job. I really don't care about
batting averages; it's all about run production.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
