<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3409 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-MYSTICS-COMETS-HN     06-13 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-MYSTICS-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Saturday afternoon, the Comets hung their second straight WNBA
championship banner from the Compaq Center rafters and got their
second set of rings from commissioner Val Ackerman.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day should have been reserved for nothing more than high
spirits and good times. And the afternoon was filled with emotion
as the Comets, after the pre-game celebrations, fed off their
feelings to run over the Washington Mystics 88-63 before a sellout
crowd of 16,285 for the home opener.
</P>
<P>
   But gaiety was mixed with sadness as the absence of
cancer-stricken point guard Kim Perrot hit home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out tonight when they introduced me,'' said coach Van
Chancellor, ``and I kind of broke down on the bench when I got my
ring. That just brought back so many great memories. I thought we
were a little bit emotionally drained at the start of the game. But
we came back, and to get our rings, raise the banner and win like
we did, what a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Comets, who set a league record with 15 consecutive wins
last year, used dominant defense and high-octane offense from
Cynthia Cooper, Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson to record their
second straight victory of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes scored 21 points and had six assists, five rebounds and
three steals, but her biggest contribution might have been on
defense. She held heralded rookie Chamique Holdsclaw to 3-for-14
shooting and six points before Chancellor turned the game over to
his reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper's 24 points led all scorers, and she clamped down on
Nikki McCray (2-for-13 shooting, nine points).
</P>
<P>
   The Comets held the Mystics to 39.7 percent shooting (23-for-58)
and scored 26 points off 21 Mystics turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The win was in contrast to the Comets' 68-64 preseason loss to
the Mystics on June 3, when McCray and Holdsclaw combined to help
Washington overcome a five-point deficit with less than two minutes
to play.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday's win came in the wake of a heavy emotional
outpouring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got my ring, all I could think about was Kim Perrot,''
Chancellor said, ``what a wonderful person she's been, how much
she's meant, how much I really wanted her here so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot missed the celebration and victory as she continues to
wage her battle with cancer. But there were other reasons for
emotions. Cooper talked afterward about how tough it was to play
knowing that her mother, who died of breast cancer during the
offseason, wasn't in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed my mom and the fact she didn't get a chance to
be in the celebration of the raising of the banner,'' Cooper said.
``I really hate that Kim wasn't here. All of the different feelings
and emotions just came to me right before we walked out to receive
our rings.''
</P>
<P>
   There was reason for Swoopes to feel melancholy, too. She went
through a divorce during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very emotional for lots of reasons,'' she said. ``And
to me, the biggest thing was that Kim was not here today. She was
so successful in everything we did last year. I was used to hearing
her in the locker room, pumping everybody up, just being Kim. Then,
to walk out there, the fans cheering us on, I was kind of
reminiscing, going back to everything we went through last year as
a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being back-to-back champions and being a part of history, the
ceremony for me was more emotional because I feel that I
contributed to last year's championship more than the year before.
And then, just to kind of think back, Eric (Jackson, her former
husband) was very supportive of me. He was at every game. And just
to know it's completely different this year
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's something that as the season goes on and we play more
games, I'll be able to handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Comets mauled the Mystics from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets led 44-33 at halftime, then used an 18-5 run early in
the second period to take control. Back-to-back treys by Thompson
(15 points, seven rebounds) and Swoopes ended the run and gave the
Comets a commanding 64-40 lead with 12:56 to play.
</P>
<P>
   It was during that run Holdsclaw had perhaps her most
confounding moments of a befuddling debut on national television.
She missed a 3-point attempt with Cooper grabbing the rebound.
Then, following Swoopes' 3-pointer, Holdsclaw missed a layup, with
Cooper again snaring the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, Holdsclaw, the No. 1 pick in the 1999 WNBA draft
from Tennessee, was 2-for-13 from the floor. She did finish with a
game-high 13 rebounds and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holdsclaw and McCray are two very talented players,'' Cooper
said. ``We knew to win we would have to stop them. Not only did we
stop them, but I think this team did a tremendous job overall. We
were able to do a lot of things, once we got good defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Chancellor turned to his reserves during most of the
final seven minutes, matters only got worse for the Mystics, who
got 13 points from Shalonda Enis and 10 from Murriel Page.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets' Jennifer Rizzotti, playing for the first time in the
regular season, came off the bench and fired in a 3-pointer with
6:41 left that put the Comets up 79-48.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the final emotions the Comets experienced would indeed be
joy and euphoria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3410 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-FINALS-HNS &LR;      06-13 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-FINALS </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Odd how we never saw this coming. It seems such an obvious, perfect
script.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The San Antonio Spurs rolled to the NBA Finals with an almost
unblemished run. They were the league's best team, unrelenting,
certain. But somehow, we never saw the ascension of the New York
Knicks coming.
</P>
<P>
   The last team in the playoffs with their franchise center
limping, then out, somehow the Knicks seemed like little more than
a made-for-the-tabloids combination of rumors and demotions, an
overheated East Coast version of the dysfunction that shut down the
Lakers and Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   But now it makes perfect sense, as if it were _ to use the word
both toss around so confidently _ destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday night in San Antonio, the Knicks and Spurs
will bring together in the NBA Finals the nation's largest market
and one of the league's smallest.
</P>
<P>
   The Finals will pit a team that thrives on controversy and one
whose idea of discord is arguing over the out-of-bounds flowers on
David Robinson's driveway.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were New York's latest wretched refuse, a misfit
collection of the dismissed (Larry Johnson), maligned (Marcus
Camby) and reviled (Latrell Sprewell).
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs were labeled ``too nice,'' then won with the flawless,
selfless confluence built around a former superstar, Robinson, who
stepped aside to create a leading role for another, Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   But for all their differences, they share a 26-year wait for the
title one will win. The Spurs moved to San Antonio in 1973 while
still in the American Basketball Association; the Knicks won their
last NBA title the same year.
</P>
<P>
   And both are brimming with confidence. The Spurs had a
spectacular three-month run to the Finals, including consecutive
playoff sweeps. The Knicks defeated the series of obstacles that
had been put before them.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks arrive having exorcised the demons of previous
playoff defeats to the Pacers and Reggie Miller, and their most
heated rival, the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a team that believes in themselves, and I think
most everything else comes from that,'' Spurs coach Gregg Popovich
said. ``That is a very together group, a very dedicated group. They
went and got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks won despite the Achilles' tendon tear that cost
Patrick Ewing the past four games and the remainder of the season.
And they vanquished the Pacers on Friday, despite a second-quarter
knee sprain to Larry Johnson, the Game 3 four-point play hero and
Ewing's replacement in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks rose above each obstacle and distraction,
including the demotion of general manager Ernie Grunfeld and
continued uncertainty over coach Jeff Van Gundy's job status.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The media) buried us, covered us, started shoveling dirt on
us,'' Ewing said. ``We just believed in ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson cannot play, the doubts likely will rebuild by
Wednesday, despite Friday's win taken largely without him. But the
Knicks have played so well despite injuries, Spurs guard Avery
Johnson said: ``I hope they don't lose Allan Houston next. Then
they might sweep us.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson is considered questionable to return in the
Finals. Without Johnson and Ewing, the Knicks would have to face
7-footers Duncan and Robinson with a frontcourt of Chris Dudley,
Kurt Thomas, Marcus Camby and Herb Williams, at 41 the NBA's oldest
player. Even with Camby coming off a phenomenal series against the
Pacers, the Knicks' offense, once built almost entirely around the
low post, will have no big men for whom they can run plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Eastern Conference finals) helped me prepare for this,
especially getting the Davis boys (Dale and Antonio) and (Rik)
Smits,'' Camby said. ``Those guys are big also.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely looking forward to the challenge of going
against David Robinson and Tim Duncan. I'm not going to back down
because they have a lot of All-Stars and a good team. We have a
good team also.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby is used to overcoming doubt. Acquired for fan and team
favorite Charles Oakley, Camby did not fit in Van Gundy's system
early in the season and was rarely used. He blossomed late in the
season as an active, athletic reserve, working in tandem with
another castoff, Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   ``What drove me in the series was way back when I got traded,
you know, people were questioning the trade, saying I wasn't going
to get it done,'' Camby said. ``Me and Latrell took it upon
ourselves to go out there, play with heart and pride and get the
job done. Now we're where we want to be, where our goal is.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sprewell, suspended by the Warriors and vilified nationally
last season for choking his coach, the turnaround has been even
greater, from, he said, ``the bottom of the barrel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we play for,'' he said. ``As a kid, you sit up
and you watch TV and you're saying, `Hey, that's Michael (Jordan),
that's Larry (Bird), and James Worthy,' some of the guys you
admire. You always hope to be in this position. To actually be
going through it and experiencing it is a feeling that I've never
felt before. I love it.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Knicks' joyous Madison Square Garden party,
the Spurs celebrated their berth in the NBA Finals with a few back
slaps and high-fives. The Knicks, with a day off Saturday and three
practice days before the Finals, likely will be able to use their
emotions better than the Trail Blazers could.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs, with nine days off since their sweep, will have a
different challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see the glow,'' Spurs guard Mario Elie said. ``Guys
are excited; guys are feeling good about themselves. This team is
hungry and focused. We're a hungry group right here.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Spurs, despite their 11-1 playoff run, have been at the
best and hungriest when things haven't gone quite so well. Though
their struggles did not last nearly as long as those of the Knicks,
the first No. 8 seed to reach the Finals, they used a 6-8 start to
come together and grow to become the championship favorites.
</P>
<P>
   With more than a week spent as toast of their town, the Spurs
will test their ability to remain humble.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we operate with a little fear, we tend to be better
around here,'' Avery Johnson said. ``When we don't have fear, when
we tend to relax and think we're really good, it's been proven
we're not very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, the Knicks are at their best when cocky. But for all
their differences, and despite their different roads to the Finals,
both teams have reason to strut on the River Walk, as if no one
else could have gotten this far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
