<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK GIVES STAR PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Mike Modano played, injured hand and all. Brett Hull
left after only three shifts because of a groin pull. The Dallas
debts piled high and then higher.
</P>
<P>
   But discipline and depth heal many wounds in the playoffs, not
to mention a pair of Joe Nieuwendyk goals, and the Dallas Stars
shrugged off adversity inside Marine Midland Arena Saturday &UR;  &LR; night
and posted a 2-1 victory over the Buffalo Sabres in Game 3 of the
Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a bad hockey game,'' said Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff,
whose club mustered a franchise-low 12 shots against the Stars.
``We didn't have it. If we play like that, we're definitely going
to lose. They suffocated us.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave the Stars a 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven
series, which resumes here Tuesday night. They now stand only two
victories away from winning their first Stanley Cup, but by that
time they could be minus a large portion of their starting cast.
None of the injuries, however, seem to have an effect. No matter
how many parts fall off, the distant sons of Norm Green's Minnesota
North Stars just seem to draw tighter on defense and find ways to
win.
</P>
<P>
   The key find Saturday &UR;  &LR; night was the pair of goals by
Nieuwendyk, who centered a line with Jamie Langenbrunner and
ex-Bruin Dave Reid. Assisted on both goals by his linemates,
Nieuwendyk erased a 1-0 deficit at 15:33 of the second period and
then popped home the winner with a sparkling wrister to the top
right corner halfway through the third. It gave the former Flame
six game-winners this postseason, tying the mark established by
Colorado's Joe Sakic in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in with a purpose,'' said Nieuwendyk, who played only
two minutes of last year's playoffs before San Jose defenseman
Bryan Marchment ripped up one of his knees with a hit from behind.
``We wanted to play a simple game. With guys on our team like Craig
Ludwig, Guy Carbonneau, and Mike Keane, guys who've been through it
all before, there's no panic on our bench.''
</P>
<P>
   The Buffalo bench, meanwhile, looked like a herd of deer caught
in the headlights of the spaceship in ``Close Encounters of the
Third Kind.'' With a packed house of 18,595 screaming and shaking
white pompoms, they came out with their least inspiring game of the
playoffs. After winning seven straight on home ice, they came out
with a clunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first chunk of adversity that we're going to have to
face,'' said Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their poor, seemingly timid play, the Sabres did manage
a 1-0 lead. Former Penguin Stu Barnes skated into the slot and
fired home a deflected pass from Richard Smehlik at 7:51 of the
second period. Sabres, 1-0, and Hull already had said goodnight
after injurying his groin. All the breaks were conspiring in favor
of the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   No one gave that bit of bad news to the Stars. Led by Nieuwendyk
and a wall-to-wall defensive game that covered nearly every inch of
the ice, the Stars ignored the obit that was being written before
their eyes. They clogged the middle and blocked shots. In fact,
they blocked 19 shots, seven more than the Sabres could put on
Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of our team,'' said Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock.
``They played with poise.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's first goal came after Hasek turned back his
forehand attempt from the slot. As he was about to crash to the ice
following a Rhett Warrener check, Nieuwendyk swept a backhander
under the fallen Hasek. Tied, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner made the key play on the winner, shaking off a
trailing Curtis Brown with a sharp stop and turn along the goal
line. Nieuwendyk shimmied into the slot, collected Langenbrunner's
feed and with a snatch and jerk lifted the winner to the top shelf
with John Bucyk-like perfection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's any secret,'' said Ludwig, admiring his
teammate's goal, ``that with this goalie you have to shoot high _
he takes away the bottom of the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres went 0 for 8 on the power play. A frustrated Modano
was caught for three minor penalties alone in the second period.
The Stars gave them every opportunity to get ahead early, but the
Sabres kept handling the puck like some oversize curling stone. The
Sabres got off 24 shots total, and missed the net on half, the
majority of those coming on the power play. By contrast, the Stars
missed the net on only four of their 33 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done yet,'' said Nieuwendyk, the favorite in the
Dallas room to win the Conn Smythe Trophy as the playoff MVP. ``But
we took a real big step.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
