<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-FIRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERMOSILLO SPARKS GALAXY VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ He only needed one look and one whip of his
right foot to get started _ but with it, Carlos Hermosillo may have
pushed the right buttons to get the Los Angeles Galaxy going again
following a convincing season debut.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't do it alone, midfielders Simon Elliott and Roy Myers
made their best contributions of the season, but Hermosillo's 32nd
minute goal fueled Los Angeles' attack as they held on to defeat
MLS champion Chicago 2-1 in front of a Hermosillo-inflated crowd of
18,102 at the Rose Bowl on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great tonight,'' said Hermosillo, playing with Los
Angeles for the first time since Chicago eliminated them last
season in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year it took me nine games to get my first goal and this
year I got one right away which is always great,'' he said. ``It's
only one game but I liked how we played and how everyone got
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also a big victory considering it came without Cobi Jones
and Robin Fraser, who are both with the U.S. National team
preparing for today's friendly against Argentina in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid called it one of the best performances
of the season, explaining that the addition of Hermosillo open's
the field offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it helps that he (Hermosillo) can finish but what also
helps is that Carlos is a presence and a known scorer,'' said
Schmid. ``The opposition ties up people with Carlos and Carlos is
such a smart player not only on the goal but he's in there on
combinations and he makes good passes to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The two goals gave the Galaxy its first multiple scoring game of
the season and ran L.A.'s record to 10-0 in games where Hermosillo
nets either a goal or assist. The victory also moves the Galaxy
(7-6, 15 points) to within three points of the third place Fire
(6-6, 18 points), giving the club its second straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid praised the play of recently acquired midfielders Elliott
and Myers, who offer playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos solid relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy's a big plus because when teams try to take away
Cienfuegos we have somebody else we can go to,'' said Schmid. ``And
in Simon, we found somebody who can playmake for us on a deeper
part of the field, which makes it easier for Mauricio as well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy had to play short-handed most of the second half
after defender Paul Caligiuri was ejected in the 51st minute for
sticking his leg at Fire midfielder Manuel Lagos.
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri may have been frustrated for failing to contain
Chicago striker Josh Wolff to start the second half. With the
Galaxy leading 2-0, Wolff easily sprinted around Caligiuri on a
long pass behind both of them. Caligiuri took a last second stab at
Wolff, but he couldn't get there, allowing Wolff to beat Galaxy
goalkeeper Kevin Hartman to the far post in the 47th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy led 1-0 thanks to perhaps its best work of the season
midway through the first half. The play started when Danny Pena
sent a pass in front of the penalty arc for Elliott. Elliott let
the ball run through his legs for a trailing Roy Myers, then kept
heading toward the Chicago goal.
</P>
<P>
   Myers was able to give the ball to Elliott as he entered the
penalty area. As soon as the Chicago defense closed, Elliott sent a
pass out to Hermosillo, unmarked on the right side. Hermosillo beat
Chicago goalkeeper Zach Thornton, hitting the inside left-post to
give the Galaxy a 1-0 lead in the 32nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy went up 2-0 in the waning seconds of the first half.
Cienfuegos sent a long cross to Elliott to the left of the Fire
goal. Elliott finished by beating Thornton to the far post.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
