<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3423 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-HNS &LR;      06-13 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SABRES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Mike Modano, he of the celebrated wrist, was game
but not totally effective. Brett Hull, who provided the difference
in Game 2, departed with a groin injury after playing just two
minutes, leaving another void.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With these Stanley Cup Finals at a crossroads _ Game 3 of a
best-of-seven series tied at one game apiece _ the Dallas Stars
showed up at Marine Midland Arena in search of another hero
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The search turned up an old one: Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not done yet,'' the Stars center said after his second
goal of the night, 9 minutes, 35 seconds into the final period,
proved the difference in a 2-1 Dallas win over the Buffalo Sabres.
``But after this one, we're a step closer.''
</P>
<P>
   In another ``biggest game of the season'' for a team accustomed
to tight spots, it was fitting Nieuwendyk would be a
difference-maker as the Stars won a second straight game and
regained the home-ice advantage they lost in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, he missed all but one playoff game after suffering a
knee injury in the opening game of the first-round series with San
Jose. As Dallas' offense ground to a halt in the Western Conference
finals against Detroit, one of the team's more skilled players
could only sit and watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt like he got cheated last year,'' defenseman Craig
Ludwig said. ``But he's making the best of it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   With Modano limited and Hull gone, the Stars needed Nieuwendyk
to come through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows Mike is hurt,'' he said. ``When you lose a guy
like Brett Hull, too, it's tough. This shows a little bit about the
character of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk was hardly alone in that regard as Modano took a
painkilling shot to a left wrist the club still officially refuses
to term broken _ a stance coach Ken Hitchcock reiterated Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a circus, isn't it?'' Modano said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   So is it broken or isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll just go along with Hitch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Stars could afford a few sideshows after a win
that ended Buffalo's streak of seven home victories in this
season's playoffs. In the course of things, the Sabres' previously
deadly power play fizzled on all eight opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to explain,'' Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff said. ``We
were pretty tight. We were squeezing the sticks pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the Stars) did a number on us tonight. They gave us a
darn good lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 is here Tuesday night, with Buffalo facing a virtual
must-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, this hardly seemed Dallas' night. Modano's status made
a tense situation all the more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody expected him to play,'' Hitchcock said.
``Even at 65 percent, he could do some things for us out there. We
really knew boarding the airplane yesterday that he was a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano, injured in a collision in the third period of Game 2,
played with a cast. But Hull left early and did not return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to play tomorrow, he (Hull) wouldn't be a player,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas weathered the emotion of an excited crowd and a team
playing its first game of the series at home, but the Stars didn't
help themselves by picking up four first-period penalties that kept
much of the play in their end.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, goalie Ed Belfour, who faced only 12 shots, had
little to do with keeping things even in the early stages. On a
night when Stars defenders blocked 19 shots, Buffalo got just three
on net in the opening period despite spending 5:45 with at least a
one-man advantage and the final 1:14 with a two-man edge.
</P>
<P>
   The lone Sabres goal was a quick-strike effort on which Belfour
guessed wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Having handled just four shots to that point, he bit on a fake
by Richard Smehlik, who shuffled the puck over to Stu Barnes. With
Belfour out of position, Barnes wristed a shot into a virtually
open net for his sixth goal of the playoffs at 7:51 of the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars continued to hamper their own cause with penalties,
and an increasingly frustrated Modano picked up two minors in the
span of less than three minutes and three in the second period
alone.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it appeared the Sabres had matters in hand, Dallas
struck back. On a nice feed from Jamie Langenbrunner, Nieuwendyk
had a point-blank shot that Dominik Hasek (29 shots, 27 saves)
managed to stop but could not control. The Dallas center reached
back in and poked the rebound into the net to tie the score at 1 at
15:33, his 10th goal of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first goal was just hard work,'' Hitchcock said. ``But
that second one _ that's a goal-scorer's goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, Nieuwendyk came through. And again, Langenbrunner did the
dirty work.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Langenbrunner dug the puck out from behind the
Buffalo net and got it out front, where Nieuwendyk found himself in
a staredown with Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   The goalie generally considered the best in the world blinked,
and Nieuwendyk lifted the puck high and to Hasek's left, just under
the crossbar, for his sixth game-winner of the playoffs, tying the
record set by Colorado's Joe Sakic in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, Dallas was in control of these Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels great,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``We've got a special group
of guys here.''
</P>
<P>
   And when one of them needed to be just a little more special
Saturday night, Nieuwendyk was happy to oblige.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3424 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-13 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HE'S earning a national reputation as baseball's Mambo King, and,
yes, Mambo King fits him well.
</P>
<P>
   But let's call him something else, too. He is Jose Lima, the
Human Dinner Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Pencil in Lima for a 7:05 p.m. start, and you're pretty much
assured of having a table around 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   He works like he dances _ fast. He plays the game the way his
music plays in the Astros' clubhouse _ bouncing all over the place
in waves of rumbling beats.
</P>
<P>
   He secures wins so fast and efficiently, even Parrotheads like
Astros manager Larry Dierker have found a sort of
cheeseburger-in-paradise affinity for the merengue music Lima
blares in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the words are,'' Dierker said, ``but I know
how the sounds go.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jeff Bagwell after Saturday night's 3-2 Lima fest, as
riveting drumbeats and trumpets sounded in the background: ``The
whole team is learning the words to this stuff. It's getting kind
of crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's getting to where you'd have to be crazy not to believe Lima
no longer is a novelty. He no longer simply is the Ricky Martin of
the major leagues, a cup of life spilling all over the field and
filling the stands with fans ready to rumba.
</P>
<P>
   He is the image of what the big leagues should be.
</P>
<P>
   If only more people started acting more like Lima and less like
San Diego's George Arias and others who get their jocks all wound
up every time Lima slide-steps across the mound after a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   If only, like Lima, everyone in the game acted as if he were
giddy about being a big-leaguer. If only fewer clung to the game's
antiquated tradition of showing all the emotion of a rosin bag.
</P>
<P>
   If only more players punched their fists into the air, danced
off the field after a big moment and screamed with joy at the
heavens whenever they felt like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an entertainer,'' Bagwell said of Lima. ``He doesn't do
anything to show anybody up, or even just for the fans. He's
enjoying every minute of this. He's loco.''
</P>
<P>
   And baseball should be loco for Lima, instead of appalled at him
like some are. He is attracting fans to the Astrodome. He is
putting up W's. He is having an All-Star year. He is entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   To end the second inning of his gritty six-hit, 10-strikeout
performance over the Padres, Lima struck out Arias with a wicked
changeup. Lima clenched his fist, screamed and slid his leg across
the mound as if performing onstage.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Arias tossed his helmet to the ground, glared at
Lima and shouted a few choice words in his direction.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, get over it, George. You struck out. It was only the first
of the three K's you had on this night. Go sit down, and if you're
lucky, maybe next time you'll hit a home run off this Mambo King,
this Human Dinner Reservation, this face of what baseball's future
should be.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Lima is showing baseball is that if it's fun and
fans that the game wants, this is how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hit a home run off of me, stop at every base and dance for
me,'' Lima said. ``I don't care. I'm going to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He has what the game needs _ personality. Mix that with a record
that improved to 11-2 with Saturday's win, and you have why 39,893
fans spent the night shimmying right along with a pitcher whose
best stuff is an 81-mph changeup.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, when most big-league starting pitchers would be
locking themselves into some sort of emotional air chamber, Lima
was working the room like it was his wedding night.
</P>
<P>
   He greeted fans, teased teammates. He even spiced things up by
smacking a shaving-cream pie in the face of Astros shortstop Ricky
Gutierrez, who was being interviewed on live television.
</P>
<P>
   Lima's cap was turned backward, his eyes darting back and forth
scanning the crowd. Fans chanted his name and held up banners
saying: ``It's Lima Time.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Lima Time. And it's time more players started acting more
like him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is supposed to be fun, and the way he plays it, he's
making it fun for everyone,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Why cling to those stuffy baseball ways that began back in the
days when the game was like the plumbing _ always outdoors?
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakest act in baseball,'' Milwaukee Brewers pitcher Steve
Woodard has called Lima.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, after breaking to a 2-0 lead, some in the Padres'
dugout began cackling and feigning Lima's slide dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were making fun of me,'' Lima said. ``Hey, fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, fine. But Lima gave up only two singles the rest of the
way, and the Padres were done. It was a head-spinning,
hip-swiveling two hours and 20 minutes. It was what the game should
be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the music follows him out of the clubhouse,''
Dierker said. ``He just takes that energy out to the mound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
