<HEADER>
A3425 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-DIAMONDBAC     06-13 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALK LIFTS ANGELS TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels catcher Matt Walbeck is
probably the last guy one would expect to steal home, and he wasn't
about to try Saturday night in the eighth inning of a tie game
against the Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   However, his bluff from third fooled Diamondbacks reliever
Byung-Hyun Kim into a balk. When Walbeck walked in to score, the
Angels were on their way to a 4-3 win before 37,916 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn's 14th homer of the year earlier in the inning tied
the game at 3 _ a feat in itself for the Angels, who hadn't scored
more than two runs in their previous four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels went into the game having lost 26 of 28 games when
they trailed after the seventh inning. But Vaughn tried to do
something about it in the eighth, waking up a crowd that the Angels
hitters seemingly lulled to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   But his homer only tied the game.
</P>
<P>
   With two out and nobody on, Todd Greene singled and Diamondbacks
starter Andy Benes was lifted for Greg Swindell. Darin Erstad
singled off Swindell, and Diamondbacks manager Buck Showalter went
to the bullpen again, summoning Kim.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus walked to load the bases for pinch-hitter Jeff Huson,
but Huson never got the chance to be a hero.
</P>
<P>
   As Kim stared in to the catcher about to deliver a 2-2 pitch,
Walbeck took a few quick steps off third toward the plate, enough
to cause Kim to jerk his right shoulder. The balk was called.
</P>
<P>
   The play was set up after Angels manager Terry Collins motioned
from the dugout to third base coach Larry Bowa to get Walbeck to
try a bluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said `Go! Go! Go!' and (Kim) looked up,'' Bowa said.
``Terry was right on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people,'' Kim said through an interpreter.
``I heard a lot of people yelling `He's going home!' I was a little
shocked and nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck, who has 12 career steals including one this season,
said he has stolen home in his career. While playing for the
Tigers, he was on the back end of a double steal, coming home when
his teammate drew a throw to second.
</P>
<P>
   He had no intention of stealing home Saturday, just to shake up
the rookie pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just moved my feet real fast to get him to see me out of the
corner of his eye,'' Walbeck said. ``And it worked because he
flinched.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a heads-up play,'' Collins said. ``More than anything
he was trying to get the guy's concentration off the hitter. And he
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek (5-1) earned the win in relief of Chuck Finley
(seven innings, three runs, six hits). Benes (4-6) got the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn has been as big a part of the offense's recent struggles
as anybody. Since his previous homer on May 30, Vaughn was 7-for-40
with no extra-base hits and only two RBI until connecting on a 2-2
pitch from Benes, hitting it into the Angels' bullpen in
left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been getting me out the past couple of days,'' Vaughn
said. ``You're constantly adjusting. I finally did what I'm
supposed to do _ drive the ball that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a big win, especially after they tore us up
(Friday) night.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Finley led off the game for Arizona with a single and two
outs later scored from second on a single by Matt Williams for a
1-0 Diamondbacks lead.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the sixth consecutive game in which the Angels'
opponent scored first. The last time the Angels scored first was
June 5, when they took a 4-0 lead on the Dodgers, only to lose,
7-4.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Angels responded in the bottom of the first with
two runs to take a 2-1 lead. Orlando Palmeiro opened in the inning
with a single and scored on a double by Randy Velarde. Two outs
later, Velarde scored on a double by Todd Greene.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley held that lead until the fifth inning. With one out
in the fifth, Steve Finley hit a one-hopper that first baseman
Darin Erstad knocked down. He retrieved it and threw to Chuck
Finley covering first. The Finleys collided, but Chuck held onto
the ball and Steve was out.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck needed a few warmup pitches to make sure he was OK to
continue, but the next batter, Jay Bell, hit his 20th home run to
tie the game at 2.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Williams hit a line drive over the center-field
fence, his 18th homer of the year, to give Arizona a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Benes cruised after the two-run first. He walked the
first two batters of the third inning, but got two big outs when Mo
Vaughn grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth inning, the Angels did not put a baserunner
into scoring position until Vaughn's homer with one out in the
eighth tied the game at 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
