<SLUG> BC-BBA-DISARCINA-LADN </SLUG>
 
DiSARCINA REDISCOVERS A-GAME 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE ELSINORE, Calif. _ Gary DiSarcina came here to rehab his
left wrist. Instead, he found a spa for the soul.
</P>
<P>
   This sleepy California League town is just an hour from Anaheim,
but light years from in-fighting and back-biting that has helped
illustrate the Angels' last-place standing in the American League
West.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody mentions the mutiny against manager Terry Collins or Jim
Edmonds' AWOL status from the team as he rehabs his own injury.
DiSarcina laughs around the batting cage like he has known these
guys his whole life _ even though he got here Monday and leaves
after today's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody who signs a five-year contract should have a clause
that says he must come down here and play one series a year,''
DiSarcina said Saturday night before the Angels' Single-A Lake
Elsinore Storm played San Diego's affiliate from Rancho Cucamonga.
``Up there, with the daily pressure to win, win, win, you forget
why you started playing in the first place. This is so refreshing,
so much fun. It really knocks the egos out. It does wonders for
your perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't much fun when he booted a high chopper at shortstop in
Monday's first game of a minor-league rehab that moves this week to
the Angels' Double-A club in Erie, Pa. But he got over it.
DiSarcina, remembering all three home runs he hit last year,
laughed when he saw he was penciled in as Saturday's designated
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   He knows these are the baby steps of his rehabilitation for a
surgically repaired left wrist that was broken early in spring
training. He has been making the Angels road trips, taking batting
practice and fielding grounders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be patient with these things,'' DiSarcina said.
``When you're younger, all you want to do is get back and sometimes
you can be dumb about it. I haven't had any setbacks yet, but I'm
here to get my timing and reflexes back. That takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina's easy but determined manner is the quality that has
made him a leader in the Angels clubhouse for most of the past
decade. He doesn't have Mo Vaughn's scowl or Collins' Type-A+
personality. But teammates respond.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is injured, DiSarcina doesn't have the usual presence
with the Angels. But he always knew he would be back by the
All-Star break. DiSarcina worries about the reception that awaits
Edmonds, who lives in Orange County but has not worked out with the
team after shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels a deep responsibility for what goes on here,'' Angels
left-hander Chuck Finley said of DiSarcina. ``This is his team.'
</P>
<P>
   The same would be true here if he wasn't expected back in
Anaheim within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Elsinore shortstop Nelson Castro said DiSarcina has made a
few suggestions that have helped his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are little things, but it means so much to hear them from
someone who has been there,'' said Castro, in his second year at
Single-A. ``I always threw sidearm to first and the throws got
away. He got me to throw more on top. Coaches have tried that, but
when he said it got through.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina says he learned that when he was in Double-A Midland,
and Texas and Angels veterans came down to play an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember talking to guys like Dick Schofield, Devon White
and Jack Howell about what it takes to get to the big leagues,'' he
said. ``I wanted to know everything. These guys are like that _
like a sponge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
