<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SUMMON LUKE, COLANGELO FROM MINORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ After Saturday's game, the Anaheim Angels
called up outfielders Mike Colangelo and Matt Luke from Triple-A
Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo, 22, is an outfielder who hits leadoff. Through
Friday, he was hitting .362 in 26 games for Edmonton after being
promoted from Double-A Erie, where he hit .339.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo was a 21st-round pick in the 1997 draft and played
most of last season at Single-A Lake Elsinore, where he hit .379.
</P>
<P>
   Luke, the former Dodger who was on the disabled list for two
months with a back injury, was hitting .429 (9 for 21) with five
home runs since his return to active duty.
</P>
<P>
   In order to make room on the roster, the Angels sent Chris
Pritchett to Edmonton and designated Tim Unroe for assignment.
</P>
<P>
   No worries: Ken Hill said he didn't have any ``pop'' on his
fastball Friday night. Just as long as he didn't hear a pop coming
from his elbow there seems to be no reason for concern.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Hill's velocity Friday was in the 87-88 mph
range, down from his usual 92-93 mph and that could be a cause for
worry. Hill had surgery on the elbow last year (June 15).
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had a dead arm, it was one of those things,'' Hill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Terry Collins didn't seem too concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You also have to look at his two (previous) starts, where he
was dominating,'' Collins said, referring to victories over the
Twins and Dodgers. ``The one thing we've tried to make sure was to
stay consistent with his rest so he'd stay in a rhythm. But it
might also be taking a lot out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Monday's off day, Hill will get an extra day's rest
before his next start, Thursday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon update: Right fielder Tim Salmon continues to make
progress while recovering from a sprained left wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon is shagging balls in the outfield during batting practice
and hitting soft toss, swinging with one hand. He won't begin
taking batting practice off live pitching for about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Better days: During his horrendous start this season, Tim
Belcher promised things would get better. Well, he was right.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher pitched his best game of the season Wednesday in a 2-1
win over the Giants. He went a season-high eight innings and
allowed just one run and four hits.
</P>
<P>
   In his first seven starts this year, he was 1-3 with a 9.89 ERA.
In last seven, he's 3-2 with a 3.79 ERA. His only bad start came
against the Dodgers that included the fight with Chan Ho Park.
Before the fight, Belcher shut the Dodgers out through 42/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think he's in a groove,'' Collins said. ``A guy like
Tim lives with command and movement. He's got to keep pitching, and
he's hit that stride.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
