<HEADLINE>
CIENFUEGOS SAYS AGE NOT CATCHING UP WITH HIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos has
struggled to find the consistency that landed himself a spot on the
MLS All-Star team the previous three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with a career best 13 goals and 16 assists last
season, but with only four assists and no goals heading into
Saturday's match against Chicago, a reporter asked if age is
starting to catch up with with.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people mention my age but there are a lot of players
five or six years older than me and I'm in much better condition
that they are,'' said the 31-year-old El Salvadoran. ``It's not my
age, the way I play on the field within the lines demonstrates I'm
only 31.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Galaxy has struggled this season, Cienfuegos says he's
an easy target to pin the blame on.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people talk about Cienfuegos, but Cienfuegos doesn't
make the team,'' he said. ``As a whole we're not playing up to a
level we were playing at last year. We're not finding a rhythm yet,
including myself.
</P>
<P>
   ___Former UCLA striker Seth George signed with the Galaxy
Friday, saying he was happy to be reunited with former UCLA coach
Sigi Schmid.
</P>
<P>
   George, 23, signed with 1860 Munich of the German Bundesliga
after graduation, but he opted out of his contract because of
limited playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy to be back in my hometown and playing for Sigi
again, Schmid said. ``I hope to bring some offense to the team,
maybe not scoring goals but setting them up and being a catalyst.''
</P>
</TEXT>
