<HEADLINE>
AS THE WRIST TURNS: MODANO SHOWS THAT HE'S A TOUGH KEN
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Rumors of his playoff demise, as it turned out,
were greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey _ that's hockey, Mike Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   He was sipping from a soda bottle with his left hand. He had
just taken 30 shifts on the ice and logged more than 18 minutes. He
had won four faceoffs and absorbed the wrist-whackings that came
with it.
</P>
<P>
   He had played tough. Yes, imagine that. Mike Modano, Stanley Cup
tough guy.
</P>
<P>
   For an unkindly large share of his hockey career, Modano has
battled his cover-boy looks and his image. To those who weren't
paying attention, Modano was the blue-eyed, sweet-skating goal
scorer. With all due respects to Barbie, he was Ken on Ice.
</P>
<P>
   But Ken, meet Macho Mike.
</P>
<P>
   He shoots, he plays. Two shots, actually. As just like that,
minutes before Game 3, the Novocaine numbed the Stanley Cup finals'
most well-chronicled wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how you get your hockey news, after Modano was
plowed into the boards last Thursday by a rugged check from
Buffalo's Jay McKee, you figured the Stars center:
</P>
<P>
   A. was faking.
</P>
<P>
   B. had a broken wrist and would be lost for the rest of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   C. would never play the piano again.
</P>
<P>
   D. none of the above.
</P>
<P>
   The correct answer, obviously, was D. I think. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it is in the NHL,'' Modano said, leaning
against his locker _ with his left hand, even _ after the Stars'
dramatic 2-1 victory over the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone hides injuries. You're not going to give any team any
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, but the continuing saga of As The Wrist Turns had
filled columns of newspaper space across two countries. There were
conflicting reports that conflicted with previously conflicting
reports. There were wrist doctors interviewed on TV, and NHL
officials interviewed about who exactly could get interviewed on
TV.
</P>
<P>
   And in the middle of it all, with his left wrist decidedly
aching, was Modano, who added to the Oliver Stone veil of intrigue
Friday by mysteriously draping his sportcoat over his left forearm,
just so the TV cameras would see.
</P>
<P>
   But, in truth, there was no mystery, coach Ken Hitchcock said
after the biggest road win of the franchise's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think everybody expected him to play,'' Hitchcock
corrected. ``I think it was necessarily a lift. I think when the
diagnosis came back that it was not broken, I think everybody felt
that even if he played with 50 or 60 percent usage there, that he
would still be an effective player for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitch added, ``We really knew boarding the plane yesterday that
he was a player.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no need to announce it, however, because full
disclosure in the NHL is apparently as elusive as front teeth. Even
Saturday night, after he had played with such relative abandon and
inspired his own team, Modano played a cat-and-mouse game with how
exactly he had the injured arm covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had kind of a little splint on it,'' Modano said at first.
</P>
<P>
   When told that Hitchcock had already revealed that he played
using a rubberized cast, Modano blinked and said, ``He did? I
wasn't going to say anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He had played better games, but maybe none more courageous. Yes,
imagine that. Modano, the Stars' John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   He said he realized that he was definitely doing to play
``probably this morning. It felt a lot better when I woke up. And
tonight, after seeing the doctor, it felt a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first two minutes of the game, Modano, who started,
grabbed the loose puck and surged in on Buffalo goalie Dominik
Hasek. He fired off a solid slapshot and then almost spanked in a
rebound. He was still skating into the Sabres zone, causing
disruption, in the final minutes when he made a textbook backhand
pass that most healthy forwards couldn't even make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shooting-wise, I felt 100 percent,'' Modano assessed. ``Stick
handling and taking faceoffs, maybe 70 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that every time he took a faceoff _ nine times in the
game _ he got slashed on the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   But that's hockey, Modano sighed.
</P>
<P>
   The assorted other wrist-slashings, he confessed, probably added
to the frustration that led to him taking three two-minutes
penalties over a 10-minute span in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   It was Modano's way of telling the frisky Sabres that neither he
nor his injured wrist are fair game.
</P>
<P>
   But play? Oh, the Stars sniffed. Macho Mike was always going to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to suck it up _ everybody's got to suck it up,'' said
defenseman Craig Ludwig. ``Mike knows that we count on him. He did
what he had to do.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a gutsy performance. It was a numbing performance, and
we're not only talking about the stunned Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mystery with, for the Stars, a happy ending.
</P>
<P>
   Fooled me. I think. Sort of. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
