<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES </SLUG>
 COLUMN-TEX 
NIEUWENDYK MAKING UP FOR TIME LOST IN '98 PLAYOFFS (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Wherever you are, Bryan Marchment, Joe
Nieuwendyk sends his love.
</P>
<P>
   This June is for you, you black-hearted knave.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's 1998 playoffs were stolen by the rogue cheap-shot
artist from San Jose in the first game of the postseason 12 months
ago. A year later Nieuwendyk has personally taken charge of leading
the Stars toward a Stanley Cup championship.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, shoot down Mike Modano. Send Brett Hull to the
hospital. Wipe out Benoit Hogue and Grant Marshall. Take your best
shot, Sabres. Somehow the Dallas Stars find a way and Saturday
night at Marine Midland Arena, that was again Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk scored two classic goals, stamping himself as the
clubhouse leader for the Conn Smythe Trophy which goes to the
playoff MVP, leading the Stars to a heart-stopping 2-1 victory over
Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   No whining now. You've had a whole 26 seconds in three full
games and then some when this series wasn't either tied or had a
one-goal difference and that was after Derian Hatcher's
empty-netter at the end of Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of time to relax.
</P>
<P>
   Right.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' victory was like a sickening kick in the solar plexus
to the Sabres, handing them their first home loss of the playoffs,
giving Dallas a 2-1 lead in the best-of-seven series and restoring
the Stars' home ice advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Not to get ahead of ourselves, because this series is still far
from over, but if the Stars finish what Nieuwendyk has started, let
me be the first to suggest that he should be at the front of the
line when it comes time for the Stars to sip from hockey's Holy
Grail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a man on a mission,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said
following another superb defensive performance by his team, which
outshot the Sabres 29-12. That's particularly impressive when you
consider that the Stars took nine penalties to just three for
Buffalo and spent most of the night fighting off the Sabres' power
play.
</P>
<P>
   Modano played _ and played well _ despite a broken bone in his
left wrist. Hull, the Stars' best long-distance shooter, left the
ice late in the first period with a strained groin and never
returned. The Stars just kept grinding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't worry about it,'' said veteran center Guy
Carbonneau, who was on the ice killing most of those nine penalties
the Stars took. ``We lost Brett and it took us 10 or 15 minutes
before we realized he wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   That elbow in your ribs is Carbonneau's. He was making a joke.
You can do that when you've just gone up 2-1 in the Stanley Cup
finals.
</P>
<P>
   But while Carbonneau and Modano and Jere Lehtinen and the Stars'
defenseman were the unsung heroes in Saturday night's critical
victory, it was Nieuwendyk and his line which stepped up to take
charge offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing as well as I've ever seen him play and I've seen
him play great,'' Stars' defenseman Craig Ludwig said. ``He missed
a lot when he couldn't play in the playoffs last year and he's
determined to make up for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Missing the playoffs last year, watching the Stars eventually
lose to Detroit in the Western Conference finals, made Nieuwendyk
realize that time is slipping away and there's no guarantee he'll
ever come this close again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was difficult last year not being a part of it,'' he said.
``Especially when you get to this point and you realize what it
takes to get here. I'm just sorry I wasn't there for my teammates
last year and I'm thrilled to be here now.''
</P>
<P>
   His two goals Saturday night were beauties, particularly since
they were the result of gritty, hard work by Nieuwendyk and
linemates Jamie Langenbrunner and Dave Reid.
</P>
<P>
   His first one, with 4:27 to play, tied the score at 1. There was
a flurry in front of Sabres' goalie Dominick Hasek and the puck
skidded behind the net. Langenbrunner centered it. Nieuwendyk
stretched to his left to control the puck and Hasek sprawled out to
cover the right side of the crease. Nieuwendyk drilled it perfectly
into the empty left side of the net.
</P>
<P>
   As pretty as that one was, the game-winner _ Nieuwendyk's sixth
of the playoffs, tying the NHL record set by Joe Sakic in 1996 _
was simply gorgeous for most of the same reasons.
</P>
<P>
   It came with 10:25 left in the game and again, it was
Langenbrunner who controlled the puck on the boards and held it,
setting up the play.
</P>
<P>
   Then ... well, let Nieuwendyk describe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the puck in there for awhile and Jamie did a great job
of getting it to the front of the net,'' he said. ``It had to go
through a few legs to get to my stick and I just pulled it to my
forehand. Hasek's always on his way down, so I was just able to get
a fortunate shot away, upstairs and top corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds so simple, but it broke about 18,595 hearts at Marine
Midland Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first goal was just unbelievably hard work by three
guys,'' Hitchcock said, ``but that second goal was a goal scorer's
goal. There are a lot of people who get the puck in that position
all year and never make that play. That is a goal-scorer's goal.''
</P>
<P>
   I'll go you one better, Hitch. I'd say it was an MVP's goal. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
