<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS SHIRT DOOMS TICKET HUNT
</HEADLINE>
 CUP JOURNAL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Outside Marine Midland Arena, waiting for Game 3
of the Stanley Cup Finals to begin, Scott Thomas was all dressed up
and had nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Thomas said, lonesomely. ``I started out
thinking I would pay $100 for a ticket, but the more grief I get,
the more I want to be inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had the cash, but he also had one incriminating problem.
The Addison resident was wearing a Stars jersey _ Joe Nieuwendyk's
No. 25 _ while a sea of red-shirted Buffalo Sabres fans washed into
the arena around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I got one for you,'' a wise-rump stopped and motioned to
Thomas. ``For you, $1,000. Just for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a credit analyst back in Texas, had been in Niagara
Falls, N.Y., all week attending a national Junior Chamber of
Commerce convention. He serves as president of the Dallas Jaycees.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas and about 10 of his fellow conventioneers gathered in a
Niagara Falls bar last week to watch the first two games of the
series on TV. Sabres fans, he said, were surprisingly respectful of
the intruders with ``foreign'' accents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mostly it was some people from Minnesota who were giving us
trouble,'' he said. ``I just told them fine, but the (soon-to-be
Minnesota expansion team) Wild is going to be in Houston soon.''
</P>
<P>
   As he sat, Thomas was joined by a pair of kindred spirits _ more
Stars fans. Paul McMorrow, age 9, was also having second thoughts
about his choice of wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   If those taunting Sabres fans only knew who young McMorrow
really was ... .
</P>
<P>
   His mom, seated at his side, is Linda Modano McMorrow _ one of
Stars standout Mike Modano's two sisters. The McMorrows live in
Boston and made the trip to see Mike play in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Aha, a scoop! Will he play in Game 3, we asked?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Linda answered. ``We didn't get to talk to him
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The McMorrows got their tickets, left by their famous family
member, and headed inside. When we left Thomas, he was still on the
sidewalk, still trying to emancipate a single Game 3 ticket from a
Sabres fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should have worn another shirt,'' he said, still
looking lonesome. TAILGATING AND THEN SOME
</P>
<P>
   Down Washington Street, in a parking lot just a half-block from
Marine Midland Arena, the burgers were grilling and the wings were
frying.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Johnson, 41, of Rochester, N.Y., was tailgating. He was also
fendering, radiatoring, windshielding and even possibly
brake-fluiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real famous out at Rich Stadium,'' Johnson assured me.
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson has done to his 1980 Pinto station wagon likely is
not covered in the owner's manual. Once red, the hood of the
rusting Pinto is now literally charcoal black. And your family
vehicle would be, too, if you used the front end of the car to
barbecue burgers, fry chicken wings, and cook eggs and bacon before
football and hockey games.
</P>
<P>
   As on a stove top, the hood of the wagon had four pans of hot
coals going. In one pan, Johnson used a shovel to cook eggs and
pancakes. A handsaw was frying strips of bacon. In an upturned Army
helmet, Johnson was deep-frying the chicken wings. A garden rake
held the burgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were these factory options on the Pinto?'' I asked Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He stared back as if I were the strange one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did I tell you I'm famous for doing this out at Rich
Stadium?'' he asked again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd offer you a beer, but we've run out of ice,'' Johnson
said, lifting the, uh, cooler, which was actually a toilet bowl. On
a good day, he said he can fit 18 cold Labatt's in it _ and have a
seat to drink them.
</P>
<P>
   The police don't hassle him, Johnson explained, because somehow
the hood-charred Pinto runs and has all of its state registration
papers, if not the Betty Crocker seal of approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at this,'' he said, pointing proudly at a bowling ball
that was propped with finger holes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what we use to drink shots from.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, because a bowler never knows when he needs a drink, Johnson
pours shots of Wisniowka Polish cherry liqueur into the ball's
finger holes. His buddy, Scott Siegel, 35, of Buffalo, demonstrated
by hoisting the ball and downing two stern drips of something red
and sticky. He would have gotten it on his shirt, but he wasn't
wearing one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done this for hockey before, but this is big,''
Johnson explained as the wings gurgled in grease, somewhere in the
vicinity of his car battery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I get you a burger or something?''
BUFFALO DID IT RIGHT
</P>
<P>
   OK, the scoreboard once came crashing down, and the place is not
exactly teeming with parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   But by all other standards, Marine Midland Arena is a handsome
place _ and a perfect reminder of everything that is wrong about
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   On its exterior portals are stone carvings of charging buffaloes
and sprawling goaltenders. Its main entry is a 330-foot long and
65-foot high glass pavilion that quickly whisks spectators to every
one of the four levels of the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1996 at a cost of $127.5 million, $72 million of which
came from private funds, Marine Midland Arena seats 18,595 for
hockey and seems vast and functional compared to cramped, lame-duck
Reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The atrium area features escalators _ are you listening, Mr.
Perot? _ that swiftly carry fans up to the upper levels. It isn't
the cardiac stress test that Reunion can be.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon in 1996, hours before a Sabres game, when the
arena was empty, the giant eight-sided message board came crashing
down onto the ice. No one was injured, and the alleged accompanying
jinx that came with the incident has been rendered forever moot by
the Sabres' play this postseason.
METALLICA NEXT?
</P>
<P>
   Could that have been ... eek ... the bride of Satan that sang
before Game 3?
</P>
<P>
   Well, one day, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Smolinska, who sang the U.S. and Canadian anthems, is, in
fact, the fiancee of Buffalo winger Miroslav Satan. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
