<HEADLINE>
HARBAUGH BECOME INTERACTIVE OWNER ON IRL PIT CREW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The list of celebrity car owners in
open-wheel racing includes actor Paul Newman, comedian David
Letterman, former NFL quarterback Joe Montana and current NFL
quarterback Jim Harbaugh.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the others, Harbaugh is hands-on in the pits. Harbaugh,
one of the founding owners of Pennzoil Panther Racing, spent last
night's Longhorn 500 working on the pit crew of race winner Scott
Goodyear. Dressed in one of the team's yellow-and-black fire suits,
Harbaugh held the sign board that directed Goodyear to his stall
along pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a small job,'' said Harbaugh, who is partners in the
team with TV executive Terry Lingner, automobile businessman Gary
Pedigo and team manager John Barnes. ``Everybody pitches in here
and I just hold the sign board. But I'm not over-the-wall. Hell,
no. My main thing is to help the guys, stay out of the way and
support the sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh's interest in Indy-car racing grew when he played for
the Indianapolis Colts. Harbaugh, who spent last season with the
Baltimore Ravens, was traded to the San Diego Chargers during the
off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh has attended every IRL race this season, including
Goodyear's first career series victory at Phoenix International
Raceway in March. After the second victory last night, Harbaugh
kept the win in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we keep playing and keep racing, good things are
going to happen,'' Harbaugh said. ``And good things happened
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh is also well aware of the dangers inherent in this
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing they tell you when you get down to that pit is
keep your head on a swivel,'' said Harbaugh, who added he would not
be wearing a helmet last night. ``Make sure you're always looking
out at the track for what might potentially go wrong. We had a
meeting yesterday with the IRL, talking about trying to make it
safer for the crew guys. They're exploring how football helmets are
designed so the guys could hear and see and get some ventilation _
and maybe a facemask so they could see below 'em, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh attended last night's race with Chargers center Kendyl
Jacox, an NFL rookie last year who played high school football at
Dallas Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just finished with about seven weeks of minicamps, spread
out from April,'' said Harbaugh, who has been installed as the
starter by new Chargers coach Mike Riley. ``Because we've got a new
coach, we're allowed additional minicamps. Believe me, we need the
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Harbaugh said he also is willing to work on the development of
second-year quarterback Ryan Leaf, the No. 2 overall pick in last
year's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not in my contract to be a mentor or anything,'' Harbaugh
said, ``but I really want to support the kid. Because he's got a
load of talent.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
