<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GREG-RAY-IRL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANO'S GREG RAY RIDES DRAFT TO SECOND IN IRL RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CARLOS MENDEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Greg Ray ran out of cars at the Longhorn 500
last night. Not his own _ rather, everyone else's.
</P>
<P>
   With a cracked cylinder head that slowed him for the final 60
laps, the Plano resident needed to draft to stay close to leader
Scott Goodyear. But with 10 of the field's 26 cars not finishing,
Ray had nowhere to turn for help.
</P>
<P>
   He had enough to hold off Sam Schmidt and secure second place,
but it was Ray's second consecutive runner-up finish in this race
at Texas Motor Speedway. He finished second in the True Value 500
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When a racer drafts, he drives closely behind another car to
take advantage of a pocket of low air resistance immediately behind
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly had the best car out there tonight in traffic,''
he said. ``But in the open, it just wasn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a near repeat of last year's June race at TMS, Ray said.
His Aurora-powered No. 2 Glidden-Menards Dallara felt strong and
passed well, he said, but with the faulty cylinder head, he was
losing about a tenth of a second per lap for the final 60 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were losing horsepower, losing water pressure _ there was
nothing we could do,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the finish was Ray's best of the season. He led 56 laps,
most in the race, after starting fourth. He took his first lead on
Lap 61 and his final lead on Lap 101, holding it until Lap 137.
</P>
<P>
   While Goodyear was uncatchable, Ray had to concentrate on
holding off a hard-charging Schmidt near the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 20 laps, I didn't lift \Roff the accelerator\S the
whole time,'' Schmidt said. ``That's good racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray hadn't finished a race this year. He had crashed in his past
two races, and a faulty gearbox cost him in the season-opener Jan.
24 at Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go into Colorado in a comfort zone now that we've put
together a complete race,'' Ray said, looking ahead to the Radisson
200 on June 27 at Pikes Peak International Raceway in Fountain,
Colo. ``We'll definitely need to start winning some of these if
we're going to figure in the point standings.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, who had crashed in his past two races (finishing 21st both
times), was tied for 20th in the point standings coming in. He
moved to eighth by earning 42 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, I'm real happy with the race,'' he said. ``You
have to start somewhere and get some points, and you do that by
getting in the top 10 and top 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he believes he can win at TMS and called last night's
race another learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting smarter, I know when to go hard, I know when to
lay low, when to be sneaky and when to show your cards,'' he said.
``But a lot of what I learned here, I won't make public
knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   But a public that included many hometown fans in the TMS crowd
of 88,000 had to be impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about the Indiana Pacers, Dallas Cowboys or
Stars, you talk about hometown advantage,'' Ray said. ``Texas Motor
Speedway has been great to me.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
