<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROCKIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS LAMENT MISSED CHANCES AGAINST ROCKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The outcome hinged on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   None involved the 1-1 fastball that Rangers center fielder Ruben
Mateo crushed for a two-run, 420-foot homer during the third at-bat
of his major-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   No, it instead came down to the two batters Rangers right-hander
Aaron Sele failed to put away on two-out, two-strike pitches and
the two retired by Colorado right-hander Curtis Leskanic during the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers' 8-7 loss last night at The Ballpark in
Arlington will be remembered as an evening of opportunities lost
instead of Mateo's coming-out party.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who entered this appearance on his best roll of the
season, failed to put away Colorado's Vinny Castilla and Todd
Helton with the bases loaded after retiring Larry Walker and Dante
Bichette on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Castilla drew a 3-2 walk to force across the first of the
Rockies' four runs that inning, and Helton lined a 2-2 fastball
between first baseman Lee Stevens and the bag for a three-run
double.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows you how important every pitch and every swing of
the bat are,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Leskanic, who retired only one of four batters during the eighth
inning before being removed by Colorado manager Jim Leyland,
delivered when the Rockies needed it the most.
</P>
<P>
   The right-handed reliever retired Ivan Rodriguez with a 3-2
slider that the Rangers' catcher took for a called third strike on
a nine-pitch at-bat with the bases loaded, and he induced an
inning-ending ground ball from third baseman Todd Zeile to preserve
the Rockies' 8-5 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so mnay things that we could have done out there
tonight to change the outcome of the game,'' said Oates, referring
to the fact that the Rangers scored only two runs despite having
the bases loaded during the seventh and eighth innings. ``It was an
uphill battle for us all night, but we had not only the tying run,
but the winning run on base during final innings. Unfortunately, we
were unable to pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored once in the eighth on a sacrifice fly by left
fielder Rusty Greer, and again in the ninth on a solo home run by
Zeile, but Colorado closer Dave Veres _ who pitched the final 1 2/3
innings _ recorded his eighth save by retiring Stevens to end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, who on Monday allowed only two runs on five hits during
the Rangers' 3-2 victory at Los Angeles, entered this start 3-0
with a 3.71 earned-run average during his previous four starts.
Colorado's Pedro Astacio (6-5) earned the victory by allowing four
runs (two earned) on eight hits and striking out seven.
</P>
<P>
   Astacio, though, did fall victim to Mateo, whom the Rangers
recalled yesterday from Triple-A Oklahoma to replace injured center
fielder Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, who went hitless during his first two trips to the plate
against Astacio, belted a 1-1 fastball into the left-center field
seats during his fifth-inning at-bat that scored second baseman
Mark McLemore and cut the Rockies' lead to 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very impressed,'' Oates said of Mateo. ``It looked like
he'd been here for some time. That's about as well as you can show
all your tools in one night. You got to see his arm strength with
that relay throw early on. You got to see his power, period. You
got to see his speed, and he was able to take a walk at the plate
in a crucial \Reighth-inning situation\S.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
