<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PENALTY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' PENALTY-KILLERS DO THEIR JOB
</HEADLINE>
 KILL-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The Buffalo Sabres' power play, a deadly weapon
throughout the playoffs, accomplished the near-impossible Saturday
night. It sapped the energy from Guy Carbonneau, the Dallas Stars'
seemingly ageless forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got me tired,'' said Carbonneau, standing in the Stars'
dressing room in a sweat-soaked T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau and his teammates on the Stars' penalty-killing unit
had reason to be tired. They also had reason to be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty-killers negated the Sabres' high-wattage, power-play
unit eight times, and the Stars defeated Buffalo, 2-1, at Marine
Midland Arena to take a 2-1 lead in the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the difference for us,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   The power play has been the difference for the Sabres much of
the post-season. They had the most effective unit in the league,
scoring 16 goals with the extra man in 15 games before playing the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas had the best penalty-killing unit coming into the Finals,
but the Sabres got the best of the special teams' play in the first
two games. They scored one power-play goal in Game 1, and both of
their goals in Game 2 came with the extra man.
</P>
<P>
   They had plenty of chances to pad their totals Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played the whole game short-handed,'' Stars defenseman
Richard Matvichuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it only seemed that way. Officially, the Stars were
short-handed eight times. Unofficially, they had another late in
the game with goalie Dominik Hasek on the bench and the extra
attacker on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, that's enough for the Sabres to score a couple of
goals. Instead, the Stars shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   The key to killing the penalties was the 39-year-old Carbonneau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carbo's been doing it for 25, 30 years now,'' said defenseman
and close friend Craig Ludwig, exaggerating a tad. ``He's a smart
player. He's not the fastest player on the ice, but he's one of the
toughest to play against because he's so smart.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mike Modano limited by a wrist injury, Carbonneau played on
the first penalty-killing unit. He won faceoffs, blocked shots and
generally harassed the Sabres. When Buffalo had a 5-on-3 advantage
for the final 1:14 of the first period, he twice broke Alexei
Zhitnik's stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' Matvichuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau had help. The Sabres didn't even get off a shot on
the 5-on-3, epitomizing an amazing period for the penalty-killers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres had four power plays in the first period, including a
four-minute stretch when Matvichuk was called for roughing with two
seconds remaining in a Luwig minor.
</P>
<P>
   During all the power-play time, the Sabres got only one shot
through to goalie Eddie Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we killed those penalties in the first period, our team
was really energized and really excited,'' Hitchcock said. ``We
really felt that was just so much confidence for us to kill
those.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had to kill two more in the second period, both
because of penalties called on Modano. Again, the Sabres failed to
score.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres had two more chances in the third period, including
one opportunity late when Tony Hrkac was called for tripping with
17:38 gone.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars killed the first 11/2 minutes, and then the Sabres
called a timeout to pull Hasek for the extra attacker. They had a
6-on-4 for 35 seconds, and the advantage for the final minute.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Stars killed it.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately, the game ended when Carbonneau and Mike Keane
both hit the ice to block a last-second shot.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Stars was that they killed all the
penalties. The bad news was that they had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we didn't want to do,'' Carbonneau said. ``We
wanted to play our aggressive game and play with emotion, and maybe
we got caught with too much emotion. Penalty-killing was big, but
we've got to cut down on the penalties.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
