<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-MATEO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CALL UP MATEO AS GOODWIN GOES ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ It could be the beginning of an era.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the beginning of an error.
</P>
<P>
   It could be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   It could be for 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   All of the above depends upon center fielder Ruben Mateo, the
crown jewel of the Rangers' minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers recalled their heralded 21-year-old outfielder from
Triple-A Oklahoma yesterday to replace center fielder Tom Goodwin,
who Saturday suffered a small tear of the flexor muscle in his left
hip. Mateo went 1-for-4 in his debut, smashing a two-run home run
in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers placed Goodwin on the 15-day disabled list and
issued No. 38 to Mateo, whom right-hander Jeff Zimmerman christened
as ``The Chosen One.'' Manager Johnny Oates inserted the
strong-armed, right-handed hitter into the Rangers' lineup, where
Mateo started in center field and hit second.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, how long will Mateo remain?
</P>
<P>
   Those in the organization lack a definitive answer, but no one
appears willing to dismiss Mateo as the simple solution to what
should be no more than a 15-day problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even answer that,'' general manager Doug Melvin said.
``He hasn't played a game yet. When you're in a pennant race like
we are, you sort of have to take things day-by-day and
week-by-week. In this case, it's a two-week period.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea,'' Oates said. ``A lot of it probably depends
on how he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, who has hit .340 with 17 home runs and 58 runs batted in
59 games this season for the RedHawks, will become the Rangers'
primary center fielder during his length-to-be-determined stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to come up here and sit on the bench,'' Oates
said, ``but that doesn't mean he's going to play every inning of
every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo arrived at The Ballpark in Arlington with no preconceived
expectations for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever God allows me to do,'' Mateo said through Luis
Mayoral, the Rangers' Latin American liaison who served as his
interpreter. ``I'll do my best and play hard to help this team win,
but the bottom line is I'll let God take over.''
</P>
<P>
   Mateo speaks English, but yesterday the Dominican Republic
native utilized an interpreter to ease a mentally taxing afternoon
that included a 2 1/2-hour, thunderstorm-induced flight delay from
Oklahoma City. Mateo experienced great success there with the
RedHawks and ranked among the Pacific Coast League leaders in hits
(81, first), runs (50, first), RBI (second), batting average
(fourth) and home runs (fourth). However, Mateo said boredom never
sat in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about staying there,'' he said. ``I never
thought about coming to the major leagues. I just took it
day-by-day.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin refused to rush Mateo to the major leagues despite the
wishes of the coaching staff, who wanted the outfielder on the
Opening Day roster. Yet, Goodwin's injury opened the door for
Mateo's much-anticipated arrival despite other available options.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could have reinstated outfielder Mike Simms from the
15-day disabled list and played reserve Roberto Kelly in center
field until Goodwin's return. Simms rejoined the team on Friday
after completing his medical rehabilitation assignment Monday, but
the Rangers chose to recall Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   Simms declined to comment on the situation. That in itself
expressed his frustration with the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have another center fielder,'' Melvin said. ``You
have to protect yourself with two players at every position.
Otherwise, you could lose a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pennants are sometimes won and lost by one ballgame. This
makes us a better ballclub than any other alternative available to
us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
