<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-DEFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES CAN'T FIGURE OUT STARS' DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ The Buffalo Sabres' offense had been stifled all
game long, smothered on the power play, stymied when playing even
strength.
</P>
<P>
   Down a goal, having fired only 11 shots on Eddie Belfour through
the first 57-plus minutes of play Saturday night, they got one last
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres went on another power play, thanks to a tripping
penalty called on Dallas Stars forward Tony Hrkac with 2:22 to
play.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sabres played like they had all night, throwing only one
more shot at Belfour before they surrendered 2-1. It was Buffalo's
first home loss of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Buffalo players knew something had gone wrong, and
they knew the Stars' tight neutral zone checking system had
something to do with it. They just didn't know what to do about it
come Game 4 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just didn't give us anything,'' defenseman James Patrick
said in a subdued Sabres dressing room. ``You can beat one guy (on
the Stars), and there's still four guys below you, blocking the net
and taking away the shooting lanes.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Patrick could describe the Sabres' offensive futility:
12 total shots, including three in the first period and three in
the third period, despite having eight power-play opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Others were generally at a loss to explain the offensive
lethargy, except to credit the Stars and their shot-blocking
prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had trouble getting the puck to the net,'' defenseman Rhett
Warrener said. ``They make a real effort of blocking shots.''
</P>
<P>
   His solution: ``Basically, what it comes down to is hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars did display some shot-blocking ability, deflecting 19
Buffalo shots over the game. The Sabres, by contrast, blocked 14.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Sabres players blamed their power play for
squandered scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play has been exceptional during the playoffs,''
defenseman Jay McKee said. ``But tonight they blocked a lot of
shots. They collapsed (on defense) very well. They play five guys
in their zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Buffalo players said that Game 3 was similar to Game 1,
which the Sabres won, except that the teams reversed their roles.
In Game 1, the Stars were unable to capitalize on numerous
man-advantage situations, and that cost Dallas the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to capitalize on your power play,'' said forward
Dixon Ward, who failed to get a shot on goal. ``We've just got to
find a way to get to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres didn't seem sure how to penetrate Dallas' suffocating
defensive schemes, however, and indicated they would spend the next
two off days trying to find a way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to figure out what we're doing wrong,'' McKee said.
``We haven't been able to generate much offensively. We'll have to
watch the videotape (of the game) and be more prepared the next
game.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking only 11 shots and mustering very few real scoring
chances in going down a game in the series, a review of the
videotape offered Buffalo its best solution for offensive woes. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
