<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-PACE-CRASH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACE CAR RUINS NIGHT FOR BEECHLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLES POLANSKY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Legendary driver Johnny Rutherford, a
three-time winner of the Indianapolis 500 and a Fort Worth
resident, thought he'd seen everything during a career that
included 24 Indianapolis 500 starts.
</P>
<P>
   But while at the controls of the pace car in last night's
Longhorn 500 at Texas Motor Speedway, Rutherford encountered
something he couldn't remember ever witnessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like that before,'' said Rutherford,
after his pace car and Donnie Beechler's car collided during a
yellow-flag situation late in the Indy Racing League event. ``It's
unfortunate, and I'm very disappointed because we knocked Donnie
\RBeechler\S out of the race when he was doing so well.''
</P>
<P>
   As the field came down the backstretch under a yellow flag on
Lap 180, Rutherford was hurrying to catch the leaders. The pace car
and Beechler, who was running in the top 10, came together as
several drivers, including Eddie Cheever Jr., tried to avoid track
debris left over from Tyce Carlson's wreck. Rutherford found
himself boxed in with nowhere to go.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began when Carlson lost control of his car while
exiting Turn 2. He turned sideways and slammed the rear of his car
into the wall and brought out the yellow flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody moved to the inside, and as I moved inside, the pace
car came out,'' Beechler explained. ``It ran over the front end of
my car and knocked us out. It's unfortunate because that's probably
the best car I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the collision deployed the airbag in Rutherford's
Oldsmobile Alero pace car, leaving an abrasion along the inside of
his right arm. He refused emergency assistance, however, and jumped
back behind the wheel of the backup pace car and finished his
duties.
</P>
<P>
   The incident spoiled what was shaping up to be a banner day for
Beechler, who had never finished higher than 10th in an IRL race.
Beechler led 26 laps during last night's race and was in front for
the final time on Lap 147.
</P>
<P>
   Beechler, while disappointed, said it was nothing more than an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were in such a hurry to get to the leader, and we
all moved at once,'' he said. ``It wasn't like they were reading a
book or something and not paying attention. It's just one of those
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford hopes some positives will come from the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's lessons to be learned from everything, and I
think chasing the leaders is something we won't do again,''
Rutherford said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 0313EDT &QL; 
