<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-INJURIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STEP UP IN SPITE OF INJURIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAULA CABALLERO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Dallas Stars winger Brett Hull played only three
shifts during Saturday night's 2-1 victory against the Sabres in
Game 3, leaving the contest in the first period with a sprained
groin and never returned.
</P>
<P>
   Did you notice?
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano played with a badly injured left wrist. His
stickhandling wasn't what he'd like it to be.
</P>
<P>
   Did you notice?
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to spot the deficiencies in the Stars' game these
days. The Stars seem to have found a way to make up for injuries,
to win despite adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when our backs are against a wall, we seem to find
another gear, we seem to play better,'' winger Pat Verbeek said.
</P>
<P>
   Modano's wrist injury didn't seem to hurt the team. Whatever
combination of magic drugs and intestinal fortitude Modano needed,
he found and swallowed.
</P>
<P>
   He won 44 percent of his faceoffs with an injured wrist, for
goodness sake.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to suck it up,'' defenseman Craig Ludwig. ``We wouldn't
expect anything less. He has to play. We count on him.''
</P>
<P>
   With Hull out of the contest early, others were counted on as
well. Center Tony Hrkac worked to redirect shots in front of Sabres
goalie Dominik Hasek. Center Joe Nieuwendyk had a two-goal night
and his line appears to grow more willful every night. Guy
Carbonneau helped kill off seven penalties, blocking three shots
and dishing out a team-high four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek said the key to this give-and-take, the balance of power
the team is feeling right now, is the product of time and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through times when Mo, Hatch and Nieuwy have all
been out and yet we still continued to win,'' Verbeek said. ``It
hasn't been a thing that just happened. It's been a steady process.
Over the last 21/2 years, our group has been pretty much the same
and we've really built on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And never missed a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said Hull is listed as day-to-day,
although he mentioned Hull has experienced this same injury twice
this season, and the most recent occurrence took him seven days to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   His team can pick up the slack, no doubt. But you have to wonder
if Hull will follow Modano's lead during this gut-check time of
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the rest of your life to heal,'' Modano said. ``This
only comes once in a lifetime.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
