<HEADLINE>
THE CLOSER, THE BETTER FOR RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATHAN SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ If winning close games is contagious, the
Rangers are in a full-blown epidemic. And if there's a cure, they
don't want it.
</P>
<P>
   At 12-4, the Rangers lead the American League in one-run
victories and winning percentage in one-run games (.750). Friday
night's 3-2 victory was their 10th in their final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates said they haven't been the stereotypical
close games where teams bunt runners over and try to manufacture a
run.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hasn't been the case,'' Oates said. ``For us, it's been a
two-out, three-run home run to win the game. It's just been one of
those streaks where everything has gone our way.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said pitching should get some of the credit. More
specifically, left fielder Rusty Greer attributed the success to a
bullpen that has a 3.63 earned-run average,second in the AL behind
Anaheim's 3.30 and fifth in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been able to either hold teams at bay late in the
game and enable us to come back and win or stop the other team from
scoring and enable us to hang on and win a one-run game,'' Greer
said.
</P>
<P>
   WELL-WORN WETTELAND
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland has been busy lately. That's been good
news for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland had appeared in 10 of the team's past 14 games before
last night, recording eight of his league-leading 21 saves in the
process. In that span, he has dropped his earned-run average from
4.96 to 3.25.
</P>
<P>
   While manager Johnny Oates said he is pleased with the results,
he is also mindful of Wetteland's workload.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize how much he's pitching this year,'' Oates said.
``He's held up well, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland shrugs off the recent busy stretch, saying it comes
with the job of being a closer. But both he and Oates said
efficiency makes the difference. The fewer pitches Wetteland has to
throw, the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the whole key,'' Wetteland said. ``Early in the year, I
was coming back from an injury and I was really struggling with my
mechanics. I was turning in 20-pitch outings, and that doesn't
help.''
AT FULL STRENGTH
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers don't think center fielder Tom Goodwin's injury will
take 15 days to heal, but that didn't stop them from putting
Goodwin on the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin said he thinks the torn left hip
flexor muscle that Goodwin suffered Friday is only a seven- to
10-day injury, which means the Rangers could have kept him active
and played a man short until he was ready. But Melvin said that
given the upcoming schedule, that wasn't an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't afford to go to New York and Boston short of
players,'' Melvin said. ``Games are too important with the position
we're in.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
