<SLUG> BC-CAR-LONGHORN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCOTT GOODYEAR TAKES LONGHORN 500
</HEADLINE>
 500-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It took Scott Goodyear 21 starts to score
his first Pep Boys Indy Racing League victory.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday night's Longhorn 500, Goodyear has won two of the
past three IRL events _ and stamped himself as a championship
contender.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear avoided the tire blistering problems that doomed
defending champion Billy Boat early and then drove away from
hometown favorite Greg Ray late to become the first two-time winner
on the IRL's 1999 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been close here a couple of times, so this is special
for us,'' said Goodyear, driver of the No. 4 Pennzoil Panther G
Force-Aurora. ``It's nice to have a win here. We're leading the
championship after our disappointment at Indy, and it was a nice
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear won his first IRL race at Phoenix International Raceway
and initially moved into the points lead on March 28. He was
running a solid fourth in the Indianapolis 500 on May 30 when an
engine failure ended his day just past the halfway mark. This
victory, by 0.888-seconds over Ray, moved Goodyear from second back
into first in the driver's championship by 19 points against Jeff
Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're chasing the championship,'' said Goodyear, whose
trademark calculating style proved a perfect fit in the first race
run under the IRL's new reduced rev limit of 10,000 RPMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't working that efficiently in traffic in the
beginning,'' said Goodyear, who took the lead for the first and
last time on Lap 166 of 208 around the 1.5-mile quad-oval. ``We
kept making wing changes and stagger changes and pressure changes
during the pit stops. I was working with the weight-jackers and
rollbars, making the car better throughout the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to play it cool and make the changes during the pit
stops so we could have a car to go racing with at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Goodyear was ready to rock, the contenders had been
reduced to Ray and Stan Schmidt. But Ray's relentless pace was
slowed by a cracked engine cylinder head with approximately 60 laps
remaining. And Schmidt began to fade soon after Goodyear drove
around him in Turn 1 and into the lead to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Ray led a race-high 56 laps in his No. 2 Glidden/Menards
Dallara-Aurora, but settled for second place at TMS for the second
consecutive June.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a track that pays dividends for aggression. That is
right up my alley,'' said Ray, perhaps the most vocal critic of the
IRL's reduction in revs from 10,300 to 10,000. ``Early on we had a
great car. We had an excellent handling race car. We certainly had
the best car out there in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``But like last year, we needed more traffic. We were losing a
10th (of a second) every lap and I could see Stan coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt closed within striking distance of Ray on Lap 206 but
couldn't find a line around the Texan, to the delight of a crowd
estimated at 88,000. Schmidt, the heir to two-time Indianapolis 500
champion Arie Luyendyk at Treadway Racing, recorded his best finish
of 1999 in the No. 99 Sprint PCS G Force-Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, who naturally races on Goodyear Eagle radials,
reported no problems with the rubber on his car. That was in
contrast to Boat and teammate Kenny Brack, the reigning Indy 500
champion, who were forced to pit on laps 17 and 19, respectively,
because of blistered right rear tires. Those green flag stops put
the A.J. Foyt Racing teammates a lap down and reduced them to
also-rans.
</P>
<P>
   Ray and Schmidt drove on Firestone Firehawk tires.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear, who started eighth, averaged 151.177 mph in a race
that saw six cautions for 39 laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working hard at Indy, making the car work around
tires that have got a lot of laps on them,'' said Goodyear, 39, a
native of Canada living in Carmel, Ind. ``The other things we're
doing I'm not telling you.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
