<HEADLINE>
TIRE TROUBLE COMMON THEME ON HOT TEXAS TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The past two Indy Racing League races at
Texas Motor Speedway have been good and bad for Goodyear Tires.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall at TMS, several Goodyear-shod drivers had trouble with
their tires.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Scott Goodyear won the Longhorn 500K with Goodyear
tires, but once again some potential front-runners had tire trouble
early in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Boat and Kenny Brack each had to pit less than 20 laps
into last night's race, each complaining of tires that were
blistering. Scott Sharp, who led the first 28 laps, was also forced
to pit early because of tire trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Lauritzen, Goodyear's operations manager for the IRL, said
that when the tires were tested at TMS in April, they tested them
at night. He added that they were expecting the race to start about
1 1/2 hours later than the 6:30 p.m. start time.
</P>
<P>
   The past two years the race had started around 8 p.m., but the
time change was announced when Fox Sports Net announced its
schedule of IRL races in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plain and simple, we came here prepared for a night race and
it ended up being an afternoon race,'' Lauritzen said. ``We did not
find out about the time change until about two weeks ago. When we
came here in April we waited until the sun went down and the track
temperature was about 90 degrees. Once the sun set \Rlast night\S
and the track temperature came down to where we tested, we had very
few problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said they had to back off to save their tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our setup was very hard on our tires,'' Sharp said after he
finished 10th. ``Because of the problems with our tires, we
purposely backed off on the speed just to make sure we were safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, Lauritzen said last night's problems were
different than the tire trouble in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some of this tread blistering in practice,'' he said.
``It was nothing related to what happened last year. This was
surface blistering because these tires held air. We did not have a
single tire go down and the carcass was intact.''
Ward loses lead, streak
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ward was the points leader and Ward had completed every lap
of every IRL race entering last night's race. That changed during
the Longhorn 500.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble started on Lap 119, when Ward, who had completed 600
of 600 laps in the three previous races, came in with a broken
right-rear wheel bearing. The problem was fixed in two stops, but
he was 32 laps down by the time he returned. He finished 18th after
completing 176 laps.
</P>
<P>
   It cost him his points lead, as winner Scott Goodyear collected
50 points to Ward's 12. Goodyear has 146 points after four races,
119 more than Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get it back,'' Ward said of the points lead. ``It was
just one of those races.'' Frustration for Cheever
</P>
<P>
   In April, Eddie Cheever surprised the Indy Racing League
community by making the switch to the Infiniti powerplant.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had Cheever won the 1998 Indianapolis 500 with the
Oldsmobile Aurora engine, but he also won the first race of 1999 at
Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Last night at TMS, Cheever, driving the only Infiniti in the
25-car field, led 13 laps and was comfortably in the top-10 late in
the race, albeit a few laps down. But on Lap 193, he was forced to
pit because of a broken battery tray.
</P>
<P>
   Despite running strong, Cheever was still a little frustrated
after a 16th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here prepared to win,'' Cheever said. ``The Infinti
engine was strong and helped secure us a fifth starting position.
We had our tires figured out. So we had every intention of taking
the checkered flag. We have only ourselves to blame for our results
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two races that Cheever has had the Infiniti he has
finished 16th and 18th.
Old trouble
Rookie John Hollansworth Jr. of Dallas fell victim to the same
problem that hurt him at the Indianapolis 500. He was stuck in
fourth gear for the final laps of that race, and last night at TMS,
it knocked him out on the 146th lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to do with the motor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, the engine couldn't handle what was asked of
it in such a high gear, and a piston failed, said crew chief Rob
Stark.
</P>
<P>
   Hollansworth, tied for 12th in the point standings coming in,
fell to 17th.
Gregoire finishes strong
</P>
<P>
   After not qualifying for the Indianapolis 500 two weeks ago, a
little added pressure was placed on French driver, Stephan
Gregoire, when his team set a goal to finish in the top five of
last night's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never put too much pressure on me,'' Gregoire said after
finishing fourth. ``I knew I had to do something great. We needed a
break because everything that had happened to us since the
beginning of the season was just bad breaks. Tonight I hope we
proved it.''
Kelley Racing struggles
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Racing placed its two drivers in the top two qualifying
positions for last night's race, but after falling well behind
early with tire blistering problems, neither pole sitter Mark
Dismore nor Scott Sharp figured in the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Dismore worked his way back through the field and grabbed
eighth, while Sharp led 28 laps early before slipping to 10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow \Rrace winner\R Scott Goodyear made the Goodyear tires
last. No one else did,'' Sharp said. ``He was just cruising. It
became real evident when I came in the first time there were
blisters, blisters, blisters.... At that point I just dropped way
back because we needed points.''
Foyt's drivers falter
</P>
<P>
   A.J. Foyt, team owner for defending Longhorn 500 champ Billy
Boat and '99 Indy 500 champ Kenny Brack, saw his drivers encounter
the same Goodyear tire problems. Brack finished 13th and Boat was
24th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we lost a lot of positions because of the right rear
blistering,'' Brack said. ``We couldn't run more than 15 laps
\Rbefore it would start to blister\S, and then I had to just reduce
speed to maintain the rear tires.''
Four drivers repeat
</P>
<P>
   Eddy Wallace, Casey Smith, Steve Kidwell and Ryan Lawler were
all repeat winners in Legends and Bandolero division races
yesterday afternoon at TMS.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace won the 25-lap Legends Pro division main event, with
Smith taking the Semi-Pro feature. Kidwell won the Masters event,
and Lawler took another Bandolero victory.
</P>
<P>
   Irving's Mitch Cook won Legends Charger division race. The
Legends will next race on the quarter-mile asphalt track inside the
larger superspeedway June 24 as the first race of the Thursday
Night Stampede.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
