<SLUG> BC-BBO-OFFENSES-RAMPAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR-LEAGUE OFFENSES SHOWING EXTRA VOLTAGE IN '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   June 5 was another bad day for the New York Mets' pitching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii, who had been the Mets' most-reliable starter,
allowed six runs on nine hits and a walk in only four innings. The
Mets lost to New York Yankees, 6-3, and their team earned-run
average moved up to 4.87, the highest since 1962, when they lost
120 games with a 5.04 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Steve Phillips, disgusted with the situation,
fired pitching coach Bob Apodaca and assistant pitching coach Randy
Niemann after the game, along with hitting coach Tom Robson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're underachieving,'' Phillips said. ``At the one-third
point of the season, we needed to right the ship, and we still have
plenty of time to get where we want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets weren't the only ones having a bad pitching day, but
that's not uncommon in major-league baseball this season, not when
the league ERAs are soaring to record heights and home runs are
flying out of the park at a record pace.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, there were 240 more home runs hit this season
compared with the same amount of games a year ago, when the
all-time record was set.
</P>
<P>
   The American League's ERA was 5.04, which would tie the all-time
worst for a league set in 1936 by the American League. The National
League ERA was 4.56, the highest this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Pick any day of the season, and there are plenty of tawdry
pitching stories to tell. June 5 is one worth examining.
The fall of the mighty
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Braves pitcher Greg Maddux allowed five runs on 11 hits
in eight innings on June 5 against the Boston Red Sox. That left
opponents hitting .330 against him, the highest batting average
allowed by a National League starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same pitcher who won four consecutive Cy Young Awards
this decade and as recently as 1995 held opponents to a .197
batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always started off pretty slowly as far as my location,''
Maddux said. ``But earlier this season, I felt my biggest problem
was not getting any movement. I'm focusing on getting mechanically
sound and finding the right trigger point, whether it's my hands,
my feet or my chin.''
</P>
<P>
   One theory being discussed behind the scenes is that Maddux is a
victim of the new strike zone. Umpires, rebelling against having to
call higher strikes, have shrunk the width of the strike zone,
meaning fewer pitches are being called strikes on the corner of the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux still got the victory against the Red Sox, despite
allowing 10 or more hits for the sixth time in 12 starts. By
comparison, he allowed 10 or more hits only eight times in 124
starts in 1993-96 during his Cy Young streak.
Resurrecting a star
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo, the only pitcher in 1995 to have a lower opponent's
batting average (.182) than Maddux, was released by the New York
Mets in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   With teams desperate for pitching, he wasn't sidelined long.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs signed him to a Triple-A contract, then
discarded him after three starts in the minors. The Cleveland
Indians put him through a tryout, but were shocked by the lack of
velocity and movement of his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers were next in line to give him a try. General manager
Sal Bando called it ``trying to catch lightning in a bottle,'' when
the Brewers signed him on April 29.
</P>
<P>
   On June 5, Nomo allowed seven runs in four innings in a 12-11
loss to the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field. Prior to that, he was
2-1 with a 2.41 ERA in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   The low-budget Brewers have been trying to catch lightning for
several years. They thought free agent Jim Abbott might be the
answer after he went 5-0 with a 4.55 ERA with the White Sox last
season. He is 1-5 with a 7.24 ERA with the Brewers. They tried Bill
Pulsipher, the once-great Mets pitching prospect, but he's on the
disabled list with a bad back. Ben McDonald and Jeff D'Amico had
careers ruined by torn rotator cuffs. Cal Eldred can't shake elbow
troubles. The Brewers even tried out 38-year-old Steve Ontiveros,
the 1994 American League ERA champion who has had three elbow
reconstruction surgeries. They haven't brought him up _ yet.
\Nsubheds:Belcher vs. Park
</P>
<P>
   Angels pitcher Tim Belcher signed a two-year, $10.2 million
contract as a free agent in the off-season. He was 4-5 with a 6.57
ERA heading into a June 5 matchup with Chan Ho Park, who was 4-3
with a 4.84 ERA. Both expected to do better this year. Park's
troubles were one reason why the Dodgers fired pitching coach
Charlie Hough.
</P>
<P>
   They took out their frustrations on each other during a
head-to-head matchup at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Park, trying to sacrifice in the fifth inning, dropped a bunt
down the first-base line and was tagged out by Belcher. Park
thought it was an excessively hard tag. The two had words, then
Park threw a forearm to the face. When Belcher tried to retaliate,
Park resorted to kick boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you do?'' Park said. ``I can't understand why he did
that to me. He pushed the ball in my chest. It feels like he tried
to hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, who had a shutout going, fell apart and lost a 4-0 lead
by allowing a grand slam to Devon White. Park was later suspended
for seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher was left with a spike wound on his left thigh and wasn't
amused to learn Park was trained in martial arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a poor excuse,'' Belcher said. ``He knows Tae Kwon Do,
so what? I like to hunt. I didn't take a shotgun.''
\Nsubheds:The Trade
</P>
<P>
   That same day, the Montreal Expos had two one and one out in the
sixth inning when Toronto Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi went to the
mound to check on starter Joey Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi, whose team trailed 1-0 at the time, said, ``Don't \Rlie
to\S me. How do you feel?''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton told him he felt fine. Fregosi left him in. The next
batter, Orlando Merced, hit a three-run homer, and the Expos went
on to win, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any regrets telling him I felt fine because I
did,'' Hamilton said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays are the one having regrets.
</P>
<P>
   They acquired Hamilton in the off-season from the San Diego
Padres, hoping to add a veteran starter who could enhance at least
their wild-card playoff chances. They not only gave up starter
Woody Williams in return but two good prospects, pitcher Carlos
Almanzar and outfielder Peter Tucci.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who spent five weeks on the disabled list with a
shoulder injury, dropped to 0-3 with a 13.21 ERA. Williams pitched
that same day in San Diego, allowing two runs in 51/3 innings
against Seattle and is 2-3 with a 3.43 ERA.
Coors Field blues
</P>
<P>
   Nomo wasn't the only pitcher to have trouble in Coors Field on
June 5. Rockies pitcher Darryl Kile allowed five runs on eight hits
in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kile is 6-9 with 6.19 ERA in 21 starts at Coors Field since
signing a three-year, $24 million contract with the Rockies. In
that same span, he's 11-11 with a 4.27 ERA in 27 games on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever is wrong with pitching in baseball, Coors Field isn't
helping matters.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' 12-11 victory on June 5 marked the 24th time both
teams have scored at least 10 runs in a game at Coors Field since
it opened in 1995. By comparison, the Rangers have been involved in
just seven such games, home and away, during the same time period.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
