<SLUG> BC-REEVES-INSIDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOBBY V. ACTS AS IF HE KNOWS HE'S A SHORT-TIMER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ It has finally happened. New York is turning
Bobby Valentine into ``Bobby Bizarro.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week wasn't a good one for Bobby V. His appearance on the
Mets' bench wearing a fake mustache and sunglasses after his
ejection from Wednesday's game was the emotional, impulsive act of
a manager realizing that his days are numbered.
</P>
<P>
   That message came across loud and clear last weekend when Mets
general manager Steve Phillips fired three of Valentine's coaches,
including hitting instructor and right-hand man Tom Robson, who had
been with Bobby V. in Texas, Japan and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The firings effectively removed Valentine's support system on a
team that already gives him no support. The consensus in the New
York media is that Phillips is hoping to provoke Valentine into
quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Valentine has shown other signs of unraveling. He
benched the hard-to-get-along-with Bobby Bonilla, reportedly
telling him he'd rather play one of his coaches in the outfield
than put Bonilla back in the field. Nothing wrong with that. Others
have had their run-ins with the difficult Bobby Bo.
</P>
<P>
   But Bonilla promptly refused to pinch-hit in two consecutive
games.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine also ripped two local beat writers on the radio and
got into a dugout shouting match with one of them later at the
ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   His Halloween costume party _ he insists he was never really
back in the dugout _ after being ejected in the 12th inning
Wednesday, had a chance to be hilarious, but his players and the
Mets' front office just aren't laughing any more. Instead, it was
simply another bizarre act in a long-running series.
</P>
<P>
   The league certainly didn't think it was very funny, hitting him
with a two-game suspension, which he's appealing, and a $5,000
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Can a pink slip be far behind?
Historic Finals
</P>
<P>
   Visiting writers from Canada and other outposts have snidely
enjoyed pointing out that Dallas' most famous landmark is a grassy
knoll downtown. What they might not know is that Buffalo shares
some of Dallas' history in that regard.
</P>
<P>
   This is a Stanley Cup Finals between the only two cities where
U.S. presidents have been assassinated in this century: John F.
Kennedy in Dallas in 1963; William McKinley in Buffalo in 1901.
Up in flames
</P>
<P>
   Collect call for Kenny Rogers: Temper, temper, Kenny.
</P>
<P>
   Remember when Rogers was with the Rangers and demolished a
stationary bike at Oakland? Punched the mound at Tiger Stadium with
his pitching hand after giving up a home run to Cecil Fielder?
Shoved a reporter out of the Rangers' clubhouse who had written
about that incident?
</P>
<P>
   He's up to his old tricks again.
</P>
<P>
   Upset after blowing a 6-2 lead at San Francisco last weekend,
Rogers ripped apart three telephones and a bathroom paper dispenser
between the dugout and the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   It was an expensive temper tantrum: The Giants sent him a bill
for $2,000. Why so high? Because the pulverized phones supposedly
were tamper-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it; I was upset. I have a temper, I've never hidden
that,'' Rogers admitted. ``At least I was smart enough to use my
right hand this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't know what he was so mad about: He'd given up just five
runs in his 6 2/3 innings, virtually a quality start by today's
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, by the way, had an open-and-shut case: They caught
the whole incident on videotape.
No heir apparent
</P>
<P>
   Word from inside the Mavericks' organization says the media had
best hold up on those ceremonies anointing Donnie Nelson, Big Don's
son and Mavs' assistant, as the next head coach of the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   That, insiders say, is far from a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly there's nothing in writing guaranteeing the
succession and the Mavericks don't have any obligation to honor
that scenario. It's one of those things that seems to have taken on
a life of its own once Big Don mentioned that he'd like to see it
happen.
</P>
<P>
   Young Donnie, by the way, is the only assistant coach in the NBA
with his own secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Divine intervention
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight hours after this newspaper ran a headline that read,
``Deion's football future: `It's up to the Lord,' came word that
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones had decided to try to negotiate an
extension of Deion Sanders' contract.
</P>
<P>
   Just goes to show that The Man does indeed work in mysterious
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Hold that thought
</P>
<P>
   Deion's Q&AMP;A with our Clarence E. Hill Jr. last week included
Sanders' weak defense about playing in the Pro Bowl. Hill asked him
if he had regrets about making that decision ``from a perception
standpoint.'' Deion's response completely missed the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barely moved in the game. ... Besides, the doctors told me
there was nothing I could do to worsen my injury, and I didn't have
a setback,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong answer.
</P>
<P>
   The point of the question was about perception and whether a
player who had missed almost six full games near the end of the
season when his team needed him badly should be showing up at the
Pro Bowl, which has nothing to do with winning and everything to do
with ego. Like it or not, that clearly sends the wrong message to
his teammates and the fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad decision, and the fact that Deion can't admit that,
even with hindsight, shows a severe lack of judgment on his part.
\Nsubheds:Passports, please
</P>
<P>
   Did you realize that every Caucasian player on the Mavericks was
born in another country? Check it out: Shawn Bradley and Dirk
Nowitzki, Germany; Steve Nash, South Africa; Chris Anstey,
Australia; Bruno Sundov, Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Just coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   Not completely.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Donnie Nelson, whose wife is Swedish, has
coached international teams and loves European players.
</P>
<P>
   Three's not the charm
</P>
<P>
   After 18 years with just one media director, the Mavericks will
soon have their third in less than a year. Tony Fay, who took over
when longtime PR man Kevin Sullivan resigned late last summer, will
now follow Sully's footsteps out the door after a dozen years with
the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Fay, 32, will join with other former Mavericks employees to
start their own public relations/event management company, with the
Sidekicks already signed up as their first client. Fay, a
season-ticket holder even before he went to work for the Mavericks,
hasn't missed a game since Derek Harper dribbled out the clock in
the 1984 playoffs against the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   He was a talented, loyal, dedicated employee, and the Mavericks
are losing too many like him.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Mavericks to go outside the organization to find a
replacement this time.
Too much weight?
</P>
<P>
   Sounds as if Edmonton might not be able to keep Doug Weight and
his $6 million contract, which translates into about $4.3 million
in U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Are you listening, Stars?
REVO'S RIMSHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Word has it that every phone in the Phoenix Suns' front office
now has Caller ID. They want to be sure they pick up when they see
it's the Mavericks calling.
</P>
<P>
   If the Spurs needed a soft pickup team to practice, while they
were waiting to see whether the Knicks or the Pacers would be
joining them in the NBA Finals, the Mavericks were available.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks coach Don Nelson says he didn't know he was violating
NBA cap rules by providing a lavish Hawaiian vacation to Gary Trent
and his family. Hey, he's only the general manager. You didn't
expect him to know the rules, too, did you?
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's no longer bogged down with his nonessential duties
as club president, the Rangers' Tom Schieffer is concentrating on
more important things, such as touring cities around the country to
study the real estate infrastructure around their ballparks.
Development: That's the new name of the game.
</P>
<P>
   NBA scouts in Chicago for last week's predraft camp were
whispering excitedly about a 7-foot-3, 320-pound Toronto prospect
named Jerry Sokolowski. One problem: He's only in the ninth grade.
The 15-year-old is expected to add another four to six inches in
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   A disgusted fan e-mailed the Chicago Tribune's Steve Rosenbloom
wondering if Notre Dame football players such as Jarvis Edison, who
fathered a child with booster Kim Dunbar, get credit for Lamaze
classes.
</P>
<P>
   Ba-da-boom!
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
