<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 12:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-13 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DANGER IN US-ONLY INVESTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week The Financial Times plastered across its front page
the news that private investors in the United States are removing
money from international investment funds as the trend to invest
only in US equities gathers pace.
</P>
<P>
   This news was based on figures compiled by the Investment
Company Institute, a trade association of the mutual fund industry.
According to the institute's research, a net $7.15 billion was
withdrawn from funds investing outside the United States in the
first four months of this year, while the industry as a whole
attracted $74.91 billion in new cash.
</P>
<P>
   The trend toward US equities-only investing began two years ago.
As recently as 1996, international investment funds attracted a
whopping $50 billion in cash. In 1997, however, investment in
international funds fell to less than $8 billion, as the ``Asian
flu'' spread across continents. That number is now negative $7
billion, despite a significant increase in overall investment.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reasons why this has occurred. First among
them is the spectacular performance of US equities. As Robert Swift
of Putnam Investments told The Financial Times:
</P>
<P>
   People are seeing that the United States has provided 23 percent
returns over the last five years, compounded, while non-US has
provided half that, and theyre saying theres no point owning this
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the war in Kosovo unnerved money managers everywhere.
Even with an end to the hostilities, there remains widespread
concern that simmering ethnic tensions in the Balkans could erupt
again at any moment and destabilize an uncertain peace.
</P>
<P>
   Third, there is a growing consensus that European companies
simply can't compete with their more dynamic US counterparts. The
rap is that Euro companies are too conservative, too risk-averse
and too hidebound by tradition and paternalism to win in what has
come to be called the new economy. AT&AMP;T reinvented itself in 18
months. British Telecom, it is said, is simply incapable of doing
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, there's the Y2K problem, the computer glitch that causes
computers to read the year 2000 as the year 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard University researcher Juan Enriquez has argued that the
Y2K problem was especially acute because of its potential impact on
emerging-market nations. Enriquez noted that many emerging market
countries _ Brazil, Mexico, Russia, Indonesia and Chile, to name
just five _ have been so bedeviled by pressing financial and social
crises that they have devoted virtually no attention to the
disaster that lurked in all of their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K, however, is not just a problem for emerging-market nations.
European countries and companies based there have also been laggard
in their Y2K preparations and contingency planning. A leading
European computer-consulting firm published a report earlier this
year detailing the inadequacy of these preparations. On top of all
the other concerns, this may be the x-factor that has been tipping
the scales against investment in European investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its causes, the trend toward US-only investing is
unsustainable in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   As former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Thursday, the
world cannot solely depend on US economic growth. If you take a
look around the global economy, said Rubin, it is still true that
the only major part of the global economy that has sustained,
domestic, demand-led growth is the United States, and that is
certainly not a healthy situation in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that there has been some good news of late.
Germany's economic output grew faster than expected in the first
quarter of this year (having fallen in the last quarter of 1998).
Japan, which has been in a depression, announced Friday that its
economy surged 7.9 percent in the first quarter of this year; a
stunning development. Emerging market countries have not seen the
kind of disinvestment that was much feared earlier this year.
Indeed, emerging market funds are, at the moment, doing better than
mutual funds that invest in Europe. And the end of the war in
Kosovo has relieved some of the tension that gripped financial
markets for the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   But the concerns remain. Money managers, after all, are in the
business of maximizing their client's investment returns. If,
collectively, they decide that Y2K and cultural dynamism and
political instability argue against investing in International
funds and that the only safe course is to pour money into US
equities, then the consequences for the global economy will be
profound.
</P>
<P>
   Following the outflows and inflows of money will thus be a major
preoccupation of US policy makers over the course of the next six
months and will determine short-term fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan may think the Federal Reserve Bank should raise
interest rates in the near future to tamp down the fear of
inflation. But he probably wont be able to do that. The United
States needs money going out into the global economy. Three-legged
stools cant stand on one leg.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
