A3483 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN14-COX     06-13 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Win or lose Senate race, Hillary will make history for women
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It seems the perfect ending for a century that started
with women seeking the right to vote: a first lady running for the
U.S. Senate while she's in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Women make up 55 percent of the voters but they are a diverse
lot. Even in New York, women won't just vote for another woman. A
lot of the Hillary haters are women, ready to aim their most
vicious darts at a woman who has outsmarted conservative
detractors.
</P>
<P>
   But nobody ever promised this first lady a rose garden.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton is an easy target because she lives the
successes and failures of the women's movement in full view. She is
the first first lady to do so. For at the heart of the enormous
gains women have made this century are the freedom and the tools to
pursue both families and careers. The pitfall is that marriages
crumble or flourish in the new kind of partnering marriage
relationship that demands. It requires, above all, men who aren't
threatened by a spouse's success, those secure in their own
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   The irony of Hillary's recent appeal to more moderates _
especially, as the polls reflect, older men _ is her loyalty to her
husband through the most nightmarish and embarrassing public
exposure any political spouse has ever suffered. It's a good bet
that Hillary lived the old cliche of standing by her man out of a
desire to preserve the dignity of her own position as much as
anything else. She has. And we have no business speculating about
her feelings for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will take a giant step for future first ladies and wives
of high-profile public figures by just running for the U.S. Senate
while her husband is still president. The backlash to the women's
movement will insist that a first lady couldn't possibly do another
job _ despite having criticized Hillary for doing too much. But
Hillary supporters say she, like most women today, is perfectly
capable of shouldering two major jobs at once.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty years after women won the right to vote, we aren't close
to equal political power. More power for women is important because
it will eventually result in a less violent, harsh and greedy
society. And a more family-friendly one. At the rate we're going,
women won't attain gender parity in Congress until 2500.
</P>
<P>
   When I first listened to Hillary at a political event before her
husband's election, I thought she was the best-informed female
political speaker I'd ever heard. She talked substance, not emotion
or party cliches. She never dodged a policy question, whether on
taxes, child care or foreign affairs. She was respectful of her
husband, but she never demurred that he knew more than she.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time during the past six years, she has taken a
softer approach, out of political necessity and respect for the
office of the presidency. But in her run for the Senate seat
representing New York, she ought to revert to the substantive,
intellectual woman she is. Then, even if she loses, she will have
opened an historic door for women who want to mix traditional with
progressive roles in a new way. Not all men or women can think
outside the box about those options yet _ but in the next
millennium, they will.
</P>
<P>
   Most women who seek political power, whether conservative or
liberal, aren't trying to flaunt anything; they're trying to fix
things. And in Washington, there's a whole lot to fix.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
