<SLUG> BC-KIDNAPPER-SELL14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kidnapper to sell house
 &HT;    ATTN: Massachusetts
 &HT;    By Michele Gelormine
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It was once known as the Pepto-Bismol house.
</P>
<P>
   The oceanfront mansion, now more famous as the house where
convicted kidnapper Stephen Fagan lives, is on the market for $3.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, 57, and his fourth wife, Harriet Golding Martin, have
done extensive renovations to the 7,154-square-foot house,
including changing the pink exterior to a more neutral color.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan said Thursday that he and his wife intend to stay in Palm
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The color was dreadful,'' Fagan said. ``Restoring a house is a
combination of joy and pain. It's a lot of work. Even before (the
arrest), we had planned to sell. It's a lot of fun to restore, but
this is a lot of square feet for two people.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan and Golding Martin bought the house for $1.6 million in
1996, under the names William S. and Harriet G. Martin. Fagan
assumed the identity of William Martin after taking his two young
daughters from his ex-wife in Massachusetts 20 years ago, fleeing
to Florida with them and telling the girls their mother was dead.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan and his ex-wife Barbara Kurth were embroiled in a custody
battle at the time. Fagan said he took the girls because Kurth was
an alcoholic and a neglectful mother. He points to Kurth's three
drunk-driving arrests _ one with the girls in the car _ to back up
his claims.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth has denied his accusations and has said she suffered from
the sleeping disorder, narcolepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Palm Beach Daily News' staff writer John Henderson contributed
to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
