<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3485 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUDENT-LOANS14-COX     06-13 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDENT-LOANS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student loans make the grade
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ After the caps and gowns have been returned, the
parties thrown and the rejection letters thrown away, the real
business of being a would-be college student begins.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Economics 101: Footing the Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Amber Meyers has that part under control. On June 5 she
graduated from Franklin High School. In August she starts her civil
engineering studies at the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Because Meyers, 18, started the scholarship and student loan
hunt during her junior year, she has lined up enough grants and
scholarships to cover half of her tuition, and an additional $6,000
in Perkins and subsidized Stafford loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little bit more that I need, but for the most part
I'm pretty well covered,'' said Meyers, who began an internship
today with the City of Kettering, part of her financial aid
package.
</P>
<P>
   The college-bound most likely have become experts in their own
right in the world of student loans. But there's a whole new crop _
students and parents _ who haven't a clue where to turn.
</P>
<P>
   If you're headed to college in the fall and haven't started
looking into student loans at all, you're awfully late, but not
without hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``If students were starting the process now at Wright State,
they wouldn't receive smaller campus-based funds (ie. the Federal
Supplemental Educational Opportunity grant, Federal Perkins loan or
federal work-study),'' said Jennifer Penick, associate director of
financial aid officer at Wright State University whose office is
dealing with last-minute financial aid processing for the
winding-down school year, summer and for the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But she emphasized that there is still aid out there to be had.
``There's still time to apply for federal financial aid and to
receive major types of federal and state funding,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meyers admits she didn't know what she was getting into before
her junior year. The first person in her family to attend college
right out of high school, Meyers said she was ``kind of dumb to the
fact. It was, 'Oh, you've got four years, don't worry about it.'
But then by the middle of senior year, you realize, 'You've gotta
pay for college.'''
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, guidance counselors, college financial aid
offices and financial institutions with whom you're familiar are
the first places to stop.
</P>
<P>
   That, coupled with the expansion of the Internet, has made
navigating the student loan process less of a headache and more of
a gold mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that you would go to your local bank, savings
and loan, or credit union and apply for a federal loan,'' said Mark
Cannon, a Miami University alumnus who serves as executive director
of the Coalition for Student Loan Reform, a Washington, D.C.-based
organization of state and private student loan companies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent times, however, mergers have made banks more
specialized in nature, with some emerging as student loan
specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, while legally still required to involve a bank
in the process as a trustee, are now becoming all-inclusive
lenders, originating loans under their own name and taking care of
all repayment obligations.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Family Education Loan Program's $33 billion annual
program has made student loans big business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are really gearing a lot of our products and services to be
able to provide loan services and products via the Web,'' said Jim
Eickhoff, senior vice president for business development and
marketing for Cincinnati-based Student Loan Funding Resources.
</P>
<P>
   Like other lenders across the country, SLFR offers its own brand
of loans. Its Jump Start Stafford loan was made available for the
first time in 1997 to Ohio students and to out-of-state students
attending Ohio schools. All recipients must be eligible for either
subsidized or unsubsidized Federal Stafford Loans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides the greatest savings. They can do no better in
Ohio,'' Eickhoff said. Based on the new federal interest rate for
Stafford loans, JumpStart's new rate should be 5.42 percent in
1999-2000, provided that payments are made on time and SLFR's
EasyPay program (their automated bank account deduction program) is
used.
</P>
<P>
   While SLFR has obviously established itself in the lending
community _ since 1984 the company has provided more than $4.5
billion in financial aid to 730,000 students, primarily in Ohio,
with $1.1 billion in loans granted for the 1998-99 school year
alone _ it is just one of countless lenders that students and
parents need to research. Finding the one that fits your individual
needs, such as discounted interest rate payments, account access
and flexible repayment alternatives is essential.
</P>
<P>
   The gateway to financial aid is the four-page FAFSA (Free
Application for Federal Student Aid), a mandatory form for college
students. Once filed, colleges use the ``expected family
contribution'' established by the FAFSA and the individual
colleges' costs to determine if accepted students are eligible for
subsidized or unsubsidized loans as part of its financial aid
package.
</P>
<P>
   Each college typically provides students with a list of
preferred lenders with whom they already have a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The whole student aid path _ including a one-page promissory
note that collects borrower information, certifications and promise
to re-pay the loan _ usually takes no more than four weeks to
process.
</P>
<P>
   The process seems cut-and-dried, but that doesn't eliminate the
questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the biggest ones is, 'Am I eligible? Do I make too much
money?''' said Denise Rossitto, spokeswoman for Washington,
D.C.-based Sallie Mae (Student Loan Marketing Association).
``People tend to think (that option) is beyond reach for
middle-class families.''
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't been the case since 1992, when the federal
government created unsubsidized loans for students from middle- and
upper-income families, regardless of income.
</P>
<P>
   What's New?
</P>
<P>
   With the recent trend in dropping student loan interest rates _
and with tax incentives and early-payment programs _ more people
are finding student loans more affordable. Each summer Congress
sets the maximum federal loan interest rates (meaning Stafford loan
lenders can go below that rate as low as they want). Last July 1
the Department of Treasury reset the rate to 6.86 percent (while a
student is enrolled) and 7.46 percent (during repayment), the
lowest rate in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years other major changes have made to make the
borrowing process easier for students and parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Master Promissory Note is a new Stafford loan
application/promissory note for the 1999-2000 academic year that
cuts down on paperwork for institutions and borrowers of Stafford
loans.
</P>
<P>
   At the discretion of each individual college, the MPN will be
used as of July 1 as a multi-year promissory note. Students will
have to fill out the form _ basically a promise that they will pay
the money back _ only once during their enrollment in a four-year
or graduate school, as long as he or she stays at that school, and
continues to borrow from the same lender.
</P>
<P>
   Sallie Mae is testing a new student loan program called
Laureate, which would give colleges the ability to provide loans
for students through the Internet, with three schools. It plans to
expand its test program to 50 more schools in the upcoming school
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're real anxious to get this across all campuses in the
country. The whole management access for financial aid officers is
just unbelievable,'' Rossitto said. ``The program will get the loan
applied for, approved, guaranteed and funds dispersed within 24
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyers credits her high school guidance counselors and family
friends with steering her in the right direction. Despite having to
re-think her college choice (the University of Notre Dame topped
her list) after looking at finances, Meyers can't wait to become a
UD freshman.
</P>
<P>
   She's also looking toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``My little brother is a freshman in high school,'' Meyers said.
``I'm telling him to start all of this earlier than me.''
</P>
