<P>
   KOSOVO-MAIN _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Tensions were high all over
Kosovo Sunday, as a second wave of NATO troops began entering
war-torn province. It was certainly higher at the strategic airport
just outside Pristina, where Serbs and Russians were blocking
further access to NATO troops one day after some British forces
were allowed to enter. The NATO security force initially was
expected to set up its command center at the airport, but that
facility's status remained unclear. Russian President Boris Yeltsin
and President Clinton spoke by telephone for an hour Sunday about
Russia's role in the peacekeeping force in Kosovo. Meanwhile, two
Yugoslav soldiers were killed Sunday morning in the Vranjevac
district in separate attacks involving the rebel Kosovo Liberation
Army, and British paratroopers shot and killed a Yugoslav police
reservist after the man fired a pistol at a NATO patrol.
Developing. (Kunstel, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIANS _PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ As German NATO troops
arrived here Sunday to secure this sector of Kosovo province, they
were greeted with cheers from ethnic Albanians who had not been
outside or very far from their homes in 78 days for fear of being
killed by Serb troops. It was the same all over the war-torn
province as the second wave of NATO troops to begin their
peacekeeping mission, with fearful Kosovar Albanians literally
stepping out into the light for the first time in weeks.
Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STANDOFF _ JERLI PRELEZ, Yugoslavia _ Among the tense
moments on Sunday between Yugoslav forces and NATO peacekeepers
coming into Kosovo, none was more dramatic than the American-Serb
standoff that took place here. (Albright, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TECH-SUMMIT _ WASHINGTON _ A three-day National Summit on High
Technology that convenes Monday will attract a who's who of U.S.
tech executives, including the heads of Microsoft, IBM, America
Online, Cisco systems and many others. The event, sponsored by the
Joint Economic Committee, will give the leaders a chance to make
their case powerfully to a Congress that is considering a wide
variety of legislation important to the industry. (Glass, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
