<P>
   DEMS-GUN-POLITICS (Washington) _ A troika of New York area
Democrats _ Nita Lowey, Rosa De Lauro and Carolyn McCarthy _ have
been leading the Democratic charge in the House for gun control,
and it's no accident that they're all women. It is a strategy,
blessed by party leaders, that reflects an attempt to change the
gun debate into an issue of child safety and the belief that gun
control advocacy will sew up support for Democrats among women in
the crucial elections of 2000. Internal party polls show that women
are caring more and more about gun safety; this at a time when Al
Gore's numbers among women are not great. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   MICH-GUN-POLITICS (Escanaba, Mich.) _ The popularity of hunting
and the nearly universal ownership of guns in northern Michigan
pose a dilemma for Rep. Bart Stupak, the four-term Democrat who
represents this sprawling, wooded region. Stupak had been one of
about 30 Democrats who consistently crossed party lines to oppose
gun control -- at least, until this spring. Dismayed by the recent
school shootings in Littleton, Colo., and near Atlanta, Stupak has
publicly suggested that he would vote for legislation this month to
require child-proof safety locks on guns, mandate background checks
at certain gun shows and ban the import of high-capacity ammunition
clips. A look at the pressures on one congressman on the issue. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-POLITICS (Washington) _ Profile of the vice president and
his campaign. After a lifetime of preparing to be president, why
does he seem oddly unprepared? By Katharine Q. Seelye. Takes
Contenders 2000 rubric.
</P>
<P>
   DEECEE-POLITICS (Washington) _ The pragmatic and cautious mayor
of Washington, Anthony Williams, is a stark contrast to the legacy
of ethical blunders from the previous administration here; but new
campaign finance charges may tarnish his squeaky-clean image.
</P>
<P>
   ICKES-POLITICS-PROFILE (Washington) _ A look at the first lady's
campaign honcho, Harold Ickes.
