<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH- </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COULD YOU PLEASE MOVE OVER A LITTLE? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The Population Reference Bureau has predicted that the world's
population will pass six &LR;  6 billion with the birth of a baby
October 12.
</P>
<P>
   The infant is likely to be a boy, because statistically, more
boys are born, and will probably be born in a Third World country,
because those countries have the highest number of births.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WORDS AT PLAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - During a Washington news conference last week at which a dozen
former senators endorsed  &UR; Al Gore &LR; , former Alabama Senator
 &UR; Howell Heflin  &LR; noted that the would-be presidential candidate is
wooden. ``Woody to me is a very proud, descriptive term,'' said
Heflin. ``Wooden in my state is seen as being solid, being sturdy
and being representative of a builder.''
</P>
<P>
   - A Berkeley resident reading the City of Berkeley's Draft
General Plan Update points to the Urban Design section on page 58,
which contains the typo cited in editing classes everywhere English
is taught: ``Encourage public art in pubic and private projects.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Patti Itano &LR;  forwards a Monterey County Herald report of a
talk given by  &UR; Joan Didion &LR;  to 175 guests at the elegant Quail
Lodge Club House, which was followed by a series of questions whose
answers she had already given. The last: ``Can you talk about why
you write?'' ``I just did,'' answered Didion.
</P>
<P>
   - The New York Observer describes New York pP &LR; ublic aA &LR; dvocate
and perennial candidate  &UR; Mark Green &LR;  greeting the Observer's
gossip-writer at a movie screening and saying, ``Enjoyed our
lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had lunch,'' answered the writer. ``Well, then, we
should,'' said the politician.
