<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3528 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-SUMMIT-0614-COX     06-13 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-SUMMIT-0614-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP RECASTS ITSELF AS CHAMPIONS OF HIGH-TECH
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress will put the lucrative high-tech world
into play this week as Republicans seek to build an alliance with
an industry that has largely been a feeding ground for Democratic
fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are sponsoring the first-ever National Summit on
High Technology, comprised of high-profile hearings before the
Joint Economic Committee to be spread over three days.
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan will be the opening
witness Monday. Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who chairs the panel,
asked Greenspan to review the ``outstanding impact this growing and
relatively new segment of the economy has had on jobs, wages and
standards of living.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Greenspan, the committee will hear Monday from IBM
chairman Louis Gerstner and Intel Corp. president Craig Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Day two of the summit will feature Microsoft Corp. chairman and
co-founder Bill Gates, who will ``explore legislative issues of
concern to this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates' top concern in Washington nowadays is the landmark
antitrust trial against Microsoft being heard in a federal
courthouse within sight of the Capitol. Republicans hope that
Gates' anger against the Democrat-run U.S. Justice Department will
yield major campaign contributions for their candidates in the 2000
elections.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the high-tech industry has become an
increasingly vital reservoir of political money. The Center for
Responsive Politics estimates that computer industry executives
gave some $9 million to Congressional candidates in the 1997-98
election cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have also been taken aback by the breadth of the
72-member high-tech fundraising committee organized by Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. As the Republican White House front-runner, Bush
counts in his financial corner such industry luminaries as America
Online's James Barksdale, Cisco Systems' John Chambers, and Intel
co-founder Gordon Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Two anti-Microsoft figures are scheduled to testify Wednesday,
Day three, at the high-tech summit: Scott McNealy, chairman of Sun
Microsystems, and Marc Andreessen(CQ), chief technology adviser to
AOL and a co-founder of Netscape Communications, absorbed by AOL in
a recent $10 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   Although accusatory McNealy and Andreessen e-mails have been
featured at the Microsoft trial, neither business leader is a
steadfast Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to counter the Republican political drive, House
Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt, D-Mo., last week named a
Democratic high-tech advisory panel. It is headed by two Silicon
Valley Californians: Reps. Zoe Lofgren and Anna Eshoo.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic activists also last week sponsored a ``technology
outreach'' day, which included informal exchanges with Microsoft
senior vice president Craig Mundie, Silicon Valley entrepreneur
John Doerr and Dell Computer chairman Michael Dell.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats are at risk of further losing high-tech support
for their failure to get behind legislation that would protect the
industry from Y2K computer damage suits. The bill faces a key floor
vote in the Senate Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Trial attorneys are preparing to file a blizzard of lawsuits
against the computer industry over the feared failure of systems
unable to deal with the date change on Jan. 1, 2000, widely known
as the Y2K computer glitch. The trial lawyers remain firmly in the
Democratic camp, which may influence what is widely seen as a close
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
