u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-OUDEH-NYT &LR;      06-13 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-OUDEH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIAN BEHIND '72 OLYMPIC KIDNAPPING BARRED FROM WEST BANK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Israeli government Sunday barred Mohammed Oudeh,
a Palestinian official who recently acknowledged playing a
mastermind role in the 1972 Munich Olympics hostage-taking episode,
from entering the West Bank to return to his home in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Bavarian prosecutors issued a warrant for Oudeh's
arrest, based on his admissions in a recently published
autobiography. In his book, published in France, Oudeh, who is
better known as Abu Daoud, described smuggling arms into Germany
and transporting the terrorists into the Olympic village before
they took Israeli athletes hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The episode, followed by a bungled rescue operation, left 11
Israelis, five Palestinians and one German dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu this morning instructed
security forces not to allow Abu Daoud, who planned the murder of
Israeli athletes at the Munich Olympics, to enter the Palestinian
Authority from Jordan,'' said a statement issued by the outgoing
Prime Minister's office.
</P>
<P>
   Oudeh, 63, a lawyer, has lived with his wife in Ramallah since
1996, when he was allowed to return from exile for a Palestine
Liberation Organization leadership meeting and stayed. During the
last few years, he has traveled abroad frequently and has enjoyed
the privileges of an Israeli-issued VIP pass that allowed him
relatively free movement through Israeli checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu also ordered Oudeh's VIP pass canceled Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli decision, while based on Munich's intent to
prosecute, nonetheless tests what some Israelis consider to be the
most difficult premise of the peace negotiations: that the past is
past and that former terrorists should be treated as partners in
peace.
</P>
<P>
   Those who experienced terrorism directly feel this most keenly.
``It is inconceivable that a man with a direct or indirect
connection with the murder of the 11 from Munich would ever be here
as a free man,'' said Uri Afek, chairman of the Israeli Olympic
Committee at the time.
</P>
<P>
   And Ilana Romano, widow of Yosef Romano, an Olympic wrestler who
died in the 1972 episode, said on Israel Radio, ``Arrest this man,
this murderer, this criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from Amman, Jordan, Oudeh criticized the
Israeli decision to bar him as hypocritical and insulting to the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Oslo, nobody was supposed to be interested in re-opening
the pages of the past,'' he said. ``The Israelis should take into
consideration that there is a peace process and that we are not
anymore enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   He mentioned that Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak talks freely
now about assassinating Palestinian operatives in Beirut in the
same era as the Munich attack. It is part and parcel of a shared
history of violence and counterviolence, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been living in the Palestinian territories for three
years without any problem,'' he continued. ``The Israeli
intelligence knew everything about me, and despite that they are
ready to re-open a historical account.''
</P>
<P>
   Daoud Oudeh, his son, said in Ramallah that there is no reason
to hold his father accountable if the Palestinian leaders above him
go untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Munich was not a one-man decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, ``Palestine: From Jerusalem to Munich,'' Oudeh said
that the Palestinians did not mean to harm the athletes taken
hostage. The Palestinians intended to take hostages and to use them
as leverage to obtain the release of Palestinians from Israeli
jails, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not issue orders to kill,'' Oudeh said in the phone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Two Israeli athletes were shot dead at the start of the
operation. Oudeh said it was because they resisted during the
storming of their compound.
</P>
<P>
   The others died from shooting during the rescue operation. In
his book, Oudeh blamed German police for ``ambushing'' the
terrorists, opening fire on them and their hostages. He also
criticized Golda Meir, then Israeli prime minister, accusing her of
intransigence during the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   In his book, Oudeh said that the spirit of the peace
negotiations demanded that the past be buried.
</P>
<P>
   On the phone Sunday, he said that the Israelis allowed him,
along with other Palestinian exiles, to return to the West Bank in
1996 based on a decision that any previous act against Israel ``is
considered legally null.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would challenge the action against him in
Israeli court.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the decision was an embarrassment to the
Palestinian Authority, making it look like the Palestinian
leadership could not ``protect its members.'' But associates said
that he does not feel that Palestinian leaders were expressing
sufficient outrage Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
