<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3533 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WANGO-LADN     06-13 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANGO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS PACK DODGER STADIUM FOR RICKY MARTIN TURNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frenzied fans turned Dodger Stadium totally loco amid screams
and cheers as Latin heartthrob Ricky Martin hit the stage Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a tight gray shirt and black slacks, Martin belted out
his chart-topping hit ``Livin' La Vida Loca'' on a podium above a
colorful flock of dancers and musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Like a Puerto Rican Elvis, Martin was a flurry of motion, every
step eliciting cheers and squeals from the mostly female crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``His personality really comes through,'' said restaurant worker
Nancy Solari, 23, of North Hollywood. ``His music is really
passionate, and he's a great performer. He's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   The 7{-hour Wild Wild Wango Tango 2, produced by local Top 40
station KIIS-FM (102.7), was a celebration of today's multiethnic
pop charts.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the spectators _ teeny-boppers, 20-somethings,
even grandmothers _ were there for Martin, the swivel-hipped
singing sensation whose single of ``Livin' La Vida Loca'' (The
Crazy Life) recently went to No.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love him,'' said Reseda resident Nancy Solari's sister
Susan, 26, who works in the TV industry. ``He's really cute, and he
can really dance. Ricky has this spark to him, and we've heard so
much about him. We're finally getting to see him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadium officials estimated that about 50,000 people attended
Saturday's show, which also included performances by Enrique
Iglesias, Blondie, 98 Degrees and M.C. Hammer. But Martin's
performance has been long-awaited by fans ever since his appearance
on the Grammy Awards in February.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 27-year-old pop superstar was a member of the teen
group Menudo and went on to star in ABC's hit soap ``General
Hospital'' and even appeared on Broadway in ``Les Miserables,'' it
was his performance at the Grammys that sparked interest among the
English-language audience.
</P>
<P>
   His self-titled English-language debut album is selling 300,000
copies a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows how to shake his hips, and he sings really good,
too,'' said Maria Gonzalez, 31, a South Bay executive assistant.
``But his hips are the best part.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Martin stopped traffic in New York's Rockefeller
Center when he performed for fans outside the studios of TV's
``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so much better now than he was before,'' said Christina
Orozco, 16, a 10th-grader from Newhall. ``He's always been good,
and he's a good actor, too, but he's really grown.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a cheap day at the ball park. Vendors did a brisk
business selling six designs of T-shirts at $25 apiece, and ticket
prices ranged from $35 to $75.
</P>
<P>
   Postal employee Carlos Gonzalez, 32, of Laguna Niguel, said he
paid $600 to bring seven members of his family to the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``My 8-year-old son and 7-year-old niece wanted to see Ricky,''
he said. ``But I'm here for Will Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd remained well-behaved and orderly through the
fast-paced show, and a broken water main that threatened the event
did nothing to dampen the spirits of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   By 3:30 p.m., all problems with the ruptured water main had been
resolved. Traffic flowed freely, and there were no incidents.
</P>
<P>
   Utility crews had worked frantically to restore water service to
Dodger Stadium after the 16-inch main ruptured just hours before
fans showed up for the sold-out concert.
</P>
<P>
   While the stadium's water supply was back by 1 p.m., the start
of the Wango Tango concert was delayed by 90 minutes to 3:30 p.m.
amid the chaos of traffic jams on surrounding freeways and surface
streets.
</P>
<P>
   But concertgoers such as 16-year-old Celeste Chavarin, who drove
in from Encino, said the postponement wasn't a big deal and that
only the show's cancellation would have been a problem for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good because we were already running late. But it would
have sucked if the concert was canceled because we would have
braved all that traffic for nothing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic on many freeways, including the San Bernardino, Harbor
and Golden State freeways, was stop-and-go for hours before the
concert was scheduled to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Peterson, 26, who flew all the way from Salt Lake City,
Utah, to attend the concert, said traffic was more a pain than
anything else. Although it took her an hour and 15 minutes more
than she expected to get to Dodger Stadium, she, too, was glad the
show was only postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have cried because I flew out here yesterday from Utah
to see this concert. I would have been really, really disappointed
if the show was canceled. It would have been fierce,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 residents of a neighborhood near Chinatown remained
without water service into the late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   With thousands of people due to arrive at the stadium, the Los
Angeles Police Department took the precaution of issuing a tactical
alert at 1:30 p.m. to ensure there was no disturbance owing to a
delay or cancellation of the highly anticipated show.
</P>
<P>
   The tactical alert, which boosts the number of on-duty officers
by holding them after their regular shift is over, was lifted at
1:55 p.m., Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no problems whatsoever,'' said LAPD spokesman Officer
Don Cox.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials also scrambled during the outage to draw up plans
on how to fight a fire under those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any pressure in most of the hydrants,'' said
Los Angeles Fire Department spokesman Jim Wells. ``We were
concerned that if there was a fire, we would have had to shuttle
water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1619EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
