<SLUG> BC-KOREA-CONFRONT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH KOREA AGREES TO TALKS ABOUT YELLOW SEA CONFRONTATIONS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ North Korea agreed Sunday to talk to U.N. military
officers in an effort to resolve the ongoing confrontation between
the South Korean and North Korean navies in the Yellow Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, for the sixth day in a row, North Korean military
vessels intruded into the waters south of the effective demarcation
line separating the seas of the two countries. The North does not
recognize the line, but in recent years it has never challenged it
so aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean patrol boats rammed North Korean vessels on Friday,
trying to drive them north and leading to a sharp escalation of
tensions. That was when the U.N. Command, which is led by American
officers and includes 37,000 American troops stationed in South
Korea, called on North Korea to discuss the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Carl J. Kropf, a spokesman for the U.N. Command, said that
North Korea had agreed Sunday to meet, perhaps as early as Tuesday.
The meetings will be held with generals from each side, the
highest-level discussions normally held, and will take place in the
border village of Panmunjon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The North's message is viewed as a positive step by the U.N.
Command,'' Kropf said in a statement. ``It remains in everyone's
interests to reduce tensions at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   South Korea seems to have stopped ramming the North Korean
boats, at least for the time being, but it has dispatched warships
to the area and put its army on alert.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides have been careful so far to avoid direct
exchanges of fire, tensions are so high that officials are
concerned that an accident or low-level officer's decision could
set off a battle that would have far-reaching consequences for one
of the last remaining frontiers of the cold war.
</P>
<P>
   After its boats were rammed, North Korea threatened to carry out
``self-defensive strikes'' against the South Koreans, whom it
accused of intruding into its waters. But North Korean declarations
are always so bellicose and extreme that it was difficult to
determine if this declaration was anything more serious than
run-of-the-mill threats and bluffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
