</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBSCRIPTIONS-SWEEPSTAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM SWEEPSTAKES OFFERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., Conn. ,  Ill.) MAGAZINES DRAWING FEWER READERS By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, America's sweepstakes companies, like American Family
Publishers and Publishers Clearing House, have filled mailboxes
with letters promising consumers millions of dollars and selling
magazine subscriptions. For years, the magazine industry has
flourished with the help of those grand, empty promises, depending
on them in the first half of the 1990s to generate a third of its
new subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the stampsheet houses, as the sweepstakes companies are
called, are under a cloud of bad publicity and government scrutiny,
first set in motion by an investigation into their practices
introduced by 32 states early in 1998. As a result, the
ever-growing lack of consumer trust and the poor performance by
sweepstakes companies are threatening to drive the magazine
industry into what some publishers are calling its own recession.
</P>
<P>
   Because Americans are responding with less enthusiasm, the
sweepstakes houses have delivered far fewer subscriptions to the
magazine publishers they tout. The good news is that magazine
publishers are finding new ways to attract subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, E. Daniel Capell, a magazine circulation analyst,
will publish a report in his newsletter, Capell's Circulation
Report, that shows for the first time the sharp downturn in
subscription rates for magazines that sell subscriptions through
the two main sweepstakes houses, American Family Publishers,
jointly owned by a unit of Time Warner's Time Inc. and an
investment group associated with the Pritzker family of Chicago,
and Publishers Clearing House, a limited partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Capell announced his survey of the circulation directors of 136
consumer magazines last week at a meeting of those executives
sponsored in part by the Magazine Publishers of America, and the
results are already sending a chill through the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The stampsheet houses typically rely on their year-end mailings
to generate the bulk of their annual responses. Capell's survey
found that subscription response rates, from the 1997-98 year-end
mailings to the 1998-99 year-end mailings, are down an average of
37.4 percent for magazines sold through American Family Publishers;
for magazines carried by Publishers Clearing House, subscription
rates are down 29.2 percent. For many magazines, these figures
represent a huge downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see serious subscription problems for
large-circulation titles that rely heavily on the stampsheets,''
Capell said. ``The women's services magazines will take the biggest
hit: Family Circle, Woman's Day, Redbook, and Ladies' Home Journal.
The newsweeklies are the next tier.''
</P>
<P>
   Capell's report comes after American Family Publishers agreed
last month to make extensive changes in its practices and settled a
civil charge filed by four states charging that it had deceived
consumers. On Friday, however, a federal judge in North Carolina
found American Family in contempt for violating a 1993 settlement
in which the company agreed to tone down its contest promotions
there.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, U.S. Senators received nervous executives from the
sweepstakes and magazine industries who were lobbying for
last-minute changes to a bill, the Deceptive Mail Prevention and
Enforcement Act, that the Senate is expected to pass before the
July 4 recess. The bill would limit the kind of solicitations that
have so beguiled consumers in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Industry response to the subscription downturn is uniformly
dour. Lindsay Valk, the director of circulation marketing for
Hearst Magazines, publisher of Redbook and Esquire, two magazines
that are heavily reliant on the stampsheets, said that some Hearst
titles ``have seen a big hit to their volume.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregory B. Zorthian, the vice president of business development
at Forbes magazine, which sells subscriptions through both American
Family Publishers and Publishers Clearing House, refers to the
sweep decline as ``a circulation recession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got people scared,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Woods, the circulation director for Prevention magazine,
which is published by Rodale, said he had expected to generate at
least 100,000 subscriptions from the stampsheets for the year-end
mailings, but got less than half that number.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Block, a founder of American Family Publishers and a former
consultant to Publishers Clearing House, estimates that for some
magazines, the subscription rate will be off by as much as 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Reader's Digest Association founded the first magazine
sweepstakes in 1962. Business boomed in the 1980's and early
1990's, then slowed a bit, partly because of consumer fatigue,
before dropping precipitously last year.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch is simple: consumers get letters exhorting them to
enter a sweepstakes. Accompanying the letters is an offer of
cut-rate magazine subscriptions. In the past, many consumers
subscribed, either because they thought it would increase their
chances of winning, or to take advantage of an inexpensive magazine
offer. Under the bill before the Senate, the sweepstakes mailing
would have to display a statement that no purchase of a
subscription is necessary to win a prize.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Holland, a senior vice president at Publishers Clearing
House, would not confirm the percentage drop in subscription rates,
but conceded that they were down.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Caughman, the chairman of American Family Enterprises,
said that ``the mass-market titles sell best with the stampsheets,
so they are therefore more vulnerable in the downturns, without
question. They are more reliant on the stampsheets. If you're `Fly
Fishing on the Housatonic,' this is not going to affect you.'' She
would not confirm the percentage of decline but said, ``We're not
down to zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Both executives defended the seductive nature of their company's
mailings. Ms. Holland said: ``The whole purpose of the sweepstakes
is merely to call attention to the offers inside. After all, we do
guarantee the lowest magazine prices.''
</P>
<P>
   With subscription rates dropping, Capell predicts that in 2000
many magazines will have to lower their rate bases, the circulation
levels that magazines guarantee to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Pashby, executive vice president of the Magazine
Publishers of American, said: ``I assume that would be a logical
progression from what has happened. However, I think that
publishers have been quick to go out and look for new ways of
reaching the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods of Prevention said that the magazine's circulation staff
is studying other ways to get subscriptions. The Internet, he said,
shows some hope; he said that Prevention now picks up 5,000
subscriptions a month from Women.com, a Web site with which it is
affiliated.
</P>
<P>
   Other publishers are relying increasingly on new kinds of
marketers, like News Subscription Services, a company in Greenwich,
Conn., that provides, for example, a method by which consumers are
offered magazine subscriptions when they order from a catalog.
Consumers who order from Lands' End, for example, may get a
solicitation for a cut-rate subscription to Martha Stewart Living.
</P>
<P>
   The sweepstakes companies, which can keep up to 90 percent in
commissions on the subscriptions, are also trying to reverse their
losses.
</P>
<P>
   American Family Publishers started an advertising campaign last
week that shows the happy, smiling, winners of prizes that start at
$1,000. ``We're focusing on showing consumers that 19,000 consumers
will win prizes from AFP in 1999,'' Ms. Caughman said. She added:
``I believe consumers love us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
