<HEADLINE>
`CLARA BOW': ONE WHO HAD `IT' IN THE AGE OF THE FLAPPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clara Bow's stardom lasted for only about a decade, through the
1920s and into the '30s, but that added up to 58 movies and an
astounding popularity that bears comparison with Jean Harlow and
Marilyn Monroe. Her winning ways are brought back in ``Clara Bow:
Discovering the `It' Girl,'' Monday's Turner Classic Movies
biography.
</P>
<P>
   Although the writers of this affectionate documentary evidently
read too many fan magazines at an impressionable age, and Courtney
Love's narration is sloppily delivered, the story is worth telling,
both for what it reveals about the exploitation of vulnerable
performers by Hollywood studios and for the details of a sad life
that belied a devil-may-care image.
</P>
<P>
   Afflicted with a mentally unstable mother and a father who seems
to have taken an interest in her only when it served his needs
(including, it is suggested here, his sexual urges), she was
rescued by the camera.
</P>
<P>
   As Monday's clips from several of her hits attest, she had
personality to spare, and her boss at Paramount, B.P. Schulberg,
worked her hard, renting her out to other studios for more than he
paid her; in 1924-25 alone, she made 25 movies, some of which have
been lost.
</P>
<P>
   She became the era's most famous flapper, a symbol of sexual
freedom, both on screen and off, and had affairs with, among
others, the silent-film star Gilbert Roland, the director Victor
Fleming, the young leading man Gary Cooper, and Bela Lugosi, a k a
Dracula. Gossips credited her with taking on the whole USC football
team.
</P>
<P>
   Elinor Glyn, the novelist who invented ``it'' and made a
lucrative deal with Clara Bow at the height of her fame, defined
the word as ``that strange magnetism which attracts both sexes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bow's bad times began with the coming of sound; this star from
New York understandably saw the microphone as an enemy. At the age
of 25 she was a has-been.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief comeback, she retired with her husband, Rex Bell,
to a Nevada ranch. There was an attempted suicide, a spell in a
mental hospital and years of loneliness. Perhaps the most touching
moment in the documentary is hearing the actress who had so much
trouble with her diction practicing Elizabethan poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Following the documentary, TCM presents three of the best-known
Bow movies: ``It,'' ``The Wild Party'' and ``Down to the Sea in
Ships.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CLARA BOW'
</P>
<P>
   Discovering the `It' Girl
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Monday on Turner Classic Movies
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
