<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, June 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Areas of dense fog with spotty showers and drizzle will prevail
early Monday from the Middle Atlantic States to southern New
England especially near the coast. The low clouds and fog will
gradually lift to allow for periods of hazy sunshine in many areas
as increasing breezes mix drier air from aloft toward the ground.
Damp conditions will linger longest near the east coast of New
England as a weak low-pressure area drifts slowly south of Cape
Cod.
</P>
<P>
   A band of clouds and thundershowers will accompany a front as it
moves from the eastern parts of the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley
early Monday to the interior Northeast on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   A few strong thunderstorms will occur to the west of the crest
of the Appalachians, especially where some hazy sunshine adds fuel
to the sultry air mass. In the wake of the front, cooler and less
humid air will spread from the northern Mississippi Valley toward
the Great Lakes states.
</P>
<P>
   Warm and muggy weather will persist over the Southeast. A cold
front moving east will promote a broken band of strong
thunderstorms near the southern Mississippi and western Tennessee
valleys. Farther east, scattered thundershowers will be common in
the humid air.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and some strong thunderstorms will move from the
northern Rockies toward the central Plains as low pressure moves
along a front separating hot air over the interior West from much
cooler air to the east. Most of the western states will have
abundant sunshine, but some isolated mountains thunder will occur
in the heat of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Alaskan Heat
</P>
<P>
   The weekend weather in central and eastern interior Alaska bore
a strong resemblance to typical spring conditions in the deserts of
the Southwest. Temperatures surged into the upper 80s and low 90s
as the circulation around a strong ridge of high pressure over the
Yukon Territory resulted in steady winds from the south at high
levels. Over 21 hours of sunshine contributed to the uncommon
warmth. The heat was accompanied by desertlike humidity which fell
below 20 percent in many locations. The heat will abate by midweek
as a cool front arrives from the western part of the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
