<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-DOBBS-NYT &LR;      06-13 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-DOBBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY ALL THE FUSS ABOUT LOU DOBBS?  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The audience for CNN's nightly business news program
``Moneyline,'' between 300,000 and 400,000 homes a night, is so
small it would not be close to qualifying as one of the 100
most-watched shows on all of cable television.
</P>
<P>
   As for broadcast television, ``Moneyline'' would be dwarfed by
the likes of ``America's Greatest Pets,'' on UPN.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Moneyline'' has become one of the most lucrative hours in
all of cable television, so important to the overall revenue at CNN
that when Lou Dobbs announced last week that he was leaving as host
of the show, it was widely regarded as a potentially serious blow
to CNN's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the disparity between viewers and dollars is that
the number of viewers is not nearly as important to ``Moneyline''
as the identity of those who are watching. That has been as pure a
collection of investment-oriented viewers in affluent households as
any on television.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of audience, which creates advertiser demand and
higher ad rates, underscores the increasing strength of financial
news and information on television, a trend that has developed over
the last several years, thanks chiefly to booming stock markets and
the ever-increasing number of stock investors.
</P>
<P>
   The impact has been most noticeable at CNBC, NBC's now-runaway
cable channel success, which by the end of this year is expected to
generate earnings in the range of $400 million, becoming the most
profitable media property owned by the General Electric Co. Those
media properties include, of course, the far more heavily watched
NBC broadcast network.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Goodman, president of CNN's sales and marketing
operations, said that advertiser demand for financial programming
has been ``huge, and it has grown at a faster rate than even the
media marketplace at large, which is hard to imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN, recognizing the growth potential _ and the blistering
profit pace being set by CNBC _ tried to expand its position in
this market by starting CNNfn, a competing all-financial-news
network, in December 1995. Dobbs, already managing all of CNN's
financial news coverage, was also put in charge of that network as
president. His leadership role at CNNfn was another reason his
departure raised concerns about the future of CNN's financial news
operations.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``Moneyline,'' it has been such a favorite with
households with incomes above $75,000 a year that its
cost-per-thousand price to advertisers, or CPM in industry jargon,
the basic measurement of the true value of a show to advertisers,
is among the best in all of television.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said that by the network's reckoning, the cost per
thousand for ``Moneyline'' is higher than that of any other
news-based program on any network _ including all the prime-time
network news magazine programs. Goodman did not disclose what the
specific price was, but he added that ``as far as we can tell, the
CPM's are second only to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said that he and many other CNN executives were shocked
last week to hear that Dobbs was leaving. But he added: ``Are
advertisers canceling? No. No one has said I don't want to be in
`Moneyline' as a result of the change.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said that while Dobbs was an important part of how well
``Moneyline'' was doing, ``agencies and advertisers recognize
people are tuning into lots of CNN financial programs, some Lou
hosted and some he didn't. The ratings are good; the income profile
is good. The audience characteristics are not unique to
`Moneyline.' They are unique to CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gralnick, executive vice president for CNN financial news,
said that ratings for ``Moneyline'' in the first three days last
week after Dobbs left were holding exactly at the level they had
been. ``It's going to be interesting to see what the brand is in
`Moneyline,' period,'' Gralnick said.
</P>
<P>
   But Peter Chrisanthopoulos, president for broadcast and
programming in the United States of the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide
ad agency, which has clients like American Express and IBM that
have been frequent advertisers on ``Moneyline,'' said: ``The
ratings will be impacted somewhat; that's inevitable when the face
on a program changes. Viewers tune in not just for content but also
for the individual who delivers the content.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that ``CNBC has good-quality business programming on at
the same hour. I do expect some erosion on CNN. That's why the
choice of a replacement for Dobbs is so crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Gralnick said of CNN's plans to replace Dobbs: ``We're in no
hurry. Getting the right host is important. But the worst thing we
can do is leap into anything. The mandate is to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   More important in the long term for CNN may be the ability of
CNNfn to grow enough to compete with CNBC. At the moment, the
competition is one-sided. CNBC is on 24 hours a day and reaches
more than 68 million homes. CNNfn is on 18 hours a day and reaches
just over 12 million homes.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bolster, the president of CNBC, said of CNNfn: ``If they
don't have enough scale, they won't have impact. CNBC is about
impact, not ratings. And in terms of financial news, does a cable
operator have to have two networks? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Gralnick said that Ted Turner, the founder of CNN and now vice
chairman of its parent company, Time Warner, ``has made growing the
distribution for CNNfn the primary goal of the company for this
year and next.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that CNNfn should move to 24-hour-a-day status by
September.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it can catch up to CNBC, however, remains a serious
question, and Dobbs' departure was widely regarded as a setback to
that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Gralnick said, ``If Lou's departure hurries the effort to add
distribution, it could end up being a good thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      06-13 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM NEGOTIATOR'S TESTIMONY HITS MICROSOFT HARD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The testimony last week of Garry Norris of IBM supplied some of
the most absorbing moments so far in the Microsoft trial. His
litany of accusations was lengthy and specific _ threats and
enticements to not compete against the Microsoft Corp. delivered at
meeting after meeting. His charges were fleshed out with the dates,
places and names, and backed up by his handwritten notes.
</P>
<P>
   Norris, who negotiated with Microsoft on behalf of IBM's
personal computer business from 1995 to 1997, was the first
representative of a PC maker to testify for the government. David
Boies, the lead trial lawyer for the Justice Department, said the
Norris testimony put a ``vivid human face'' on what he called
``some of the most important evidence in the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet antitrust experts say that the Norris testimony was not a
knockout punch on its own and that its legal power may hinge on
earlier testimony, in closed sessions, on the prices Microsoft
charges PC makers for its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Big, powerful and itself long a target of government antitrust
suits, IBM was an imperfect object of sympathy as the
representative witness for PC makers. Ever since IBM selected
Microsoft to supply the operating system for the first IBM PC in
1981, IBM has been out-hustled and outsmarted by Microsoft in the
PC business _ not the sort of behavior the nation's antitrust laws
were meant to prohibit.
</P>
<P>
   The government, of course, had recognized that IBM's size, reach
and complicated history with Microsoft could be used by Microsoft's
lawyers to try to undercut its contentions. For months, the Justice
Department had urged other major computer makers to take the stand
_ and it pushed particularly hard for Ted Waitt, the chairman of
Gateway Inc., who ultimately decided against it.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's defense, antitrust experts say, may be that IBM was
told it would pay a higher price for Windows unless it agreed to
``reduce, drop or eliminate'' shipments of OS/2, IBM's competing
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, such an invitation to a competitor to reduce
competition would be an antitrust violation, even if the offer were
rejected. But the legal standard in such cases, established in a
1984 ruling involving American Airlines, is that the evidence be
``uniquely unequivocal'' _ in the airline case, the evidence was a
tape-recorded offer to jointly raise fares.
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft, there is no such clear-cut evidence. The
contract proposals presented in court were a series of suggested
discounts on the price of Windows if IBM agreed to certain
promotion and marketing efforts on behalf of Windows. No Microsoft
contract offer, Norris conceded, stated specifically that IBM must
``drop or eliminate'' OS/2. But he insisted that the overall effect
of the Microsoft terms would be to ``kill OS/2 in the markeplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, antitrust experts note, it is certainly legal for
Microsoft to offer a distributor _ as the IBM PC business was _
incentives to aggressively distribute its product. If accepting
those incentives means featuring Microsoft's Windows over OS/2 _
made by another unit of IBM _ that is mainly a business decision
for IBM to make, they say. IBM turned down the Microsoft proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A shrewdly devised offer by Microsoft perhaps, but antitrust
experts say it was probably not a violation. ``It will be very
difficult for the government to prevail on the OS/2 allegations,''
said William Kovacic, a law professor at George Washington
University.
</P>
<P>
   The Norris testimony, however, went well beyond the OS/2 charge.
He asserted that Microsoft repeatedly offered IBM better terms and
prices for Windows if it favored Microsoft products ranging from
so-called office productivity applications to its Internet browsing
software. When IBM rejected those proposals, Norris said, Microsoft
charged IBM more for Windows than it charged other major PC makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strongest Norris testimony was when he recounted the
incidents of IBM not using other Microsoft software and then
getting punished on the price of Windows,'' said Robert Litan of
the Brookings Institution, who is a former senior official in the
Justice Department's antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft insists there is no evidence that IBM paid a higher
price for Windows than its competitors. The exception was the
Compaq Computer Corp., which received a significantly lower price,
Microsoft says, because it shared in the costs of developing
Windows 95 _ a straightforward business rationale for different
terms, says Microsoft, not punishment meted out by a monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   But the government introduced an IBM document that cast doubt on
Microsoft's statement. The document, an internal memo, said IBM
believed it paid $5 to $15 more for each copy of Windows it loaded
on its machines than did Compaq, Hewlett-Packard or Dell Computer.
``IBM,'' the May 1997 document stated, ``currently pays a higher
royalty than our leading competitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the detailed, company-by-company information on the
prices to makers for Microsoft's industry-standard Windows
operating system was submitted in previous testimony. To protect
confidential commercial information, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
took that testimony in closed sessions.
</P>
<P>
   If the industry pricing information shows that IBM was paying
more than comparable PC makers, the Norris testimony may add more
legal ammunition to the government's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent the Norris testimony fits into the pattern of
Microsoft threats and punishment, it is another piece in the
puzzle,'' Litan, the former Justice Department official, said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
