   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MAINE _ On an off day in Kennebunkport, we talk to the
locals about the prospects of a second stint as the summer White
House; will the down easters have to fight with Athens, Texas for
that honor? Bush owns a lake home there. The mayor says the town is
ready to expand the airport to accommodate Marine One, if
necessary. (Greenberger, Austin American-Statesman). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Story will be filed by 7 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH-HEATWAVE _ ATLANTA _ Record highs have touched 100 degrees
in recent days in Cary, N.C. Substantial rain hasn't fallen for
weeks. Still, computer programmer Robert Bonham doesn't worry about
running out of water. His grass might turn brown, but that's more a
nuisance than a crisis. ``The expectation is that I pay for water
like I pay for cable. I expect it to work,'' Bonham said. ``I won't
think about it unless we get to a point where there's so much
growth the city can't deliver it.'' It's almost reached that point
in Cary and other fast-growing areas of the Deep South _ not just
because of an early season drought but also because of a decade of
intense growth and development. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KIDNAP-SELL _ Convicted kidnapper Stephen Fagan has put his
house on the market for $3.5 million. (Gelormine, Palm Beach Daily
News) MOVED. ATTN: Massachusetts
</P>
<P>
   STUDENT-LOANS _ DAYTON, Ohio _ After the caps and gowns have
been returned, the parties thrown and the rejection letters thrown
away, the real business of being a would-be college student begins.
Call it Economics 101: Footing the Bill. A discussion of student
loan options with Web site and contact information. (Townsend,
Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
