<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina) _ Russian soldiers continued to occupy
Pristina airport Sunday, blocking the entry of British troops, in
an embarrassing impasse for NATO's nascent peacekeeping effort.
While Clinton discussed the stalement with Yeltsin by telephone,
British officers fumed in private that the place they had picked
for their headquarters had been confiscated by interlopers.
Commanders spent much of the day, without apparent success,
searching for an alternative location. There was no triumphal news
conference on the airport tarmac, as had been expected, by Gen.
Wesley Clark, the NATO commander. British paratroopers shot a Serb
policeman dead Sunday afternoon, after he fired gunshots near one
of their patrols. In Prizren, to the south, German troops came
under sniper fire, then killed a Serb as he tried to attack them in
a battered yellow car. Even as the peacekeepers began to enter
Pristina, departing Serbs torched Albanian houses and a mosque near
the city center. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Pristina) _ An enormous column of Serb civilians
followed their army and police out of western Kosovo on Sunday,
moving slowly on the narrow roads past a column of Italian troops
and armor moving the other way, toward Pec and Prizren. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GOLAN (Dateline TK) _ The settlers in Golan appear
willing to put the interests of the country ahead of their own, and
leave if that is what it takes to have peace. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   HAIR-DRUGTEST (New Orleans) _ De La Salle High School, a
parochial school, is one of a handful of schools around the country
that tests for student drug use by taking hair samples. The testing
has been a big success at De La Salle, with parents almost
unanimously in favor of it. Now, two public school principals want
hair testing at their schools. The ACLU, among others, is opposed.
By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTERS-BIOLOGY (San Francisco) _ In a world where computers
were once casual and isolated tools, but are today increasingly the
very fabric of modern business life, computer researchers say they
are detecting an ominous trend toward programs that mimic viruses
and pestilence in the physical world. Like biological diseases,
which exploit the most basic mechanism of life: the power of DNA to
replicate itself, the subculture of modern virus writing is now
manipulating that same power within the world of interconnected
computers. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MALE-AUPAIRS (New York) _ Male au pairs are becoming more
common, as English girls refuse to come here in the wake of the
Louise Woodward case. By Lisa Foderaro.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON (Purchase, N.Y.) _ A look at Larry Johnson
and his injured knee; he may not play until Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   QWEST-USWEST-FRONTIER (Undated) _ Making the brashest
telecommunications move in years, Qwest Communications
International Inc., a young, high-flying communications carrier,
said Sunday that it was making an unsolicited $55 billion bid to
acquire U S West, Inc., the old Baby Bell local phone giant, and
the Frontier Corp., one of the nation's biggest long-distance
companies. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
