<HEADER>
A3567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STANDOFF-0614-     06-13 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STANDOFF-0614-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TENSE STAND-OFF GREETS US TROOPS' ARRIVAL IN KOSOVO
 &HT;    400&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN; KOSOVO-ALBANIANS.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERLI PRELEZ, Yugoslavia _ American troops, probably the most
vilified among the NATO peacekeepers by Kosovo's bitter ethnic
Serbs, finally began their official peacekeeping mission in Kosovo
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   And on a day filled with tense moments between NATO and
Serb-dominated Yugoslav troops throughout the war-torn province,
American paratroopers were barely two hours into their mission
before a brief, but tense stand-off ensued.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 members of the 82nd Airborne out of Fort Bragg, N.C.,
had landed in this southern Kosovo village to begin establishing
the American operations base of Kosovo Force (KFOR), when an
obviously drunken Serb soldier got out of a bus carrying a
Russian-made Kalashnikov and threatening to fire at them.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans had blocked the Serb troops' planned exit road
toward Yugoslavia to make way for nine M1A1 battle tanks coming
around the next bend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to . . . kill them all,'' the Yugoslav soldier
yelled as he approached the newly established American checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   Before the stunned paratroopers could draw their weapons, the
unnamed Serb soldier was seized and disarmed by other Serbs who ran
out from the convoy. One of them yelled out, ``Don't . . . shoot
because they'll . . . kill us all.''
</P>
<P>
   After a tense five-minute discussion between American sentries,
led by Sgt. 1st Class Mladem Fulir, and the Serb convoy commander,
the convoy carrying about 300 heavily armed Serb troops -- waving
obscene gestures and looking stone-faced -- turned around and took
a longer route toward the Yugoslav border.
</P>
<P>
   It was Fulir, 40, a cigar-chomping Croatian American doubling as
translator and lead sentry, who ordered the convoy in Serbian
either to give up its weapons or turn around.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very lucky,'' Fulir said later.
</P>
<P>
   Though heavily outgunned on the ground, the American
paratroopers were protected overhead by two Apache helicopters that
circled the convoy as it passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little better than we thought it was going to be,''
said Sgt. Kendall Holse, 30, of Amarillo, Texas. ``We were prepared
for the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The paratroopers helicoptered in on Blackhawk choppers ahead of
Alpha Company of the 2nd Battalion, 505th Parachute Infantry
Regiment, as the advance element in the American sector, setting up
camp on the road between the towns of Urosevac and Pozaranje.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   When Brigadier General John Craddock's helicopter touched down
in this wheat field 20 miles south of the provincial capital
Pristina, some local villagers cheered and others wept tears of
gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to over-dramatise it,'' said Craddock, but there
was no mistaking the joy of the Kosovars, who chanted ``USA!'' and
``Thank you'' and rushed to shake the general's hand.
</P>
<P>
   After a 30-minute briefing on Jerli Prelez the general walked
out to greet about 100 ethnic Albanian residents of the village,
many of whom said they had not been out of their houses for three
weeks out of fear of Serb atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very happy because the Serb criminals are going
home forever,'' said Avni Rejebi, 27, a professional soccer player
from the nearby village of Tankovic. Craddock's arrival marks the
start of the official Kosovo presence of the United States, which
flew 80 percent of the sorties in the 11-week NATO air war on
Yugoslavia but enters the embattled province a day after its
European allies.
</P>
<P>
   Some 400 American troops were to be here by the end of the day
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
