<HEADER>
A3570 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MALE-AUPAIRS-ART-830(     06-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALE-AUPAIRS-ART-830(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PARENTS ARE NOW CHOOSING MALE AU PAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSSINING, N.Y. _ When Michael Aitchison and his wife, the Rev.
Claire Woodley-Aitchison, began looking for child care after
arriving in Westchester County a few years ago, they thought about
getting an au pair from overseas. They assumed it would be a young
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly wanted girls,'' Aitchison said. ``We tried all
the tricks. It wasn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the couple's three young boys were a tough
sell, and the best candidates politely declined. Then, through
``chance, default or an act of God,'' as Ms. Woodley-Aitchison, an
Episcopal priest, put it, they found Jais, a young man from
Denmark, and they have had male au pairs since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a testosterone zone, and it takes a very special
woman to survive in a household of men, especially if you're not
related to them,'' she said. ``With three boys, having male au
pairs made so much sense. They were able to match my sons' energy
level and show them the ropes.''
</P>
<P>
   While they are still the exception, male au pairs are emerging
as a child-care alternative in suburbs and cities across the United
States. Often inspired by a sister's previous experience, the men
are interested in becoming au pairs for many of the same reasons
that women are: adventure, a chance to improve their English and
the opportunity to experience American culture firsthand and on the
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   For the families, young men make good role models for boys and
willing companions in such pursuits as climbing trees and finding
frogs. And their presence can send a subtle message to boys and
girls, parents say, about gender roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my kids to grow up thinking that only women care
for children,'' said Jennifer Crewe, a publishing executive who
lives in New York City with her husband, two sons and a male au
pair from Poland. ``I want them to know that both men and women can
do both sorts of things.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is still small, with fewer than 500 male au pairs
nationally among the half-dozen agencies approved by the federal
government to supply au pairs. But agency officials report that the
numbers of male au pairs have risen steadily in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years ago we had no male au pairs, but now we have families
who request them, and the numbers have been increasing every year
for the last few years,'' said Paul Christianson, director of Au
Pair USA, a division of the nonprofit organization InterExchange in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Au Pair USA currently has 150 male au pairs from 19 countries
out of a total network of 1,500 au pairs. Christianson said that
because there were so many more men from other countries interested
in becoming au pairs here than there were spaces available, the
pool of men was especially strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have to sell male au pairs,'' he said. ``We could
probably have two or three times the number of male au pairs if the
demand was there. As a result our standards are infinitely more
scrupulous with the selection of male au pairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Agencies have started to promote young men as an option for
families partly out of necessity. Since 1997, when the British au
pair Louise Woodward was convicted of second-degree murder, the
once-abundant supply of au pairs from Great Britain has largely
dried up, and agency officials have scrambled to fill the vacuum.
They have turned to countries like South Africa, Brazil, Poland and
Japan to recruit young women _ and men.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge for us is that families have a
preconceived notion of what an au pair is _ Scandinavian, tall,
blond,'' said Heidi Woehl, director of Au Pair Care in San
Francisco. ``But now you might have a Mexican au pair or a Czech au
pair.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the mid-1980s tens of thousands of au pairs from overseas
have cared for children through a program regulated by the U.S.
Information Agency. Initially, the agencies were allowed to recruit
only from Western Europe, but the program was recently expanded to
include any country with which the United States has diplomatic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   The program, in which women and men between the ages of 18 and
26 are in the United States for one year on a special visa, was
intended to provide both affordable child care and a cultural
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Families pay an upfront fee of $4,000 to $5,000 a year to cover
health insurance and travel expenses. The au pairs are paid a
weekly stipend, typically $140 to $160, and they are not to work
more than 45 hours a week or more than 10 hours a day. Their
primary responsibility is to care for children, which includes
preparing meals, doing laundry and keeping the children's rooms
tidy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the number of au pairs in the United States at
any given time has fluctuated between 11,000 and 13,000, with
12,000 projected for this year. A big change has occurred in the
number of British au pairs, which dropped to 882 in 1997 from 2,115
the year before, according to the U.S. Information Agency. The
agency does not track the number of male au pairs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Male au pairs say they get double-takes from Americans who
cannot believe any young man would want to spend his days running
after toddlers or folding laundry. Depending on where they are
from, the men can get equally strong reactions from friends and
families back home.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Schjerning, an au pair from Denmark who cares for an
11-year-old boy with cerebral palsy in Croton-on-Hudson, said his
Danish friends ``accepted it'' and did not make a fuss. But for
Inaki Gorraiz of Spain, a former soccer goalie with rugged features
who cares for a 9-year-old girl and a 6-year-old boy in northern
Westchester, the reaction at home was very different.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends were amazed,'' he recalled. ``A couple of people I
know said, `Are you gay?' I said, `Of course not.' I thought it was
so stupid. Anyone can take care of children if they like them.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gorraiz, 23, the decision to be an au pair for a year was,
in the long run, a way to realize his dream of studying film at the
University of California at Los Angeles. He needs to improve his
English to gain admission to the program, and his young charges are
helping him do that. (He also happens to love children, he says,
and had experience baby-sitting in Spain.)
</P>
<P>
   The other day, he and the 9-year-old, Elizabeth Migliorelli,
were watching ``Willie Wonka and the Chocolate Factory'' together,
and she explained the meaning of several unfamiliar words. He, in
turn, helps her fine-tune her soccer skills. ``He's a great goalie,
he's fun to play with and he doesn't cheat,'' she said after giving
Gorraiz a high-five during a skirmish with her brother.
</P>
<P>
   The growing number of male applicants to the U.S. au pair
program reflects the greater acceptance of male involvement in
child rearing in some European countries, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a deliberate effort to include male staff as part of
early childhood programs in Scandinavia, France and Belgium,'' said
Dr. Sheila Kamerman, a professor in the School of Social Work at
Columbia University who does comparative research on family issues
in industrialized countries. ``They think it's important for young
children to be exposed to males as well as females.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the United States, one lingering concern is the
possibility of sexual abuse, agency officials and parents say. In
1993, a male au pair from Germany pleaded guilty to sexually
molesting an 8-year-old Massachusetts boy. Last year the agency
that had placed him, Au Pair in America, in Greenwich, Conn., paid
a settlement to the family after a civil suit. The agency no longer
recruits men.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents say that having a female care giver does not
insulate them from tragedy, as illustrated by the case of Ms.
Woodward, whose conviction in the death of 8-month-old Matthew
Eappen was reduced to manslaughter. Other parents acknowledge the
possibility of abuse by young men but say they are alert to signs
of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust my creep factor,'' said Ms. Woodley-Aitchison, who
leads sexual misconduct awareness workshops for the Episcopal
Diocese of New York. Her husband, a psychotherapist, also conducts
the workshops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what to look for,'' she said, ``and our guys never
presented any of those signs.''
</P>
<P>
   Christianson of Au Pair USA called pedophilia a ``horrible
mental disease'' but ``very, very rare.'' He added: ``Do we
penalize the entire young male population because of something
that, statistically, is a very remote possibility? I just don't
think it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Aitchisons, couples who have had one male au pair often
become repeat customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families can be a little hesitant about looking at male
applicants but usually once they go with a male, they tend to stick
with men,'' said Shauna Gallegos, executive director of Au Pair
Programme USA in Salt Lake City, an agency that will place 30 male
au pairs this year, up from five in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of male au pairs is putting a new twist on the old
joke about wives who wanted to screen out attractive female au
pairs who might turn their husbands' heads. Morten Kublick, Ms.
Woodley-Aitchison's 23-year-old au pair from Denmark, is a body
builder with blond hair, piercing blue eyes and a cool, calm
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends come over,'' she said, ``and ask, `Oh Claire, how
did you arrange this?' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
