<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the Kosovo-related stories that The New York Times is
planning for Monday, June 14, 1999. The N.Y. Times News Service day
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (Pristina) _ Russian soldiers continued to occupy
Pristina airport Sunday, blocking the entry of British troops, in
an embarrassing impasse for NATO's nascent peacekeeping effort.
While Clinton discussed the stalement with Yeltsin by telephone,
British officers fumed in private that the place they had picked
for their headquarters had been confiscated by interlopers.
Commanders spent much of the day, without apparent success,
searching for an alternative location. There was no triumphal news
conference on the airport tarmac, as had been expected, by Gen.
Wesley Clark, the NATO commander. British paratroopers shot a Serb
policeman dead Sunday afternoon, after he fired gunshots near one
of their patrols. In Prizren, to the south, German troops came
under sniper fire, then killed a Serb as he tried to attack them in
a battered yellow car. Even as the peacekeepers began to enter
Pristina, departing Serbs torched Albanian houses and a mosque near
the city center. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   (With photos, map.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SCENE (Pristina) _ An enormous column of Serb civilians
followed their army and police out of western Kosovo on Sunday,
moving slowly on the narrow roads past a column of Italian troops
and armor moving the other way, toward Pec and Prizren. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TENSION (Prizren) _ Two Serbs in a small yellow car
opened fire Sunday evening on a group of just-arrived German
peacekeepers. The peacekeepers fired back, killing one of the men
and seriously wounding the other in a tense and unsettled second
day of NATO's arrival in Kosovo. The body of the Serb, wearing
civilian clothes, still sat slumped late Sunday night in the
bullet-riddled car facing the barrel of a German tank, a bloody
reminder of the dangers of this peacekeeping mission as it moves
into Kosovo before the heavily-armed Serb troops have moved out. By
Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Prizren) _ In the next three months of Kosovo's
summer, hundreds of thousands of poor Kosovar villagers will cross
from Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro to go home again. But in
these first days of open borders, most are too afraid of
still-retreating Serbs and landmines in the countryside. By
Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Urosevac, Kosovo) _ On the second day of NATO's
operation in Kosovo, American ground troops began to enter province
in force today, but their progress was far from swift and their
control over what will ultimately become the American sector in
southeast Kosovo was anything but ironclad. By day's end, there
were supposed to be nearly 2,000 soldiers and marines in Kosovo,
but the heavy, rumbling convoys left their bases in Macedonia late
and bogged down on the road to Kosovo. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES (Hallac, Yugoslavia) _ A month after refugees
reported that Serb paramilitaries killed 46 people during a two day
rampage through this village and a nearby hamlet in mid-April, a
visit to both sites on Sunday revealed compelling evidence that
mass killings did in fact occur. In this village, a swathe of fresh
digging that appeared to be a mass grave lies feet from a bullet
pocked wall. And in nearby Ribar, twenty-six new graves in the
local cemetery and two dozen burnt houses stand as evidence of some
form of attack. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ Clinton and Yeltsin reached no
agreement on Sunday on the standoff between NATO troops and a small
group of Russian troops in Kosovo but agreed that NATO and Russian
military commanders should meet quickly to try to end the problem,
White House officials said on Sunday. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ The chief negotiators for Russia and
NATO haggled for a fourth day to no avail over how and where
Russian troops would serve in a Kosovo peacekeeping operation. By
Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALLIES (Berlin) _ The Kosovo crisis has brought radical
changes to the European continent: thrusting Germany into a leading
military role not seen since 1945, galvanizing attempts to forge a
common European defense policy, and altering Europe's relationship
with the United States. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JSTARS (Aboard the JSTARS surveillance plane over
Albania) _ This rebuilt Boeing 707 carries the U.S. Air Force's
newest and most advanced system for watching enemy troops from the
air. The system has assumed a key role in both picking targets and
monitoring the peace agreement. Though used experimentally during
the Persian Gulf war, the Joint Surveillance Target Attack Radar
Systems are still so new that the Air Force and Army have only four
of them worldwide _ two of them now in the Balkans. Unlike its
better-known predecessor, the Airborne Warning and Control System,
or AWACS, this system was designed to scrutinize events on the
ground over a wide area.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SWISS (Geneva) _ Fearful of too many refugees flooding
into the country, Swiss voters on Sunday overwhelmingly approved
tighter rules for asylum seekers. Already home to some 180,000
Kosovar Albanians, Switzerland has been experiencing an enormous
influx of refugees fleeing the turbulent province. With arrivals up
by 60 percent over last year at this time, Switzerland is expecting
as many as 60,000 refugees by the year's end, giving it the highest
number per inhabitant in Europe. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SUVA (Suva Reka) _ This is the most ruined town in
Kosovo, an ethnic Albanian city where, before this war began in
late March, the Kosovo Liberation Army was strong and Serb police
rarely entered. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
