<HEADER>
A3573 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FALLING-TV-STARS-ART-     06-13 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALLING-TV-STARS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV BUSINESS ASKS: WHERE HAVE ALL THE BIG STARS GONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television has more channels than ever before, more prime-time
shows than ever before and, of course, more commercials than ever
before. And yet, to the consternation of many television industry
executives, the one thing it seems to have fewer of is one of the
most essential commodities of the business: stars.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, television seems to have smaller stars than
it once had. In interviews with executives from networks, studios
and talent agencies, the list of names that were consensus choices
as unquestioned television stars of the magnitude of some of the
names of the past _ even the not-all-that-distant past of five
years ago, the era of Jerry Seinfeld, Tim Allen and Roseanne _ was
remarkably short. It basically began and ended with one name:
Calista Flockhart of Fox's hit ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons range from the spread of the television audience
over an increasing number of channels to the networks' strategy of
targeting specific age and gender groups.
</P>
<P>
   The falloff in widely recognized, mass-appeal stars has some
serious implications for the television business, more than the
problems it causes for TV Guide magazine, whose editors admit a
certain desperation in trying to find 52 stars a year for their
covers. (The magazine has gone so far afield lately in its
starvation hunt for identifiable TV names that it put the cast of
``Star Wars'' and the Latin singer Ricky Martin on two covers in
the past month, though neither has much of anything to do with
television.)
</P>
<P>
   For broadcast networks, which continue to market themselves as
the one source for advertisers to achieve mass reach, the faces and
names of stars are at the center of marketing strategies. In his
first executive change, Garth Ancier, the new president of NBC
Entertainment, added a new head of casting for the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think a great part of the identification of a network is
the faces of its stars,'' Ancier said. ``They represent your
network and create your brand. They're all important.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet there does not appear in the networks' current roster to
be a host of likely successors to Seinfeld, who left his NBC comedy
last season, and Allen, who wrapped up his hit comedy, ``Home
Improvement,'' last month for Walt Disney's ABC _ and no one in the
same universe of appeal as icons like Lucille Ball, Jackie Gleason,
Mary Tyler Moore and the Bill Cosby of the 1980s (though the Bill
Cosby of today remains perhaps the biggest name still working in
prime time).
</P>
<P>
   One clear indication of the decline in recognizability of
today's television stars is the so-called ``TV Q'' poll, conducted
by Marketing Evaluations Inc. Stars are ranked in this poll based
on both popularity and familiarity. In the latter category,
television stars have recorded a sharp drop-off in scores over the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, for example, the top 25 female television performers
averaged a 68 percent familiarity score. By this year that number
fell to just 50 percent. Among male performers, the top 25 had a
score of 70 as recently as 1996. This year it is down to 58.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're talking about the kind of star who could not walk
through Times Square without stopping traffic,'' said Alan Berger,
the executive vice president of the television division of the
International Creative Management talent agency, ``I really don't
think many of today's stars would qualify.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger emphasized today's stars because he acknowledged that
Cosby remains a star of enormous recognition and popularity, and
Michael J. Fox of ABC's ``Spin City'' is another completely
familiar and popular figure. Other stars on their second or third
go-rounds of stardom (all, not coincidentally, at CBS, the network
that trades most heavily in stars from the past) include Ted
Danson, Don Johnson and Dick Van Dyke.
</P>
<P>
   But all of these performers owe their stardom much more to their
previous work than their current work. Johnson, in fact, is often
cited as the kind of white hot star of a generation ago, when he
was in ``Miami Vice,'' that is rarely if ever generated today.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of the network late-night entertainment shows have
also detected for some time that, as one executive producer put it,
``The number of stars who will move the needle of the ratings has
dwindled drastically.'' And among the few stars that do have an
impact on the ratings, he said, virtually none is a current
television star.
</P>
<P>
   So where have all the big stars gone? More than anything, they
have gone the same way the big hit shows have gone: to smaller fame
in smaller arenas. David Poltrack, the executive vice president of
research for CBS, said the entire scale of television had to be
reduced, based on declines in network viewing percentages. He
pointed out that hit shows of the past reached 30 to 40 percent of
the viewing audience. Now a show is a hit if it reaches 15 to 18
percent of the audience. And shows on one new network, WB, are
being called hits when they reach only about 5 percent of the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than the overall reduction in what constitutes a
hit-sized audience, it is the willingness and even the desire of
some networks to seek only a small slice of the total viewing pie
that is contributing to what one talent agency executive called the
``Honey I Shrunk the Stars'' trend in television.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is best exemplified by WB, owned by Time Warner and
Tribune Co., which limits its viewing targets to the audience
between the ages of 12 and 24. WB stars like Sarah Michelle Gellar
of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' Katie Holmes of ``'Dawson's
Creek'' and Keri Russell of ``Felicity'' are enormously popular
with female teen-agers, for example. But many adults would have no
idea who they are.
</P>
<P>
   That's fine as far as WB executives are concerned because they
have willingly defined themselves as a network with a narrow goal:
Be a hit with the young. ``When you have niche networks, you're
going to have niche stars,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said this limitation had an impact on the other end of
the age spectrum at CBS, which has numerous shows with big overall
ratings but a large percentage of viewers over 50 years old. That
drastically limits the number of performers whom non-CBS executives
would identify as true wide-appeal stars.
</P>
<P>
   Ancier said that Roma Downey, the star of ``Touched By an
Angel''(who happens to have one of the highest current Q-scores of
any female star on television), was not quite in the big star
firmament because so many younger people would not be able to
identify her.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Ancier said, Ray Romano, the star of one of the
biggest comedies on television, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' cannot
be ``called a big star, though he's talented enough to be one.''
The reason, he said, is that CBS' audience is so dominated by older
viewers that Romano is not as widely popular as he might be.
</P>
<P>
   Of course Romano, a family man, does not get his name bounced
around in the entertainment tabloids either. Along with Dennis
Franz, star of ABC's ``NYPD Blue,'' he is what Berger called ``a
regular guy.'' That can impede stardom a bit, for as Ancier put it,
``Part of being a star is having some mystery about you.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors in the star drought that are cited by
networks and studio executives:
</P>
<P>
   _ The prevalence of news magazines. There are 12 prime-time news
hours on the air every week, which takes away hours that could be
filled with star-driven shows. Of course the news magazines do have
some stars of their own, including some iconic figures like Barbara
Walters and Diane Sawyer.
</P>
<P>
   _ The surge in animated shows. Next season there will be six on
the air. Needless to say, these do not create stars in the
traditional sense, though Ancier argued that ``Bart Simpson is one
of the most recognizable faces in the world; so is Homer.'' But
Nancy Cartwright and Dan Castellaneta, who speak the words for
those characters, go through their daily lives unacknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   _ The near endless coverage of every move a new star makes in
magazines and on television magazine shows like ``Entertainment
Tonight'' and ``Access Hollywood.'' One talent agency executive
suggested that ``the public goes through stars faster than ever
before and then gets sick of them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The trend, of more than 10 years, toward what is known as the
``ensemble show'' and away from what is called the ``single-star
vehicle.'' At least 20 network series could be called ensemble
shows. ``It's always harder for a star to emerge from an
ensemble,'' Berger said. ``George Clooney did it. But it's hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney burst out of the hit NBC drama ``E.R.'' as a star of
national stature. This was certainly confirmed when he signed on to
play the lead in the ``Batman'' movie series. But ``E.R.'' allowed
him to reach the biggest and most representative audience in
television.
</P>
<P>
   A WB star, James Van Der Beek of ``Dawson's Creek,'' had a movie
success more typical of today's television stars. His movie,
``Varsity Blues,'' was a box office hit, yet all the executives
interviewed for this article agreed that Van Der Beek had not yet
come near broad star status, because the same smallish audience
that watched his television show went to see the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``To build a star out you have to put him in a movie where he
plays a different role,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble of six actors in NBC's hit comedy ``Friends'' have
certainly made it to wide national recognition, most of the
executives said. But that group consciously marketed themselves as
a group from the beginning _ and they may be individually less
celebrated because of it.
</P>
<P>
   One reason why Calista Flockhart had such wide support as an
unquestioned television star is precisely because her show is a
star vehicle _ the title is her character's name. It is, thus, a
show about her.
</P>
<P>
   But another reason may be Ms. Flockhart's ascension to one
traditional Pantheon of universal television stardom: the cover of
Time magazine. With Seinfeld gone, Ms. Flockhart is alone among the
new crop of television stars with that achievement, though in her
case it has less to do with her star power than with what the
character has come to represent. Still, even on the Time cover, it
was Ally McBeal who appeared (along with Susan B. Anthony and Betty
Friedan), representing some form of postfeminist icon. Ms.
Flockhart's face might have been there, but her name was not.
</P>
<P>
   But even the near stars and niche stars of today's television
shows are turning up monthly on numerous magazine covers. That is
partly a function of their being always more identifiable than the
latest cover model, and partly a function of the stratification
that is taking place in all media. One television studio executive
said that television was becoming more and more like music radio.
``Each music genre has its own station,'' the executive said.
``That's the direction television is going toward.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Ms. Flockhart, the group of performers most industry
executives cited as the top level of stardom in television today
included names like Drew Carey and Jenna Elfman of the ABC comedies
``The Drew Carey Show'' and ``Dharma and Greg''; Kelsey Grammer of
``Frasier'' and the six-member cast of ``Friends'' on General
Electric's NBC; and David Duchovny and Gillian Anderson, stars of
``The X-Files'' on Fox, a subsidiary of News Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jenna Elfman is sort of a typical star of today's
television,'' said one senior executive at a talent agency. ``She's
like an almost-star. She might get there someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
