<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOMMERCE-SPEED-500&AMP;A     06-13 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOMMERCE-SPEED-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPING A BETTER LANGUAGE FOR WEB TRANSACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word NUMBER in parentheses has been used in the 4th graf
instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper
systems.) 
(lb) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aiming to make shopping on the Web easier, a consortium of
credit-card companies, Internet merchants and developers of online
payment technologies plans to announce on Monday that its members
have agreed to develop a standard for executing electronic commerce
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The standard, known as electronic commerce modeling language,
will eventually enable consumers to buy from multiple Web sites
without re-entering data like a name, shipping address or
credit-card number. The coding of so-called electronic wallet
software will store such customer information on a secure server
and is intended to pass the data to different merchants' Web sites
with fewer problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an important first step,'' Ken Cassar, digital
commerce analyst for the Internet research firm Jupiter
Communications, said. ``A lot more needs to be done, but the
parties who've joined in are pretty much the ones you'd want.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, electronic wallet technologies have faltered because
the coding used by merchants to format checkout pages has varied
widely. For instance, the code used to indicate a consumer's
credit-card number could begin with ``CC(NUMBER)'' in some cases,
and ``CN'' in others. The wallets were sometimes unable to
recognize the variations, and thus could not work with many sites.
As a result, consumers have generally ignored the wallet companies.
</P>
<P>
   That situation will change, according to the electronic commerce
consortium, which includes America Online, Microsoft, Dell
Computer, Compaq Computer, Visa USA, IBM, Sun Microsystems,
Mastercard International and American Express, as well as a host of
Internet merchants and electronic wallet providers.
</P>
<P>
   Once merchants can essentially speak the same language, wallet
companies will be able to offer consumers the prospect of one-click
checkout across many sites.
</P>
<P>
   Such a feature could increase Internet sales substantially,
since customers often bail out of transactions rather than go
through several time-consuming steps to complete a purchase. In
February, a report by Jupiter found that 27 percent of online
buyers abandoned their orders before checkout for that reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be particularly important for attracting new
customers,'' said John Pettitt, chief technology officer for
Beyond.com, a software retailer. ``Every time you ask a customer to
do something, you risk losing them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitt said Beyond.com offered one-click checkout to America
Online customers who had signed up for its Quick Checkout
electronic wallet, and he said the feature had ``been very
successful for us.'' Aside from that, however, he said Beyond.com
had declined to do business with other companies that offer
electronic wallets, like Cybercash and Transactor Networks,
``because they don't have a critical mass of users.''
</P>
<P>
   One reason for that lack of critical mass is that consumers see
little reason to sign up with an electronic wallet company that
does not have a large number of merchant partners.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   According to Cassar of Jupiter, electronic wallet companies have
made little headway until now in part because they have had to
persuade retailers to format their sites to conform to their
particular wallet technology. The hope has been to sign up enough
retailers to become the de facto standard and thereby consolidate
the market. ``But instead they've Balkanized the market,'' Cassar
said.
</P>
<P>
   At stake for wallet companies is not only the potential to
charge a fee for each transaction processed, but also the
opportunity to gather valuable consumer data. ``If I've got a
wallet company and I build a list of 100,000 names and addresses of
people who've bought from Barnesandnoble.com, that's pretty
valuable,'' Cassar said.
</P>
<P>
   While the electronic commerce consortium's agreement on how to
define data overcomes one hurdle in the effort to spread the use of
electronic wallets, the use of consumer data represents a far more
thorny issue. The wallet companies say they will protect consumers'
privacy. But there are others who might object to such gathering of
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm a merchant who competes with Barnesandnoble.com, I'm
not going to be happy about a wallet company selling that
information to a competitor,'' Cassar said.
</P>
<P>
   Since credit-card companies already sell lists along those
lines, he added, they will probably resist any efforts on the part
of wallet companies to compete on that front, as could portals like
America Online, which can use such information to deliver more
advertisements to highly specific audiences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
