<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARMINA-BURANA-2NDTAK     06-13 0194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARMINA-BURANA-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: more contradiction.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orff never joined the Nazi Party, although he cooperated with it
to survive. For example, he accepted a commission to write a
replacement score for ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' by Mendelssohn,
whose work was banned because he had been Jewish. The initial Nazi
response to ``Carmina Burana'' was negative: officials condemned it
as pornographic and derivative of African-American styles. Orff
denied impure intentions, but as the decades have proved, the
work's eroticism and the rhythms that link it to rock lay at the
heart of its appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond whatever conflicts emerge over copyright, the
reverberation of ``Carmina Burana'' through Nas' ``Hate Me Now''
sets one thing right. By linking Orff's work with hip-hop,
African-American culture's latest path to world dominance, ``Hate
Me Now'' has resurrected a latent spirit within this creature.
</P>
<P>
   The crashing tympanies of ``Carmina Burana'' will resonate as
long as rhythm itself continues to define this musical epoch,
connecting Africa to Europe and our own shores. That is not merely
some Gothic reverie; it is a truly universal sound.
</P>
</TEXT>
