<HEADLINE>
U.S. TROOPS ARRIVE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia _ It was only a matter of minutes after
Sgt. 1st Class Mladen Fulir and the rest of his platoon from the
82nd Airborne Division clambered from Black Hawk helicopters when
the confusion and complexity of NATO's initial days of occupation
in Kosovo were cleared.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up a checkpoint on the road east of here, the Americans
first encountered a convoy of Yugoslavian military trucks, escorted
by a Russian armored vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Fulir let it pass, but he stopped a bus full of armed Serb
soldiers that came later, ordering them to hand over their weapons
or turn around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave them the choice,'' said Fulir, a Croatian-born
paratrooper still fluent in Serbo-Croatian. And so they left, as
did another truck with three Serb soldiers that arrived at the
rural crossroads soon after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't give you my gun,'' one of the Serbs said teasingly as
he climbed back into the driver's seat, ``because you won't give it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   On the second day of NATO's operation in Kosovo, U.S. ground
troops began to enter the province in force on Sunday, but their
progress was far from swift and their control over what will
ultimately become the American sector in southeast Kosovo was
anything but ironclad.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, there were supposed to be nearly 2,000 soldiers
and marines in Kosovo, but the heavy, rumbling convoys left their
bases in Macedonia late and bogged down on the road to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred marines from the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit
made it only as far the Stankovec 2 refugee camp north of
Macedonia's capital, Skopje, before receiving orders to stay at a
British base there for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders attributed the delays to traffic and the logistical
challenge of moving troops from several NATO allies along the
narrow road that wends its way through the mountainous border with
Kosovo, though German and Dutch forces continued to cross on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Yugoslav troops, still in Kosovo, intermingled with
the peacekeepers in convoys large and small, with soldiers waving
Serbian flags along with AK-47s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They almost seem happy,'' said Sgt. 1st Class John D. Tucker,
a platoon leader of a pair of Bradley armored combat vehicles
making its way to the checkpoint, which for now remains the core of
the American-controlled sector.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO officials here say the Yugoslav forces have, so
far, cooperated with the operation and kept their pledges to
withdraw. By Sunday evening the U.S. troops in Kosovo had
encountered no significant resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Each American going into Kosovo carries a blue card spelling out
the ``rules of engagement'' for whenever troops encounter soldiers
or civilians. The rules say they should use minimum force, only
when NATO forces are directly threatened.
</P>
<P>
   But in a province racked by warfare and ethnic hostilities and
full of weapons, NATO commanders are afraid encounters like those
at the checkpoint could quickly turn violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important we get in there and look formidable and
professional for the community,'' Lt. Col. Bruce Gandy, the
commander of ground forces for the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit,
told officers preparing to send a force of 2,000 marines into
Kosovo early Sunday. ``If we do that, I think it has a capacity to
dissuade any hostile action.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Americans will ultimately control a sector from Urosevac
through Novo Brdo, taking over from French forces who arrived on
the first day. In the beginning the sector will be divided between
Army and marines.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. forces began pouring across the border in Kosovo at
midday Sunday, led by the 82nd Airborne and tanks and other armored
vehicles from the 1st Armored Division. As they drove north, they
passed towns ravaged by President Slobodan Milosevic's campaign
against Kosovo's Albanian majority, including Kacanik, Gabrica and
Urosevac.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of minefields laid by the Serbs were marked off with
yellow tape and warning signs. Along the road, there were also men
wearing uniforms of the Kosovo Liberation Army, as well as clusters
of refugees walking home, but otherwise the towns were deserted.
</P>
<P>
   The scene surprised Lt. Charles Hitchcock, commander of an M1-A1
Abrams tank. ``I didn't think everybody had left,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
