<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-GOLAN-ART-1120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS OF GOLAN HEIGHTS PONDER THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAALE GAMLA, Golan Heights _ After 20 years in this leafy,
peaceful farming collective, Yigal Kipnis has grown quite attached
to the view from his tree-shaded back porch _ terraced hills
undulating down to the Sea of Galilee.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand how hard it would be to give it up, a
home and a life built from scratch in a sparsely populated
wilderness area that Israel seized from Syria during the 1967
Arab-Israeli war and formally annexed in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a civil engineer, Kipnis turned pioneer at the age of
28 when he and his wife, Mira, like thousands of other Israelis,
heeded their government's call to go forth and settle the Golan. It
was an adventure that became a life as they raised four children in
this 60-family collective, while Kipnis tended mango groves and
Mrs. Kipnis taught chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   But as Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak prepares to restart
negotiations with Syria, Kipnis, like many here, seems ready
intellectually, if not emotionally, to consider leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our political interests and our personal interests are at odds
here,'' Kipnis, 49, said. ``And I don't think we can put our
personal interests before the idea of a full peace with Syria. We
hold onto hope that those of us closer to the shores of the Galilee
will be able to stay. But even that is probably not realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprising many Israeli analysts, residents of the Golan Heights
voted overwhelmingly for Barak, even though he had stated clearly
his intention to move forward on peace with Syria. The possible
implications for them were clear, since most analysts say at least
partial withdrawal from the Golan Heights is a precondition for
peace with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   But while no one wants to give up their home, many said they
voted not parochially but as Israelis, concerned about the nation
as a whole. In fact, the Third Way, the party whose single issue
was preserving the Golan, captured only 14.8 percent of the votes
in the Golan itself and, flaming out completely, lost all of its
four seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Yehuda Harel, a Third Way founder who is now a former member of
parliament, said it was his party, and not the issue, that had
failed. ``A total collapse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Israelis as a whole have relegated the issue of the Golan
Heights to the back burner. It barely came up explicitly during the
campaign, as it did in the 1996 elections, when cars throughout the
country carried bumper stickers reading, ``The nation is with the
Golan.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it arose only implicitly as the unspoken second half of
Barak's promise to withdraw troops from southern Lebanon within a
year. Since Syria effectively controls Lebanon, most _ but not all
_ analysts see a safe withdrawal from Lebanon as inevitably linked
to a withdrawal from the Golan, too.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis love the Golan, a beautiful area dotted with dairy
farms, fruit groves, waterfalls and ravines. If it were given up,
the Israelis would also lose their only ski slopes and one of their
few fine wineries.
</P>
<P>
   But eager to see a withdrawal from what is seen as a futile
conflict in Lebanon, where 25 to 30 Israeli soldiers die a year,
many Israelis try not to think too hard about the consequences for
the Golan. Polls show most expect the territory to be given up.
</P>
<P>
   Golan residents resent keenly the link with Lebanon _ even those
who understand it as a diplomatic reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're presenting us as responsible for the deaths in
Lebanon,'' said Orly Feldman, who manages the guest cottages at the
Merom HaGolan kibbutz. ``Instead of blaming the government for not
making a decision on withdrawing from Lebanon, people are blaming
us just for being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the settlers in the West Bank, the Golan settlers, who
number about 18,000, tend to be kibbutznik types. Most are secular
and center or left politically.
</P>
<P>
   A pioneering Zionist spirit drove the original settlers to
transform barren land. In the last 10 years, they have been joined
by thousands of Russian immigrants. Over time, they all have
coexisted with the tightknit Druse community of about 17,000, who
have remained loyal to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   For years, although many Golan settlers believed in making peace
with the Palestinians, they were silent peace supporters because of
the inherent contradiction in their position. They did not support
peace negotiations with Syria, too.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a tranquil zone, free of the rocket attacks that
plague residents of the northern border with Lebanon, they
preferred the existing situation: no active hostilities, if no
peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why rock the boat?'' Harel asked. ``We succeeded in making
something here that is a little better than Israel itself. I never
lock my home. The air is clean. We have a lot of very modern
agriculture and great wildlife. We live in peace with the Druse and
with the religious. We don't have Arabs or ultra-Orthodox, so we
don't have tensions _ except for the looming question of our
fate.''
</P>
<P>
   A historian and an iconoclastic politician, Harel, 64, spoke in
a cafe in Katzrin, the largest town in the Golan. He shared
cappuccino and pastry with Ramona Bar Lev, a longtime friend and
fellow Golan defender.
</P>
<P>
   Although his face is rippled with character and time, his eyes
twinkled and he did not wear his defeat with great melodrama.
Instead, he analyzed.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the electoral failure of the Third Way reflected
its constituents' disappointment with the fact that the Golan party
had joined Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's conservative
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The Third Way's larger failure, he said, was that, as a small
party, it had ended up marginalizing the issue of the Golan, which
is a national concern and not a special interest.
</P>
<P>
   Shrugging, he said he had led a national mobilization on behalf
of the Golan more than once before and he would do so again, when
the time demands it.
</P>
<P>
   Both Harel and Mrs. Bar Lev said the election results were no
reflection on Israelis' concern about the Golan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman's party got only a half percent, and no one says
that means Israel no longer believes in womankind,'' Harel said.
</P>
<P>
   They also discount a recent poll published in the Maariv
newspaper in which 42 percent of Golan residents surveyed said they
were prepared to leave in exchange for a full peace with Syria and
compensation from the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
   ``People cannot say what they will do,'' Mrs. Bar Lev said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Golan residents think it is pointless to worry too
soon and shut out the political talk, assuming they have a future
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, we bury our dead here,'' said Mrs. Feldman,
the kibbutz hotel manager. ``What more can we say?''
</P>
<P>
   She continued: ``I can also add that the subject of leaving has
never come up with my husband or any of my four children. We're not
suppressing it on purpose. But if every two years we started making
evacuation plans, we'd drive ourselves nuts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Druse residents of the Golan _ Arabic speakers who belong to
a sect that is an offshoot of Islam _ do not know what to think
about the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   In Majdal Shams, the largest Druse town in the Golan, Syria lies
on the other side of a rusty chain-link fence that divides both the
town and families. For years, divided families have gathered on
either side to converse across a gulch with loudspeakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that we will only be under Israeli rule for not
much longer,'' said Saleh Ibrahim, 23, a barber at the Salon
Majdal. ``But Barak, Netanyahu _ we don't trust any Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   His customer, Ramia Ibrahim, 19, said: ``If there's peace, Syria
will come. If not, they won't. Either way, we're here.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, Israelis held fast to the credo that the Golan,
from whose heights Syria had once repeatedly shelled Jewish
settlements, was essential for Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when Yitzhak Rabin, the prime minister
assassinated in 1995, and then Shimon Peres, his successor, first
began considering territorial concessions in the Golan, neither
Israelis nor Golan residents were ready to follow them. It seemed
too abrupt a shift in thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Under Netanyahu, official talks with Syria came to a halt,
although he has recently acknowledged holding private negotiations.
The Golan fell off the political map. But rising concern over
Israel's debilitating engagement in Lebanon has produced widening
support among Israeli politicians for the idea that trading land in
the Golan for peace would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Now with Barak, a former general, in command, the public,
including Golan residents, seems more willing to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could not do it in one minute, to change our focus,''
Kipnis said. ``But now we are ready to. It's not fair to say to the
people of Israel, `Don't make peace for Israel because we have a
personal problem with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kipnis said this wistfully, munching on corn on the cob in his
backyard. The personal problem, he added, belongs to his
generation, those who literally tilled the soil. His children, he
said, will move on, the way he moved on from his birthplace.
</P>
<P>
   Harel's Third Way party did leave behind one key contribution to
the cause: a law that calls for a referendum and a parliamentary
majority to approve an Israeli withdrawal from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Standing atop Mount Beltan, surrounded by schoolchildren
visiting an empty army bunker, Harel gazed down at the Syrian
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are years I say the Golan Heights is not for sure,'' he
said, smiling, ``and there are years I say it is not a lost
cause.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
