<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3585 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QWEST-USWEST-FRONTIER     06-13 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QWEST-USWEST-FRONTIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QWEST MAKES   HOSTILE BID FOR U S WEST , ALSO SEEKS FRONTIER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Bermuda)   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Making the brashest telecommunications move in years, Qwest
Communications International Inc., a young, high-flying
communications carrier, said Sunday that it was making a hostile
$55 billion bid to acquire U S West Inc., the old Baby Bell local
phone giant, and the Frontier Corp., one of the nation's biggest
long-distance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest is trying to take U S West and Frontier, formerly
Rochester Telephone, away from one of its main rivals, Global
Crossing Ltd. of Bermuda. Like Qwest, Global Crossing has built a
billion-dollar business in recent years by exploiting the surging
worldwide demand for electronic communications.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, U S West agreed to merge with Global Crossing
in a stock deal that the company then valued at $37 billion.
Frontier agreed to be acquired by Global Crossing in March for
$10.8 billion in stock. Now Qwest wants to win them both.
</P>
<P>
   The Global Crossing-Qwest showdown is just the latest bombshell
in the telecommunications business, which has come to resemble the
railroad and steel industries of a century ago in its ruthless
dashes for assets and market share. For consumers, the whirlwind
means that the companies that deliver their communications links
with the world are changing faces even as they try to offer
integrated bundles of telephone and Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the proposed acquisitions of U S West and Frontier, we
take the next logical step in accelerating our delivery of
Internet-based, broadband communications services to customers,''
said Joseph P. Nacchio, chairman and chief executive of Qwest. In a
statement, he said the proposed deal would create an ``Internet
communications powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming all parts of the deal are completed, Qwest said its
offer represented a 45.8 percent premium over U S West's stock
price on Friday and 35.3 percent over Frontier's stock price.
Global Crossing's stock price, and thus the value of its offer for
U S West, has declined since last month.
</P>
<P>
   Like the last big communications takeover fight, Worldcom's
brassy $36.5 billion victory over British Telecommunications and
GTE in 1997 to acquire MCI Communications, the No. 2 long-distance
carrier, this latest fight underscores the power of young,
fast-moving companies in the face of more sluggish seniors.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the Qwest offer is a sign that deregulation and the
growth of the Internet are only accelerating the pace in the
telecommunications business. Worldcom got its start in the 1980s
and was still considered an upstart when it went after MCI, but
Qwest and Global Crossing did not even exist in their current forms
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest is controlled by Philip Anschutz, the reclusive Denver
tycoon, and emerged from Anschutz's takeover of the Southern
Pacific railroad in 1988. Qwest has used rights-of-way from the
railroad and others to build an advanced nationwide fiber optic
communications network. Global Crossing was founded a few years ago
by Gary Winnick, formerly an associate of the junk-bond financier
Michael Milken at Drexel Burnham Lambert, and is building an
international undersea fiber optic communications system.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies have raised billions of dollars from investors
based on their founders' financial pedigrees and on their ambitious
business plans.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the most valuable communications asset in the world
probably remains the simple copper telephone wires that enter
almost every American home. U S West, which emerged from the
breakup of AT&AMP;T in 1984, controls millions of those wires. Global
Crossing and Qwest each covet that direct link with customers, even
though U S West is growing slower than the other Bells and even
though U S West's 14-state region includes many less-profitable
rural areas in the western United States.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that the Telecommunications Act of 1996 bars the
Baby Bells, including U S West, from selling long-distance services
such as those offered by Global Crossing until they convince
regulators that they have opened their local networks to
competitors. U S West is far away from winning any such case, which
could make the quest for U S West somewhat quixotic.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest's offer would give U S West shareholders Qwest stock
valued at up to $80 for each of their shares. But if Qwest did not
also reach a deal with Frontier, the value would be cut to $78 in
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest would also give Frontier shareholders $20 in cash and
stock valued at up to $55 for each of their shares. Again, if Qwest
did not also reach a deal with U S West, the value of the Frontier
deal would fall to $73 total for each share, from $75. Qwest would
also assume $11.4 billion in U S West and Frontier debt.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, shares of U S West closed at $54.875, up 56.25 cents
on the New York Stock Exchange, and Frontier's shares ended at
$55.4375, down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest's shares, meanwhile, rose $1 in Nasdaq trading, to close
at $44.875, and Global Crossing's shares ended at $50.75, up 25
cents.
</P>
<P>
   No matter whether Global Crossing or Qwest wins U S West, the
combined company will not be allowed to sell long-distance
telephone or data service to U S West's current customers, at least
for now. That is somewhat deflating for Global Crossing, which,
through its deal for Frontier, has wanted to acquire a roughly $100
million long-distance business in U S West territory. But the
regulatory questions could be a concern for Qwest, which is in fact
based in Denver, the same city as U S West.
</P>
<P>
   But propelled by their hard-charging and well-respected chief
executives, both Qwest and Global Crossing seem to be betting that
they can stampede the regulators, that the issue can be finessed or
that U S West will win long-distance approval in the normal course
sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Global Crossing has described themselves as the wet Qwest,
Qwest under the ocean,'' Nacchio said in an interview, ``They have
aspirations to be like us but they're not. We've completed our
nationwide network. They have one cable under the Atlantic.''
</P>
<P>
   Nacchio said he expected to hear from U S West and Frontier
within a few days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is the personality and reputation of those chief executives,
Nacchio of Qwest and Robert Annunziata of Global Crossing, that
could well make the tangle over U S West more rancorous than the
recent fight over Mediaone between AT&AMP;T and the Comcast &UR;  &LR; Corp..
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and Comcast cut a deal that seemed to make everyone
somewhat happy, giving AT&AMP;T control of Mediaone and Comcast up to
two million new cable customers. It may be tougher for Qwest and
Global Crossing to strike a similar arrangement because Nacchio, a
former AT&AMP;T executive, and Annunziata, who built Teleport
Communications Group, one of the early competitors to the Bells in
local markets, both want to step into the ranks of the elite global
communications carriers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
