<HEADLINE>
MORE LINKS FOR THE EXTREME HACKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are enough conventional sites for those
serious about the game of golf. But if you've got a wango tango for
some alternative equipment, sportswear and general celebration of
hacker heaven, sign on here.
</P>
<P>
   The Summer '99 edition of the San Francisco-based magazine
Schwing! (look for Ali Landry on the cover) offers a starting
point, accepting advertisements from companies that fit this genre.
</P>
<P>
   Allow us to recommend these top three: XGolf (www.xgolf.com),
which has a nice list of cliches to use on the course, Hack Daddy
(www.hackdaddy.com), which includes the ``History of Hack,'' and
Whole In One (www.wholegolf.com) for reviews of products you won't
find in Golf Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Also, two worth bookmarking as their sites currently undergo a
facelift _ Ogio (www.ogio.com), which has a wild collection of bags
and an amazing shoulder harness to carry them, and Fringe Golf
(www.fringegolf.com), which stands to be a supersite for all
off-the-beaten-cartpath needs.
</P>
<P>
   _The Golf Academy of Hilton Head Island at Sea Pines in South
Carolina (www.golfacademy.net) offers a unique Father's Day
present: A $1,195 gift certificate that includes a three-day golf
school enrollment with Class A PGA instruction, daily rounds of
golf (including the legendary Harbour Town Golf Links) and a set of
irons. Dad must use the certificate by March 30, 2000. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
