<SLUG> BC-OZZFEST-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
 ROCK REVIEW: HINTS OF DIVERSITY AMID THE POWER CHORDS AND MAYHEM
 (nk) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; HOLMDEL, N.J. _ Basic black and power chords are constants in
heavy metal, and there was plenty of each at Ozzfest, the 16-band,
11-hour concert that appeared twice at PNC Bank Arts Center here.
</P>
<P>
   At Ozzy Osbourne's fourth annual summer roadshow _ featuring his
reunited original band, Black Sabbath _ songs about death, the
Devil, anger and rebelliousness were all good-time music for fans
who came to jump and howl along. Bands performed on the center's
main stage and on a smaller one in a field, where the size of the
dust cloud measured the enthusiasm in the mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   Only in heavy metal could a revived oldies act _ Black Sabbath
played songs from the late 1960s and early '70s _ headline a bill
of '80s and '90s bands without a significant generation gap. Metal
still serves its time-honored purposes: venting defiance, repelling
adult authority and, in its lyrics, examining issues of power,
death, faith and identity that other pop glosses over.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ozzfest reveals that current metal is a many-splintered
thing. Speed-metal knocked down barriers between heavy metal and
hard-core punk in the 1980s, and the pure, whipsawing impact of
guitars, drums and bass was in exhilarating form with Slayer, whose
songs are physiologically engineered to provide a testosterone
rush. Growled lyrics about mayhem, hammering one-chord stretches
topped by streaking lead guitar, and pauses for fist-pumping
between tempo changes felt like a combination of a massage and a
motorcycle chase.
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s metal has been learning from hip-hop, alternative
rock and dance music. Hybrids were everywhere at Ozzfest. System of
a Down played the day's most volatile music: vocals that jumped
from howl to screech, riffs that suddenly switched from stomp to
dirge to nagging repetition to pummel, and a midset rant about the
politics of bombing Yugoslavia. Hed(pe) segued bratty Cypress
Hill-style rapping into its metal growl, with funk and reggae
syncopation in its guitars.
</P>
<P>
   The Deftones, drawing from alternative rock, set sustained
melodies against a hard-riffing onslaught, like troubled lullabies
during an earthquake, though the songs seemed amorphous and
self-indulgent onstage. Primus, a band enthralled by its own
cleverness, played dumbed-down songs with musicianly filigrees, not
realizing that a cliche played with a smirk is still a cliche.
</P>
<P>
   Drum machines and synthesizers helped to drive Static-X,
Apartment 26 and the more impressive Fear Factory, who merge hard
core's righteous fury with industrial rock's mechanistic drive. Rob
Zombie's B-movie-inspired songs combine a heavy-metal stomp with a
steady dance-music thump; he had the day's theatrical extravaganza,
with makeup, a flashing ``666'' sign, go-go girls and puffs of
flame. Slipknot, from Des Moines, accessorized basic songs by
performing in red jumpsuits and clown and ghoul masks.
</P>
<P>
   Ozzfest '99 offered a hint of diversity amid the overwhelmingly
male and white performers. The day's first set was by Drain S.T.H.,
a female hard-rock band from Stockholm. The tour lineup also
included Puya, which raps and growls its lyrics in Spanish and
layers conga drumming, horn-section lines and mambo rhythms amid
thrashing guitars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Ozzfest bands are all descendants of Black Sabbath. The
way Tommy Iommi on guitar, Geezer Butler on bass and Bill Ward on
drum slammed out slow riffs _ guitar and bass in unison, drums
thudding and rumbling _ and then shifted into double time was a
revelation that rock has never outgrown. The same tactics, as
updated by Metallica, were used at Ozzfest by Godsmack, Pushmonkeys
and Flashpoint.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night Osbourne's voice was a wreck; he said he had
suffered three broken ribs from a fan's bear hug earlier this week.
So Black Sabbath featured Iommi on guitar, making each riff
adamantine and turning each tempo shift into an upheaval. His
lead-guitar solos went into stretches of triplets and Blues 101
squiggles.
</P>
<P>
   But Black Sabbath earned its legacy by realizing it was no
longer a second-rate blues-rock band, but a monolithic riff
builder. Its original lineup made those riffs resonate while the
crowd yelled all the lyrics it knew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1910EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3596 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVISIONS-NYT &LR;      06-13 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVISIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGERS WHOSE ART TRANSCENDS THE SONGS THEY SING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MARGO JEFFERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wasn't it Barry Manilow who crooned ``I am music, and I write
the songs''? What a terrible thought. If music had meant well by
us, surely he or she or it would not have chosen that particular
mouthpiece; surely music would have wanted us to have better songs
and better singers.
</P>
<P>
   Every age deifies certain kinds of talent, and ours pays too
much obeisance to singer-songwriters, our modern troubadours. It's
pretty hard to be good at both, especially since so many singers
insist on writing their music  &UR; and  &LR; their lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   People devoted to performing nothing but their own work can grow
very tiresome unless they are quite extraordinary. What's the best
test of singer-songwriters once we've grown accustomed to their
lure as performers? When and whether other singers perform their
work, I think, and whether that work changes over the years.
</P>
<P>
   If you're singing all your own songs, you're writing to the
contours of your own voice and the limits, not just the strengths,
of your temperament. It's a great thing to be able to write for
other voices, to tell stories and distill emotions not your own.
</P>
<P>
   Singers are never merely interpreters of other people's music
unless they are dull, dumb or derivative. There are too many ways
(still) to work with, through and past a lyric, too many ways
(being discovered or rediscovered) to use one's voice without the
aid of conventional language, drawing on sounds, syllables,
overtones, microtones and all kinds of breath patterns.
</P>
<P>
   So let us take two recent recordings and treat them as case
studies in interpretation and composition.
</P>
<P>
   _ `THE GOSPEL SOUL OF MARION WILLIAMS' (Shanachie Spirit Feel):
Marion Williams sang gospel music and nothing else all her life.
(She died in 1994 at 67, having received a MacArthur grant and a
Kennedy Center Honor for lifetime achievement in her last years.)
The gospel repertory is filled with spare and simple Anglo-American
hymns and with African-American songs derived from spirituals and
revival meetings, with some blues and jazz infusions. Elaboration
and improvisation are a must.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was a fierce and potent soprano who could sing at any
tempo: a furious syncopated march, a pure adagio, a pulsing blues.
And when she sang a capella, she knew that, rather than being
released from what the other instruments did, she had become
responsible for what they did. Her timing on ``Sit Down Servant''
was as taut as any drummer's, and she picked her notes so that you
hear the harmonies as well as the melody.
</P>
<P>
   She could growl like a man, a fact that always reminds of the
line in Bessie Smith's ``Black Mountain Blues,'' ``All the birds
sing bass.'' (Gospel thrives on these transgender vocalizings.) The
blues tonalities on songs like ``Savior, Don't Pass Me By'' are
gorgeous and feel invented on the spot, not dutifully inserted.
(Stylistic dutifulness is the bane of much contemporary blues
singing.)
</P>
<P>
   All the material of great blues and gospel singing, so abused by
soul singers today, is here: the varied timbres, the breath as a
musical device, the well-tempered moans and slides, the melisma
used discreetly, not as a substitute for true pitch or true
feeling.
</P>
<P>
   She was a great singer. And this wasn't just because of her
amazing technique. (She could go overboard with it at times.) It
was because of her emotional resources. ``Just a Closer Walk With
Thee'' is an old song that has lived through many renditions. They
all fell away when I heard Williams sing it.
</P>
<P>
   _ CASSANDRA WILSON, `TRAVELING MILES' (Blue Note): Here is a
best-selling album by a wonderfully astute young singer with a
voice that quickens your senses instantly: low and lustrous, but
slightly overcast. ``Traveling Miles'' is a homage to Miles Davis.
It contains Ms. Wilson's reinventions of songs Davis wrote (like
``Blue in Green''), collaborated on (like ``Seven Steps'') or did
celebrated versions of (Wayne Shorter's ``ESP,'' Cyndi Lauper's
``Time After Time'' and Snow White's ``Someday My Prince Will
Come'' by Frank E. Churchill and Larry Morey).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wilson has written lyrics for the Davis instrumentals, and
she has written lyrics or both music and lyrics for five additional
songs. I went to a concert at Lincoln Center last winter that Ms.
Wilson devoted to Davis, and I was enthralled. The same gifts are
on this album: the way she plays with meter, her delicate tonal
shifts, the unpredictable but unforced phrasing, the harmonic
sophistication joined to an easy, bluesy swing.
</P>
<P>
   But this album satisfies me much less than the concert did, and
that's because I do not find Ms. Wilson an interesting songwriter.
The song of hers that works best, ``When the Sun Goes Down,'' is
the song closest to a traditional blues. And her best lyrics, for
Davis' ``Run the Voodoo Down,'' are also drawn from the
well-stocked living library of blues imagery.
</P>
<P>
   Her songs _ and this is true on other albums, too, like ``New
Moon Daughter'' _ dissipate into wispy melodies and too-pretty
musings. But the tepid melody and too-pretty words of ``Someday My
Prince Will Come'' arouse her critical and creative instincts, and
the tension between the song and her twangy, restless arrangement
makes it alive and emotionally unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   I think it is very hard to be a truly exceptional singer right
now. There is so much material around you can make every kind of
mistake. Ms. Wilson's choices are always interesting, though; they
include the Monkees, Joni Mitchell, Robert Johnson and musical
theater songwriters from Irving Berlin to Lerner and Loewe. There
are so many styles and techniques, too _ jazz, rock, all the
highways and byways of new music and world music _ that it requires
enormous taste, technique and imagination to choose songs that you
can make yours in a way that has depth as well as flash.
</P>
<P>
   Fine songwriters and fine singers are collaborators. Less than
fine songwriters ought to fall on their knees and pray that a
creative singer will take what they've done and make it up all over
again. At its best, interpretation is revelation. Why should
singers or listeners settle for less?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
