u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWERS-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-13 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWERS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETERS BET ON `AUSTIN POWERS' TO ENDEAR THEM TO THE YOUNG
</HEADLINE>
   (With AUSTIN-POWERS) 
(nk) 
 By PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The magazine ad features comedian Mike Myers as the British
spy-a-go-go, Austin Powers. He is lounging in a royal blue satin
robe with a milk-filled martini glass in hand and a milk mustache.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milk keeps my bones strong,'' says the advertisement for the
National Fluid Milk Processor Promotion Board, ``so I can keep my
mojo working overtime. Oh, behave.''
</P>
<P>
   Behave, indeed. As the international man of mystery himself
might say, what's going on with the sexy advertising, baby?
</P>
<P>
   With the release last week of New Line Cinema's ``Austin Powers:
The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' a rush of promotional tie-ins has
arrived. That is no surprise, since the original Austin Powers film
from 1997 has developed an almost cult-like following among that
most elusive of advertising audiences _ young people.
</P>
<P>
   More remarkable is that some fairly mainstream marketers are
running advertising that might make some viewers blush. And
apparently, they can get away with it because it is all part of the
joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a spoof,'' said Jay Schulberg, vice chairman and chief
creative officer at Bozell Worldwide in New York, part of True
North Communications, which created the milk board's ad. ``He's a
lovable rogue. We are very careful about who we use in advertising,
and there is no one who we'll use that is offensive to any segment
of the population.''
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are willing to take a calculated risk with an
on-the-fringe character in order to reach their target audience,
Jack Trout, a Greenwich, Conn.-based marketing consultant, said.
Linking with Austin Powers is corporate America's attempt to be
seen as cool in the eyes of the youth market. It is hipness by
association, Trout said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an in-joke and it's only in among the crowd they want to
talk to,'' Trout said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the film's title has a bit of the in-joke about it. In
England, the slang word ``shag'' is blatantly sexual, and its
American counterpart would never be used in mainstream advertising.
Nevertheless, it is being played up in a big way in ads here.
Virgin Group's Virgin Atlantic has renamed one of its airplanes the
Shaglantic. Cadbury-Schweppes PLC, the maker of Mott's fruit juices
and apple sauce, is introducing Shagadelic Shakers, ready-made
cocktail mixers in bar-like shakers. The last Mott's film tie-in
was with ``Rugrats: The Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The British are aghast at the use of word,'' said Don
Moriarty, managing director of CMG Communications in New York,
Virgin Atlantic's ad agency. ``But here, it's much more vague. It's
more suggestive than literal.''
</P>
<P>
   Heineken USA said it was ``very cognizant and had substantial
discussions'' about use of the word, but decided it was acceptable
because it was a send-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Myers' appeal is naughtiness, but it's good clean fun,''
a Heineken USA spokesman, Dan Tearno, said.
</P>
<P>
   The ads play up Austin Powers' comical penchant for sexual
innuendo and double entendre, which is all part of the film comedy
about a mod 1960s spy who is ``cryogenically'' unfrozen in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Take the billboard for Virgin Atlantic Airways, which has Powers
announcing a new fifth flight daily from New York to London. ``Five
times a day,'' says the headline. ``Yeah, baby.'' And then there is
the Heineken commercial, which shows a beautiful woman giving
Powers a massage when she stops suddenly. ``Why'd you stop?'' he
asks. ``I was admiring your Heiney,'' the woman responds, and the
spot quickly cuts to a bottle of the imported beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to use a property, you have to be true to
it,'' said the head of Heineken's agency, Lee Garfinkel, chairman
and chief creative officer of Lowe &AMP; Partners/SMS in New York, part
of the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   New Line saw long before the latest film release that it had a
hot property in Austin Powers and approached promotional partners,
marketers said. But Mott's sought out New Line independently, after
developing the retro cocktail mixers, when a marketing executive
saw the Austin Powers promotional materials at last year's
licensing show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the big `ta-da,''' the executive, Mike Judlowe, said.
``It is everything we were trying for: to be younger, to take
advantage of the retro trend, to be fun and naughty. You couldn't
dream up a fit like this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Virgin jumped on the opportunity as part of its campaign to
become known for its London destination, and also because, like
Austin Powers, the quirky airline and its impish owner, Richard
Branson, are known for ``serious fun,'' Moriarty said.
</P>
<P>
   Virgin was also aware of the growing underground popularity of
the original Austin Powers film. The film's phrases are now so much
a part of the American lexicon that phrases like ``Yeah, baby'' and
``Oh, behave'' are seen on placards at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once it becomes part of the culture, it becomes sort of
de-sexed,'' said Barbara Lippert, advertising critic for the trade
publication Adweek in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lippert said the advertising tie-ins were appropriate and
did fit. ``The whole thing is aimed at the sensibility of a
12-year-old boy and that's who advertisers want to reach, even if
that 12-year-old is 24,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the milk board came by Myers because he spoofed
its milk mustache campaign in the first film without its
permission, Schulberg said. Now, it is using him to reach young
people, one of its four key audience segments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you have very targeted marketing _ everything is sliced
and diced,'' Schulberg said. ``It's the same with the movie _ he's
going after a very specific niche and it's totally appropriate for
that audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Myers, a writer and co-producer of the film, was involved in
much of the advertising, the agency executives said. He went on
shoots, did radio voiceovers and signed off on the final product.
In one instance, he outright rejected a Virgin ad that he
considered ``over the line,'' Moriarty said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very conscious of where the line is and not going over
it,'' Moriarty said. ``Once you go over the line, it ceases to be
funny.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1923EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JSTARS-705&AMP;ADD     06-13 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JSTARS-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB WITHDRAWAL IS MONITORED FROM THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE JSTARS SURVEILLANCE PLANE OVER ALBANIA _ Almost as
soon as their battery of radar screens locked onto Kosovo shortly
after dawn on Saturday, it was obvious to everybody here that the
Yugoslav forces were on the run.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors told the story in Technicolor: a stream of magenta
and yellow dots _ representing vehicles ranging from tractors and
trucks to tanks _ inched along Highway 17 and Highway 11 through
the Kosovo capital, Pristina, and north toward the province's
border with the rest of Serbia, the main republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Both roads are NATO-approved retreat routes for the Yugoslav
forces, but they had been almost empty just on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, as NATO troops moved into Kosovo for the first
time, the team of Air Force and Army technicians watched the
minute-by-minute progress of convoys that stretched as far as 20
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like day and night,'' said Indy, one of this flight's
two senior directors, who like other crew members would identify
himself only by his nickname. He studied some of the 18 computer
screens on this rebuilt Boeing 707. ``If we had seen this the last
time, we would have sent aircraft in immediately. It would have
been a turkey shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   This aging airplane carries the U.S. Air Force's newest and most
advanced system for watching enemy troops from the air. The system
has assumed a key role in picking targets and monitoring the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   There are clear limits to how much can actually be seen from
this distance. The radar system tries to distinguish between tanks
and ordinary trucks, but its guesses are often incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women in this plane are miles from the combat zone,
generally out of range of missile attacks and protected by a shield
of fighter jets. Yet as they crouched before their screens in the
darkened fuselage, they followed the humblest movement on the
ground with an almost haunting degree of intimacy.
</P>
<P>
   They scrutinized a small caravan of trucks that had wandered off
the main highway. They zoomed in on the areas where Serbian forces
are allowed to congregate before leaving. They watched as NATO
vehicles moved north from neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is information warfare,'' said Kujo, the flight's other
senior director. ``The key to success for troops on the ground has
always been the ability to look over the next hill, and this takes
it to a new level.''
</P>
<P>
   Though used experimentally during the Persian Gulf war, the
Joint Surveillance Target Attack Radar Systems are still so new
that the Air Force and Army have only four of them worldwide _ two
of them now in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike its better-known predecessor, the Airborne Warning and
Control System, or AWACS, this system was designed to scrutinize
events on the ground over a wide geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   The radar aboard this plane, housed in a canoe-shaped hull on
the bottom of the fuselage, can see all of Kosovo in one view. It
can also zoom in on scores of small patches simultaneously, serving
up images demanded by the on-board technicians as well as requests
from commanders at the Combined Air Operations Center in Vicenza,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The Jstar planes fly some of the longest missions of any
aircraft used in the Balkans. A typical flight lasts more than 17
hours, and the longest mission so far lasted 21 hours. All flights
require two midair refuelings as well as backup pilots and crew
members. Takeoff is usually before dawn from Rhine-Main Air Force
Base in Frankfurt, Germany. Given the preparation beforehand and
the debriefings afterward, crew members routinely work 24 hours
straight.
</P>
<P>
   Once in position, they transmit not only images but analytical
reports all day long. Ken, a burly technician sitting next to the
senior leader, banged out hourly reports describing scores of
activities along all the Serbs' approved ``egress routes.''
</P>
<P>
   In the very rear of the plane, a small group of Army technicians
ran their searches on behalf of ground forces in Macedonia.
Specially equipped Humvees allow Army units to receive the full
stream of Jstar images and radar mapping and to convey information
requests to the plane.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though the dramatic movements back toward northern Yugoslavia
were Saturday's big news, much of the effort here was to spot
unusual or quirky behavior that might be a tipoff to unexpected
problems.
</P>
<P>
   That was why Indy had locked the system onto a curious parade of
trucks, nine big ones and six small ones, that were traveling well
wide of the authorized road between Prizren and Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Though heading parallel to the approved road, it was wandering
suspiciously. Indy instructed the system to take a close look every
few seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to watch the main roads,'' said Indy. ``But really
good surveillance, I think, comes from looking for things that
don't seem quite right.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many weapons in this war, the Jstar missions embody a
curious blend of extremely advanced technology mounted on almost
shockingly old equipment.
</P>
<P>
   To save money, the Pentagon decided to build the Jstars
surveillance system into 35-year-old Boeing 707s. This one, Kujo
said, had been a cargo plane for the Australian airline Qantas.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force officials say this decision made good sense, because
the 707s remain reliable workhorses.
</P>
<P>
   The system, including the plane, cost about $250 million,
officials said, but one commander on the ground said, ``Buy a radar
and get the plane for free.''
</P>
<P>
   But the creakiness of this plane became apparent. Fumes,
probably from the plane's overloaded air-conditioning system,
required the entire crew to strap on oxygen masks twice on
Saturday. To solve the problem, the aircraft commander shut off all
extra electricity for the last hour of the flight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real heroes in this are the maintenance guys,'' a crew
member said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the headaches, the Jstar has become immensely popular
with NATO commanders and even with fighter pilots who were once
dubious about accepting guidance from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the war started, people didn't know quite what to do with
us,'' said Indy. ``But after they started getting our flow of data,
they wanted more and more sorties. The biggest problem now is that
we can't fill all the demand.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1930EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
