<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3608 &Cx1f; tth-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PHO-SPI &LR;      06-13 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PHO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHO, VIETNAM'S NATIONAL DISH, STIRS UP WARM MEMORIES OF SOOTHING
SOUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PHUONG LE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Nothing recalls home for me quite like a steaming bowl
of pho.
</P>
<P>
   Fragrant and comforting, this Vietnamese beef noodle soup is
made from a stock of slow-simmered beef bones.
</P>
<P>
   Rice noodles are topped with thin slices of raw beef and choice
meats, ladled with steaming broth, then garnished with a medley of
crisp bean sprouts, sprigs of sweet basil, slices of green chili
and a squeeze of lime.
</P>
<P>
   The national dish of Vietnam, it is the one meal I must have
when I find myself in an unfamiliar place.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese get sentimental, even giddy, when it comes to
pho, and I count myself among the most egregious offenders. Indulge
in this delicate soup on a weary day and it is easy to see why
poems have been penned in its honor.
</P>
<P>
   Pho is a part of my pysche even though I spent most of my life
in the United States. (I was born in Saigon, but my family
immigrated to the United States in 1975 when I was almost 4).
</P>
<P>
   Pho (pronounced ``fuh'') sustained me through blustery winter
days in Chicago. It offset stress during graduate school in
Michigan. Eaten in a run-down, questionable shop in Munich, it was
a salve for homesickness. Short of curing heartaches, pho has done
much to alleviate disappointments over the years.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the one meal that cements my family _ more than any
fat-breasted turkey on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I visit my family in San Jose, Calif., where pho shops
abound, we religiously pile into the car and drive straight to our
favorite restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   We order from memory. The bowls arrive, crowding every inch of
the table, and a silence ensues as we perform the ritual of
seasoning the soup with herbs and condiments.
</P>
<P>
   Pepper, squeeze of lime, touch of hoisin sauce, a bit of
Sriracha chili sauce. Handful of raw bean sprouts. Pluck of basil
leaves and other herbs. A slice of green hot pepper for spiciness.
</P>
<P>
   These days I seek out pho for the joys of slurping bowls so
large they're dubbed ``train-sized'' in Vietnamese. I also seek it
for the associations with family, culture and my mom's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   I still negotiate the lines between my two cultures with
clumsiness and uncertainty, but put a bowl of pho and a glass of
iced coffee in front of me and there is little doubt about who I
am: Vietnamese to the core.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants now make pho so efficiently and cheaply that fewer
and fewer people feel the need to cook it at home.
</P>
<P>
   My mom never taught me or my older sister how to make pho, but
we learned enough from watching her on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   While growing up, I awoke most Saturday mornings to the sweet
smells of her pho simmering on the stove. My mom already had
returned from the Asian market with a bag of beef neck or shank
bones and prepared the stock.
</P>
<P>
   While keeping careful watch over it, she dispensed tip after
cooking tip.
</P>
<P>
   She raved about a market where rice noodles were made fresh
daily, or told me to freeze the beef so it is easier to slice. Be
sure to clean the bones, she said, and don't let the broth boil too
much or the anise may break.
</P>
<P>
   Those tidbits stay with me now, despite my ambivalence to them
back then.
</P>
<P>
   My mom never kept a recipe. The process was ingrained in her
mind, taking root there by watching her own mother cook pho in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   I made pho for the first time on a bitingly cold day in Ann
Arbor, Mich., when I couldn't bear to drive the hour to the nearest
restaurant and couldn't endure my craving.
</P>
<P>
   Several Vietnamese friends and I gathered in one friend's
kitchen that afternoon and recalled how our mothers prepared pho.
We fumbled with the measurements; one friend phoned her mother to
beg step-by-step instructions.
</P>
<P>
   As we cooked pho that day, mimicking our mothers' gestures, we
swapped childhood stories and wistfully recreated our homes.
</P>
<P>
   Then we sat down and slurped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
