<HEADER>
A3609 &Cx1f; tth-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-PHO-RECIPE-SPI &LR;      06-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-PHO-RECIPE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMMERING FOR HOURS ESSENTIAL FOR THE BEST PHO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pho begins with beef bones, extracting its flavor during several
hours simmering with onions, ginger and star anise.
</P>
<P>
   Star anise is a star-shaped, brown, slightly bitter pod that
gives pho its unusual fragrance. Store-bought fish sauce (nuoc mam)
adds flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The broth is simmered for several hours. Packaged rice noodles
are boiled, drained and topped with slices of raw beef that cook
and curl in the bowl once steaming broth is ladled on top.
</P>
<P>
   A tangle of fresh basil, bean sprouts and green chili peppers
make the soup a savory, healthy meal. Or try lime wedges, fresh
sprigs of cilantro and, for pungency, Asian basil (smaller and with
more of a licorice flavor than its Western counterpart).
</P>
<P>
   Several Asian supermarkets in Seattle's International District
stock these ingredients. Some sell packaged, ready-made pho, or
pho-flavoring for the broth.
</P>
<P>
   You should also have a jar of dark sweet hoisin sauce and a
squeeze bottle of Vietnamese chili sauce. Mix them together to make
a dipping sauce for the meat.
</P>
<P>
   A splash of the fish sauce _ a condiment made from pickled
anchovies _ is optional, taking the place of salt.
</P>
<P>
   The following recipe takes some shortcuts or makes slight
adjustments to the ``traditional'' method of preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Pho
</P>
<P>
   (Vietnamese Beef Noodle Soup)
</P>
<P>
   For Pho:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces rice sticks
</P>
<P>
   4 green onions, white part minced, green part finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   6 cups beef stock (preferably homemade)
</P>
<P>
   6 thin slices fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   3 star anise
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons brown sugar or to taste
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter cup fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces beef tenderloin or sirloin, partially frozen
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size white sweet onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   12 fresh Thai or regular basil leaves, thinly slivered
</P>
<P>
   For Vegetable Platter:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fresh mung bean sprouts
</P>
<P>
   8 sprigs fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   8 sprigs fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   2 jalapeno or serrano chilies, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 limes, cut into wedges
</P>
<P>
   Hoisin sauce and Vietnamese chili sauce for serving
</P>
<P>
   To prepare Pho, soak rice sticks in cold water until soft and
pliable, 30 minutes. Combine white part of green onions, beef
stock, ginger, star anise, cinnamon, brown sugar and fish sauce in
large pot and simmer until well flavored, 10 minutes. With slotted
spoon, remove star anise, cinnamon and ginger and discard.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, slice beef across grain as thinly as possible. (This
works best if meat is partially frozen. It's even easier if you
have a meat slicer.)
</P>
<P>
   To prepare Vegetable Platter, arrange sprouts, mint, cilantro,
chilies and lime wedges on platter.
</P>
<P>
   Just before serving, bring broth to boil. Add rice sticks and
simmer until soft, 1 to 2 minutes. Stir in beef and remove pan from
heat. (The heat of the broth should be sufficient to cook the meat.
If not, cook until beef is done.) Stir in onion slices. Ladle soup
into bowls. Garnish each bowl with shredded basil and chopped onion
greens. Serve at once with Vegetable Platter on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Have diners add bean sprouts, mint and cilantro, chilies and
lime juice to their soup to suit their taste. Mix equal parts
hoisin sauce and chili sauce in small dish and use mixture as dip
for beef.
</P>
<P>
   Makes four servings.
</P>
<P>
   Rice sticks are noodles made from pureed cooked rice, ranging in
size up to one-half inch in width. (I prefer one-quarter-inch-wide
noodles for this soup.) They can be found at Asian markets, gourmet
shops or in the Asian food section of most supermarkets. If
unavailable, in a pinch you could make this soup with conventional
wheat noodles.
</P>
<P>
   From food writer Steven Raichlen, author of ``The Barbecue
Bible'' (Workman Publishing, 576 pages, $27.95). Recipe distributed
by the Los Angeles Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp Spring Rolls
</P>
<P>
   (Goi Cuon)
</P>
<P>
   with dipping sauce
</P>
<P>
   1cup (approximate) vermicelli rice noodles
</P>
<P>
   8 to 12 medium shrimp
</P>
<P>
   4 sheets rice paper, 8 to 10 inches in diameter
</P>
<P>
   4 lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   20 or more mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch cilantro sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Soak the rice noodles in hot water for about 15 to 20 minutes or
until soft. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile boil the shrimp for several minutes until just pink,
then peel and slice in half lengthwise.
</P>
<P>
   Gather all ingredients in the same area to assemble.
</P>
<P>
   Moisten the rice paper by soaking it in a bowl of hot water for
20 seconds or until softened. Place the rice paper on a plate and
let dry slightly before working with it.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the rice paper, place 2 or 3 shrimp. Try to
form a neat 3-inch row. Add a quarter of the noodles, some lettuce,
mint leaves and a few cilantro sprigs. Do not overfill. Roll up the
rice paper (like a burrito), trying to keep the contents inside
fairly tight as you roll.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat the steps. Makes four rolls.
</P>
<P>
   Spicy Dipping Sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 small garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   one-quarter teaspoon red (serrano) chili peppers, seeded and
minced
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons nuoc mam (fish sauce)
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients. Test and adjust to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnamese style iced coffee
</P>
<P>
   (Ca phe sua da)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark-roast coffee
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sweet condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   Ice cubes to fill an 8-ounce glass
</P>
<P>
   Strong dark-roast coffee is brewed in a stainless steel
percolater that rests on the coffee cup. Buy the coffee and
individual percolaters in any Vietnamese market.
</P>
<P>
   Place the milk in the bottom of a coffee cup. Place coffee
grounds in the coffee press and screw lid. Rest the percolater on
top of the cup and pour boiling water into it. It will take about
10 minutes to drip through.
</P>
<P>
   Can be served hot or cold.
</P>
<P>
   For iced coffee, fill a separate glass with ice cubes. Once the
coffee drips through, stir the coffee and milk in the cup and then
pour into the glass of ice and stir again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
