<HEADER>
A3610 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-NYT &LR;      06-13 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS EMBARRASS NATO AS PEACEKEEPING FORCE OCCUPIES KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, France)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Russian soldiers occupying Pristina's
airport blocked the entry of British troops Sunday in an
embarrassing impasse for NATO's nascent peacekeeping effort in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton discussed the stalemate with his Russian
counterpart, Boris Yeltsin, by telephone, British officers fumed in
private that the place they had picked for their headquarters had,
in effect, been confiscated. Commanders spent much of the day,
without apparent success, searching for an alternative location.
There was no triumphal news conference on the airport tarmac, as
had been expected, by Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the overwhelming might of seemingly endless columns of
NATO soldiers and machines spreading out through the battered
province, it was a somewhat faltering start to the first full day
of the effort to restore peace to a land where Yugoslav forces and
the conduct of war have driven more than a million ethnic Albanians
from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, some 2,000 American soldiers were supposed to enter
Kosovo. But the progress of their heavy, rumbling convoys was slow,
and several hundred Marines got only as far as a refugee camp back
in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   British paratroopers shot a Serb policeman dead here Sunday
afternoon after he fired gunshots near one of their patrols. In
Prizren, to the south, German troops came under sniper fire, then
killed two Serbs who tried to attack them.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the peacekeepers began to enter Pristina, departing
Serbs torched Albanian houses and the home of the imam of
Pristina's oldest mosque. Albanian gunmen killed at least one Serb
policeman, and there were unconfirmed reports from local Serbs that
10 Serbs had been abducted and at least six killed in Pristina
suburbs and around the province. A Yugoslav police general, Obrad
Stevanovic, was talking to British forces to try to get the
kidnapped Serbs released, local Serbs said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate incident, a German journalist was shot dead south
of here by unknown gunmen. A second German journalist was severely
wounded and later died, the German foreign ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Pristina's airfield was the scene of genteel contention
throughout the day, as British and other NATO officers gritted
their teeth and left it to the politicians and diplomats to try to
wrest the airport from the Russians and find them a niche in the
peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians number only about 200, under the command of Col.
Gen. Victor Zavarzin, who was promoted to that rank only Saturday.
They had hastily painted a ``K'' on their armored vehicles over the
first letter of the acronym for the U.N. Bosnian peacekeeping
mission, SFOR, to match the mission here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing what they're told,'' said Capt. Martin Gorwin, a
British commando officer at the head of a long column of armored
vehicles and troops who had spent the night outside the Russian
roadblock at the edge of the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't just push through with his superior force,
Gorwin replied: ``I'm not going to bully my way through. I'm not
going to escalate the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian presence, represented by an armored personnel
carrier parked sideways across the road, created a strange
situation. Yugoslav soldiers were inside the airport perimeter and
were helping to man the roadblock, and loitering around the nearby
village, studiously ignoring the British troops.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces also set up roadblocks on the other side of the
airport, nearer the city, where they turned back journalists,
saying they were doing so on Russian orders.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the morning, the Russians also turned back a French army
convoy, which was on the way to its sector in northern Kosovo. As
the officials argued, a French commander, in frustration, turned to
a journalist to ask the codes for dialing Macedonia on his cell
phone so he could ask his superiors for instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's in charge,'' shrugged a Yugoslav army officer
standing nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The military agreement signed last week by NATO and Yugoslav
generals required the Serb-dominated army and police units to
withdraw from clearly delineated parts of Kosovo over 11 days, but
it never said in what order.
</P>
<P>
   So even as some 10,000 NATO troops poured into the province over
the last two days, there were still plenty of Yugoslav troops in
Kosovo, intermingled with the peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   In several areas around the airport, the Yugoslav forces _ and
many civilians _ were packing up to leave. Most Serb men by the
roadside, in uniform or not, seemed to be carrying a rifle of some
kind. One stocky man wearing a black leather vest leaned in the
door of a bar with crossed bandoliers of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Serbs were leaving in military trucks, but others
were almost a mirror image of the Albanian refugees, joining
convoys of sputtering farm tractors dragging carts piled high with
belongings, except that several of the Serbs perched on top were
heavily armed.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the withdrawal agreement, the armed Yugoslav
forces will have until Wednesday to withdraw from Zone I, which
includes Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   As they left, plumes of smoke marked torched buildings. Bursts
of gunfire were heard.
</P>
<P>
   In the village of Sofalia, near the airport, Serbs had set fire
to most of the houses around 1 p.m. Sunday. British troops trying
to reach the area were turned away at a Serb roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Around 10 a.m., neighbors said, Yugoslav army soldiers set fire
to the house of the Hoxha, or Muslim priest, attached to the Sultan
Murat mosque, the oldest in the city. A plaque on the mosque says
it is a historic monument protected by the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday morning the downtown streets of Pristina were still
filled with armed Serb police and soldiers, apparently on duty. In
the Grand Hotel, gunmen with bandanas on their heads and
Kalashnikov assault weapons dangling down their backs on long
slings leaned on the lobby counter.
</P>
<P>
   But gradually throughout the day, the British military presence
increased on the city streets. More and more heavy Challenger tanks
and Warrior fighting vehicles took up position, covering most major
intersections by dusk.
</P>
<P>
   British paratroopers began building a camp in a park atop a
hill, setting up radio antennae and tents amid a swarm of ethnic
Albanian children and more reserved, but equally admiring, older
people. A large house nearby flew the black and red Albanian flag.
</P>
<P>
   The paratroopers, in their distinctive maroon berets, began
sending out street patrols to make their presence felt. Columns of
soldiers in full gear stalked through the streets, some wheeling
and walking backwards, weapons at the ready.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of these patrols that on Sunday afternoon shot dead a
uniformed reserve Interior Ministry policeman. A preliminary
report, said Capt. Cameron Jack of the paratroopers, was that the
man had opened fire on the patrol, was given a warning and then was
shot dead. There was also a possibility that the man was shooting
in the air, a common practice among Serbs here. After paratroopers
sealed off the shooting scene, British military police and Serb
police began a joint investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
