u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-13 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO NOT LET AGING MUSHROOMS GO GENTLE INTO THAT GOOD NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe how many hog uteruses they sell at
Uwajimaya.''
</P>
<P>
   You could hear necks crack from four different directions when
Richard Sieger dropped that bit of information into a casual
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later he was giving us his recipe for goat's head
with lentils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like to try things and I'd always heard that goat eyes
are supposed to be a delicacy,'' Sieger confessed. ``Actually, I
suspect the lentils would have been better without the goat's
head.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Does Agnes eat everything you cook?'' Sieger was asked. His
wife answered the question with a nod. She edits papers on advanced
physics at the University of Washington. That explains her
forbearance.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband designs kitchens and was attracted to the writings
in this column several years ago, when a recipe for horse jerky was
included. I became aware of him when he sent me a newspaper
clipping about a man who sought lasting fame by eating a bicycle _
gear shift, rubber tires, red reflector and all. Sieger wanted to
know if I had any expertise in bicycle cookery.
</P>
<P>
   If I had said yes, Agnes might have had another surprise on her
plate for dinner that night.
</P>
<P>
   It should come as no surprise to learn that Richard Sieger is
also an expert on the collection and cooking of the tuberous
polypore, the shaggy parasol, the wood blewit and blue legs. Which
is to say he is a prominent member of the Puget Sound Micological
Society and as such is able to exercise his curiosity on all
varieties of fungi. He is also able to steer neophyte mushroom
gatherers away from stinking parasols, weeping slime veils and
blue-footed scaly-tooths.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps his proudest possession is a hat he discovered in
Europe. It looks like a felt fedora. It was actually made out of
one giant forest mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   If the owner ever faces a mushroom emergency in his kitchen, he
can probably pull a ``feather'' out of his hat.
</P>
<P>
   Sieger knows just what to do with all kinds of mushrooms,
including aging ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do with that cheap bag of aging button mushrooms
from the supermarket?'' Sieger asks, then answers his own question.
``I bought some meat that was on sale and made sausage. The Polish
butcher who sold me the hog casings asked what I was going to make.
I told him `mushroom sausage.' He assured me that mushroom sausage
isn't Polish. Neither am I. I'm German, but I was afraid to tell
him that. Patrice Benson, who taught me how to make sausage, is
Polish, however, and that should count for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is Sieger's recipe for:
</P>
<P>
   It Isn't Polish Sausage
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds boneless pork shoulder
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds lean beef roast
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds agaricus bisporus (button mushrooms)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon black peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 head garlic
</P>
<P>
   One and one-half tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   One-half tablespoon ground nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Hog casings (optional)
</P>
<P>
   The hog casings are optional because you can make bulk sausage,
cook it in patties then wrap and freeze the remaining sausage in
one-pound packages.
</P>
<P>
   Sieger says to cut the pork, beef and mushrooms into pieces that
will fit into your meat grinder. Crush the peppercorns and add them
to the mixture. Put all the garlic cloves through a garlic press,
then mash the pulp with the salt.
</P>
<P>
   Add the garlic, salt and nutmeg to the meat mixture and blend
with your hands. Grind the mixture with a coarse blade. If the
patties don't hold together, moisten the mixture with a little
wine, he advises.
</P>
<P>
   How do I dispose of button mushrooms from the supermarket? I
might stir up a batch of:
</P>
<P>
   My Mustard Mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup butter
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 pound mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup dry vermouth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter in a skillet and saute the onion two minutes. Add
the mushrooms and saute another five minutes, stirring
occasionally. Add the vermouth and stir-cook until most of the wine
has boiled away.
</P>
<P>
   Remove pan from heat, stir in the mustard and add salt and
pepper as needed.
</P>
<P>
   Pass as a side dish or spoon the mushrooms over cooked pork
chops or chicken breasts. In fact, these mushrooms are so good you
could probably serve them over barbecued bicycle tires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
