<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-0614     06-13 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIANS-0614-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO TROOPS STRUGGLE TO MAINTAIN CONTROL AMID ``FLOWERS AND
HATRED
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-MAIN; KOSOVO-STANDOFF.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ On a day that saw hulking NATO armored
cars bedecked in flowers of gratitude, the sunburns sported by
ethnic Albanians explained both the euphoria and the anger visible
on the streets of Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   Frightened ethnic Albanian residents of this picturesque valley
city said they had rarely ventured outside their homes during the
78 days of NATO bombing and the Serb oppression rampant here.
</P>
<P>
   They came into the light Sunday morning to greet German NATO
peacekeepers and by mid-afternoon, the men in T-shirts and women in
sundresses were bright red from searing sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we are free. The Serbs are going back to Serbia and can't
come back,'' said Blerim Mydyti, 28, who brought a video camera to
record the thousands celebrating.
</P>
<P>
   It was a feeling echoed and a scene repeated all over Kosovo
Sunday as the second wave of NATO forces made their way into the
war-ravaged province.
</P>
<P>
   In the southern Kosovo village of Jerli Prelez, some ethnic
Albanians cheered and others wept tears of gratitude as U.S. Brig.
Gen. John Craddock's helicopter touched down in a field where
American troops from the Kosovo peacekeeping force (KFOR) are
planning to establish an operations base.
</P>
<P>
   After a 30-minute briefing, the general walked out to greet
about 100 local villagers, many of whom said they had not been out
of their houses for three weeks out of fear of Serb atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   They said they had been in hiding without food since Serb forces
swept through the village several weeks before and shot dead three
villagers in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very, very happy because the Serb criminals are going
home forever,'' said Avni Rejebi, a 27-year-old professional soccer
player from the nearby village of Tankovic.
</P>
<P>
   In Prizren, security was clearly not restored by Sunday night.
Gunfire could be heard around the city and people were hunkered in
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed a continuation of a way of life they hoped was ending
with the arrival of NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said most shops and businesses had been closed since
the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia began March 24, and the
Serbs intensified their ethnic cleansing campaign against Kosovar
Albanians. Many windows in downtown shops were broken. Classes had
been suspended in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Phone service had been cut off to ethnic Albanians, though not
to ethnic Serbs. Sunday night, phone lines were open to all and the
circuits were jammed.
</P>
<P>
   Families had stocked up on food before the bombing; surviving on
bread often baked at home. They said elderly people were sent into
the streets for purchases with the expectation that they were less
likely than younger relatives to be arrested by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Some estimate that more than half of the 150,000 ethnic Albanian
population of the Prizren area had fled to neighboring Albania. But
there were still large, relieved crowds, to greet German troops.
</P>
<P>
   They cheered soldiers and tossed them in the air. Adolescent
girls asked them to sign their names on the their forearms. They
sang, danced and punctuated chants of ``NATO!'' ``Clinton!'' and
``Albright!'' with three sharp claps like a basketball crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But, even with the arrival of several thousand German troops,
there was fear, hatred and death in Prizren Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   German officials said about 3,000 Serb police and military were
still in the area, as their deadline for withdrawal does not come
until Tuesday. And they were angry.
</P>
<P>
   CNN reported that German NATO troops killed a man who threatened
to shoot them from an approaching car. Non-uniformed Serb militia
posted checkpoints -- in violation of the Military Technical
Agreement with NATO -- and brandished guns at journalists and aid
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Serb civilians, a minority of about 10,000 in the city, lined
the streets with their belongings stuffing their cars as they left
in fear of Albanian reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Though thousands of ethnic Albanians celebrated in the day, by
nightfall the streets were quiet and ethnic Albanians were back to
the habits of the previous two months. Windows were shuttered in
fear that Serbs would see lights on and force themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   Especially under wraps during the last 78 days were young men.
Throughout Kosovo, Serbs have rounded them up as a way to strike at
the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. The KLA seeks to make Kosovo
independent from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, a group of young friends greeted each other for the
first time in weeks, though they were neighbors in hiding. Some
said they knew young men killed or arrested and said many houses in
surrounding villages were burned. They said that, in fact, central
Prizren was let off easier than other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope next week we can start to live like normal,'' said
Kastriot Bajraktari(CQ both), a 29-year-old who hopes to re-open
his J&AMP;B Bar soon.
</P>
<P>
   Many in Prizren said that, as the withdrawal became inevitable,
Serb soldiers had come to their homes demanding money or cars. They
also said that Serb police had come asking for the names and ages
of all residents, perhaps a way of checking on whether they had
lowered the numbers of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time today since the NATO bombing began I am out
walking,'' said Violet Gashi, a 30-year-old English teacher. Her
brother, fearing arrest, had fled the country, but she stayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better to die in your house, in your mother land than in
another country,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
