<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOSSEN SAYS HE WON'T BE PUNCHING BAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ P.J. Goossen was prepared to give up a year and a
half ago.
</P>
<P>
   The North Hollywood resident had broken his foot four days
before he was scheduled to fight Roberto Duran in November of 1997.
He lost a rare opportunity to beat a big-name opponent and his
career was in jeopardy because of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   He was so pessimistic about his future that he considered
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Well, things have a way of working themselves out: Goossen is
scheduled to fight another major figure _ Hector ``Macho'' Camacho
_ on Friday in Struthers, Ohio, in a bout that will be televised on
ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't believe it's happening,'' said Goossen, 29.
``After all I've put into this, finally, something good is
happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``... No matter what happens, at least I will have had the
opportunity to show what I can do, to see if I have it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he have it?
</P>
<P>
   Goossen (19-1, with 13 knockouts) understands that he's been
hired as a foil. Camacho (68-4-1, 33 KOs) has more big paydays
ahead of him. Goossen's job is to keep the former four-time world
champion sharp until a !ital!real opponent comes along.
</P>
<P>
   And who could blame Camacho? His four losses have come against
some pretty heady talent _ Greg Haugen, Julio Cesar Chavez, Felix
Trinidad and Oscar De La Hoya _ and he's never been knocked out.
Journeyman Pat Lawler is probably the best fighter Goossen has
beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Also, because of the foot injury, Goossen sat out 15 months. He
has fought only once _ a third-round knockout of Stacey Goodsen
last September _ in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 37, Camacho has to be considered a significant favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think I pose no threat,'' Goossen said. ``I'm
sure he thinks that, too. I've boxed (in the gym) for years with a
lot of really good fighters, though: Ike Quartey, Shane Mosley,
Reggie Johnson, Steve Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's a veteran, but I think I have some skills, too.
</P>
<P>
   If Goossen wins, he could find himself in position for a
big-money fight and/or a world title shot.
</P>
<P>
   He's marketable: He has a good record, he has a well-known last
name, his blond hair sets him apart and, if he beats Camacho, he
will have bolstered his resume.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Goossen, P.J. father/trainer/manager, said he already has
spoken with promoter Bob Arum about a possible matchup with WBC
super welterweight champion Javier Castillejo.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Duran disappointment doesn't seem as devastating
as it once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's all worked out for the good,'' Pat Goossen said.
``No one would have seen the Duran fight (which wasn't to be
televised) and I think Duran was already being dismissed as an old
man. This is Camacho and ESPN. A national TV audience will get to
see P.J.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally.
</P>
<P>
   It's his time: Heavyweight Michael Grant, who faces Lou Savarese
on Saturday in New York, is one of the nicest guys in boxing. After
all, how many fighters say ``God bless you'' to opponents before
every bout?
</P>
<P>
   However, it's time for him to speak up about what he perceives
as an injustice: Grant, 29-0 (21 knockouts) and the heir apparent
to the heavyweight throne, sees marginal fighters like Vaughn Bean
and Zeljko Mavrovic getting title shots and now he wants his turn.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, he wants WBC champ Lennox Lewis but acknowledges
it could take a while.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the best heavyweight in the world, is negotiating a
rematch with Evander Holyfield and has a mandatory due against No.
1 contender John Ruiz. He also reportedly has a few others ahead of
Grant on his to-fight list.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he knows that's the fight that could propel him to
stardom and he wants it badly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the fight I want,'' he said. ``They could pay me
$100,000 if they want. I don't care. That's the fight I want,
that's the fight people want to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I see (the likes of Bean and Mavrovic) fighting for the
title and then I look at myself and ask: `How many young fighters
do you have to fight to get a shot at the belt?' It can be very
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, there's Savarese (39-2, 32 KOs), a plodding
15-1 underdog but an experienced opponent.
</P>
<P>
   His goal is simple: Show the world why he deserves an
opportunity to fight for a world championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's !ital!how I beat Savarese that will leave its mark on the
public,'' he said. ``If I stop him between the first and third
rounds, I think the public will gravitate to me a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on the card, heavyweight Jeremy Williams of Long Beach
faces Hasim Rahman.
</P>
<P>
   Big Bear confrontation: The Oscar De La Hoya-Fernando Vargas
feud is progressing.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, who will defend his IBF junior middleweight title
against Raul Marquez on July 17 in Lake Tahoe, was the special
guest at a well-advertised promotion at a Big Bear restaurant that
was televising the Roy Jones-Reggie Johnson fight two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Guess who showed up: First Marquez and then De La Hoya, Olympic
teammates in 1992 who also train in Big Bear.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, who had his championship belt as part of the promotion,
challenged Marquez to take it from him and also directed ``one or
two'' insults toward De La Hoya, whom he has said he doesn't like.
</P>
<P>
   There were no fisticuffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `C'mon, take it right now, come and get it right
now,'' Vargas said in reference to Marquez. ``That was it. We left
it at that. Then we were watching the fight and De La Hoya comes
in. He never once turned to look at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Marquez said he and De La Hoya were there simply to watch the
fight and no head games were intended.
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   More Vargas: Rolando Arellano, Vargas' manager, has a long-range
plan for his fighter:
</P>
<P>
   Beat Marquez, fight Quartey in his subsequent fight or the one
after that and then face Olympic gold medalist and WBA junior
middleweight champion David Reid in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbit punches: De La Hoya has fired longtime adviser Mike
Hernandez as part of an effort to gain more control of his career.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders whether trainer Emanuel Steward might still be
around had De La Hoya made this move earlier, although De La Hoya's
father, Joel De La Hoya Sr., also reportedly played a role in
Steward's dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   Letting Steward go was the biggest mistake in De La Hoya's
career....
</P>
<P>
   Former contender Tony Ayala, who was released from prison two
months ago after serving 16 years for rape, reportedly will return
to the ring on July 21.
</P>
<P>
   No opponent has been selected for the 37-year-old, but the fight
will take place in his hometown of San Antonio....
</P>
<P>
   Oldies night, in which six former champions average 43 years of
age, is set for Friday in Fayetteville, N.C., on pay-per-view
television. The cost: 19.95.
</P>
<P>
   What idiot would pay to see that?...
</P>
<P>
   Two amateurs to watch are Larry Mosley and Jose Navarro of Los
Angeles, both of whom have well-known older brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley, the younger brother of IBF lightweight champ Shane
Mosley, won the 147-pound title at the U.S. Boxing Challenge over
the weekend to earn the right to fight in the world championships
in August.
</P>
<P>
   Mosley is regarded as a can't-miss star.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro, whose older brother Carlos is a rising pro, finished
second in the 112-pound class. He will compete in the Pan Am Games,
which are late next month and in August.... Boxing is coming to San
Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   A card promoted by Martinez Bros. Boxing Team is scheduled for
Friday night at the Elks Lodge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
