<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SWISS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS VOTERS TIGHTEN RESTRICTIONS ON REFUGEES LOOKING FOR ASYLUM  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ Fearful of too many refugees flooding into the country,
Swiss voters overwhelmingly approved tighter rules Sunday for
asylum-seekers and trounced a government proposal for paid
maternity leave.
</P>
<P>
   Voting as part of Switzerland's direct democracy system,
citizens cast more than 70 percent of ballots in favor of the
government measures to cut down on the number of refugees to be
given permanent asylum. Already home to some 180,000 Kosovar
Albanians, Switzerland has been experiencing an enormous influx of
refugees fleeing the Serbian province. Switzerland is expecting as
many as 60,000 refugees by the year's end _ giving it the highest
number per inhabitant in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The government measures allow collective admission for certain
groups of refugees, such as the Kosovo Albanians. But this limits
refugees' right to make a case for individual persecution, which is
necessary to be granted permanent asylum. Refugees without identity
papers can be ejected more quickly under the new controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a side to Switzerland that is very generous, giving
millions to refugees and a stricter side that wants to make sure
that people coming in are not abusing the law,'' commented
Christian Levrat, of the Swiss Organization for Aid to Refugees in
Bern.
</P>
<P>
   Voter approval was strongest in the German-speaking part of
Switzerland, where Kosovo Albanians have been denounced in
newspapers as criminals and drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The geographical split also surfaced in the vote on giving Swiss
women maternity benefits similar to those in other west European
countries. Although Switzerland requires by law that women take
eight weeks off after the birth of a baby, it has failed four times
to put fiscal muscle behind its policy, which was first adopted in
1945.
</P>
<P>
   The major sticking point with voters appeared to be financing,
estimated to cost $333 million a year, initially from surplus
government funds, then a small sales tax increase. Employers
battled the proposal, arguing the additional cost would encourage
jobs to leave Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   President Ruth Dreifuss, interviewed in Bern after the vote,
said the defeat reflected a combination of fear of adding a new
social benefit, and indifference to the economic plight of new
mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said they would like to launch a new proposal
that such benefits be paid by the employer. Some Swiss women
receive such coverage from their workplace, but the benefits are
not mandated by law. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss also voted, for the third time, to approve the
government's program that allows subsidized heroin treatment. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3624 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      06-13 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, YELTSIN AGREE TO LET MILITARY LEADERS SETTLE TROOP
CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin failed Sunday to end the standoff between NATO troops and a
small group of Russian troops in Kosovo but they agreed that NATO
and Russian military commanders should meet quickly to try to
resolve the issue, White House officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After an hourlong telephone conversation, the two leaders
decided that commanders should find a solution ``military to
military and general to general,'' said Mike Hammer, a spokesman
for the National Security Council. He described the tone of the
conversation as ``constructive'' and said Clinton and Yeltsin were
scheduled to speak again on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But while the American and Russian political leaders are
apparently expecting their military commanders to hammer out a
deal, NATO's chief military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said
Sunday that the negotiations are in fact ``a political problem
first and foremost'' and that ```this is not the kind of issue that
military commanders on the ground or their troops are going to be
able to resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just telling you at this point it is really sort of a
nonmilitary issue,'' he said of the early arrival of about 200
Russian troops in Kosovo last week, speaking on the CBS News
program ``Face the Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The solution is not here. The solution is wherever this
problem originated _ Moscow perhaps. But it is not here,'' Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what appeared to be an obvious contradiction between
Sunday's statements from the White House and those from Clark,
Hammer, the National Security Council spokesman, said that in fact
there was no difference in their views.
</P>
<P>
   While military commanders might work out the details of how to
end the standoff between NATO and the Russians, he said,
``ultimately the practical arrangements would have to be blessed at
the political level in Moscow and NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Clinton administration officials and uniformed military
leaders continued to play down the potential threat posed by
Russia's decision to send a small but determined group of soldiers
into Kosovo without warning before NATO troops arrived in the
Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that we should get overexcited about what is
going on,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said on NBC's
``Meet the Press.'' ``They want to be part of the KFOR force,'' she
said, referring to the NATO-led peacekeeping operation in Kosovo.
``We want them to be part of it. I think they got a little bit
ahead of themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   She noted that 10,000 to 15,000 troops under NATO commanders are
heading into Kosovo. ``The Russian component is about 200, so I
think we don't want to overestimate all of this,'' she said. ``It
is being handled in the proper channels.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the movement of the Russian troops into Kosovo, a
violation of assurances made repeatedly to NATO and to the United
States, reflected ``some political confusion'' in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was her ``conviction'' that Yeltsin ``is in control,
but I think that what happened here was that he said he wanted
Russian forces to be a part of the peacekeeping operation. This was
his plan, and I think that the military kind of got a step ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that a resolution of the standoff
would probably involve placing about 2,000 Russian troops in a zone
of operations within one of the five NATO sectors in Kosovo:
American, British, French, German and Italian.
</P>
<P>
   Under one proposal, the Russians would not answer directly to
NATO but instead to military commanders of a non-NATO country that
is friendly to the alliance, such as Finland, who would in turn
answer to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would allow the Russians to turn down NATO orders to
carry out missions but would require the Russians not to intervene
when NATO forces carry out the same orders in the Russian zone.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that it would be impossible to give the Russians
their own sector, as Moscow has demanded, ``because one of the
things we want to avoid and will avoid is a partition of Kosovo,
and that would contribute to it.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials fear that if the Russians fully control a region
of Kosovo, it could become a de facto Serb state within Kosovo,
given the close cultural and political ties between Russians and
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think culturally, historically, they still side with the
Serbs,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen said of the Russians on
CNN's ``Late Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have to be very careful. We have to make sure that this
agreement stands. And it cannot stand if there is going to be a
posture struck by the Russians that they are there to defend the
Serb population against the Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their participation, though welcomed, has to be under the
aegis of the authority of the NATO command structure,'' he added.
``There can be no separate command structure. So we are working
through those details.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that the NATO deployment was going ``according to
plan _ actually slightly ahead of plan.'' The Russian troops at the
Pristina airport were ``no impediment,'' he said. Clark said there
had been ``no plans at this point to make any substantial use of
that facility anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   While several hundred American troops have already begun moving
into Kosovo, Gen. Henry H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, said Sunday that the deployment of the full American
contingent of nearly 7,000 troops would probably not be completed
until midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Also appearing on CNN, he said troops of the 1st Infantry
Division, who are now stationed in Germany, would begin to arrive
``within about 30 days and then complete that probably within about
the 45- to 60-day time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor Cohen would provide any timetable for the
departure of American troops from Kosovo, a deployment that many
diplomats and military officials feel could last for years, given
the ethnic hatreds that have shattered Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can predict how long,'' Cohen said.
``It's going to be some time. We shouldn't have any short time
frame. It's going to take time. It's going to take money. But we
went into this conflict with the purpose of achieving a just
result, and we are going to have to stay the course.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
