<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3629 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TENSION-ART-56     06-13 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TENSION-ART-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SERBS FIRE AT GERMANS, WHO KILL THEM BOTH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ Two Serbs in a small yellow car opened
fire Sunday evening on a group of German peacekeepers who had just
arrived. The peacekeepers fired back, killing both men in a tense
and unsettled second day of NATO's arrival in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The body of one of the Serbs, wearing civilian clothes, still
sat slumped late Sunday night in the bullet-ridden car facing the
barrel of a German tank, a bloody reminder of the dangers of this
peacekeeping mission as it moves into Kosovo before the heavily
armed Serb troops have yet moved out.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs do not have to withdraw from this region until
Tuesday, German officials here said. That created one problem after
another in this mostly Albanian city in southern Kosovo, where
gunfire rang out repeatedly during the day. Serbs set up at least
one illegal checkpoint here and a riot nearly broke out after
Albanians began stoning the cars of Serb civilians fleeing the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not exactly under control, I think you can see,'' Patrick
Pogelt, a corporal in the German army, said in downtown Prizren,
which was covered with broken car glass and filled with cheering
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   The 500 German troops who arrived here handled the situation
with, at times, exceptional bravery.
</P>
<P>
   In the early afternoon, more than a dozen Serb soldiers, angry
at the stoning of civilians' cars, marched abreast up Vidovdanska
Street toward the German troops and began firing their automatic
rifles into the air. People dived to the ground, into shops and
under cars.
</P>
<P>
   An army reservist, Maj. Dr. Harald List, rushed alone up to the
Serb soldiers, batted a rifle butt away, and then herded the
soldiers back down the street.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans spent the rest of the afternoon negotiating the
escape route of Serb troops. Several thousand of the Serbs are now
south of the city, and they have demanded to march out on foot
through the crowds of ethnic Albanians who, many of the Germans
feared, might try to seek revenge for Serb atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tense situation,'' said 1st Lt. Marc Huhnholz, who
worked as a monitor in Kosovo for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe earlier this year. ``The people are very
happy to be able to go out again. They are very happy not to live
in fear.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they are turning very aggressive against the Serbs,'' he
said. ``Normally they are not.''
</P>
<P>
   There was jubilation as well as anger here. The crowds wildly
cheered the Germans, covering their tanks with purple, yellow and
orange flowers. Women asked the soldiers to autograph their arms,
and at one point, the crowd bounced three German soldiers,
struggling to balance their automatic rifles, into the air.
</P>
<P>
   Yet people described months of terror here; In late May, they
say, at least 30 people were massacred near the hospital in the
Tusuz neighborhood of Prizren. Nazli Tyfekci, 22, said he was one
of 150 young men arrested by Serb soldiers three months ago and
forced to dig trenches near the border.
</P>
<P>
   Verin Badallaj, 22, said they were stoning the cars for the Serb
civilians for a good reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all our cars,'' he said. ``They stole our cars last
night and the day before.'' People said that Serbs were also
looting houses around Prizren for the last few days, as they began
to flee the city in numbers. Residents say about 10 percent of the
130,000 people who live here are Serbs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The NATO entry into southern Kosovo got off to a rowdy start
Sunday morning, when hundreds of Kosovar refugees and other
Albanians crossed a fence into Kosovo before the border with
Albania was opened.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it was an emotional moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy,'' said Syl Shala, a 22-year-old refugee from
Prizren as he crossed the border to the Serb customs house. ``The
worst thing was this border checkpoint. When we crossed the border,
they said to us: You'll never get back.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, most of them apparently Albanians from inside
Albania, it was an opportunity for destruction. People ripped to
shreds Serb and Yugoslav flags. Then they looted the customs house
itself, smashing the glass and stealing everything.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Prizren on Sunday evening, the car with two Serbs drove
quickly up to the peacekeepers stationed next to the Hotel Theranda
and a crowd of celebrating Albanians. Martin Fletcher, a
correspondent with NBC, who is staying at the hotel, said the men
opened fire on the peacekeepers from the car. One German soldier
was hit, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the impact of the bullets on the pavement while
people were running away,'' he said. ``So it was really quite lucky
no one else got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The German troops then opened fire on the car, killing the
driver instantly. Nick Jennings, an NBC producer, said that as he
was giving first aid to the gravely wounded passenger, who later
died, someone pulled a hand grenade from the man's pocket.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs in town did not want to be interviewed, so it was
unclear if the troubles of the Germans troops were related at all
to the historical hostility between Serbs and Germans
</P>
<P>
   The last time German troops came through here was in 1944, as
they retreated from Greece through Albania in World War II. On
Sunday, Sgt. Jens Schluender, surrounded by girls, bragged that the
platoon he commands became the first to be deployed by air _ in a
helicopter drop Sunday morning from Macedonia _ since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very new for us,'' Schluender said. ``For me it's a very
great, very special thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
