A3638 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-MAINE14-COX     06-13 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MAINE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Maine residents flash back to first Bush presidency
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, MAINE _ Most folks here didn't complain when
former President George Bush's motorcade snarled traffic. And when
an anti-Gulf War protestor disrupted a church service attended by
Bush, congregants simply drowned him out with an impromptu
rendition of ``God Bless America.''
</P>
<P>
   The drum-beating broccoli on the village green, however, was a
little much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cold here at the time and we were hoping they'd turn
into frozen broccoli and go away,'' town manager Jane Duncan said
of the anti-war demonstrators who _ costumed as former President
George Bush's least favorite vegetable _ beat their drums 24 hours
day for as long as the president was in town.
</P>
<P>
   Because George and Barbara Bush own a home here, Kennebunkport
served as a sort of summer capital during the Bush administration.
On Sunday, residents had a flashback _ and possibly a taste of
what's to come _ when Texas Gov. George W. Bush rolled into town
with a media horde of presidential proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush, the early favorite to win the White House in 2000,
was taking a break from his first out-of-state campaign swing to
spend time with his parents. His visit reminded people here of the
first Bush administration _ and got them talking about the
possibility of a second.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan said a presidential presence creates certain challenges
for a small town, and some residents ``hope all the tourists stay
away, whether they're politically related or not.'' Overall,
however, she believes most of Kennebunkport would welcome regular
visits by a second President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Labelle of Kennebunkport's Shawmut Inn said dealing with
the media horde that followed President Bush ``became a routine.''
This weekend, many of the approximately 200 reporters covering Gov.
Bush's campaign stayed at the Shawmut.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, it gives you a pride in your heart again,''
said Labelle, who is confident that a second President Bush would
vacation in Kennebunkport.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Athens, Texas, hope not. The governor has a
vacation home of his own in Athens, and Mayor Jerry King says the
East Texas town would love to be a second presidential home. In
fact, city officials are already talking about expanding the
airport and sprucing up downtown to get ready. They've even
discussed plans for a presidential museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our feeling around here is that Governor Bush is really
president-elect,'' King said. ``We're very hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   King proudly noted that ``laid-back'' Athens residents don't
hassle Bush when they see him at Brookshier's Grocery Store or
Mazzio's Pizza. And he is confident that the governor, an avid
fisherman, can't do any better than nearby Rainbow Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty well known for our big bass that we have,'' King
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
