<HEADER>
A3659 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLOMBIA-PROSECUTOR-B     06-13 1589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-PROSECUTOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICING DEMOCRACY FROM A BUNKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His office is a bunker, inside a maze, within a fortress. At
day's end, 30 bodyguards, four armored cars, and several police
motorcycles escort Alfonso Gomez Mendez home. Gomez Mendez is
Colombia's chief prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Long gone are the days when Gomez Mendez entertained friends on
the terrace of his Bogota apartment. Today he cannot step out there
for a breath of air; the doors are sealed and bulletproofed. The
doors to his bedroom are reenforced with steel.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia's cumulative and intermingling violence _ a 40-year
insurgency, 20 years of narco-corruption; 15 years of dirty war,
and a decade of a war on drugs _ has shredded most of the country's
democratic institutions. The prosecutor's office is among the few
that have survived, and it has done so despite Gomez Mendez's
probes into the most sensitive political crimes, and his insistence
on justice for those who routinely stage assassinations and
massacres.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of survival is astronomical, too high for most
Americans to imagine. In the last two years, 19 of his staff have
been murdered; 10 have been driven into exile by death threats.
</P>
<P>
   Colombia is on the eve of long-awaited peace negotiations that,
despite a rocky prelude, many still hope will end the violence.
Gomez Mendez, on a visit to Washington this month, talked with
writer Ana Carrigan about what his life is like, and what's in
store for his country. Here are edited excerpts from their
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can a Colombian chief prosecutor ever relax? When was the
last time you went to a restaurant with friends?
</P>
<P>
   A. I rarely go. If I do, the owner lets me know he would like me
to leave because he fears he will lose his customers. He will offer
to send meals to my office just to keep me away. So I lunch
everyday in my bunker.
</P>
<P>
   That is also the reason I cannot travel on a commercial flight.
Even 10 years ago, when I was attorney general, I boarded a
commercial flight one day and this woman said, ``Senor Gomez, why
are you exposing us to danger? Why can't you travel in your own
private plane?'' So I don't go out much. I spend the weekends shut
up in my apartment, like a prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the hardest thing?
</P>
<P>
   A. The loneliness. I can have no personal life. I can't even
keep my family with me. My eldest son just had to leave the country
because of threats from (paramilitary leader) Carlos Castano. And I
feel very isolated. I know some democrats in Colombia understand
what I am doing and support me, but they are afraid to say so in
public. So the only things that appear in the press are the lies,
the personal attacks, to which I cannot respond.
</P>
<P>
   Take our struggle to combat the paramilitaries. In Colombia many
people believe that because the paramilitaries fight the guerrillas
they should be supported. Often, even important people come to me
and say: ``How is it possible that you are putting the
paramilitaries in jail when they are helping us to fight the
guerrillas?''
</P>
<P>
   I think Colombians have not understood the gravity of the
paramilitary menace. Ten years ago, when I was attorney general, I
said that the problem of the self-defense groups _ as they were
known then _ was extremely serious and that unless something was
done about the tolerance for these people among certain sections of
the armed forces the problem would spin out of control. Today I
believe it is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Two weeks ago, the sudden resignation of the minister of
defense appeared to bring Colombia close to a military coup. Then
spokesmen for the army and and the government denied that anything
had happened. What is the truth?
</P>
<P>
   A. What happened on that day should not be minimized. In spite
of what has been said, I do not consider it normal that half the
generals and most of the colonels should all resign on the same
day. I think the Army was upset by the way the peace process has
been handled, and I agree that the president needs to bring them
into the process with him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. At the time, there were reports that the generals were
angered by your investigations of army officers allegedly complicit
in paramilitary massacres and high-profile assassinations. It was
also reported that President Pastrana agreed to the generals'
demands that no officers would be retired from active service
because of ongoing investigations by the prosecutors, and that he
would not press for passage through Congress of the military penal
code reforms. What will be the implications for your work?
</P>
<P>
   A. The prosecutor's office is independent of the executive, and
we will continue working in our own, solitary way. I know I am
rowing upstream against the current. I know there are many circles
in Colombia who think I am wrong to investigate members of the
armed forces. Yet I consider that there is no alternative. We
cannot retreat. We are not _ as our enemies claim _ ``persecuting''
these officers, nor presuming their guilt. But these investigations
must be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, the question is whether it is possible to
investigate criminal actions which are alleged to have been
committed by members of the armed forces or not. My position is
that in a ``rule of law'' country, a democracy which respects the
law, it must be possible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is there a conflict between the struggle to combat impunity
(for those who commit crimes) and the peace process?
</P>
<P>
   A. I said at the start of the peace process that impunity should
not be the price of peace. At least not for all crimes. Not for
massacres. Nor for crimes against international human rights laws.
I know this is unpopular. The guerrillas consider me an obstacle to
peace. Colombians say to me, ``Look, we've been fighting for 40
years, we must do everything in our power to have peace.'' But I
think giving amnesty to people who have kidnapped, tortured, and
killed civilians is not the way to build a stable and lasting
peace. Even peace should have its limits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What, in your view, are the main pitfalls ahead for the peace
process?
</P>
<P>
   A. Colombians were led to believe at the start that just because
the president and Tiro Fijo (leader of the guerrillas) had met,
peace would somehow follow automatically. Now people have grown
impatient. They think peace has failed. Colombians don't want to
understand that a peace process is very long, very difficult, and
very complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Secondly: There is no consensus in Colombia concerning the
concessions which will have to be made in return for peace. If you
look at the agenda (for negotiations) . . . everyone is agreed
about the need for social justice, the urgency to combat
corruption, to defeat impunity, etc. The problem comes with the
``how.'' How do you achieve these objectives? No one is preparing
Colombian society for this ``how.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there has not been enough discussion about the
necessity that the state should not lose its legitimacy by
employing the same methods the delinquents use. I am referring to
the paramilitaries and the problems of combating them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. International human rights organizations like the
Inter-American Commission and the United Nations have called for
the abolition of Colombia's ``faceless'' courts (in which judges,
prosecutors, and witnesses are masked). They charge that the use of
anonymous, or ``faceless'' judges, prosecutors, and witnesses does
not provide due process guarantees for criminal defendants. Why are
you opposed to abolishing these courts?
</P>
<P>
   A. As a law professor, I too would oppose them. But you must
recognize the Colombian reality; 211 judicial workers were murdered
in this country before we had the faceless courts.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to testify in Paris against ``the Jackal'' and
then go for a quiet stroll on the Champs Elysees. It's quite
another to go to a town in Colombia run by the paramilitaries and
testify against Carlos Castano. Or can you imagine a witness
testifying against the guerrillas in a zone controlled by the
guerrillas?
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to say: The witnesses must be identified and the state
should protect them. Do you have any idea how much it costs when
the witness says: You must not only protect me, you have to protect
my family, you have to take my children and my brothers and sisters
and find them homes outside Colombia?' That's not possible for
Colombia. I think the international community has initiated this
debate without an adequate understanding of Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In March, guerrillas of the Armed Revolutionary Forces of
Colombia (or FARC) admitted to abducting and murdering three young
American activists in a region close to the Venezuela border. Your
office has since issued an arrest warrant for the guerrilla
commander of the region. In Washington, there have been calls for
his extradition. How do you feel about extradition?
</P>
<P>
   A. If we succeed in arresting the people who committed this
crime, then I prefer to put them on trial in Colombia. That, for
me, is the ideal. They should go on trial for murder and
kidnapping, and if guilty they should be sentenced to the maximum
penalty allowed by the law in Colombia. That is 60 years in jail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. You admit you get little support or even understanding for
the job you are doing. Yet you risk your life daily. Why do you go
on?
</P>
<P>
   A. (A long pause) Because I love my country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
