u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEMS-GUN-POLITICS-NYT     06-13 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-GUN-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3 VOICES INSISTING ON GUN CONTROL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Almost every day, the three lawmakers hold a news
conference, resurrecting the same pleas and plaints and seeming
never to tire of their mantras.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn B. McCarthy, D-N.Y., begs Americans to think about
all the children killed by gunfire. Rep. Nita M. Lowey, D-N.Y.,
decries the influence in Congress of the National Rifle
Association. Rep. Rosa L. DeLauro, D-Conn., urges common sense over
abstract ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes other Democrats join them, sometimes not, but these
three are always there, perhaps the most insistent voices and the
most public faces attached to their party's battle in the House for
new restrictions on firearms.
</P>
<P>
   It is no accident that they are all women.
</P>
<P>
   With an eye not only on the fate of legislation scheduled to
come to the House floor on Wednesday but also on the pivotal 2000
elections, Mrs. McCarthy, Ms. Lowey, Ms. DeLauro and their party
leaders are betting that gun control is a sure winner among women
voters and that it makes sense to have women sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it from party polling, and I know it from personal
experience,'' Ms. Lowey said. ``In the supermarket, they're the
ones who stop me with one kid in one hand, another kid in the
other, and say, `What are you going to do about this?'''
</P>
<P>
   That is especially good news for Democrats at a time when their
party's most likely presidential candidate, Vice President Al Gore,
has not come close to sewing up the kind of backing from women
voters that swept President Clinton into office.
</P>
<P>
   In one national poll last month, Gore had less support among
women voters than either of two contenders for the Republican
Presidential nomination: Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
front-runner, and Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists are hoping that Gore's firm stand for gun
control will help. At a Capitol Hill news conference to promote the
issue just before Memorial Day, Gore positioned himself beside a
mother whose son had been killed by gunfire, and the tableau of
House Democrats around them was disproportionately female.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are leading the charge on this,'' Ms. DeLauro said.
</P>
<P>
   That is true outside the Democratic Party as well. Mrs. Dole has
spoken out more loudly and frequently in favor of new restrictions
on firearms than any of her Republican rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Among moderate House Republicans who support the gun-control
provisions that were passed by the Senate, Rep.e Marge Roukema of
New Jersey and Rep. Constance A. Morella of Maryland are
particularly prominent, and both have been invited to join the
president at a White House rally and news conference on Tuesday
that will feature female lawmakers who favor gun control.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats have been most assiduous about framing and
promoting the issue of gun control in a manner that pivots off the
school shooting in Littleton, Colo., and that is intended to appeal
directly to women.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding alarms about the prevalence of guns in America, they no
longer talk of crime but of child safety, with the presumption that
the phrase will resonate especially strongly with women. They seem
to miss the irony that the same political party that claimed
ownership of the position that women could be more than mothers is,
in this instance, casting them primarily in that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that affects children,'' Mrs. McCarthy said,
``and I think women find they have a maternal instinct about
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is the explanation or not, polls taken by Democrats
show that women care more about gun-control legislation than men do
and are more likely to let their votes be influenced by a
candidate's position on gun control, according to several
Democratic aides.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCarthy, Ms. Lowey and Ms. DeLauro were not recruited for
their current roles in light of those findings. Rather, they said,
they stepped to the foreground of an issue they had long been
passionate about and that party leaders almost immediately
encouraged them to stay there.
</P>
<P>
   They form an interesting trio.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCarthy, whose husband was killed by gunfire on the Long
Island Rail Road, speaks softly but carries a heavy burden of
sorrow that seems to tug downward on her features, giving her a
world-weary mien.
</P>
<P>
   It is she who, in addition to appearing at a never-ending string
of news conferences, makes the most frequent trips across the aisle
of the House to solicit support among moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they see me as someone who is not on a political
agenda,'' said Mrs. McCarthy, whose grown son, Kevin, her only
child, was critically injured by the same hail of bullets that left
her a widow. ``This is personal for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lowey, whose decade in the House makes her the most senior
member of the three, radiates an assurance and serenity that helps
veil the partisanship of her verbal attacks. Ms. DeLauro is
preternaturally intense, a live wire whose words rush out like
sparks.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, these three have become central players in
the lobbying effort to make sure as few Democrats as possible leave
the party's fold on gun control and as many Republicans as possible
side with Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic aides grumble that the job has been thrust upon
Mrs. McCarthy, Ms. Lowey and Ms. DeLauro because many senior
Democrats have been reluctant to assume aggressive roles on an
issue that they believe helped cost them their majority in the
House in 1994. During that election, the NRA backed Republicans
against Democrats in a number of crucial Congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are differing opinions in our caucus,'' Ms. Lowey
acknowledged. ``But if the House doesn't pass gun control, that
failure will be on the doorstep of Republican leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
