<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICKES-POLITICAL-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD ICKES RETURNS, A HAPPY WARRIOR FOR MRS. CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Ickes is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With all the cuts and bruises he bears from the
Clinton incumbency _ five grand jury summonses and a searing
banishment by the president himself _ Harold M. Ickes would seem
the last guru in town to be advising Hillary Rodham Clinton on the
joys of the political arena.
</P>
<P>
   But here he is, attracting hail-fellow backslaps and waves in a
restaurant a block from the White House, a man restored to his
combative element as he eagerly maps out the first lady's approach
to a Senate run from New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guarantee that Hillary Clinton will go toe to toe with the
best of them,'' Ickes says as exuberantly as a prize fight
corner-man summoned back to the championship canvas. ``In any ring,
I'd put my money on Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   As he relishes that possibility, Ickes' own passion for politics
is glaringly clear, all the way back to clubhouse fights in New
York with the likes of the late former congresswoman Bella Abzug, a
beloved politician in his memory. ``Listen you, I'll mash you into
Broadway!'' he recalls threatening Ms. Abzug as they exchanged
brickbats in the old days.
</P>
<P>
   No less will Mrs. Clinton be up to whatever Abzugian
cut-and-thrust might still be required in the streets and rural
hamlets of New York, Ickes firmly insists, even against the
pugnaciously ambitious Republican contender, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Creatively profane and fiercely partisan, Ickes is a 59-year-old
Democratic warhorse and former deputy chief of staff at the White
House. Through thick and thin, Whitewater and campaign finance, he
labored in the West Wing _ only to be dropped by the president in a
power squeeze two years ago as Ickes hoped for the chief of staff's
job. Thereafter, as he sought to establish a consulting business,
Ickes &AMP; Enright, he has been relentlessly summoned and vetted a
dozen times by prosecutors and Republican congressional committees
searching for administration scandal.
</P>
<P>
   After such rough times, Mrs. Clinton's evolving candidacy is
presenting him a note of grand redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, they're my friends,'' Ickes said, spiritedly
responding to the question of why, after all his travail in
associating with the Clintons, he would be there for them now.
``I've known them for 25 years,'' he said, describing them as two
of the most progressive and effective Democrats he has known in 35
years of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Years back, he had avoided politics and sneered at Washington
power-tripping as the teen-age son of Secretary of the Interior
Harold Ickes in the Roosevelt administration. He became a dropout
who preferred working at the family's bluegrass sod farm in Olney,
Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running away from my father for years,'' he admitted,
noting he drifted west to become a horse wrangler and get a pilot's
license, and then finally went to college at Stanford. There, he
signed up for the 1964 summer protest tour against racial
segregation in the Deep South, where he lost a kidney in a mob
beating. By 1967, at the side of Allard K. Lowenstein, the storied
liberal organizer, Ickes was fully hooked, plunging deeply into the
Democratic insurgent politics that, in 1968, toppled President
Lyndon B. Johnson over the issue of the Vietnam war.
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, he worked for assorted candidates, scuttling
about convention halls, raising money and becoming a specialist in
campaign law arcana that he refers to as ``the incumbents
protection act.'' In a way, Ickes has now come full circle,
operating as an unabashed political insider in the capital he once
shunned. He and his wife, Laura R. Handman, a lawyer, have a
13-year-old daughter, Charlotte Jane, who attends Sidwell Friends,
the exclusive school spurned by the young Ickes (and which Chelsea
Clinton attended).
</P>
<P>
   But friendship and ideas, not clinging to power, is the true
stuff of politics for him, he maintains. His shepherding of Mrs.
Clinton in what he calls her ``great adventure'' is a matter of
abiding friendship, he says, stressing she is deep into the
venture, ready to rebut all carpetbagging notions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know _ Hillary just told me _ that Orange County is
the largest producer of onions east of the Mississippi?'' Ickes
asked with an innocent grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Hillary the only time I would urge her not to run was
if I felt she could not deal with the press,'' Ickes said,
admitting concern and foreseeing a ``trial period'' if she runs,
when ``the Fourth Estate will see if she can take the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like a hazing period,'' he said, insisting Mrs.
Clinton would weather it favorably.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has the chutzpah and the grit,'' he said with the panache
of the wannabe cowpoke. ``Even if she loses it will be worth the
candle _ for her and her supporters. The cautious side of our
nature says, don't do it; the bold says, go for it. You know what?
You've got to give her credit: she'll probably go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Swearing happily at the idea, Ickes exulted that all the shared
trials and tribulations of the Clinton incumbency might yet prove,
for Mrs. Clinton, to be mere roadwork for a match with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ``My view?'' he said, hunching in like a corner-man before the
bell. ``Keep her cool. Her initial instinct might be to take him
head-on. But I suspect she'll end up feinting, sidestepping, and
then coming back at him,'' he said, flashing a jack-o'-lantern grin
as he envisioned his fresh prospect. ``As you grow older, you learn
to feint more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
