<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLAND-POPE-ART-NYT &LR;      06-13 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLAND-POPE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING HISTORY WITH THE POPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARSAW, Poland _ Finding herself once again at the spot where
she and more than a million other Poles gathered 20 years ago to
greet Pope John Paul II, Anna Jamroz, 42, could not help comparing
the two Masses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought of freedom when he spoke,'' she recalled of
that historic moment when the newly elected pope gave his first
homily in Poland and gave spark to the Solidarity workers'
movement, which eventually brought down Communism. ``I remember so
well the spontaneity, the enthusiasm. We were so joyful, we wept.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same Warsaw square Sunday, once again there were at least
one million people and tears as the ailing pope, wearing a small
bandage over the cut he received when he fell on Saturday, repeated
the same words he delivered on June 2, 1979, which sent a frisson
of rebellion throughout Poland: ``Let the Holy Spirit bring renewal
on the face of the land _ this land.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the pope instructed Poles to use their hard-won freedom
to follow God and the church. As if to set the standard, he then
beatified 108 Catholics killed by the Nazis during World War II as
martyrs who died defending their faith.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jamroz, a hospital psychologist, said her thoughts at the
Mass were mostly about those who were suffering under Poland's
newly minted democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is freedom, and so many of us think only about our
own business,'' she said. The nurses at her hospital have been on
strike, along with nurses throughout Poland, protesting low wages
that rarely exceed about $180 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to think more about the poor, unemployed and the
homeless,'' she said. ``We need to use our freedom to understand
each other better.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope himself came close to tears a little later in the day,
when he knelt to pray in a military cemetery in Radzymin, where
more than 1,000 soldiers died in 1920 repelling an advance by
Soviet forces seeking to spread the Communist revolution further
west.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd chanted, ``Speak to us, speak to us,'' prompting the
pope to scrap his plans for a silent tribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, you are right,'' he replied. ``You know, I was born in
1920 at the time when the Bolsheviks were on their way to Warsaw. I
feel I have a heavy debt to those who fought against the Bolsheviks
and won.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian A. Hendler, 94, said he viewed the pope as still quite
young. He sat in the front row with fewer than a dozen other
veterans in faded uniforms covered in medals, basking in
acknowledgments that were not allowed under Communist rule and that
even today are dimmed by fresher memories of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1920 he was a 15-year-old Boy Scout who volunteered for the
front. ``I would like people to remember that it wasn't just young
men,'' he said. ``There were also Boy Scouts in the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who held four events Sunday, has kept up a grueling
schedule. His voice has stayed firm, but age and Parkinson's
disease have taken their toll, and Poles cannot help noticing.
``You can tell he is very weak,'' noted Lukasz Kadzinski, 22, a
third-year seminarian in Warsaw. ``What is extraordinary is that he
makes a lot of jokes.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope has command of close to a dozen languages, but Polish
is his mother tongue. On many occasions he has broken through the
solemnity of the moment to tease his audience.
</P>
<P>
   He did it again at his last event, a prayer service in
Warsaw-Praga, on the eastern side of the Vistula River. As a huge
crowd chanted over and over, ``We love you,'' the pope smiled and
said, ``Since you are busy shouting now, I will take a short
rest.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to insure a wholesome visit for the pope, the
Polish government banned alcohol sales in every town he visited. In
Torun local officials prevented the sale of vodka, wine and beer _
and also ice cream and mayonnaise, fearful that sober pilgrims
might somehow contract salmonella poisoning and disgrace their
town.
</P>
<P>
   Warsaw has been under strict prohibition for four days. The
nuptuals of Anna Sztampke, 26, and Barlomiej Golab, 27, may well
have been the first dry wedding in the capital's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to book the restaurant a year ahead of time,'' said
Malgorzata Sztampke, the mother of the bride. A few couples danced
listlessly. Other guests wistfully sipped orange soda while eying a
fully-stocked bar guarded by a fierce waiter. ``The pope and my
daughter's wedding are two very special events,'' Mrs. Sztampke
said firmly. ``I am happy they could coincide.''
</P>
<P>
   Storefronts of every book shop in Warsaw are filled with John
Paul II _ biographies, the pope's own many writings, colorful
coffee table books and calendars. But inside, Polish intellectuals
can find the kind of trendy modern philosophers the pope deplores _
Michel Foucault, Jacques Derrida and Terry Eagleton, the
post-postmodernist author of ``The Illusions of Postmodernism.''
</P>
<P>
   The pope, who relied heavily on former colleagues at his alma
mater, the Catholic University of Lublin, to write ``Fides et
Ratio,'' his encyclical on the ills of contemporary philosophy,
seems eager to stamp out at home the kind of moral relativism that
flourishes in the West. Archbishop Jozef Zycinski of Lublin, a
philosopher of science, recently came to the pope's aid by
publishing several articles attacking Polish postmodernism.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the empiricist has no clothes, though. ``There are
almost no postmodernists in Poland,'' explained Cezary Wodzinski, a
philosophy professor at the Polish Academy of Sciences in Warsaw.
``Postmodernists are for church theologians what Jews are for the
nationalist Catholic extremists,'' he said dryly. ``In Poland they
are both an imaginary enemy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
