<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3686 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-AIR-SHOW-SPI &LR;      06-13 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIR-SHOW-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANE MAKERS EXPECT ORDERS TO FALL SHARPLY THIS YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Commercial airplane orders will be down significantly
this year because of the global economic slowdown, executives of
The Boeing Co. and rival Airbus Industrie warned Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see substantially fewer orders for the industry than we saw
last year,'' Boeing Commercial Airplane President Alan Mulally told
reporters at the Paris Air Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason is a slowdown in the economy, especially in
Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Asia also offers hope of a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see that leveling out next year.... We are cautiously
optimistic because of Asia that we will see orders start to come
back in 2001.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Sunday, Mulally also said Boeing will stick
with its 100-seater 717.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very bullish on the airplane,'' he said.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales have been slow for Boeing's newest and smallest plane, and
many industry analysts have speculated the 717 will soon get the ax
if sales don't pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has 110 firm orders for its 717, with options for 110
more.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran (formerly ValuJet), the launch customer for what was a
McDonnell Douglas plane until the 1997 merger with Boeing, will get
its first 717 in September. Boeing flew one of the planes that will
go to AirTran to the Paris show as part of an aggressive marketing
campaign to win new customers.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said executives
were reviewing the 717 project as part of a companywide initiative
to seek out ``value destroying'' programs and either fix or get rid
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have completed our analysis, and we are going to go forward
on the 717, the 737, the 757, the 767, the 777 and the 747 because
they are all value-creating projects,'' Mulally insisted.
</P>
<P>
   His comments came during a news conference where he and other
executives gave an overview of Boeing's three divisions _ the
Commercial Airplanes Group, the Military Aircraft and Missile
Systems Group and the Space &AMP; Communications Group.
</P>
<P>
   When asked after the news conference if he were certain the 717
program would not get the ax, Mulally replied ``absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 100 percent behind it,'' he said. ``We are absolutely
committed to the 717.''
</P>
<P>
   And he reaffirmed his earlier comments that the value analysis
was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have completed it with all our airplane programs, and we
are going ahead with the lineup that we showed today.''
</P>
<P>
   That lineup included all Boeing planes now in production other
than the MD-11, MD-80 and MD-90. After the 1997 merger, Boeing
announced it would phase out production of those McDonnell Douglas
planes that are built in Long Beach, Calif., along with the 717.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Boeing is cutting production of its flagship 747 to
two planes a month, mostly because of the Asian economic slump,
Mulally said the plane has plenty of orders left.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has delivered about 1,200 of the jumbo jets over the past
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think customers will want another 1,000 over the next 20
years,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Customers may want a 747 with greater range as well as one that
can carry more people, and Boeing is prepared to build a newer
version 747 if that's what the marketplace decides, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will keep upgrading the 747,'' he said. ``If customers want
a little bit more range and a little bigger girth, we will make a
bigger 747 for them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Boeing has ``a lot of option'' with the 747.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step probably will be a little more range,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Boeing briefing, Airbus Managing Director Noel
Forgeard took the same auditorium stage to talk about the European
airplane maker.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said Airbus will go ahead with the development of a
super jumbo that it has dubbed the A3XX. It will carry as many as
600 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has long maintained that its analysis of the market shows
there is not enough demand for a plane the size of the A3XX that
would justify its huge development costs.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said Sunday that development of the A3XX will cost
about $11 billion. That is up a billion dollars from a year ago,
when Forgeard told reporters at the Farnborough air show in London
that development of the A3XX would be about $10 billion. Until
then, Airbus had maintained that the plane could be developed for
only $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus is convinced there is a market for 1,500 planes the size
of the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium of four European partners is working with 20
airlines to define the plane. Those airlines, including United,
Japan Air Lines and British Airways, all want Airbus to build the
A3XX, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Airbus hopes to launch the A3XX next year and have it
ready for market entry by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   It will be at least 15 percent more efficient than Boeing's
747-400, he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   But Forgeard said the decision to go ahead with development will
not be made until he's certain Airbus will get a 20 percent return
on its investment.
</P>
<P>
   For Europe, the biggest news at the air show Sunday was an
announcement by Forgeard that two of the four Airbus partners had
made peace in what had become something of a civil war over where
the new A318 would be assembled.
</P>
<P>
   The A318 will compete with Boeing's 717 in the 100-seat market.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospatiale Matra, the French Airbus partner, wanted the A318
to be assembled in Toulouse, where it builds the A320 and the
widebody Airbus planes.
</P>
<P>
   The German partner, DaimlerChrysler Aerospace AG, _ which Friday
acquired a controlling interest in CASA, the Spanish partner in
Airbus _ wanted to assemble the new plane in Hamburg. The A318 is a
shortened version of the A319, which is assembled in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   As part of an agreement reached in the past few days, Forgeard
said Hamburg will get to assemble the A318, but some A319 assembly
work will be shifted to Toulouse.
</P>
<P>
   At the Airbus news conference, Forgeard was asked about
Mulally's bleak 1999 order assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not as pessimistic as our competitor,'' Forgeard said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Airbus should land at least 300 new airplane orders this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Paris show, Airbus had a total of 153 orders in
1999. Like Boeing, it will add to that number over the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally had told reporters at Sunday's press conference that
1999 orders will be down as much as 40 percent from 1998, when
Boeing customers ordered 656 airplanes. Boeing later issued a
clarification, saying Mulally was talking about the overall airline
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Mulally, president of Boeing Commercial Airplanes Group,
said that he thought airplane orders in dollars would be 30 percent
to 40 percent less than they were in 1998 for the entire commercial
airplane industry,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, Boeing has only 52 firm orders worth about
$3.9 billion at list prices. That number, though, will increase
sharply over the next few days during the world's oldest and
largest air show. Boeing is expected to announce several orders
here, including one for about 100 Next Generation 737s by
International Lease Finance Corp. Forgeard said Airbus, which
launched its first plane, the A300 at the Paris show 30 years ago,
said Airbus is now Boeing's equal in market share.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the world's two remaining makers of commercial jets
with more than 100 seats put their spin on who's the top dog.
</P>
<P>
   While Airbus has gained market share against Boeing, Mulally
noted that Boeing delivers more planes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing delivered a record 560 planes and expects to
deliver 620 planes this year.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus delivered 229 planes in 1998 and will deliver fewer than
300 this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent of all planes delivered last year were Boeing
planes,'' Mulally said, adding the same will be true in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
