<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, THE ELDER, PASSES THE BATON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine _ With the craggy Maine coastline at his
back, former President George Bush _ poised, animated and
displaying not a bit of regret _ stepped aside Sunday to advance
the presidential ambitions of his son, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas. It was a poignant, if staged, familial passing of the baton,
suggesting that a victory by Governor Bush in 2000 might redress
the lingering memory of his father's defeat by Bill Clinton seven
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my chance,'' former President Bush said, standing with
his son on the lawn of his family compound as the wind blew in from
the ocean. ``And I got some things right. Maybe I messed some
things up. But it's his turn now in the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it did not quite turn out to be the younger Bush's day.
For all his attempts at deference to his son, the older and more
seasoned Bush dominated their joint appearance, which came as the
former president held a family celebration of his 75th birthday,
which actually was on Saturday, and a day after Governor Bush
declared his presidential intentions in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush was reflective, light-hearted and charming. He
grinned and waved from the microphone as he caught sight of
familiar faces from his old White House press corps. He confessed
his own errors as a campaigner and said he would stay out of his
son's campaign. ``He doesn't need a voice from the past,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as the younger Bush retreated to the house for a
nap, the former president lingered on the lawn, inviting question
after question until a young aide, tugging on his coat sleeve,
pulled him away.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the former president, who seemed startled at the
size of the press corps that turned out _ 28 television crews,
including some from Japan and Germany _ had a chance to reflect on
the changing in the Bush family fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean I was unpopular,'' Bush said to a reporter who had
asked about his defeat. ``And I was. But what goes around comes
around, and I guess I was elected president once back in 1988. And
then I see George out in Iowa and I say, Hey _ I've been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush allowed that his son might be the better campaigner. ``I
used to get a little uptight from time to time, mainly in the last
year of my presidency,'' Bush said. ``I think I was better earlier
on. But I got _ I knew I was in a very difficult fight. Maybe I let
it show too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even as he promoted his son, Bush recoiled when a
reporter suggested this was the start of a new American dynasty.
``Family,'' Bush responded firmly. ``I don't like the dynasty
concept. We never felt that we were entitled to something.''
</P>
<P>
   The former president repeatedly said he had no intention of
telling his son how to run for president. ``He doesn't need advice
from me,'' he said. ``I'll be there to support him if he just needs
help and someone to love him. But we're not, I'm not, in the advice
mission business.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, Bush's syntax collapsed in on itself. The former
president stopped himself, grinning at the memories of White House
press conferences gone by. ``I'm the same guy,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
