<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ADS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD-BLOCKING SOFTWARE WORRIES SOME E-COMMERCE, MEDIA COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN COOK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Since the invention of the remote control, television
viewers have had little trouble ignoring commercials. It's as
simple as turning the channel, hitting the mute button or heading
to the bathroom for a three-minute pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding advertising on the Internet, however, has never been
that easy. Online banner ads, which command a prominent position on
many Web sites, are facts of life in the cyber-marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   But now with the introduction of software from companies such as
Siemens AG, WRQ Inc. and Junkbusters Inc., Web surfers have the
ability to simply turn off Web ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like a mute button (for the Internet),'' said Anne
Marshall, product marketing manager at Seattle-based WRQ, which
last July released ad-blocking software called AtGuard.
</P>
<P>
   The software, which sells for $30, works as a filtering device,
blocking advertisements before they are downloaded on a Web page.
</P>
<P>
   That has several benefits for computer users.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does it give them control over the marketing messages
they receive, it also speeds up Internet performance by eliminating
clunky banner ads and graphics. In some instances, download times
can be cut from 2 minutes to 30 seconds, Marshall said.
</P>
<P>
   While the ad-blocking technology benefits consumers who feel
bombarded with product pitches, it is causing a stir among
e-commerce and media companies that hope to generate revenue
through online advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something that could be a concern for us,'' said Andy
Liu, chief executive of FreeDollar.com, a new Seattle startup that
plans to make money by selling targeted advertisements and e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   The filtering technology, which also blocks unwanted e-mail and
Web identification tags known as ``cookies,'' has forced some
e-commerce companies to re-evaluate their business models and
advertising strategies.
</P>
<P>
   Due in part to the blocking technology, Bellevue-based
Altrec.com, an Internet retailer of outdoor gear and apparel, has
decided to focus more on print, radio and television advertising in
an upcoming national marketing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``These blocking issues are just another reason why it is
important to build brand awareness offline,'' said Erick
Soderstrom, vice president of marketing at the 25-person startup.
``We are keeping a keen eye on the resources we spend on online
advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad-blocking issue recently landed Seattle-based RealNetworks
in a bit of hot water.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle pioneer of streaming media software last month
canceled an agreement to distribute the AtGuard product after some
of RealNetworks' key customers, which include major e-commerce and
media companies, complained that the software could hurt their
advertising revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said WRQ's software is not designed to damage
advertisers or companies that make money through online
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``WRQ buys advertising, so we are not against it,'' she said.
``What this product does is allow the user to choose.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Avenue A, which coordinates online advertising
efforts for e-commerce companies, could feel a big impact from the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-year-old Internet startup generates revenue by placing
online advertisements for top-tier clients such as Eddie Bauer,
Soma.com and uBid. But Mike Leo, co-founder of the 90-person
company, is not too concerned about ad-blocking products such as
AtGuard, Web Washer and InterMute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get this question all of the time,'' said Leo. ``But the
fact is right now there are very few people who are using this
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall would not disclose revenue figures for AtGuard. But The
New York Times recently reported that the popularity of the
software is on the rise and that Siemens' Web Washer product is
being used by about 1 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that is a small percentage of the estimated 76.5 million
Web users in the United States. And it is not yet a threat to the
$4.4 billion that research firm Jupiter Communications estimates
companies will spend on online advertising by next year.
</P>
<P>
   The software is not curtailing Eddie Bauer's online advertising
plans. Steve Kahn, marketing manager for interactive media at the
Redmond, Wash. retailer, said Eddie Bauer is planning to ``ramp
up'' its banner ads on Internet shopping sites in the coming
months.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kahn believes consumers should have the choice to block
advertisements, he added that many shoppers want information on new
products, discounts and other services delivered through
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Even if more people adopt the ad-blocking technology, Avenue A's
Leo believes advertising will continue to drive e-commerce and
media Web sites. The alternative _ paying subscription fees to
access Web sites _ is a model that has failed in the past, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this issue becomes larger _ at this time it is a small blip
on the radar screen of publishers _ 99.8 percent of people will say
give me an advertisement over paying for content,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
