A3697 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-13 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE WRONG WAY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many of my readers are, in S.J. Perelman's phrase,
``afflicted with total recall.''
</P>
<P>
   They remember that one week ago, under the heading ``Lessons of
Kosovo,'' the lead sentence in this space was ``In Kosovo, the
Western world is doing the right thing in the wrong way.'' My
conclusion: ``Civilization is more civilized for having intervened
to do the right thing. Next time we are more likely to do it the
right way.'' Emphasis was added in the subhead: ``Right thing,
wrong way.''
</P>
<P>
   With that nicely balanced opinion off my chest, I settled back
to watch the president of the United States address the nation. One
of my Bernese mountain dogs, Emily _ a hundred pounds of wriggling
love _ was at my side.
</P>
<P>
   (Emily is no ordinary bitch. Last month, she was Chairbitch of
the Washington Humane Society's annual ``Bark Ball,'' and impressed
500 black-tied owners and their 200 canine companions with her
incredible response to a complex command. When I said ``Sit!''
Emily actually sat, to the cheers and excited yapping of the
audience.)
</P>
<P>
   There was President Clinton on the tube from the Oval Office.
Over one shoulder was the Robert Berks bust of Lincoln, over the
other the Jo Davidson bust of FDR, both castings evoking memories
of great wartime presidents. Behind him was an array of 400
medallions presented to him by members of the armed forces, proof
that the defense establishment is devoted to him.
</P>
<P>
   On this serious occasion, Clinton's demeanor was formal and his
tone suitably solemn. I was part of the vast American public
listening to our elected leader _ until he came to the last line:
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kosovo,'' he concluded, ``we did the right thing. We did it
the right way. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's talking to me, personally,'' I said to Emily. ``He
disagrees with what I wrote were the lessons of Kosovo, and he is
sticking it in my ear in front of the whole world.''
</P>
<P>
   Emily put a large paw on my arm and gave me a look that said:
``There's nobody there. All that flickering light on the screen is
not accompanied by a human scent. You only imagine somebody is
talking directly to you, but my nose assures me nobody is there.''
</P>
<P>
   She's ordinarily sensible, but in this case she's mistaken.
Maybe the president does not deign to read op-ed pages, but his
speechwriters surely do, and this was Clinton's most direct
engagement of my position since he threatened to punch me in the
nose for calling his wife a congenial lawyer, or whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Pleased with his ringing refutation of my judgment, the proud
possessor of 400 military medallions repeated it to Jim Lehrer in a
PBS ``Newshour'' interview the next day: ``I'm confident that I did
the right thing in the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus has the president found his phrase to reject any error. Was
it ``the right way'' to promise Milosevic no ground war from the
start? Turning truth on its head, he told Lehrer: ``Repeatedly . .
. I said I thought we ought to be planning for ground forces.''
There goes that old compulsion to prevaricate when it's not
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Was bombing at little risk from three miles up the best way to
save innocent Kosovars being killed on the ground? That lesson was
slyly twisted by Clinton into ``the suggestion that our moral
position would have been improved if only a few Americans had
died.'' Low blows do not get any lower _ even as he suggests that
his critics ``lighten up.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it ``the right way'' to trust Russia, NATO's opponent, to be
NATO's negotiator? Because Clinton naively believed Yeltsin, the
airfield of Kosovo's capital _ our designated command center of the
occupation _ was pre-emptively seized by pro-Serbian Russian troops
as if opening a Templehof. (Now we learn that one quick-stepping
company of the Red Army might have taken Paris during the Cold War
before musclebound NATO could ever get its gear in gear.)
</P>
<P>
   This stonewalling leaves me trying to explain to Emily that the
man on the screen is personally taking me on because he refuses to
admit he was fallible on anything. She continues to insist that
nobody is there and she may be right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
