</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON SAYS HE'LL PLAY, BUT CAN'T SAY WHEN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Larry Johnson pulled into the parking lot and
creakily eased his way out of his car soon after the sun rose
Sunday. It was 6:30 a.m., but Johnson, in pain from his sprained
right knee, had alerted the team's trainer Mike Saunders to be
ready to start treatment early. So Johnson, hooked up to an
electronic stimulation machine, then to an ultrasound, then packed
with ice, then trying on braces, whiled away his morning, finally
peeking at a videotape of the collision with Indiana's Travis Best
that had put his availability for the National Basketball
Association finals in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors had told Johnson that he probably saved himself
further injury because, after Best rolled into him, Johnson picked
up his right leg right away. It was that instinct _ instead of
planting the foot _ that may have salvaged his chances of playing
when the Knicks face the San Antonio Spurs in the
four-of-seven-game series that begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``About Game 1, I don't want to say no and then play,'' Johnson
said. ``It's sore now. I can't straighten it. But this is the
finals, so I've got to get out there. The doctors reassured me that
it's not torn and that, with a brace I can't _ knock on wood _
reinjure it by playing. That's all I needed to hear. With pain,
we've just go to fight through the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wore no brace as he talked. He was annoyed by the bulky
one that had hobbled him Saturday and he later took it off to do
some pool exercises on the day after the Knicks clinched their
series against the Pacers. He watched the final two minutes of that
game while awaiting his magnetic resonance imaging test at a
hospital. He was mad and glad at the same time, bothered that he
was missing the celebration, thrilled that he was going to his
first NBA finals in his eight-year career.
</P>
<P>
   But the joy has been tempered by this latest setback. Johnson
has played the season in almost constant pain from knee and back
injuries, but it has been nothing like this. He thought, when he
was curled up at the baseline, screaming, that his season was over.
He thought it on the way to the hospital. Only when the doctors
told him that it was just a sprain, that he could be ready in a
week or two, did Johnson believe he would return.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he cannot jog, cannot even straighten the leg. He did not
practice with the team today, and nobody knows when he will again.
Johnson said the knee felt better on Saturday, when he worked out
in the pool, but not so good today. That is why he called Saunders
and why he will let the doctors put a time line on his recovery.
Game 3, the first in Madison Square Garden, is next Monday _ 10
days after the injury. Whenever it is, Johnson is convinced that he
will play in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pain is pain,'' he said. ``What I hate more than sitting out
is being on the floor and not being 100 percent. You know you can
make this move, or guard this guy better, but something is
hampering you from doing it, and in the NBA finals I hate that more
than sitting out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks need Johnson. San Antonio, which has won 42 of its
last 48 games, has been so dominant since starting the season 6-8
that Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy said: ``I told our video
coordinator to put up all their losses; I want to see the teams
that beat them in the last three months. And he gives me this
little stack of tapes.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson, who is averaging 12.7 points a game in the playoffs,
cannot play on Wednesday, Van Gundy has a hard decision to make: to
start Marcus Camby or Kurt Thomas. Either one is an enormous gamble
against a team that features the extraordinary tandem of Tim Duncan
_ whom Van Gundy calls the best player in the league _ and David
Robinson. With a starting lineup that pits Thomas and Chris Dudley
against the twin towers, the Knicks risk getting into foul trouble
quickly. The Spurs would surely pound the ball down low to exploit
the absence of Patrick Ewing and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Start Camby instead, and Van Gundy loses the burst of energy
that a revitalized Camby has provided coming off the bench in the
playoffs. If all three big men pick up quick fouls, the Knicks,
already down to nine players, will be faced with the prospect of
getting minutes from 41-year-old Herb Williams, who has appeared in
just two minutes of one game of this playoff run. If Johnson does
become available, does Van Gundy put Latrell Sprewell back on the
bench so Johnson can play small forward instead of power forward?
Van Gundy also has to decide whether the Knicks should double-team
Duncan and Robinson and dare the Spurs' backcourt to beat them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Indiana, Rik Smits will draw a foul, but he's more of a
jump shooter, so you're not going to get in real foul trouble with
him,'' Van Gundy said. ``Antonio Davis did a good job of drawing
fouls against us. But these guys play both guys who can draw fouls.
Obviously, we're going to have to do a good job of playing post
defense and trying to manage our foul situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Johnson is lost for any significant time, his absence may
be felt even more acutely in the locker room, or during a practice,
than on the floor during a game. Then, no game plan Van Gundy can
devise will make up for his loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means we're going to have to post-up the guards more if
he can't play,'' guard Chris Childs said. ``But it's not just his
play, it's his leadership. He's our captain; he's the first guy
here. We're going to miss his points, but more, his character. All
I would tell him is `Rub some dirt on it.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
