r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-USWOMEN-LADN     06-13 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-USWOMEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPECTATIONS RUN HIGH FOR U.S. TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It was ignored by NBC's live cameras during its
gold medal-winning victory over China at the 1996 Olympics in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the time has come for the U.S. women's national soccer team
to unleash eight years of relative obscurity when it visits Giants
Stadium in front of a national television audience Saturday against
Denmark in its opening game of the 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the gold medal, the women's team has grown in
popularity, becoming what U.S. coach Tony DiCicco describes as the
``standard'' for the rest of women's soccer to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Even though China has beaten the U.S. twice recently and Norway
or Germany can defeat the team on any given day, the American women
are expected to raise the FIFA Trophy this summer when the third
Women's World Cup final is concluded at the Rose Bowl on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a fair expectation? Not really. But the U.S. women are
playing at home, coming off an Olympic gold medal and have the
revenge factor fueling those expectations after losing the 1995
World Cup to champion Norway.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the U.S. also has the best training facilities,
best farm system (college talent) and has the benefit of keeping
its women together on a year-round basis.
</P>
<P>
   Factor all that together and one can see why the U.S. is
considered the world leader in women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our expectations are distant to what the men's Brazilian team
faces in terms of the pressure to win, but, in some respects, we
share their expectations on a world level,'' DiCicco said. ``No
matter where they (Brazil) take the field and no matter who's on
their team that particular day, they're expected to entertain and
expected to win. Not just by the Brazilian fans, but by every fan
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a wonderful expectation that is to carry. And at some
levels we carry that expectation also. And to tell you the truth,
we absolutely love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Brazilians, the American's expectations were built on
tales rather than television.
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. team won the inaugural 1991 Women's World Cup in
China following a 2-1 victory over Norway, they had to send faxes
and make phone calls to get the word out to friends and family
members.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one met us at the airport; there were no ticker-tape
parades,'' said striker Mia Hamm, laughing. ``One of our sponsors
took an ad out in the papers to let people know we had won.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicicco had two images from that tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we arrived at JFK after we won it, there were literally
less than five people there to greet us. One was Bora Milutinovic
(U.S. men's coach at the time) and the others I'm not sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other image comes from Michelle Akers. She was sitting
next to an older American woman on the ride home. The woman asked
her what she had just done, and Michelle told her we had just won
the first Women's World Cup in China. The lady said, `That's nice.'
I mean, there was no significance to the event outside of our
little world.''
</P>
<P>
   When the U.S. failed to recapture the 1995 World Cup in Sweden,
few noticed their 1-0 loss to Norway in the semifinals, either.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. was hoping its popularity and women's soccer in general
would reach a larger audience during the 1996 Olympics, but NBC
failed to show the team's thrilling 2-1 victory over China on live
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very disappointing,'' said U.S. forward Tiffeny
Milbrett. ``I don't know how many people on this team would say it,
but our team was very upset it wasn't shown. We felt like here you
have a gold-medal contender and it seemed like they just didn't
care enough to put us on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all changed now. Every minute of every game building up
to the final will be aired nationally on either ABC, ESPN or ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. is grouped in the first round with unlikely challengers
in Denmark, Nigeria and North Korea, but as the tournament gets
into the later stages the parity among the final eight teams will
be closer than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of differences between the first two World
Cups and this one,'' said Hamm. ``So many more teams out there can
compete for this title. I think in 1991 there were maybe four or
five teams. But now you have to adjust tactically and make
different decisions on how you attack and defend in every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to be a walk in the park. A lot of people are
expecting us to win, but this is the most competitive tournament
we've ever played in.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran defender Brandi Chastain said the pressure to win isn't
as high as the media is making it out to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to win the tournament, that's our goal. We wouldn't
have started training in January if we thought for one minute we
wouldn't win,'' said Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the expectations that communities across the United
States are placing on us are much greater than the expectations
we're putting on ourselves, because we have control of the
situation,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure we feel is only coming from within. It's not
coming from the media. It's not coming from our families. It's not
coming from soccer communities. It's coming from the 18 players
participating in the World Cup. We know what we're capable of
achieving so the pressure in that sense is lessened.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
