<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: KURT THOMAS, STEPPING UP AND RETURNING TO TEXAS IN
TRIUMPH  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The Knicks gathered and practiced Sunday. This
was Day One of a final championship push, a difficult day of coming
down from the thrill of Friday's Eastern Conference championship
victory, preparing for Game 1 on Wednesday against mighty, rested
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward framed the coming struggle as a battle between
David and Goliath: the undermanned Knicks against the thunderous
Spurs with the twin towers Tim Duncan and David Robinson. The story
of the conference championship was the transformation of the
Knicks' front-line players. The National Basketball Association
finals depend on the blossoming of lesser players in undetermined
yet critical roles. The blossoming of players like Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   As his teammates left Sunday after exhaustive interviews with
the news media, Thomas, the Knicks' 26-year-old power
forward/center, stayed late and took waves of medium-range jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   For the last several weeks, Thomas played his role; he has been
the Knicks' amorphous big body, grabbing rebounds and battling the
likes of Mourning, Mutombo and the Davises. He has played defense,
and he has played aggressively, while trying to stay out of foul
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With 6 minutes 3 seconds left in the first half on Friday,
Thomas' importance to the team escalated: Larry Johnson, the
Knicks' third wheel of a self-styled scoring triangle, went down
with a knee injury. Even if healthy, the 6-foot-5-inch Johnson was
going to have difficulty against the Spurs' tall, active, agile
front line. The Knicks need a 6-9 presence to mix, to defend and to
score perhaps as many as 12 points. Enter Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to help us win,'' Thomas said. ``If it's no
points, I'll do that. If it's playing defense, rebounding, I'll do
that. I've never won a championship at any level. Whatever it takes
to win, I'll do.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his ``aw, shucks'' demeanor and inoffensive
corporate-speak, Thomas does not lack confidence. During a team
meeting last April when the team was slumping at a crucial
juncture, Thomas, apparently feeling that none of the other Knicks
were willing to step up, told his teammates that he wanted the
ball. They looked at him as if he were crazy, but he got the
message across: somebody had to make it happen or it wasn't going
to happen. Two games later, the Knicks came from 20 points down to
beat the Heat in Miami in a game most players credit with
catapulting them through the Eastern Conference playoffs. With
Johnson injured, the Knicks need size and point production, and
Thomas will have an opportunity to walk the walk.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' realistic confidence was built in his college days in
Fort Worth, where he was facing players of NBA quality. ``If the
ball comes to me and I have an open shot, I'll take it,'' he said.
``But I'm not going to force anything. I'm not coming in thinking
I'm going to score 20 points.''
</P>
<P>
   As a senior at Texas Christian University, Thomas became one of
only two players to lead the National Collegiate Athletic
Association in scoring and rebounding. He enjoyed an outstanding
rookie season with Miami, which selected him 10th over all in 1995.
The next season, Thomas injured his ankle and played only 18 games.
He was traded to Dallas in midseason and played just five games
because of the same injury. At the end of the season he was a free
agent. He chose the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this is really like my second year in the NBA,'' Thomas
said. ``I'm still trying to find my groove. I just feel so thankful
to be able to run up and down the court, to be able to jump and not
be injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas earned a degree in psychology from TCU with a minor in
criminology. He freely uses psychological ploys in competition. His
wild-eyed, no-holds-barred approach is part of the mind games that
make the opposition increasingly leery: everyone fears a wild man.
Indiana's Antonio Davis complained that Thomas ``has really taken
it upon himself to just be dirty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the referee has to step in and take care of it,'' he
added, ``or we'll take care of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in control,'' Thomas said. ``I know what I'm doing. I play
hard. Somebody elbows me, I'm going to elbow them back. My daddy
taught me that if someone hit you, you hit them back.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip to Texas will be Thomas' triumphant return.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people told me, `Don't go to New York,''' he said.
``They said that I won't play, that I won't do what I want. Now I'm
coming back for the first time; I'm coming home the right way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
