<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UPBEAT AIRBUS CHAIRMAN FORECASTS 28 PERCENT SALES GAIN
</P>
<P>
   Nokl Forgeard, the chairman of Airbus Industrie, said the
European consortium expected sales to be $17 billion this year, up
from $13.3 billion in 1998. At the Paris Air Show, the French
executive also reiterated commitments to build the proposed A3XX
super jumbo and to transform Airbus from a consortium into a
corporation like its archrival, Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the president of Boeing's commercial airline
business caused a stir when he said that Boeing's orders might fall
30 percent to 40 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   `POWERS' SPINS OFF COLORFUL TIE-INS
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream marketers, like Heineken USA with its spot involving
a massage, are pushing the conventional boundaries of taste in
campaigns linked to the film ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged
Me'' and its comically lascivious title character.
</P>
<P>
   WITNESS COULD HURT MICROSOFT
</P>
<P>
   Last week's testimony in the Microsoft trial by an IBM executive
was absorbing _ a lengthy and specific litany of threats and
accusations, fleshed out with names and dates and backed up with
handwritten notes. But legal experts say it was not a knockout
punch.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE TOOL MAKER BOUNCES BACK
</P>
<P>
   After winning dominance in one software-related market only to
see it nearly disappear, Greg Galanos began looking around for new
territory to conquer. He may have found it in the need for tools to
create software for consumer electronics devices.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE SHOPPING STANDARD PLANNED
</P>
<P>
   A consortium of credit-card companies, Internet merchants and
technology developers plans to announce that it will develop a
standard for executing electronic commerce transactions. The
standard will eventually enable consumers to buy from numerous Web
sites without re-entering personal data.
</P>
<P>
   CARVER STORIES COME TO LIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Three previously unknown short stories by Raymond Carver were
discovered by his widow, the poet Tess Gallagher, after an editor
at Esquire asked her to look through the author's writing desk in
search of material that might be used to mark the 10th anniversary
of his death. The first of the stories, ``Kindling,'' will be
published in the July issue of Esquire, with the other two
following over the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY IS POWER, EVEN ON TV
</P>
<P>
   CNN's nightly business program ``Moneyline News Hour'' reaches
just 300,000 to 400,000 homes. But it is one of the most lucrative
hours in cable television, and emblematic of the rise of financial
news on television.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO STAND OUT IN A CROWD
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman has been hired to address an Internet marketing
conference this week in San Francisco. Organizers say the
flamboyant basketball player, known for colorful hair and a
penchant for incongruous attire, has this tip: Outrageousness pays.
</P>
<P>
   ENVIRONMENT-FRIENDLY LUBRICANT
</P>
<P>
   Two entrepreneurs have patented a vegetable-oil lubricant that
they hope will replace petroleum-based products.
</P>
</TEXT>
