<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES GAIN IN EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT VOTE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Europe's center-left governments suffered a sharp
setback Sunday as conservative parties gained votes and won enough
seats to become the largest group in elections to the European
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat was particularly crushing for Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder's governing Social Democrats in Germany, whose share of
the vote plunged to 31 percent compared to 40.9 percent in national
elections just nine months ago, computer projections showed.
</P>
<P>
   The center-right Christian Democrats advanced to 48 percent, a
sharp gain from 35.1 percent last September, as voters registered
their unhappiness with a stagnant economy and Schroeder's failure
to have an effect on high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   With center-left governments in office in the four largest
European countries _ Germany, France, Britain and Italy _ the
results suggested an electorate unmoved by what has been portrayed
as NATO's victory in Kosovo and more concerned with a European
economy that is scarcely growing while America's booms.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, there was no evidence of any war euphoria carrying
the governing parties to victory. But voter turnout for elections
to an assembly whose real power remains limited was extremely low,
suggesting that the importance of the swing to the right should not
be exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Early projections showed that center-right parties _ gathered in
a grouping known as the European People's Party _ would gain about
219 seats, 18 more than in 1994, and become the largest political
force in the 626-member assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The socialists, who emerged from the last elections in 1994 as
the strongest party with 214 seats, appear certain to lose at least
30 seats and might finish with as few as 179 seats, the projections
said.
</P>
<P>
   Those center and socialist parties are certain to remain by far
the largest groupings, trailed by the pro-market liberals with
about 48 seats and the environmentalist Greens with about 39. Other
seats were split among extreme-right and extreme-left movements and
a number of regional parties.
</P>
<P>
   The assembly, which generally meets in the eastern French city
of Strasbourg, has limited powers, but is able to veto the European
budget and also call for the dismissal of the European Executive
Commission, a power it exercised for the first time earlier this
year when several commissioners were accused of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   This flexing of parliamentary muscle against the officials who
propose policy and run the community's affairs day-to-day was
widely seen as a boost for greater democracy in the European Union.
But voters were apparently unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout in Britain was just 23 percent, a mere 27 percent in
Finland, 47 percent in France and 56 percent in Germany. This
suggested that neither the Parliament's greater prominence nor the
arrival of the common currency, the euro, had convinced people that
voting in Europe-wide polls is important.
</P>
<P>
   The conservative gains reflected a devastating defeat for
Schroeder in Germany and what appeared to be a poor showing by
Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor party in Britain. Voter turnout
in traditional Labor areas was very small, while conservative
constituencies voted in larger numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The French vote, marked by the highest abstention rate in any
nationwide poll, was extremely fragmented. The Green vote surged to
more than 10 percent from less than 3 percent in the last European
poll in 1994, while pro-European and anti-European conservative
parties shared close to 25 percent of the vote. The socialists of
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin gained about 20 percent, exit polls
showed.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, the result amounted to a stark warning to Schroeder
that his military and diplomatic efforts in Kosovo have not
impressed the people who voted for him because he promised to
create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The German unemployment rate, still more than 10 percent and
close to 20 percent in many parts of the former East Germany, has
not come down since he took office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
