<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUNKDRIVING-DECLINE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS FOR DRUNKEN DRIVING ARE DOWN, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal report says that arrests for drunken
driving have declined about 18 percent since 1986, suggesting a
lessening of the problem, but a campaigner against drunken driving
said people would continue to die on the roads unless more
preventive measures were taken.
</P>
<P>
   The report, issued Sunday by the Justice Department's Bureau of
Justice Statistics, said the number of people arrested for driving
while intoxicated had fallen to about 1.5 million in 1997, the last
year in which statistics were tallied, from about 1.8 million in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of arrests fell from 1,124 per 100,000 licensed drivers
in 1986 to 809 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, the decline in arrests came in a period when the
number of licensed drivers increased by about 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the decline in arrests might be attributed
partly to the aging of licensed drivers. The older the driver, the
report noted, the lower the rate of arrests for driving while
intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in the period in which arrests declined, there were major
campaigns against drunken driving, notably that of Mothers Against
Drunk Driving.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Schiavone, president of the National Commission Against
Drunk Driving, a private organization, said that the campaigns have
had an impact in reducing deaths and injuries caused by social
drinkers but not those caused by persistent or problem drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixty-five to 70 percent of people say in surveys that they
have used a designated driver or have been one themselves,''
Schiavone said, referring to the practice of selecting one member
of a party to be a nondrinker who can drive the others home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more people need to be aware of it,'' he said. ``It has
to reach 90 percent because that will get to the hard-core
persistent driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiavone said, ``The hard-core drunk drivers make up only 1
percent of drivers on weekend nights but are responsible for 50
percent of the deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   To reduce the deaths caused by persistent drunken drivers,
Schiavone said, there must be mandatory alcohol treatment programs
for those convicted of driving with high levels of alcohol in their
systems, as well as devices that can prevent an intoxicated person
from starting a car.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department report also found that there had been an
increase in the number of drunken drivers in what it called
correctional supervision _ on probation or in jail or prison _ from
270,000 in 1986 to 513,000 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews conducted by the Justice Department, people in
jail or on probation gave answers that seemed to support
Schiavone's contention that hard-core drinkers constituted the
major problem.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the drunken-driving offenders in the jail survey said
they had consumed the equivalent of at least 12 beers or six
glasses of wine when arrested. Half of those on probation said they
had consumed the equivalent of at least eight beers or four glasses
of wine.
</P>
<P>
   The average blood-alcohol concentration was 0.24 percent for
offenders in jail, the Justice Department found, and that of those
on probation was 0.19 percent. A concentration of 0.10 percent is
the legal limit in most states.
</P>
<P>
   The report will be available on Monday at www.ojp.usdoj.gov/bjs,
the Web site of the Bureau of Justice Statistics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
