<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AT THE TURTLEBACK OPEN, WINNER MAY BE OVER PAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its formal title is the 99th U.S. Open Championship, but it's
really the Turtleback Open.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the scraggly rough and glassy greens that usually
define the Open, the primary protector of par 70 over the 7,115
yards of Pinehurst No. 2 will be the greens that resemble the hump
of a turtle's shell, a snapper turtle that will devour stray
approach shots. Any shot that is less than precise will trickle off
the slippery crowned greens into shallow fairway-like areas
requiring delicate chip shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the greens stay firm,'' said Tom Meeks, the Open's marquis
de sod, ``I think the winning score will be two or three over par.
If rain softens the greens, it could be anywhere from four to eight
under.''
</P>
<P>
   The Open hasn't had a winner with a 72-hole score over par since
1978, when Andy North shot one-over 285 at Cherry Hills, outside
Denver. In the 1974 massacre at Winged Foot, in Westchester County,
N.Y., just outside New York City, Hale Irwin won with a seven-over
287. At Olympic in San Francisco last year, Lee Janzen had an
even-par 280 for his second Open title.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few of the Open golfers have played Pinehurst No. 2, but
Janzen knows it from the 1992 Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I studied every green and made notes on where the best places
were to chip from, and where the places were that absolutely could
not be chipped from,'' he said recently. ``I shaded the best areas
in my course book. That week I pretty much looked at certain pin
placements and if they were near the shaded areas, I went for the
pin. If they were in areas that if I hit the green on the short
side, it was difficult, then I aimed for the middle of the green.''
</P>
<P>
   Janzen shot a five-under 279 in that Tour Championship, tying
for second to Paul Azinger's winning eight-under 276. Since then,
Pinehurst No. 2, designed originally by the legendary Donald Ross,
has been renovated slightly for its first U.S. Open, starting
Thursday in the sandy pine forests of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We added some length and we expanded the greens to Ross'
original dimensions,'' said Rees Jones, the Open's architectural
consultant. ``But the most important thing is, we re-established
the chipping areas where Ross wanted the ball to go if the approach
shot isn't precise enough to stay on the green. It's a course that
I think will favor the international players more accustomed to
recovery shots.''
</P>
<P>
   If Seve Ballesteros were still in the prime of his genius at
recovery shots, he would be the golfer to beat. But his protege,
the two-time Masters champion Jose Maria Olazabal, has the finesse
to be the first European to win the Open since Tony Jacklin of
England in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chip shots can be played with a putter, a sand wedge, a 7-iron
or an 8-iron, even with the 3-wood that Tiger Woods sometimes
uses,'' said Meeks, the U.S. Golf Association's director of rules
and competitions. ``The scariest green is the fifth, the par 4
that's now 482 yards. The left front of that green is very hard.
We'll be careful with the pin position there. We don't want another
San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   At Olympic last year, Meeks' pin position on the back left of
the 18th green in Friday's second round turned into a travesty for
some golfers. When Payne Stewart missed a sidehill 8-foot birdie
putt, he watched his ball trickle 20 feet below the cup. He missed
that par putt and eventually lost to Janzen by a stroke. Tom Lehman
four-putted there that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the greens at Pinehurst to be faster than 10
1/2,'' said Meeks, referring to a relatively gentle Stimpmeter
reading. ``As for the Bermuda rough, the game plan is to keep it at
three inches. We don't want guys having to hit a sand wedge out of
it to get back on the fairway. We want them to be able to at least
hit a 7- or 8-iron.''
</P>
<P>
   For a century, Pinehurst has been considered America's first
golf resort. James Walker Tufts, a wealthy Bostonian, purchased
6,000 acres (at $1 an acre) in 1895 and laid out a nine-hole course
that evolved into Pinehurst No. 1. He hired Ross, who used metal
scrapers pulled by horses to build the greens on No. 2, long one of
America's best courses; it's currently rated ninth by Golf Digest
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord made golf courses,'' Ross once said. ``Golf
architects merely discovered them. A hole should look as if nature
left it there.''
</P>
<P>
   In earlier years, Pinehurst No. 2 was the site of the 1936
Professional Golfers' Association Championship and the 1951 Ryder
Cup matches. It was an annual PGA Tour stop for the North and South
Open (won by Ben Hogan, Byron Nelson and Sam Snead) and later for
the World Open and the Hall of Fame Open.
</P>
<P>
   As some courses do, No. 2 slowly deteriorated. But in 1984,
ClubCorp purchased what is now the Pine-hurst Resort and Country
Club (with eight courses) and restored No. 2 to Ross' concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 2's greens are designed to repel shots, not accept them,''
said Don Padgett, a former PGA of America president, who is now
Pinehurst's director of golf. ``And when the ball rolls off the
green, it will roll as far as its momentum will take it.''
</P>
<P>
   As if it rolled off a snapping turtle's back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
