<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-SPURS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FRUITLESSLY FOR FLAWS IN THE SPURS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy has kept a bit of
his long years as an assistant coach with him. Preparing for a
playoff series, he has always been able to dissect hours of tape,
finding a slight flaw in an opponent.
</P>
<P>
   But when he picked up his stack of videos on recent losses for
the San Antonio Spurs, he found a few problems. First, the stack
was not very tall, with the Spurs dropping just four games since
April 1, including just one in the post-season, an opening-round
loss to the Minnesota Timberwolves. Since then, they have swept
through the Los Angeles Lakers and the Portland Trail Blazers.
There was no glaring weakness he could find.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their losses came on back-to-back games or when they had more
travel,'' Van Gundy said today. ``There wasn't anything San Antonio
didn't do well. That's what I was looking for, some nugget. What
there was was no nuggets.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs boast talented players like Tim Duncan and David
Robinson, one trait that Van Gundy saw in the Spurs this season is
the same resolve that he believes carried the Knicks through hard
times all the way to the National Basketball Association finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so easy today to point the finger and blame,'' he said.
``Everybody gives you the opportunity. The resolve that built up,
we became a team that really, truly was only focused on the team,
instead of saying that you're a team, but really only caring about
individual accomplishment. I think that really gave us a resolve in
close games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can only get to that point when you're tested. San Antonio
did the same thing. They started out 6-8. They could have started
blaming and pointing fingers. Now they've obviously been more
dominant than we have and they got it earlier, but I think they got
it earlier only because they didn't have personnel changes like we
had. We had major personnel changes and injuries that had us backed
up early.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs changed their fortunes quickly, turning a 6-8
start into the NBA's best record at 37-13, the Knicks are still
enjoying the underdog role that they have carried throughout the
post-season. Told that his team had been installed as a
double-digit underdog in Game 1 of the finals, point guard Chris
Childs said he would not have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can say whatever they want to say,'' Childs said.
``We're here. We're confident in our abilities. I'm glad they're
underestimating us. Each series they have, and we won. I don't want
them to change their mind and pick us as favorites now.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Dudley sees the adversity that the Knicks have faced as a
part of everyday life for a New York team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're used to it,'' Dudley said. ``You get kind of, not
immune, but battle-tested. In New York, everything that happens is
magnified, and after a while it doesn't bother you. In the two
years I've been here we've had to go through so much, it doesn't
faze us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
