<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY WON'T PHIL-IBUSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The question hardly stumped the stumping Bill
Bradley, who shoulda seen it coming all the way from Inglewood as
he shook babies and kissed hands at the famed Farmer's Market on
Third and Fairfax during a prez campaign visit Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any way you can convince Phil Jackson to take the Lakers
job?'' someone asked about his former New York Knicks teammate and
huge supporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll make up his own mind,'' Bradley said before
breaking out a smile. ``You know, that's the real reason why the
campaign goes through here this week.''...
</P>
<P>
   _Dennis Rodman was the best thing that happened to the Lakers
last season, by the way.
</P>
<P>
   Remember how Rodman was owner Jerry Buss' force-fed addition to
the roster, despite the misgivings of exec Jerry West? So when that
mission aborted and Buss' image started to drift back to that of a
meddling owner who goes over the heads of his own well-paid experts
(nixing the Mitch Richmond trade, hiring Randy Pfund and Magic
Johnson as coaches), you know darn well he listened when West
insisted Jackson was the Zen Master needed for this team without a
soul.
</P>
<P>
   The reported $24 million that Buss will pay to the son of a
preacher man from North Dakota not only goes to the coach's salary
but toward restoring Buss' persona....
</P>
<P>
   _Besides, Buss must figure that with Jackson in charge, it'll
improve Rodman's chances of a return engagement....
</P>
<P>
   _In Bradley's extraordinary ``Values of the Game'' book of
essays (which Jackson writes the forward), one of the few he
singles out in the dedication is West....
</P>
<P>
   _Jackson in L.A. could boost Bradley's campaign financially and
give it a higher profile. Michael Jordan has already chipped in a
grand to the fund and will make appearances for Bradley. Other
supporters, according to Washingtonian magazine, are Pistons star
Grant Hill and his dad Calvin Hill, Padres president Larry
Lucchino, Wizards owner Abe Pollin and ProServ founder Donald
Dell....
</P>
<P>
   _By the way, Rodman's TV series, ``S.O.F.: Special Ops Force,''
has been canceled. After one season. Which is longer than he lasted
as No. 73....
</P>
<P>
   _John Elway told the Rocky Mountain News last week that his
involvement with an L.A. NFL expansion group has been greatly
exaggerated. ``The media has it a lot further ahead than it is...
much, much, much further,'' he said....
</P>
<P>
   _New York Daily Newies say Wayne Gretzky and family have vacated
New York and are moving back to L.A....
</P>
<P>
   _Is Janet Jones still a wannabe actress?...
</P>
<P>
   _Post-Agassi activity from future ex-wife Brooke Shields: She
was filming this weekend off Melrose in a chick movie called, ahem,
``After Sex.''...
</P>
<P>
   _Tony Mota _ yup, another one of Manny's kids _ is hitting .352
with 10 homers and 47 RBI for the Dodgers' Double-A San Antonio
squad. All three stats rank fifth in the Texas League....
</P>
<P>
   _Dick Enberg is, as expected, genuinely humbled by the NFL
bestowing upon him the Pete Rozelle Award for his lifetime work as
a broadcaster, which will be presented in August at the Pro
Football Hall of Fame induction ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the award alone makes it fantastic,'' Enberg said
Sunday before heading out to cover the U.S. Open golf tournament
for NBC this week. ``There was a time when I was just a lonely
little Rams announcer for KMPC when Rozelle sent me a handwritten
note saying, `What a good job you're doing and the NFL is proud to
have people like you broadcast their games.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, how much is that worth at that time when you're wondering
if you're any good at all and the commissioner of the National
Football League writes you a personal note.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
