<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS DEFFEAT YANKEES, 8-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Andy Pettitte's coat-hanger shoulders slumped forward
while he tried explaining another loss and the reason he
surrendered many hits and runs to the Florida Marlins. Between his
sullen answers, he stared like a 10-year-old peering outside on a
rainy day.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the New York Yankees wore this particular expression
after their 8-2 loss to the Marlins on Sunday; even while winning
enough to be in first place in the American League East, the
Yankees have suffered so many ugly defeats this year that it's as
if they pull these death masks out once or twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter had a single and a double in his first two at-bats,
accounting for his sixth consecutive multiple-hit game; he had 13
hits in 27 at-bats on the road trip and increased his batting
average to .380. Jeter did not finish the game well, though: He
struck out with runners at first and second in the fifth inning and
again in the eighth with a runner on first and nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Yankees had won three straight games before Sunday,
and yes, they passed Boston in the standing on this six-game road
trip. But the consistency that made the Yankees proud and distinct
last year has eluded them.
</P>
<P>
   They began this trip with a horrible performance against
Philadelphia and ended it with another on Sunday. As a result, they
will begin a weeklong homestand on Monday still trying to put
together a solid monthlong stretch of baseball in which they pitch,
hit and catch well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was our record on this road trip, 3-3?'' Jeter asked
rhetorically. ``Well, I don't think anyone here is happy with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre said, ``This was a bad game today.''
</P>
<P>
   And Pettitte, who permitted nine hits, two walks and six runs in
five-plus innings, did not know why; his stuff was pretty good, he
said. Pettitte (3-5) was able to throw strikes with his curveball
when he was behind in the count, and he had decent control of his
fastball inside and outside. But he and the Yankees made enough
mistakes to lose again. ``I'm just disgusted right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte retired the first two batters in the second inning.
Danny Bautista then blooped a hit between right fielder Paul
O'Neill and second baseman Chuck Knoblauch _ the first example,
catcher Joe Girardi said, of how Pettitte was hurt by bad luck.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte walked the next batter, Mike Redmond, and then the
Marlins' pitcher, Alex Fernandez, singled through the middle. It
was a garbage run that left Pettitte wondering why he threw
Fernandez a fastball, not something off-speed.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again the next time through the lineup. Two outs,
runner on second, and Pettitte walked Redmond and Fernandez smacked
a run-scoring single through the middle. In the fifth inning with
the score tied at 4-4, Pettitte tried ramming a fastball inside to
Bruce Aven, who bashed the first of his two home runs. Girardi said
the pitch Aven hit represented perhaps the only physical mistake
Pettitte made all day.
</P>
<P>
   If only Bautista's hit didn't fall in. If Pettitte hadn't been
quite so careful with Redmond. If only there was more run support.
Pettitte sat in front of his locker, shoulders bent forward,
staring blankly.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds here at the weekend comprised mostly Yankees fans,
some transplanted from the north, others attracted by the success
of the franchise, all of them expecting more of the same. When
Pettitte was relieved with nobody out in the sixth, he walked off
the mound and into a shocking hurricane of boos.
</P>
<P>
   His ERA is 9.88 over his last three outings, and he was booed
after his most recent outing at Yankee Stadium. Pettitte may have
had that great season in 1996 and important World Series
performances in '96 and '98, but the fans seem to have put him on
notice.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees didn't look any better after Pettitte departed. They
failed to score in the last five innings, O'Neill broke back and
let a fly ball fall in front of him and Bernie Williams overthrew a
cutoff man. They looked tired, Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees are a funny team, a high-ranking member of the
organization mused last week. In 1998, they would bury bad teams
like Florida, hammering away until they were certain to walk away
with a sweep.
</P>
<P>
   But the '99 Yankees haven't demonstrated a killer instinct; if
they were baseball lions last year, then they are more like hyenas
this year, doing just enough to get by. They play well for a few
games and give the impression they are about to embark on a
significant winning streak, and then have an awful day. The
questions about just how good the Yankees are this year linger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
