<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER AND AGBAYANI LEAD METS OVER BOSTON, 5-4 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One is 40 years old and needs seven pages in the
Mets' media guide to paint the corners of a sturdy pitching career
that has taken him to all-star and World Series games. The other is
27 and barely rates seven paragraphs to recap what, until now, has
been an unremarkable professional journey.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser showed all those pages were deserved by throwing
six solid innings against the Red Sox Sunday. And Benny Agbayani
continued to pile up type, banging his ninth home run in his last
14 starts. Hershiser and Agbayani combined to anchor a 5-4 victory
over Boston before 46,473 fans at Shea Stadium, the Mets' sixth
victory in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Though he has played only 38 major league games in his
seven-year career dating to last September, Agbayani may soon need
to borrow manager Bobby Valentine's dark glasses and tape mustache
to avoid being swarmed in New York.
</P>
<P>
   With two out in the fifth inning, he crushed a changeup from Red
Sox starter Mark Portugal 383 feet into the left-field bleachers
for a 1-1 tie. It was his 10th home run in 73 at-bats this season
and his second in two days after missing a game with an eye injury
sustained in a batting-practice accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really sparked us when Benny hit it so solid,'' Valentine
said. ``It was one of the first solid hits, and it lifted us.''
</P>
<P>
   It ignited a three-run, five-hit rally.
</P>
<P>
   First Rey Ordonez, then Hershiser _ a career .206 hitter _
singled up the middle. Ricky Henderson slapped a line drive to
right, scoring Ordonez, and Edgardo Alfonzo tailed one past
second-baseman Jose Offerman to bring Hershiser lumbering home from
second and put the Mets up by 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets did not acquire Hershiser last March for his bat.
They signed the 15-year veteran and free agent to turn in the kind
of effective and efficient performance that could give the team's
overworked bullpen some time in the shade. Coming into the game,
Hershiser (6-5) was second only to Masato Yoshii in innings pitched
with 59.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser scattered five hits and struck out five over the first
six innings, Boston scoring on doubles by John Valentin and Troy
O'Leary in the fourth. Although O'Leary homered into the Mets'
bullpen with two out in the sixth, narrowing the margin to 3-2,
Hershiser appeared strong enough to pitch deep into the game.
</P>
<P>
   He was also getting help. The Mets answered O'Leary's homer in
the bottom of the sixth after Piazza led off with a double,
extending his hitting streak to 17 games. Portugal was replaced by
Jim Corsi who, after retiring Robin Ventura, gave Brain McRae an
0-1 fastball to drive 391 feet over the right center-field fence
for a 5-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser opened the seventh by walking shortstop Jeff Frye
and giving up a single to Trot Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   With the set-up man, Armando Benitez, and the closer, John
Franco, unavailable after back-to-back days of strong work,
Valentine intended for Turk Wendell to pitch in the seventh.
Instead of him, however, Valentine opted at the last minute for the
left-hander Dennis Cook, knowing that the Red Sox had the
right-handed-hitting Nomar Garciaparra, who took the day off,
available to pinch-hit in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Cook walked the bases loaded, which allowed Offerman to knock
Frye in on a fielder's choice and move Nixon to third. Then Jason
Varitek hit a sacrifice fly to send Nixon home to cut the Mets'
lead to 5-4 before Cook struck out John Valentin to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orel was fabulous,'' Valentine said afterward. ``If he didn't
have to score from second, he may have had enough gas in the tank
for the seventh.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser insisted his own mistakes got him in trouble. ``I
almost wasted good stuff today _ I grooved a fastball that gets
knocked out and I walk a .228 hitter,'' he said of the O'Leary
homer and Frye's base on balls.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Greg McMichael, in only his second appearance
since returning on June 11 after rehabilitating a right rotator
cuff strain, held the Red Sox despite an error by Ordonez and a
single by O'Leary. The Red Sox left two men on base when McMichael
struck out Brian Daubach and Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg was very good considering where he's coming from,''
Valentine said. ``Cook's stuff wasn't as good as it usually is, but
we got by with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Wendell's turn in the ninth and, as expected, Garciaparra
pinch-hit for pitcher Tim Wakefield. He doubled down the left-field
line.
</P>
<P>
   But the right-hander then got Offerman to pop out, whiffed a
swinging Varitek to end the inning, and in the ninth it was once
more Agbayani time. Wendell, in search of his second save, watched
Valentin lace a ball into left. Agbayani, hardly a graceful
fielder, broke in, realized the swirling winds were blowing the
ball out, circled back and gathered the ball in.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Valentine tried to argue that Agbayani's
background _ his father was a ballroom dancing instructor _ endowed
him with balance and movement. But the rookie wasn't thinking of
his father. He was thinking of Mets coach Mookie Wilson, his
unofficial fielding adviser, as soon as the ball was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and thought, `When is this ball going to come
down?' '' Agbayani said. ``The wind was blowing it around pretty
good. I just wanted to keep moving my legs _ that's what Mookie
told me to do, and he's played a lot of outfield in this stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   It looks pretty much as though Agbayani will, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
