<SLUG> BC-BKN-SABRES-RUFF-530&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUFF OFFERS TOUGH LOVE TO THE STRUGGLING SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ In his long career as a National Hockey League
player, Lindy Ruff was one tough customer. He collected 1,264
penalty minutes, roughly 12 for every goal he scored. He even
fought a guy named Ted Bulley. Ruff's suggestive surname, blond
mustache and high hairline could fit well in a roster of
professional wrestlers like Hulk Hogan or Jesse Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   The mouth below the coach's mustache wore a little frown on
Sunday, and Ruff's words were not soothing. Because his Sabres lost
by 2-1 to Dallas on Saturday night to fall behind, two games to
one, in the Stanley Cup finals, Ruff was ready to rumble, at least
orally. He criticized several Sabres, a few by name and one in
particular. It is a risky motivational tactic that sometimes
backfires on coaches. But Ruff, a second-year coach, is running out
of ideas and games.
</P>
<P>
   His harshest words were for Miroslav Satan, a forward who scored
40 goals in the regular season, missed most of the playoffs with a
broken foot and has no points in this round. Satan (pronounced
shah-TAN) is from Slovakia, and it is not uncommon for North
American coaches and reporters to find fault with European players
when a team slumps. (By contrast, North American players who do not
perform well in the playoffs are usually described as ``tired'' or
``playing over injuries.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the added ice time might get him going,'' Ruff said
of Satan, who played 26 minutes 36 seconds. ``Obviously, we need
him. If we are going to win the series, we need our big players to
do something for us. The added ice time didn't result in a big plus
for us. We tried everything. We didn't get a lot out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff tried to get Satan away from Dallas defensemen Derian
Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk, but that is hard because they play
so much. ``He's going to have to fight his way through it,'' Ruff
said of Satan.
</P>
<P>
   But Satan and other Buffalo forwards were also frustrated by the
Dallas forwards, who scurry to backcheck against rushes going the
other way. ``There were a couple opportunities where it looked like
Satan might be able to beat a defenseman one on one,'' Ruff said,
but ``he had a forward in his back pocket lifting his stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Satan got two of Buffalo's 12 shots against Ed Belfour. After
Stu Barnes gave Buffalo a 1-0 lead, Joe Nieuwendyk of the Stars
scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars lost their sniper Brett Hull in the first period with
a groin strain. Coach Ken Hitchcock said Hull would probably not
play in Game 4 on Tuesday and might not be back until Game 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   Satan was asked about the pressure. Like many of the European
players who speak English as a second or third language, he was
blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do feel the pressure,'' Satan said. ``I try to respond
the best way I can. But right now, they are backchecking hard.
There is not too much room. Not only me but the whole team. It is a
problem to create anything in their zone. That's the key why we had
only 12 shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Satan said he did not think his teammates were down. ``We're
going to try to play the best game we played ever in the regular
season or playoffs,'' he said. ``That's going to be on Tuesday.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ruff briefly and lightly criticized the first line, centered by
Mike Peca, the Ontario-born captain who has one goal and no assists
in the series. Ruff also defended his matchup of Peca as a checker
while suggesting he might revise it. Ruff continued to put Peca
against Dallas center Mike Modano, who has an injured left wrist,
instead of against Nieuwendyk, who did the most damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line as a whole hasn't got much done for us offensively,
which has hurt us, with the amount they've been playing,'' Ruff
said of Peca's line. ``He's played a lot. Is he worn down? I think
there's a lot of players that are a little bit worn down.''
</P>
<P>
   As for matchups, Ruff said he still thought Curtis Brown could
cover Nieuwendyk, but he added, ``We might have to switch the
matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca said: ``We didn't have our greatest game. We lost, 2-1. The
guys are still positive. This is the greatest adversity we've
faced. This team seems to thrive on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano complained that the Sabres slashed his injured wrist on
face-offs, but Peca said, ``Well, he had a wrist protector on, so
it didn't matter if we whacked at it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Peca and his teammates professed optimism that was belied by
their glum expressions. Rob Ray, the senior Sabre, discussed the
pessimism in Buffalo, where the football Bills lost four Super
Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they were unsuccessful it was like a major letdown for
the city,'' Ray said. ``You not only feel the pressure for yourself
but of everyone else when you are walking down the street. They
make such a big thing of it. There's a lot of added pressure
because this city has never been able to win a major championship.
Each time you get this chance, you get this close, you start
thinking about it, and they start bringing it up. That added
pressure is there. It's something you just can't avoid. They don't
allow you to avoid it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
