</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, YELTSIN UNABLE TO SETTLE KOSOVO MATTER &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle &HT;    WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Russian President Boris
<TEXT>
Yeltsin failed Sunday to resolve the confusing issue of Russian
troops in Kosovo, but the United States continued to downplay the
importance of the surprising deployment.
<P>
   The two presidents spoke by telephone for one hour Sunday
morning and agreed to talk again today after NATO and Russia
generals resume negotiations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should get overexcited about what is going
on. It is being handled in the proper channels,'' said Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright on NBC's Meet the Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian dash into Kosovo on Friday, beating allied troops
into the Serbia province, continued to baffle Western leaders. Some
200 Russian soldiers now control the airport in Pristina, the
Kosovo capital.
</P>
<P>
   The development left the allies wondering who was in control of
the Russian military and whether it signaled greater problems in
Moscow for Yeltsin's government.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hammer, a spokesman for the National Security Council, said
Clinton and Yeltsin discussed ways to ``advance Russian
participation'' in the peacekeeping efforts known as K-For for
Kosovo Force. He said they agreed Russian and NATO generals should
continue the discussion about ``suitable arrangements'' for Russian
troops to join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin issued a statement saying, ``Both sides emphasized
the need for intensive dialogue, including between military
officials, with the aim of quickly finding an agreement on the
implementation of the peacekeeping operation.'' It said the
presidents would probably talk again today.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin now claims to have endorsed the troop deployment.
However, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov on Friday initially
assured the White House that Russian troops then on the move would
not enter Kosovo. Once they did cross the Kosovo border, he called
their deployment a mistake and pledged their withdrawal. The troops
were thought to be under orders from Russian generals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is, quite frankly, making them appear a little inept, as
opposed to what they're attempting to do and demonstrate they have
some international muscle,'' said Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware,
senior Democrat on the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, on Fox
News Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Russia, which helped broker the peace plan, now wants to play a
greater role in the peacekeeping force. It balked at Western
demands that its soldiers must be under NATO command and that it
would not be allowed its own sector. NATO had created five sectors
to be patrolled by specific allied forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to be a part of a K-For force. We want them to be a
part of it. I think they got a little bit ahead of themselves but
there are now military-to-military discussions going on and
obviously political discussions going on,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said NATO will not relent on the issues of unity of
command and a Russian sector. She said to give Russia its own area
to patrol could lead to the partitioning of Kosovo, which the West
will not allow.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, called the
Russian action ``a bizarre incident.'' He told CBS' Face the Nation
that the issue must be resolved politically.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still there. We are in the area with a sizable number
of troops. This is and has been a political issue first and
foremost. There is no desire to have any confrontation and we're
doing everything we can to avoid such an unfortunate event.
Instead, we're going to resolve this through political means,''
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said NATO had no plans to ``make substantial use'' of the
airport and the K-For's deployment into Kosovo is unaffected. Some
10,000 allied soldiers, out of an expected force of 50,000, were in
Kosovo
</P>
<P>
   ``They were to be an advance party in the event that Russian
troops were flown into the airfield,'' he said, dismissing any hint
of danger in their deployment. ``Your dealing with the actions and
the intent of some very high level people in that capital (Moscow)
and really they have to account for what happened. All we know is
we have a very small number of Russian troops there. They are not
impacting on our move.''
</P>
<P>
   The commander estimated that about 11,000 of the 40,000 Yugoslav
forces have withdrawn so far. ``There's every indication that
they're doing their best to pullout on schedule,'' he said.
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic must remove all his forces
from Kosovo by next Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the best face on the Russia advance was Jamie Shea, the
NATO spokesman, who appeared on ABC's This Week. ``I think we were
surprised, quite frankly, but on the other hand it's good the
Russians were in such a hurry to join us,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said British Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson, commander of NATO
forces in Kosovo, would not order the Russians to leave. ``This
issue is being worked at a number of levels and I have no doubt
that within the very near future we will find effective
coordination arrangements to get the Russians fully on board,''
Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
