<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3777 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-NATO-BOS &LR;      06-13 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-NATO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORADIC VIOLENCE ACCOMPANIES NATO'S ENTRY INTO KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Outbursts of violence marked NATO's second day in
Kosovo, as peacekeeping troops shot and killed two Serbs and some
Serb soldiers appeared to be torching ethnic Albanian homes on
their way out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a small contingent of Russian forces blocked a
British peacekeeping mission from entering the airport in the
provincial capital of Pristina, a product of the ongoing dispute
between Russia and NATO over what role Russian troops should play.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and Russian President Boris N. Yeltsin spoke
Sunday for the first time since Russian troops unexpectedly entered
Kosovo ahead of NATO, apparently at Yeltsin's command. Despite what
aides said was a ``constructive'' conversation, the main sticking
point _ whether Russians should be allowed to patrol their own zone
outside NATO control _ remained unresolved, and Russia refused to
back down from what a day earlier had been dismissed as a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the rest of the peacekeeping mission appeared to be
moving rapidly ahead, with Yugoslav troops retreating out of Kosovo
at a pace US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright described as
``terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are watching the fact that the Serb withdrawals were
happening on or ahead of schedule,'' Albright said. In Macedonia,
NATO's top commander, General Wesley Clark, said Serbs had given
``every indication they're doing their best'' to exit the province,
which, according to the peace agreement, they have seven days left
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's incidents of violence seemed the result of isolated
attacks. In the southern town of Prizren, German troops shot and
killed a Serb, and critically wounded another, after the men sped
past in a car and fired shots out the window. A German soldier was
injured by a bullet that hit his arm.
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, British forces said they killed an off-duty Serb
police officer who began firing on them. Some 25 miles to the
south, two German reporters were killed when unidentified snipers
shot at their car in a Canadian-controlled sector, according to a
Foreign Ministry spokesman in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Pristina suburb of Sofali, which is mostly inhabited by
ethnic Albanians, several houses were seen burning from the road,
where Serb troops blocked Western troops and journalists from
proceeding. The library of a historic mosque in Pristina was set on
fire after the explosion of a gasoline bomb.
</P>
<P>
   One German soldier said armed Serbs were everywhere, calling
them ``drunks with guns and grenades.''
</P>
<P>
   However, no casualties were reported in the streets of Pristina
or Prizren, despite the enormous crowds of ethnic Albanians who
gathered to form a gauntlet for departing Serb troops _ and a warm
and cheering receiving line for NATO. Gunshots rang through the
air, and some Kosovars hurled stones at departing Serbs before
showering roses on arriving NATO tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the United States also added to the 60 US troops
already in Kosovo, sending in 400 soldiers from the US Army's 82d
Airborne Division along with nine tanks and several Bradley armored
vehicles, according to Pentagon officials. In general, NATO troops,
who will ultimately number 50,000, kept moving into their specific
sectors continued as planned despite the confrontation with the
Russian military.
</P>
<P>
   ``No plans have been disrupted whatsoever by this bizarre
event,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   But the British Army did appear to have lost time setting up
camp at the Pristina airport, where a Russian armored personnel
carrier Sunday refused to let a group of 50 British soldiers travel
to the airport, provoking the commander of the British unit,
Brigadier Adrian Freer, to shout and gesture. His efforts were in
vain.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian refusal to allow NATO to set up its headquarters at
the airport came as US officials refused to let Russia even
consider its main objective: patrolling a separate zone in the
north of Kosovo, where most of the province's Serbs live.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, speaking Sunday on NBC's Meet the Press, insisted the
Russians ``will not have their own sector and the unity of command
must be honored.''
</P>
<P>
   However, she added: ``The Russian component is about 200, so I
think we don't want to kind of overestimate all of this. They got
in. They got in ahead of themselves, is my sense about this. I
don't think that we should get overexcited about what is going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin said Sunday that Clinton and Yeltsin agreed in their
phone conversation ``to continue an exchange of opinions'' on
Russia's role in the international peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone will stay where they are during the
transitional stage,'' said Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and Clinton are expected to meet next Sunday in Cologne,
Germany, at a summit of the leaders of Russia and the Group of
Seven industrial powers called to discuss the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's takeover of Pristina's airport stunned NATO and put new
strains on diplomatic relations already badly frayed by Moscow's
opposition to the alliance's airstrikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, talks in Moscow ended without a conclusive agreement. US
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said the United States was
ready to concede Russia a ``zone of responsibility'' in Kosovo
under NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   But Russian officials expressed frustration with the US
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their mentality is still, unfortunately, not aimed at
partnership,'' Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander Avdeyev
told Russian television. ``American diplomacy does not want to meet
Russia halfway, to let it have a worthy place'' in the peacekeeping
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Russian news agencies reported that the military would like to
add to the force in Kosovo, but Talbott said Russia promised not to
deploy any more troops in Kosovo without NATO approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect any more surprise steps from the Russian
side,'' he said after his meeting with Ivanov. It was Ivanov who
promised Friday that Moscow would not order its troops to enter
Kosovo, hours before the Russian peacekeeping troops did just that.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Ivanov had called the move a ``mistake'' and said the
troops would be ordered out of Kosovo. But Sunday, Ivanov shrugged
off the fact that he had been unaware that Russian troops were
about to enter Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not the chief of the general staff, and I don't give
orders to troops,'' Ivanov said. ``Someone gives orders. Why do I
have to know about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Globe staffer David Filipov contributed to this report from
Moscow. Material from the Associated Press was also used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
