<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-SERBS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN SOLDIERS KILL SERB IN SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ German soldiers shot and killed one Serb
gunman and wounded a second in a firefight here Sunday, a deadly
end to a tense first day of the international peacekeeping presence
here.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear whether the Serb gunmen were
paramilitaries or civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings followed a day of intense hostility between
Albanians and Serbs, and Serbs and peacekeepers, on what was the
first day of a scheduled three-day Serb military pullout from
Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   Albanians who thronged the streets of the old town for the first
time in months were stunned to have the fresh peace broken by the
shootings, which occurred at about 9 p.m., just after Albanians
were jubilantly celebrating the foreign troops' entrance into town.
</P>
<P>
   As they approached the center of the city on a main street along
the Bistrica River, sniper fire crackled from a hill and houses.
German soldiers took cover and began shooting back.
</P>
<P>
   The Germans' heavy fire blasted a yellow Lada car with two
occupants. One was killed immediately, the other was critically
wounded. German soldiers said that the men shot first and that
grenades and semiautomatic weapons were found in the car.
</P>
<P>
   Germany's ZDF television showed video of the two Serbs shooting
from inside the car close to a German army checkpoint. The arrival
of 1,200 German and Dutch Kosovo Force troops was meant to turn
over control of the Prizren region from the Serb military to
international peacekeepers. The shootings were a disturbing sign
that some Serbs will not withdraw quietly.
</P>
<P>
   In late afternoon, marauding Serb soldiers stormed Prizren's
central square, beating ethnic Albanians and barely quelling a
stone-throwing attack by ethnic Albanians against a group of
outnumbered Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb soldiers hit chanting Albanians with the butts of their
guns, and fired two shots into the air before German soldiers
persuaded them to lower their weapons and retreat. Some Albanians
had been pelting rocks at the packed cars of departing Serb
civilians, who were afraid to stay in the almost-liberated southern
Kosovar city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will come back again, and we will kill you!'' a retreating
Serb soldier yelled at a crowd of Albanian residents, who were
spitting and shouting epithets.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 3,000 Serb police, army soldiers and
paramilitaries, considered the most brutal of the Serb military
contingents, are supposed to be out of Prizren by Tuesday. The city
is in the west of Kosovo, where some of the heaviest fighting
occurred, and where some of the worst atrocities are believed to
have been committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are like cowboys, going through the streets, shooting
into some house,'' said Armid Berisha, a 40-year-old car mechanic.
Many residents also reported that the Serb paramilitaries had been
looting in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
   Serb paramilitaries posted a checkpoint on main road leading out
of Prizren, stopping many civilians from entering or leaving. An
Albanian translator was pulled out of a car and harassed by a
gun-wielding paramilitary soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``With an action like this, we will always have personal
friction and emotional problems that will impede a very quick
carrying-out'' of the transition of power, said German Brigadier
General Fritz von Horff. But ``while we may not have everything
under complete control at the moment, we have enough of a presence
in town to have a safe withdrawal of all forces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Albanians, virtually imprisoned for months by the
overwhelming presence of the Serb military, threw flowers at the
K-FOR tanks, waved and chanted ``NATO! NATO'' as the tanks cruised
the winding streets. They lined up to have their photos taken with
the foreign soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs made their displeasure obvious at the peacekeepers'
arrival. They erected illegal checkpoints for K-FOR and Western
vehicles as they made the trek from Kukes, in northern Albania, to
Prizren. German and Dutch K-FOR tanks and vehicles were not stopped
from rolling into town. But paramilitaries glared at the NATO
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In town, the streets were filled with nervous Serbs. ``I love
Albanians. I want to stay, but I am very afraid,'' said 76-year-old
Kustist Zorka, weeping softly. She wanted to deliver some bread to
her son, a Yugoslav soldier who was leaving town, but she could not
make it through the crowds and the Serb checkpoint to find him, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She was soon surrounded by young Albanians. ``How many Albanians
did your son kill?'' Ilir Morina, 19, shouted at her.
</P>
<P>
   Then he shrugged. ``The old woman is safe,'' he said. ``How can
I do anything to her? But I don't know how they can stay here,''
Morina said of the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees trickled across the Kosovo border with Albania, against
the urgings of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees.
The UN agency is warning ethnic Albanians that it is not yet safe
to go back _ a point that was made clear by Sunday's activity in
Prizren.
</P>
<P>
   The area between Albania and Prizren is a stark picture of the
ravages and damage of war. The streets are pocked with holes from
de-mining, and KFOR says many more mines have been planted only
inches off the road.
</P>
<P>
   House and restaurants were burned and gutted. NATO bombs have
left huge craters in the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Many Albanians went at least as far as the border Sunday
morning, camping out early to greet the peacekeeping troops. By
mid-day, the Albanians had raced over the border crossing and
looted the Serb border checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
   One man from Prizren was delighted to find his own license
plates, which Serb police had confiscated from him when he was
forced over the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to put these on my car,'' said 60-year-old Kurtish
Krasniqi. ``And if I can, I will go back to Kosovo tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
