<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3779 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ALBANIANS-     06-13 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-ALBANIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN SISTERS THANK SERB POLICEMAN FOR SURVIVAL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UROSEVAC, Yugoslavia _ Pale and shaking with excitement, the
Veliu sisters, Fikrete and Sadete, emerged into the sunlight
Sunday, strolling through their hometown for the first time in 12
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   They were giddy that the war was over, appalled at the looted
shops, hopeful that their loved ones would return from exile.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of town, anxious Serbs like Ranko Davidovic, a
23-year-old student, stood in the square, arms folded as NATO tanks
rumbled by.
</P>
<P>
   For the Veliu sisters, who are Albanian, and Davidovic, who is a
Serb, the arrival of NATO troops means different things and
inspires different emotions. Ethnic Albanians see the NATO troops
as liberators, as guarantors that the 850,000 refugees forced to
leave Kosovo will be able to return home soon.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs in this town of 60,000 are not quite sure what to make of
the new occupying army. They bristle at foreigners replacing their
own troops. But there is also a grudging acceptance that NATO
troops are needed because Serbs fear that without the soldiers they
will be driven out by Albanians seeking revenge.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in Urosevac Sunday is happening throughout Kosovo,
as the Kosovo-Force, or K-FOR, peacekeepers fanned out across this
province and residents adjusted to the shifting balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   Like every town in Kosovo, Urosevac is in transition, as an
occupying army rolls in, a defeated one rolls out, and those who
briefly ruled the roost worry about how their former neighbors will
react when they get back.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians who stayed here, mostly hidden, seemed to
appear from nowhere Sunday, lining the main road just outside town
to cheer the British troops that are part of the K-FOR vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   Little boys used mud to spell NATO and UCK, the Albanian letters
for the Kosovo Liberation Army, on discarded pieces of styrofoam as
a greeting for the British soldiers. Little girls brought forth
bouquets of flowers and kissed soldiers on the cheek.
</P>
<P>
   The Veliu sisters, Fikrete, 22, and Sadete, 25, said they and
five other members of their family spent the war in their house on
the outskirts of the town. Their pale white skin lent credence to
their story.
</P>
<P>
   The family had stockpiled food, but they were virtual prisoners
in their home. Most other Albanians, who make up about 75 percent
of the town, fled, including their sister and her seven children.
But they decided to take their chances and stick it out.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons they decided to stay was that a Serb
neighbor named Dragan, a local police officer, promised he would
protect them. He kept his word Saturday night. As NATO troops
prepared to enter the town, some masked Serb paramilitary police
came into their neighborhood, determined to torch the Albanian
homes.
</P>
<P>
   As the terrified Velius huddled inside, listening to the
conversation, they heard Dragan convince the paramilitaries, who
were not from Urosevac, that the homes around his were not
Albanian. Those same paramilitaries were blamed by residents here
for looting shops before they left town Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Dragan packed his car full of clothing and his wife and
four children. He and all other Serb police and troops must leave
the province under terms of the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came to us and said, `I'm sorry, I have to go. I can't live
here anymore.' It was very hard to say goodbye. If he wasn't there,
we wouldn't be alive,'' said Sadete.
</P>
<P>
   The Velius vowed to protect Dragan's home if any Albanians come
looking to burn it in revenge. Fikrete, however, said she doubted
that such reprisals would be common.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't do what they did to us,'' said Fikrete.
</P>
<P>
   Fikrete said their existence during the war was a combination of
sheer boredom and, when they heard gunshots outside or thought the
police were moving in, sheer terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stayed home, watched TV, waited for NATO,'' said Fikrete.
</P>
<P>
   As the Albanians come back, the Serbs leave. On the road that
led out of this town, a half-mile convoy of Yugoslav army vehicles,
and passenger cars filled with civilians, waited to leave. The
troops were withdrawing from Kosovo, some with their families. The
main road into Pristina was choked with NATO armored vehicles and
Serb refugees from the countryside, fleeing north to get away, they
said, from the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA was very much on the minds of Serbs in Urosevac Sunday,
too. Zvonko Janicijevic, 42, was one of several refugees from the
nearby village of Stimlje who showed up in town saying that he and
his family had been chased out of their homes by the KLA Saturday
morning, as British troops were on their way north from Macedonia.
He said the Albanian rebels sprayed houses with gunfire, and that
he was barely able to get out with his two children.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA ``took advantage of the vacuum,'' said Janicijevic,
whose story spread like wildfire through an already worried Serb
population. ``They are not terrorists, they are bandits.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbs here are ready to believe that the KLA has been given a
free hand by NATO. And yet there was little animosity expressed
toward NATO troops by Serbs. On the contrary, many came out to wave
and shake hands with members of the Royal Highland Fusilliers of
the British Army.
</P>
<P>
   As a NATO tank rumbled through the town center, Janicijevic
waved enthusiastically at a soldier whose head was outside the
tank. The Scottish soldier waved back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see them,'' Janicijevic said. ``I want K-FOR in my
village.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish soldiers said they had been warmly greeted by most
local residents. But they said some withdrawing Serb troops had
shouted, ``NATO go home!''
</P>
<P>
   One of the Scottish soldiers, Daryl Gibson, said he appreciated
the humiliation felt by the retreating Serb soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``One minute they're holding out, the next they're told to clear
out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the local water plant, who would not give his
name, said Saturday's heavy thunderstorms had knocked out water to
the town, but that repairmen could not get to the site 4 miles away
because the area was crawling with KLA rebels. He said he appealed
to K-FOR for an armed escort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general told me they didn't have enough people to go up,''
he said, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   Nemanja Stefanovic, 35, said that local Serbs were watching the
K-FOR troops, which he called ``UN troops,'' to see how they act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that the UN troops will guarantee our safety,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
