</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON'S MAYOR FACES A CAMPAIGN-FINANCE INQUIRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So far Anthony A. Williams, mayor of the District
of Columbia, has committed few of the ethical and managerial
blunders that characterized the previous administration, but now
campaign-finance charges are threatening his squeaky-clean image.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Williams took over a city plagued with financial
crises and began making striking changes. But now the city's office
of campaign finance is asserting that Williams violated city law by
not promptly disclosing two consulting arrangements in July and
August 1998, when he was running for office. A hearing on the issue
is set for this week.
</P>
<P>
   A clause in the campaign law requires candidates to report
changes in their income or alterations to their financial
disclosures within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   Williams served as the city's chief financial officer for three
years before quitting to run for mayor, a race he won last
November.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has shown confidence in Williams, passing bills that
would shift authority for the day-to-day operation of the District
government back to its elected officials from the control board
that Congress created to oversee its finances in 1995. In a speech
this spring at the National Press Club in Washington, Williams said
that ``restoring faith and confidence in the government'' was a
major focus of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Marion S. Barry, who did not seek re-election last year,
preceded Williams as mayor, serving three terms from 1978 to 1990
and returning to office in 1994 after a six-month prison term on
drug charges. Barry's personality and politics shaped the District
for almost two decades, establishing a reputation for
out-of-control government.
</P>
<P>
   Williams filed a financial statement on July 17, 1998, about a
month after resigning as the city's chief financial officer and
announcing his candidacy for mayor. The statement indicated no
outside income. But two weeks later, on July 31, Williams accepted
a consulting fee of $30,000 from the Arthur Andersen accounting
company. On August 6, he signed a contract with Nationsbank Corp.
for $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until April, in financial statements that all
District officials are required to file annually, that Williams
disclosed information on his outside employment. After that filing,
the office of campaign finance asked for more information, and on
May 28, Williams complied.
</P>
<P>
   Williams issued a statement saying that ``nothing improper
occurred'' in the work he conducted for the two companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have disclosed the fact of my outside employment
earlier and inadvertently failed to do so,'' Williams said. ``For
this oversight, I am sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has been ordered to appear at a hearing before the
director of the campaign finance office and the District's board of
elections and ethics on June 16. The campaign finance office could
impose a $1,000 fine, $500 for each violation.
</P>
<P>
   Williams contends that his work was not a conflict of interest,
and that the work with the two companies did not ``involve their
relationship with the District of Columbia.'' However, Peggy
Armstrong, the mayor's spokesman, said Williams would provide any
information that would be helpful. The city agency has asked for
Williams' financial records, including canceled checks and
statements showing the dates and amounts of his contracts with
Arthur Andersen and Nationsbank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
