<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3785 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICH-GUN-POLITICS-TRI     06-13 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-GUN-POLITICS-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMEN AT RISK OVER GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ESCANABA, Mich. _ As the House of Representatives prepares to
vote this week on gun-control legislation, the popularity of
hunting and the nearly universal ownership of guns in many rural
areas has put congressmen from these areas at special political
risk _ particularly Rep. Bart Stupak, a Democrat whose district
encompasses Michigan's northernmost reaches.
</P>
<P>
   Shootings in schools have alarmed millions of Americans over the
last several years, but here and in many other northern Michigan
communities, the first day of deer hunting season each November is
an official school holiday so that children as young as 5 can join
their parents in the woods. While the minimum legal age for
shooting a deer in Michigan is 15, the law is widely flouted, with
boys and girls as young s 10 often bagging their first buck during
their holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody hunts that day,'' said Jason Malner, a ninth grader
who owns three rifles and two shotguns. ``I use the 0.243 for deer,
I use the 12-gauges for rabbits and partridge and I use the 0.22s
for fooling around and shooting at targets,'' he said as he ate a
steak at the Buck Inn Restaurant here with his mother, Pam, who
confirmed his gun inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Stupak, a four-term Democrat whose wooded district is three
times the size of New Jersey, shares his constituents' love of deer
hunting, going out every year with his 19- and 16-year-old sons. A
former police officer in Escanaba who also spent a decade as a
Michigan State Police trooper, Stupak was one of about 30 Democrats
who crossed party lines to oppose gun-control legislation _ at
least, until this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Dismayed by the recent school shootings in Littleton, Colo.,
Stupak has publicly suggested that he would vote for legislation
this month to require child-proof safety locks on guns, mandate
background checks at certain gun shows and ban the import of
high-capacity ammunition clips. But Stupak said in an interview on
Saturday that he would vote against any broader legislation, like
raising the minimum age for buying a handgun to 21 from 18.
</P>
<P>
   Because most members of Congress staked out their positions on
gun control long ago and have not changed them much, Stupak's
openness to any new legislation at all has brought national
attention and lobbying by gun control advocates and opponents
alike.
</P>
<P>
   The National Rifle Association has sent out at least three
rounds of letters to members living in Stupak's district, asking
them to try to persuade him to change his mind, and has paid for
advertisements on a radio station in Traverse City, said Stupak,
who received copies of the letters because he is a member of the
rifle association. The association declined to comment. Stupak said
he had also heard that gun-control advocates would start taking out
opposing radio and newspaper advertisements in his district on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews over the weekend with two dozen of Stupak's
constituents here in this logging town of 15,000 people, 320 miles
northwest of Detroit, and with seven constituents in Marquette, a
shipping and tourism town 60 miles north of Escanaba, suggest that
Stupak is running some political risks by showing an interest in
gun-control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Local residents are leery of anything labeled gun control. Yet
when asked about the specific rule changes favored by Stupak, many
said they were in favor.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest opponents of gun control seem the most willing to
base their vote in next year's election on Stupak's gun legislation
vote. Keith Grabowski, 47, a burial vault salesman who attended a
walleye fishing tournament over the weekend with his 10-year-old
son, said he had known Stupak since high school. Stupak grew up in
a nearby town and had dated, and later married, the best friend of
Grabowski's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of friendship and consistent political support,
Grabowski said he would probably not vote for Stupak again if he
endorsed a broad gun-control bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up here, people have lived with guns, and sure, there's an
occasional accident, but if the kids are taught right there's no
problem at all,'' Grabowski said, adding proudly that his son,
Justin, had shot 12 partridges during hunting season last year.
</P>
<P>
   Standing near Grabowski at the fishing tournament's headquarters
at the local fairgrounds on Saturday were Jeff and LeeAnne Iverson.
Iverson, 30, a truck mechanic who hunts deer and bear, said the
government should enforce existing laws better instead of drafting
new ones.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Iverson, 25, a nursery school teacher who accompanies
her husband on hunts but does not do any shooting, said she favored
safety locks on guns and more background checks because ``too many
guns that aren't used for hunting get out on the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   In Marquette, Diane Botsford, 42, a nurse who has a 13-year-old
son, said that she wanted all the restrictions favored by Stupak
and more. ``Definitely we need to crack down. Guns should not be in
the hands of kids,'' she said as she walked her labrador next to
the marina.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the Buck Inn Restaurant in Escanaba, Mrs. Malner said
that she favored more checks on the backgrounds of gun buyers.
``You're never in that much of a hurry to get a gun that you can't
wait for a background check, unless you want it for something
bad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Malner, who cleans offices at night, said that
teen-agers like her son Jason would inevitably own and handle guns,
so safety locks were useless. ``If they want the gun, they're going
to get it off of there,'' she said, later adding that though the
family's guns were not locked up, Jason was allowed to use them
only while hunting with his father.
</P>
<P>
   At the restaurant's bar, across from a stuffed black bear head,
four drivers of cement mixers agreed that it was pointless and
unnecessary to put limits on gun sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I want to go shoot someone, I'm not going to buy it in a
shop, I'm not going to buy it at a show or anywhere I have to give
my name,'' said one driver, Donald St. Cyr. ``I'm going to buy it
on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   But St. Cyr said that he would vote again next year for Stupak
regardless of the congressman's votes on gun control. Stupak
frequently tours the district, and among politicians, St. Cyr said,
``he's the only one I see other than at election time.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Another driver, Mel W. Hanson, 58, said he had never run into a
problem with guns in a lifetime of hunting deer, partridge and
rabbits. ``I've never been threatened up here by anyone with a
gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two miles away, on the shores of a bay of Lake Michigan, a city
park ranger on a bicycle, Robert Freidhoff, 20, said that he and
some of his friends thought something should be done to limit the
availability of guns to children but that the issue divided the
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say we're split right down the middle,'' Freidhoff said.
``You ask one person, they'd say yes; you ask another person,
they'd say no.''
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Stupak said that his biggest concern was that if he voted for
even a limited bill, he would be accused at the next election of
restricting people's access to guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what I'm going to do,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3788 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-FATHER-BOS &LR;      06-13 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-FATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENT VOWS TO SIT ON SIDELINES DURING SON'S CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine _ For months, George W. Bush has fretted
over the legacy of his father, the former president. While the
younger Bush made his fortune and was elected governor of Texas
partly on his father's name, he worried that his chances of
becoming president would be hurt by the mixed memories of his
father's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, on the eve of Governor Bush's visit to New Hampshire,
which holds the nation's first primary, father and son seemed to
strike a deal. Former president Bush vowed to stay out of his son's
campaign and said, ``I don't care about the issues.'' Governor Bush
responded by saying that he didn't care about losing because he had
his father's love.
</P>
<P>
   To make sure no one missed the message, the two George Bushes
discussed the matter in one of the most unusual press conferences
in their family's history before a throng of 300 journalists at the
family compound, at the edge of a flower-scented promontory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unpopular. I was,'' the former president said with
uncommon bluntness, when asked why his low standing in 1992 has
been followed by his son's rapid rise. ``Maybe I'm a little
egotistical, but surveys I've seen have been rather pleasant about
me. . . . Let him find his own way. He doesn't need a voice from
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, both Bushes have a common ground that helps explain the
son's ambition: Both were shaped by the father's 1992 election
defeat. While receiving little coverage at the time, George W. Bush
played a key role in the campaign, serving as a go-between with
campaign officials and his father and often offering strategic
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sky high after Desert Storm, only to sink . . . pretty
darn low,'' the former president said. ``He was with me in the ups
and downs.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush's friends say he is still stung by his father's
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first-son syndrome,'' said Mary Matalin, the
political director of President Bush's 1992 campaign, who often
worked in coordination with George W. Bush. ``George W. always was
his father's most trusted, first-among-equals son. He was the one
we all went to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, George W., who last November was elected to a second
term as governor, said his father's loss had ``liberated'' him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have half his friends and all his enemies,'' the governor
said. ``If things don't work out, I'll still have a father and a
mother and a wife that love me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, referring to the family estate on Walker's Point, where
Texas and US flags snapped in the ocean breeze, he said: ``This is
an appropriate place to talk about this because this is the place
we find love and comfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his White House years, former President Bush had come
to this sprawling, shingled home by the sea to seek a month-long
respite from the turmoil of Washington. He would race in his
cigarette boat, power-walk on Goose Rocks Beach and play endless
rounds of golf. He usually kept the press at bay, meeting perhaps a
few times each season with a small group of reporters. By the time
he ran for reelection, one of his slogans was ``Annoy the media _
Reelect Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, with many of the news media who had covered his
presidency now focused on his son, the mood was giddy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where were you in '92?'' Barbara Bush asked by way of
greeting. The ``photo opportunity'' of the two Bush couples turned
into a 30-minute question and answer session that focused almost
entirely on why the elder Bush had been unpopular and his son is
not. Throughout it all, the former president seemed reflective and
tranquil. When he tripped on his syntax, just as in the old days,
he exclaimed, ``I'm the same guy!''
</P>
<P>
   All around this quintessential Yankee tourist haven, the Bushes
are not just back in town; they also seem to be back in power, even
though George W. Bush has a long way to go before winning the
Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father was never comfortable in this role,'' said one top
adviser who has worked for both Bushes and who asked not to be
identified. ``George W. clearly is. His father would make joking
references to the `vision thing,' like saying, `Is this the place
where I have to insert this vision part into the speech?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The adviser said, ``I can't tell whether (former President Bush)
is more delighted that his son is running for president or that he
doesn't have to be in the middle of it and take all the
hurly-burly.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor came here to celebrate his father's 75th
birthday Saturday. But the timing of the visit attracted far more
attention, tucked between campaign visits to Iowa and New
Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking thing about the two George Bushes is how
differently they prepared for the presidency. Both men started out
in similar ways. George H. W. Bush gained notoriety because he was
the son of the former senator from Connecticut, Prescott Bush. Both
went to Phillips Academy, the elite prep school in Andover, Mass.,
and Yale University. Both men went to West Texas hoping to strike
it rich in the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   But here the similarities end. The senior Bush spent much of his
life preparing to be president, as a congressman, ambassador to
China, Republican Party chairman, and vice president. The junior
Bush, who never thought much about politics during his youth, lost
a race for Congress, got rich partly as a result of deals with his
father's friends, and became governor partly because of his
father's fame.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, then-President Bush spent much of the fall campaign
ridiculing the idea that a governor with no foreign policy
experience could aspire to the White House. Bush, asked Sunday
whether his son has properly prepared to be president, said that
``everybody has his own experience. I had no comparable executive
experience . . . running the state of Texas as governor.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush, who always touted his past when running for
president, made fun of such a strategy Sunday. ``I was called the
`resume president,' but I never felt people were saying that with
awe and respect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are many ways in which Governor Bush is emulating
his father. Former president Bush's call for a ``thousand points of
light'' has turned into Governor Bush's proposal for ``armies of
compassion.'' The former president's push for a ``kinder, gentler''
America has morphed into the governor's declaration that he is a
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   But the younger Bush is trying to avoid some of the problems
encountered by his father, who was goaded into running to the
political right in the '92 race in an effort to beat Patrick
Buchanan and other conservatives in the primaries, and then was
unable to reposition himself in the political middle for the
general election against Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to the surprise of some aides, Governor Bush last week
appeared to set himself up to repeat one of his father's most
famous mistakes by declaring that he would oppose any tax increase
if elected president, echoing former President Bush's famously
broken vow, ``Read my lips, no new taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Given how the former president vividly recalls that he was
unpopular when he left the White House, he said that he doubted he
would appear at many more events with his son. But if all else
fails, he said he had a backup plan: ``Unleash Barbara.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
