<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 23:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOMINGO-MAYOR-ART-2TA     06-13 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINGO-MAYOR-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTO DOMINGO MAYOR IS STEEPED IN THE MERENGUE, AMWAY, AND NOW
TRASH
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic _ Sitting in the balcony of
his unfinished mansion high on a hill that overlooks the Arroyo
Hondo River here, Johnny Ventura was the picture of contentment
recently as family members came and went around him.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter-in-law brought his baby granddaughter over for some
cuddling as he ate lunch, his doting wife kept ordering dishes to
the table, and one of his seven children came over to chat.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of a life Ventura, 59, had crafted for himself
in semiretirement after more than 40 years in show business as the
Dominican Republic's most popular merengue singer. He dissolved his
band in 1992 and cut down on performances and decided, he said, to
pay more attention to his business as a distributor for Amway.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed last year when his friend and fellow longtime
politician in the Dominican Revolutionary Party, Jose Francisco
Pena Gomez, died of cancer in the middle of a campaign to become
mayor of this capital city.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura was Pena Gomez's running mate, for the job of vice
mayor. Ventura had filled the position before and describes it as
``almost decorative.'' He had little choice but to step in as
mayoral candidate, with Peggy Cabral, Pena Gomez's widow, filling
in for vice mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Ventura is Santo Domingo's reluctant mayor _ not as
contented or as universally adored anymore after his first year in
office. And he is deeply involved in the city's most pressing
issue: trash.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the magnitude of the problem, and so visible is the
uncollected garbage around here _ in gutters, on medians, in
rivers, on hillsides _ that a cruise line dropped Santo Domingo
from its itinerary this year after passengers complained of the
city's filth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trash is killing us _ there are mosquitoes, mice,'' said
Demetrio Bobea, 43, a handyman here. He said he still dances
Venturo's merengues, but in a bad mood.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura is no stranger to politics, having for decades combined
musical stardom with commitment to his political party, a social
democratic group he joined 37 years ago and calls ``the party of
people's hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Born Juan de Dios Ventura Soriano to a poor Santo Domingo
family, Ventura worked odd jobs while going to school before he won
a radio amateur contest in 1956 and abandoned dreams of becoming an
architect to find fame as a performer.
</P>
<P>
   With a deep baritone and an elegant stage presence _ he is a
slim 6-foot-1 _ Ventura, who is also an arranger and composer, is
internationally recognized for merengue of picaresque lyrics and
blistering dancing and for infusing music of rural roots with urban
grit.
</P>
<P>
   He still manages to sneak in performances, making appearances on
a daily television variety show here, ``Super Afternoon,'' and
playing at weddings, private parties and, in April, at a campaign
rally in Panama for a losing presidential candidate, Martin
Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   But Ventura, who also acquired a law degree, said that after
growing up apolitical under the military dictatorship of Rafael
Trujillo, he counted himself among the youth emboldened to demand
and work for change after the dictator died and his abuses became
well known.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to help in his country's transition to democracy,
Ventura said, he served as Santo Domingo vice mayor and in the
Dominican Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But being mayor is another matter. ``The mayor gets the
complaints of citizens,'' Ventura said. ``People don't think their
problem will be solved unless they see the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   While recognized by both critics and fans as honest and well
meaning, he presides over a city government with scarce resources
and a bureaucracy bloated by political patronage. He has also
wrestled with the central government, which is ruled by a different
party, over control of municipal matters, including garbage
collection.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura sees disorderly population growth in Santo Domingo, now
home to about three million, as a fundamental flaw that generates
the trash problem and many others.
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that the city is short at least 675,000 housing
units and that ``the immense majority of the people of Santo
Domingo live in inadequate housing.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent tour of the city he pointed at the illegal housing
that has encroached even in expensive neighborhoods _ clusters of
structures made out of a patchwork of cement blocks and scraps of
wood and zinc that sit perilously along riverbanks and hillsides or
are wedged in under bridges and other housing.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, which Ventura attributes to the influx of Haitians
and Dominicans from the countryside coming to the city for jobs,
was blamed for many of the deaths during Hurricane Georges last
year. But squatters have rebuilt in many of the same spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the police realize what's going on, there are 600 little
houses'' Ventura said. ``Look how they throw the trash everywhere
because garbage trucks can't get in. And they blame me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura said he needs control of the contract that the national
government has with the company that picks up trash in 80 percent
of the city for better oversight. He contends the collections often
are incomplete in the coverage area. But his critics note that he
could use the city's resources in the meantime to at least clean up
tourist areas like the old section known as the ``colonial zone.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They also fault him for failing to use his popularity as an
entertainer to rise above political warfare and to summon support
for this and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, who said he was working on blanketing the city with
trash receptacles, said he was also seeking an inventory of
government properties, looking for space to build affordable
housing to sell to people and ``turn squatters into homeowners.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My great dream is the reurbanization of the city of Santo
Domingo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the public grumbling, some city dwellers still honk and
wave when they see him. ``People still love me a little,'' the
mayor said half-jokingly as two young men pulled alongside to wave
hello with big smiles.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, he said, he is still asked to perform. His
latest recording, to be released this year, is his 100th. Last year
he published a book about his rags-to-riches story titled ``Johnny
Ventura: A Little Bit of Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't retire until my faculties'' fail me, he said. ``I feel
I'm a better singer now.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about his political ambitions after four years as
mayor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather finish my term,'' he said, ``and go play with my
grandchildren.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
