u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-NYT &LR;      06-13 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-AIRBUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING WORKS ON ENDING OUTPUT WOES AS AIRBUS OPTIMISM SOARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LE BOURGET, France _ Perhaps it is just the home turf advantage.
But at back-to-back news conferences at the biennial Paris Air Show
here Sunday, the contrast between Boeing Co. and its archrival,
Airbus Industrie, could not have been more vivid.
</P>
<P>
   While Alan Mulally, the president of Boeing's commercial
airplane business, politely answered questions from the packed
auditorium of reporters, Nokl Forgeard, the French chairman of
Airbus, was mobbed by photographers who treated him like a visiting
rock star.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally repeated Boeing's view that there was no need for a new
superjumbo jet carrying 600 passengers and he caused a stir when he
predicted that Boeing's orders this year would be just 30 to 40
percent of what they were in 1998. Boeing later said that what
Mulally meant to say was that orders for commercial jets from both
manufacturers would be down 30 to 40 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard was much more loose and upbeat. He said Airbus, which
is owned by four European partners, expected to see sales rise to
$17 billion this year from $13.3 billion in 1998. He also
reiterated a commitment to build its proposed A3XX superjumbo and
to transform itself from a consortium into a single company like
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed A3XX is a 600-seat craft and would cost $12 billion
to develop. Asked about an investigation by European and American
regulators into accusations that Airbus and Boeing conspired to
raise prices, Forgeard, who began his career as a French
bureaucrat, dismissed the charge with an English obscenity.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast between the executives reflects the recent fortunes
of the two competitors. Boeing, which is the world's biggest
aerospace company and America's single-largest exporter, is still
trying to recover from its decision to sell a record number of
airplanes at bargain prices. The action resulted in production
chaos two years ago that erased Boeing's earnings and sent its
profit margins tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus, on the other hand, has cut costs while seeing the
popularity of its airplanes steadily grow over the last five years,
bringing it close to its goal of achieving a 50 percent share of
all new jet orders. So far this year, Airbus has sold 153 jets to
Boeing's 52. That may change later this week when Boeing is
expected to announce an order for 100 single-aisle planes from
International Lease Finance Corp. But Airbus, too, will be
announcing another 40 new orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not as pessimistic as my competitor,'' said Forgeard, who
added that complacency was now Airbus' worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Airbus faces a distinct set of challenges. Ending the
latest reports of wrangling among the four partners, Forgeard said
a deal had been worked out between Aerospatiale Matra SA of France
and DaimlerChrysler Aerospace AG of Germany that cleared the way
for production of the A318, a new, single-aisle 100-passenger jet
that would be the smallest in the Airbus family.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Airbus already has more than 100 orders for the
A318, Aerospatiale executives balked at investing in the new plane
because they were concerned that Aerospatiale was getting too
little of the work. Forgeard said the new jet would be assembled by
DaimlerChrysler Aerospace, or DASA, in Hamburg, Germany. But at the
same time, DASA agreed to shift some assembly of the larger A319
from Hamburg to the Aerospatiale factory in Toulouse, France, which
is also where Airbus has its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard praised the agreement, saying that it would give Airbus
more flexibility by insuring two strong assembly lines for its
single-aisle jets. The Airbus single-aisle family, which also
includes the A320 and A321, has been selling strongly over the last
18 months, surpassing Boeing's rival 737.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Aerospatiale and DASA, which each hold a stake
equal to 37.9 percent, Airbus is owned by British Aerospace PLC and
Construcciones Aeronauticas SA of Spain. The rift over the A318 is
the latest example of the tensions between Airbus partners that has
delayed its transformation into a single corporation from a
consortium that farms out production of different sections of every
plane to the four partners.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard, who became leader of Airbus last year, has insisted
that the airplane maker must make the change if it is to continue
to compete effectively against Boeing. But efforts to move forward
with the privatization have foundered because of disagreements
about how to value each partner's assets and because of the
dizzying pace of European aerospace consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Construcciones Aeronauticas, which had been wooed by
all three of the other partners, announced that it would merge with
DASA. And DaimlerChrysler is considering selling a minority stake
in DASA to the public to pay for further expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Forgeard said that DASA's deal with Construcciones Aeronautics
would have little effect on the consortium and that both companies
would continue to keep their seats on the Airbus board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
