<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DELAYS-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING WAYS TO CUT THE WEB-PAGE WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The word ASTERISK in parentheses has been used instead of the
symbol, which is non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(lb) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In high-tech business circles, people often talk about how
things happen faster in ``Internet time'' _ deals are made faster,
technology changes more rapidly and companies succeed or fail in a
much shorter time frame.
</P>
<P>
   But for most consumers, ``Internet time'' is a much slower
concept _ the often interminable wait for a Web page to show up on
a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   The bottleneck is bandwidth _ the capacity of Internet services
to deliver Web pages and other data to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce companies, while constantly adjusting to operating at
lightning speeds to keep pace with Internet technologies, must
reconcile themselves to the fact that their customers are living in
what amounts to slow motion on the other end of the line. As a
result, these businesses have to make difficult decisions about how
to attract and keep customers within the limited bandwidth
available.
</P>
<P>
   For all the growth experienced by e-commerce sites in the last
year, ``speed is still clearly a limitation,'' said Cliff Sharples,
founding chairman of Shop.org, an e-commerce trade group, and chief
executive of Garden.com, a gardening supplies site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to quantify the business we're not doing because of
it, but I'd have to say it's pretty significant,'' Sharples said.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and telecommunications companies are working furiously to
deliver high-speed connections to more consumers, but in the
meantime, Internet retailers are not sitting idly by.
</P>
<P>
   For one, they have put an emphasis on designing pages that load
quickly. E-commerce executives and site designers say they
generally try to adhere to the eight-second rule _ after eight
seconds of waiting for a Web page to load, consumers become much
more likely to abandon the effort. But no matter how strenuously
online businesses work to reach or exceed that goal, they often
fail, especially with users who connect at home through dial-up
modems.
</P>
<P>
   According to Nielsen/Netratings, which measures Internet
audiences, home users had to wait an average of 28 seconds to load
Web pages of the 109 most visited e-commerce sites last month. And
Keynote Systems Inc., an Internet performance measurement firm,
reported that business users wait an average of eight seconds to
load each page, typically through faster T1 lines.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce executives across all categories know they must beat
those times or face an exodus of customers. Jonathan Morris,
executive vice president of Bluefly, a discount apparel retailer,
said the need for a fast site forced the company to change or delay
the development of certain features. ``There are things we could do
that we're holding off on because it might adversely affect the
consumer's experience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the company had a zoom feature, which allowed
customers to look more closely at a product's fabric _ an important
capability, because a computer screen cannot convey fabric texture
nearly as well as a catalog can. However, Morris said users
``didn't love the feature, as it did put an additional strain on
our servers'' and subsequently slowed the service.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting such features, he said, gives the company more chance to
employ a sophisticated database that can track inventory as a user
enters the site and can serve registered customers images of items
they might like. On a site already heavy with graphics, such a
system could slow page loads long enough to lose a customer. ``It's
a balancing act, maybe more in our category than others,'' Morris
said.
</P>
<P>
   That balancing act applies to other aspects of Web design as
well, said Andrew Sather, senior vice president of Sapient, an
Internet design and consulting firm. Bandwidth concerns, he says,
force Internet companies to make hard choices about optimizing
their sites to appeal to certain customer groups, such as those
with higher-speed connections, while possibly alienating users who
connect at lower speeds.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sather says that Sapient recently designed the
Virgin Megastore Web site (www.virginmega.com), ``and we optimized
it for a higher-end user.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made assumptions _ about things like screen resolutions,
browser, modem speed _ that were pretty ambitious,'' he said,
``because the company wanted to push the envelope with what they
could do on the site.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the site is heavier on graphics than, say,
E(ASTERISK)Trade, another site Sapient designed. ``With
E(ASTERISK)Trade, you want to cater to the super high-tech day
trader,'' Sather said, ``but also the older couple who are dialing
in with an antiquated laptop from an RV somewhere in the Grand
Canyon.''
</P>
<P>
   Sather said that among the e-commerce categories hurt by slow
connection speeds are those that are ``more lifestyle-intensive,
such as anything trying to target the youth culture with moving
images _ that sort of thing.'' In such cases, he said, ``there's
more competition for bandwidth between product presentation and
lifestyle presentation, but at some point you have to be King
Solomon, and split the baby and decide.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For other e-commerce categories, too, a sluggish Web ``can have
serious economic impact,'' said Jack Staff, chief economist at Zona
Research, an Internet research firm. ``Those most at risk are the
sellers of apparel, where visual presentation is so important, and
technology products that require more explanation on the pages,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce sites willing to spend money can, however, find ways
to increase speed without making compromises on site design. For
instance, through applications developed by companies like Akamai
Technologies, Staff said, sites can cut the time it takes to
download a page to a range of half to a tenth of the usual time.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai generates a global map of Web traffic conditions and
serves the pages of client Web sites over the most efficient route,
using more than 600 servers on 25 networks in Europe, the United
States and the Pacific Rim. David Goodtree, an Akamai spokesman,
said the service cost between ``a couple of thousand and tens of
thousands of dollars'' a month, depending on the traffic served,
and its clients include Yahoo and Apple Computer, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Such technologies may be crucial even if companies like
Motorola, Sun Microsystems, Cisco Systems and AT&AMP;T succeed in their
quest to deliver faster connection speeds to Internet users using
digital subscriber telephone lines and cable modems within the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   But even if they do, the increase in bandwidth may continue to
be canceled out by an equal or greater increase in the number of
Internet users, cautions Fritz Mueller, director of product
marketing for Keynote Systems. That, in turn, could leave
e-commerce companies precisely where they are today: hoping for new
technological breakthroughs as they scramble to make the experience
worth the customer's effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like disk space,'' Mueller observed. ``No matter how much
you get, you use it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2302EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 23:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3824 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-TAX-CUTS-NYT &LR;      06-13 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-TAX-CUTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS PUSH TAX CUTS, BUT VOTERS SAY DON'T BOTHER
</HEADLINE>
   (Previously budgeted at NY-TAX-CUTS) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANSONIA, Conn. _ A $50 gift from the state Capitol for every
adult might seem a welcome bonus on the steep streets of this
blue-collar town, which has been the victim of a depressing parade
of fires, strikes and bankruptcies in the century since its now
ghostly riverfront factories churned out anything molten, from
bayonets to thimbles.
</P>
<P>
   The average annual per capita income here, about $23,000, ranks
157th out of Connecticut's 169 towns. Even Ansonia's leading
conversation piece, a plaque marking the high-water mark from the
still lamented flood of 1955, corroded away and is now just a
memory.
</P>
<P>
   But the sales-tax rebate that Connecticut lawmakers approved
with much self-congratulation before adjourning on Thursday is seen
by many here as wasteful and even insulting, considering what they
say the state could buy if the whole $110 million were used in one
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``People take $50 and think, `whoop-de-do,''' said David Ings,
31, a construction laborer. ``They're just paying us off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ings' feelings reflect what some pollsters are calling a waning
appetite for tax cuts in the New York metropolitan area, eight
years after fury over Connecticut's new income tax produced a
stream of death threats to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   With a booming economy producing a happy electorate, many voters
are telling pollsters they want government to use this time of
plenty to rebuild schools and roads, instead of returning the
bounty a few dollars at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Legislatures in 36 states cut taxes last year, according to the
National Conference of State Legislatures, and with revenue in most
states running ahead of projections, at least that many are
expected to do so again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Among them is New Jersey, where Gov. Christie Whitman described
a property-tax rebate as ``from the State House to your house''
when she signed it in April.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, lawmakers continue to wrangle over a budget that
was due on April 1, but significant tax cuts remain part of all
three competing proposals.
</P>
<P>
   As irresistible as tax cuts may seem to politicians, polls have
found that voters are increasingly skeptical. In one of the
starkest findings, 78 percent of respondents to a University of
Connecticut poll said they would rather have the state use its
surplus on services for citizens, while just 18 percent said they
would prefer a rebate.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, taken from April 6 to 13, surveyed 500 adults and had
a margin of sampling error of plus or minus five percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we do tax questions, we don't find much hostility to the
tax levels that exist in the tri-state area,'' said Maurice
Carroll, the director of the polling institute at Quinnipiac
College in Hamden, Conn. ``People are saying: `The state has a lot
of stuff to do. They have the money, and they should spend it on
that stuff instead of sending it to me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, a Republican who proposed the Connecticut
rebate, was elected in 1994 in part on his 26-page plan to
eliminate the state income tax over five years.
</P>
<P>
   But with the tax-cut fever broken, he has retained high approval
ratings despite having abandoned that promise long ago, and it was
not even an issue during his re-election campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick S. Yang, a partner in a Democratic polling firm,
Garin-Hart-Yang Research Group, said that even today, few voters
would turn down a tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people are not as interested in that as they have been in
the past,'' Yang said. ``In good economic times, people feel they
can look beyond their own pocketbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   A leading Republican pollster, Frank Luntz, agreed. ``In today's
economic environment,'' he said, ``the demand for tax cuts is not
as great, because money is more plentiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz said that apathy about taxes is most pronounced at the
state level, where people are less concerned about wasteful
spending than they are when they think about Washington. ``The
closer you are to home, the more willing people are to pay taxes,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
