<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCIAL PUTS REPORTER IN TIGHT SPOT  
 ESQUIRE EDITOR HELPS UNCOVER CARVER STORIES  
 HOPES FOR A BEST SELLER ABOUT AGING NUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual items.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not real news, but it looks and tastes just like real news!
</P>
<P>
   In a national commercial that began showing over Memorial Day
weekend, Mary Civiello, a reporter for WCBS-TV news in New York
City and, until recently, an alternate anchor on CNBC, stands in a
grocery store, suited up and coiffed as if for a television
broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   A microphone appears in front of a man and then a woman, who
declare their approval of Benecol, a Johnson &AMP; Johnson margarine
product that the company says helps to lower cholesterol levels.
</P>
<P>
   After the consumers offer their testimonials, Ms. Civiello looks
into the camera and with on-the-scene newscaster aplomb, says,
``Benecol actually helps promote lower cholesterol levels.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial has been shown during local news broadcasts in
New York on WCBS and WNBC; on the national networks NBC, ABC and
CBS, and on the NBC cable networks, MSNBC and CNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Should a television news reporter promote a product in
commercials? Tom Goldstein, the dean of Columbia University's
Graduate School of Journalism, said, ``Everyone should be forgiven
one lapse, but she has to decide whether she wants to pursue a
career in serious journalism or in something else, it seems to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Civiello defended her appearance in the commercial. She has
been a freelance reporter appearing on WCBS as often as twice a
week, since leaving a job as anchor on WNBC-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the public is pretty savvy these days,'' she said. ``I
have taken this time in my life to look around at all the
possibilities, and this commercial happens to be the most visible
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But the commercial's visibility has deprived Ms. Civiello of her
freelance anchor job at CNBC. Martine Charles, a spokeswoman for
CNBC, said that Bruno Cohen, senior vice president of business news
for CNBC, had told Ms. Civiello that she could no longer appear on
CNBC. ``We don't feel that on-air journalists can be both on-air
talent and pitch product,'' Ms. Charles said. ``It's a conflict of
interest. CNBC can't appear to endorse any one product.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bill Carey, the news director of WCBS-TV, said, ``It is
clearly a slippery slope when reporters start endorsing products
and end up in commercials.'' He would not comment on Ms. Civiello's
fate but said, ``We are not interested in running this commercial
on any news broadcasts that she appears on in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   Esquire Editor Helps Uncover Carver Stories
</P>
<P>
   The stories sat there for more than a decade, unseen and unread,
in a writing desk that Raymond Carver's widow, the poet Tess
Gallagher, could not bear to open. But now they are out, at last:
three previously undiscovered stories by Carver, the noted author
of short stories.
</P>
<P>
   The first of them, ``Kindling,'' about a man ``between lives,''
appears in the July issue of Esquire. The other two, ``Dreams'' and
``Vandals,'' will appear in the magazine over the the next several
months.
</P>
<P>
   It was the prodding of a senior Esquire editor, Jay Woodruff,
that finally brought the stories to light. ``I was always reluctant
to do it,'' Ms. Gallagher said about opening the desk, which sits
in her home in Port Angeles, Wash., just as it did in 1988, when
Carver died of cancer at age 50. ``I knew that there would be a big
disruption once it was opened.''
</P>
<P>
   But she changed her mind when Woodruff asked her last year
whether there might be anything of Carver's ``still around'' that
could be used to commemorate the 10th anniversary of his death.
``That's when she asked me if I'd be interested in helping her go
through his desk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Port Angeles in March. Together they went through
Carver's papers, finding lots of scraps and other ephemera. Inside
a drawer of folders were drafts of the three stories, as well as
long fragments of others that were ultimately deemed too incomplete
to publish.
</P>
<P>
   Carver became well known for his stories portraying the lives of
those he called ``the working poor.'' He published 10 books of
prose and poetry during his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Gordon Lish, Carver's one-time editor, has said
he was responsible for the quality of Carver's early works by
virtue of the enormous revisions he says he made. Ms. Gallagher has
disputed that.
</P>
<P>
   Woodruff said that the new stories needed very little editing,
just ``typical housecleaning for grammar and typographical errors,
things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These are stories he was actively working on in his prime,''
Woodruff said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BERNARD STAMLER
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for a Best Seller About Aging Nuns
</P>
<P>
   As a young schoolboy at the Sacred Heart Catholic School in
Redlands, Calif., David A. Snowden learned his lessons from stern
nuns with a penchant for giving him ``a piece of their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a lesson that endured. His exploration of the brains and
the aging patterns of an elderly group of nuns from the order of
the School Sisters of Notre Dame has turned into his life's work _
a career of research, lectures and an unlikely book proposal about
centenarian sisters who provide some tantalizing clues to resisting
the ravages of Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Oliver Sacks meets the Delaney sisters,'' said Snowden's
agent, Gail Ross. ``It's really cutting-edge science writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowden's proposal has already provoked a fierce bidding battle
among 11 New York publishers _ with Bantam Books paying more than
$560,000 to publish ``Aging with Grace,'' which will be promoted
with much more than a prayer from the nuns.
</P>
<P>
   Deals have already been struck with publishers in England and
the Netherlands, Ms. Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Snowden, an associate professor of preventive medicine at the
Sanders-Brown Center on Aging at the University of Kentucky, has
pledged to donate half of the profits to the School Sisters of
Notre Dame. More than 600 nuns have participated in his research
project. Some sisters will donate their brains to the study after
they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten my career from their generosity,'' Snowden said.
``And to be honest, I don't see anything else in my career for the
rest of my life. They've been incredibly generous to me. And with
this I can sleep at night.''
</P>
<P>
   _ DOREEN CARVAJAL
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
