<HEADLINE>
KELLER, REYNA LEAD THE WAY AS U.S. TOPS ARGENTINA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two plays will forever be etched in the memories of
the players and the crowd of 40,119 in Sunday's international match
between the United States and Argentina at Robert F. Kennedy
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The first was a penalty-kick save by Kasey Keller of the United
States and the other was Joe-Max Moore's goal that gave the
Americans a 1-0 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Employing a formation of three defenders, five midfielders and
two strikers, the United States, 24th in the world in the latest
FIFA ranking, won because of individual efforts by Keller, Moore
and Ernie Stewart, who made the pass that led to the game's only
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Keller's save on Gustavo Lopez's penalty kick came in the 40th
minute. The goalkeeper dived to his left to grab the thunderous
shot, delighting the Americans in the crowd, who met the challenge
from Argentina's supporters with loud cheers of ``USA! USA!'' in a
stadium decorated by American and Argentine flags.
</P>
<P>
   The loudest cheers by the American supporters came in the 88th
minute, when Moore's left-footed blast from 15 yards, after a
marvelous back-heel pass from Stewart, eluded the Argentine
goalkeeper German Burgos. It was the 19th international goal for
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the biggest goal I've ever scored,'' Moore said. ``When
the result is 1-0 against Argentina and you score the only goal, it
doesn't get any bigger than this. I'm glad I came on and had an
impact on the game.'' Moore entered the game as a substitute in the
60th minute in place of the injured Eddie Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Sending Moore into the game was one of several brilliant moves
by Bruce Arena, whose record is 4-1-1 in 1999. He replaced Steve
Sampson as coach of the national team this past autumn. It was
Arena's first game back here after leading D.C. United to two Major
League Soccer titles.
</P>
<P>
   Arena and many of his players took the triumph against one of
the world's powers in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this means is that we're rebuilding our program,'' Arena
said. ``It's a good win against a good team. Does it say we're
going in the right direction? Yes, but not more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Arena said the national team will be better a year from now. But
the team will have to be on top of its game next month in the FIFA
Confederations Cup in Mexico, where the United States will play
Brazil, Germany and New Zealand in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find the right combinations of players as we go along,''
Arena said. ``We have a lot of other players to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Claudio Reyna will be the key to the national team no matter how
many players Arena sees. Reyna was the best player for the
Americans Sunday; he worked tirelessly offensively and defensively.
Reyna has always had the skill, acceleration and vision, but his
game has been elevated to a higher standard since he has been
playing a key role for the Glasgow Rangers in Scotland after his
transfer from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Claudio was outstanding,'' said Arena, who coached Reyna at
the University of Virginia for three years before the player left
for Germany. ``The game featured great battles and we won a share
of those battles.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyna seemed to win all his battles in the bright sunshine.
Wearing the captain's armband, Reyna sprayed the field with passes
and made a number of key plays defensively in the penalty area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing against Argentina for me is the most special game,''
said Reyna, whose father, Miguel, played in Argentina before moving
to Springfield, N.J. ``I was obviously motivated to play well
because some of my family still lives in Argentina and I knew they
were watching.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
