<HEADLINE>
MORE OF THE SAME FOR DISNEY ONLINE CHIEF  
 A BIT OF FLAMBOYANCE FOR AN INTERNET CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After seven years at Walt Disney Co. developing new Internet
businesses, Jake Winebaum has decided to call it quits to do
something different. His goal? To develop new Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old head of Disney's Buena Vista Internet Group
resigned last week to form a start-up incubator, Ecompanies, along
the lines of the entrepreneur Bill Gross' Idealab, which has
overseen the creation of dozens of thriving Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Winebaum, along with Sky Dayton, the 27-year-old founder of
Earthlink Network Inc., said that at Ecompanies he would focus more
on the start-up and operations of the businesses rather than the
initial ideas.
</P>
<P>
   There are currently at least 150 Internet start-ups, operating
on venture capital, that are seeking chief executives, Winebaum
said. He suggested that the number of ideas had outpaced the
availability of management skill.
</P>
<P>
   While Idealab, which started Citisearch and Goto.com, casts a
wide net in its search for start-ups, Winebaum said Ecompanies
would focus its activities more narrowly.
</P>
<P>
   Winebaum and Dayton met at an industry conference two years ago
and discovered they had something in common besides a passion for
start-ups: extreme snowboarding.
</P>
<P>
   They have been snowboarding together ever since, often
discussing start-up ideas on trips.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks ago, Winebaum called Dayton to say he was
thinking of quitting Disney to focus on one of his ideas. Like
Winebaum, Dayton was ready to start all over again, having seen
Earthlink, an Internet access provider, grow to $176 million in
revenue last year.
</P>
<P>
   Winebaum and Dayton hold majority stakes in Ecompanies, while
Disney and Earthlink are investors, an arrangement that will give
the two entrepreneurs the kind of control they both miss. The next
step is to find someone to oversee the company's venture-capital
fund. ``Sky and I both really like the start-up phase,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Winebaum joined Disney in 1992 when it acquired his magazine,
Family Fun. From there, he started several online ventures for
Disney, including Disney.com.
</P>
<P>
   A Bit of Flamboyance for an Internet Conference
</P>
<P>
   What has Dennis Rodman got to do with the Internet industry?
Until this week, almost nothing. But on Thursday, the flamboyant
professional basketball star will take the microphone at the Web
Attack Internet marketing conference in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tchong, producer of the conference, said he hoped to get
Rodman to talk about his coming electronic commerce venture, which
Tchong stumbled upon in the course of a trademark search on the
term Webzilla.com. The search turned up Rodman's venture,
Rodzilla.com.
</P>
<P>
   The point of inviting Rodman to the conference, Tchong said, is
to illustrate to Web marketers that they need to be outrageous to
be heard above the noise. ``There's got to be hundreds of pro
basketball players today, but ask anybody to name two and they'll
say Michael Jordan and Dennis Rodman,'' Tchong said. ``Now that's
brand marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodman has not been asked by the conference organizers to make
any prepared remarks. But he has been instructed on precisely what
to wear. The contract for his appearance requires Rodman _ who
apart from his hair color is perhaps best known off the court for
donning a wedding dress and other outrageous attire _ to wear a
T-shirt bearing the logo of Iconocast, the Web marketing consulting
company that is sponsoring the conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
