<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWA-AGREEMENT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWA REACHES TENTATIVE AGREEMENT WITH UNION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Trans World Airlines and the union
representing 16,000 employees, including flight attendants and
mechanics, reached a tentative agreement on new contracts Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by TWA's Machinists union members, the new contracts
will avert the possibility of a strike that could have devastated
the St. Louis-based carrier.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative agreement comes less than one week after voting
began on contract proposals that TWA described as its ``best and
final'' offer. Machinists union leaders had recommended its members
reject those proposals, and TWA employees in Kansas City and St.
Louis appeared to have voted down the company's $350 million
package last week.
</P>
<P>
   Company and union officials declined to disclose information on
the new pacts Sunday, saying they will first be presented to TWA
workers. Details are expected to be released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The new contracts cover three employee groups at TWA: mechanics
and related workers, flight attendants and passenger service
employees. About 2,300 mechanics work at TWA's overhaul base at
Kansas City International Airport. TWA has about 40 customer
service employees in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   William O'Driscoll, lead negotiator for the union, said the
negotiating committee will recommend that its members accept the
latest package. Once again, union workers at various TWA locations
will be meeting to vote on the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to complete the voting by July 10,'' O'Driscoll
said. ``Then we can get back to helping run the airline.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA and the Machinists began meeting again on Tuesday, said
William F. Compton, the airline's president and chief executive
officer. He said talks continued around the clock until a tentative
agreement was reached Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the employees,'' Compton said of the new
agreement. ``And it's one the company can live with, so we can take
the company to the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether employees last week voting and apparently
rejecting TWA's ``best and final'' offer prompted management to
return to the bargaining table, Compton said: ``There's always been
an interest in having a package endorsed by the Machinists. It's
always better to have a deal endorsed by both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   TWA's effect on the Missouri economy is significant. The airline
operates a hub in St. Louis and has nearly 9,000 employees there.
TWA has about 3,500 employees in Kansas City, operating the
maintenance base and an administrative center.
</P>
<P>
   Although details of the new contract proposals were not released
Sunday, TWA had said its previous offer would bring its employees'
wages to 90 percent of the industry standard by July 2001. For
mechanics, that would have been a maximum wage of $23.16 an hour
from the current top pay of $17.93 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders had stated for several months that a contract
bringing wages up to the 90 percent level of industry standard was
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials, meanwhile, had said that TWA's financial
condition was such that it could not afford anything more.
</P>
<P>
   After more than two years of negotiations, a federal mediator
declared an impasse on May 10, triggering a 30-day countdown after
which the Machinists would be free to strike TWA. That deadline had
been extended until the end of June while voting was conducted on
TWA's ``best and final'' offer.
</P>
<P>
   With TWA holding about $200 million in cash and given its shaky
financial state, company officials and airline analysts alike
agreed that TWA could not survive a full-scale strike. But the
threat of a shutdown at TWA was beginning to affect decisions made
by the flying public.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are indications that travel agents and corporate travel
planners are beginning to book away from TWA, especially in the
first half of July,'' said David Levine, airline industry analyst,
in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   Compton said that while TWA's passenger loads have remained high
in June, it was evident that business travelers were beginning to
look to other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a situation like this, you tend to lose the
higher-yield customers, which are the business travelers,'' he
said. ``Certainly, that has a negative effect on the company. But
with this tentative agreement, we can avert that in the future and
continue to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Nelson, president of Machinists Local 1650 in Kansas City,
said it will be up to the members to decide whether the new
contracts are good for them. However, he said it was crucial to get
an agreement that the union's negotiating committee endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic,'' Nelson said. ``We've been waiting for this a
long time. We've had to live under three concessionary contracts,
so these improvements are long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   Company and union officials said they hoped the new agreement
will go toward healing wounds that had been created by the arduous
negotiations. Many of TWA's employees have expressed frustration
with what they perceived as the company's unwillingness to bring
wages up to industry standard. Meanwhile, TWA officials contended
the Machinists were unwilling to agree to work rule changes that
are in place at all other major airlines, keeping TWA at a
competitive disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   One employee said a banner was hung prominently last week at the
overhaul base next to the TWA logo, stating: ``The concession stand
is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Driscoll said the new agreement should soothe labor-management
relations at TWA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3890 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-POWERS-640&AMP;ADD     06-13 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-POWERS-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUSTIN' SEQUEL IS BEHAVING VERY WELL AT BOX OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Maybe it's the dumb sex jokes. Maybe it's the
bathroom humor. Maybe it's the awful teeth and equally awful
cranberry-colored crushed-velvet suit proudly displayed by the
goofy hero.
</P>
<P>
   Or quite possibly it's the blizzard of promotions, publicity and
advertising tie-ins by the comedian Mike Myers, the star of
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me,'' his sequel to the
successful 1997 homage to James Bond.
</P>
<P>
   The sequel opened to nothing less than the extraordinary
box-office tally of $57.2 million, including Thursday night
previews, a result that underlined not only the strength of the
teen-age audience but also the hunger of the older crowd for
raunchy, seriously silly and over-the-top jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's caught the Zeitgeist,'' said Mike De Luca, president of
production at New Line, which made the film. ``People want to laugh
right now. The movie is extremely uncynical. It's almost innocent.
In a world where we're saturated with hypocrisy, there's something
about this that's refreshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Friedman, who oversees New Line's marketing with Rolf
Mittweg, put it another way. ``He's so politically incorrect,''
Friedman said of Powers. ``He says what he wants. Young people love
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The film itself, written by Myers and a former ``Saturday Night
Live'' colleague, Michael McCullers, is a sequel to ``Austin
Powers: International Man of Mystery.'' That spoof of 1960s spy
movies cost $18 million and earned $54 million at the box office.
The sequel cost $33 million and by Monday night will have earned
more at the box office than the first film in its entire run. No
other sequel has matched that.
</P>
<P>
   What the new Austin Powers is actually about is not entirely
clear. It's something about a mad-with-power Dr. Evil (also played
by Myers), who has drawn up a scheme to steal Austin's libido,
known as his mojo. Austin seeks to reclaim his mojo.
Double-entendres stamp almost every scene.
</P>
<P>
   The characters include a beguiling agent, Felicity Shagwell
(Heather Graham); Mini-Me (Verne J. Troyer), an extremely evil
midget, and Frau Farbissina (Mindy Sterling), whose last name, a
Yiddish word for sourpuss, sums her up.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is mainly the '60s in their most madcap form. ``It's
absurdly silly, irony-free,'' said Jay Roach, who directed both
Austin Powers films. ``There's a nostalgia involved, filtered
memory through which everything seemed really bright, uninhibited,
free-spirited.'' With a laugh, he added: ``It's not accurate. It's
not authentic. It's the theme-park version of the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes the film's success so unusual is that it rests
largely on the success of the video of the first Austin Powers.
That video was released in late 1997 and turned into a cult hit.
The movie was Billboard's top-selling video in its category in 1998
and has been in the top 10 since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The video served as a two-hour marketing tool for the new
film,'' Friedman said. ``People viewed the video repeatedly. A lot
of kids couldn't get enough of that video.'' (In the process, lines
from the film like ``yeah, baby,'' ``shag you, rotten'' and ``oh,
behave'' became commonplace at high schools around the United
States.)
</P>
<P>
   What helped too, of course, was the relentless promotion for the
movie by Myers. According to Daily Variety, New Line has spent more
than $40 million promoting the new film, but these costs have been
offset by fees from various licensing partners.
</P>
<P>
   Promotion campaigns for the movie involve toy makers and
fast-food chains, and the list of marketing partners includes
Virgin Atlantic, Starbucks, Heineken and Philips, the electronics
concern. Myers has appeared in virtually any magazine and
television show that would have him, although New Line's publicity
chiefs refused to show the film to journalists until the last
minute.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Roach, the director, said that in both Austin Powers films he
wanted to convey the free and sometimes reckless spirit of
comedians as varied as Peter Sellers, the Monty Python troupe,
Jonathan Winters, Woody Allen and Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is in all of these comedians,'' Roach said, ``the pure
delight of finding absurd, silly, ironic-free associations that's
sometimes clever, sometimes primitive and always delightful to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Has New Line approached Roach about a third Austin Powers?
``They've brought it up,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
