<SLUG> BC-GUNS-NRA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CONTINGENT GETS READY TO FIGHT GUN CONTROL IN HOUSE THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVUE, Wash. _ A trio of House Republicans who managed the
effort to impeach President Clinton predicted they will
successfully defend gun owners' rights in a House fight this week
over proposed gun safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is using the National Rifle
Association as a ``red herring'' in an effort to slap more controls
on gun-owning Americans, said the GOP congressmen during a weekend
visit here.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee Republicans predicted Saturday
that Democrats living in rural areas will join them in trying to
block gun restrictions passed by the Senate last month.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control is expected to spark verbal fire in the House this
week when the House takes up the Senate-passed juvenile justice
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow the votes: You are going to see a coalition of
Republicans and Democrats fight for Second Amendment rights: They
will vote against extreme measures and defend the right to bear
arms,'' Rep. Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle's Democratic Rep. Jim McDermott countered that
recent school shootings have turned public opinion in favor of gun
safety measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans used to accept that there were shootings in our
cities,'' McDermott said. ``They felt that, if you moved to a
suburban area, you would be protected from gun violence. The
Colorado and Georgia shootings show that you are not protected.
Your children are not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham said he expects Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., the
longest-serving House Democrat and former board member of the NRA,
to lead the fight for a softer gun-show provision than the one
passed by the Senate last month on a dramatic 51-50 vote. Vice
President Al Gore, as the Senate's presiding officer, broke the
tie.
</P>
<P>
   The three GOP impeachment managers _ Graham, Rep. Asa
Hutchinson, R-Ark., and Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif. _ visited the
Puget Sound area Saturday to speak at a rally and fund-raising
dinner for the King County Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``They carried with them our strong belief that this president
should be impeached,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., in a fiery
warmup speech for her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn voiced hope that after the 2000 election, ``representatives
like Jim Rogan and Asa Hutchinson will populate the Republican side
of the House of Representatives.'' (Graham was not at the rally,
but spoke at the dinner.)
</P>
<P>
   While looking back proudly at the impeachment effort, the House
Republicans' main focus was the upcoming House firefight over gun
restrictions. Hutchinson later took a ``redeye'' flight to
Washington, D.C., so he could appear Sunday on CBS' ``Face the
Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert voiced hope last month that the
House would go along with provisions of the Senate bill. But he has
since retreated under fire from GOP troops.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert comes from ``an anti-gun state'' _ Illinois _ and took
his initial position without consulting Republicans from the South
and West, traditional strongholds of the NRA, Hutchinson said at a
GOP reception here.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the House Rules Committee have drafted a bill
that includes several Senate-passed provisions _ mandatory child
safety locks and a juvenile Brady law provision barring for life
gun ownership by anyone convicted as a juvenile of a violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   The House Republicans left out other Senate provisions. Gone is
a ban on the import of ammunition clips holding 10 or more bullets.
Another omitted amendment would direct the Federal Trade Commission
to look into marketing of guns to children.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would require background checks on all purchases
at gun shows where 50 or more guns are available. The House bill
exempts gun shows with fewer than 10 vendors, no matter how many
guns are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill would delay transfer of a gun to a buyer for up
to three business days so a federal tracking system can check for
any felony convictions. The House bill would give the system 72
hours _ even on holiday weekends when records might not be
available.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he will sign the bill as passed by the Senate
even though it does not contain all the gun control measures he
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens should not be prevented from making ``legal gun
purchases'' when technical means are available to quickly check for
any criminal background, Graham said in arguing for the House
version of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., took a different view. Inslee lost his
central Washington House seat in 1994 after backing a ban on
semi-automatic assault rifles. He was elected last year to a
suburban Seattle seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic purpose of the Senate bill was to close a
loophole,'' Inslee said. ``Background checks work. They have kept
firearms out of the hands of thousands of convicted criminals. The
question is, do we let people avoid the safety net by walking
around the corner to a show where there are a hundred guns sitting
on a table for sale?''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan, a former judge and gang-crime prosecutor, rejected
Democrats' contention that the Littleton, Colo., killings and other
school shootings make the case for tighter gun regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 20,000 gun laws on the books in this country that did
not stop what happened at Columbine High School,'' Rogan said in a
weekend interview.
</P>
<P>
   The California Republican charged the Clinton administration
with ``scapegoating,'' and added: ``Taking deaths in schools, and
blaming it on the NRA, is unfortunate and unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson drew prolonged applause at Saturday's rally as he put
the issue in stark terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a constitutional liberty that gives citizens of this
country the right to bear arms. We should not make it impossible
for citizens, men or women, to defend their family, home and
property,'' Hutchinson said.
</P>
<P>
   A private poll, conducted last month for the National Republican
Congressional Committee, found 80 percent support for expanded
background checks on gun purchases. In results leaked to the press,
it also found 45 percent of all voters less inclined to support a
member of Congress linked to the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't place much stock in those polls,'' Rogan said. ``I
know a poll can be skewered by how you word the questions. I know
this: If you ask if people believe in the right to defend
themselves and their families, the answer is an overwhelming yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Inslee, by contrast, said he detects that public opinion is
``moving away from ideology'' on gun safety issues. He described
measures pending in Congress as ``modest'' compared with the 1994
assault weapons ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reasons are many, but basic to it is the steady
accumulation of victims,'' he added. ``Since 1994, more than 1,000
little kids have died in accidental shootings. Those are as much a
part of the carnage as mass homicides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not Littleton so much as one tragedy at a time driving
people toward common sense,'' said Inslee.
</P>
<P>
   The House gun debate this week is likely to be a free-for-all.
``Denny Hastert is just throwing it out to the House to let it go
any way,'' McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats will have their eyes on suburban Republicans,
including those who have voted with the NRA. ``Jennifer Dunn is a
perfect example: She is a person who represents a district with
towns like Littleton, Colorado,'' McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Behrens-Benedict, a Democrat who took 40 percent of the
vote against Dunn in 1998, said last week that she is running again
on a gun control platform.
</P>
<P>
   Graham said Republicans will join in passing mandatory trigger
locks, and barring lifetime gun ownership for any juvenile who
commits a violent crime. He predicted that the NRA will score
victories as well as suffer defeats on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, when this is over, the Democrats will join us in
addressing the media culture of violence that is more responsible
(than guns) for this problem,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
