<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SICKLY SABRES HAVE NO CURE FOR STARS FLU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Contrary to expectations, the sun did come up
yesterday in the birthplace of chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, the Buffalo Sabres didn't seem to notice.
</P>
<P>
   Their swagger is gone. The coach no longer is announcing that
the opposing Stars cheat. If there's a game plan for Game 4 and
points beyond, the Sabres appear to still be searching for it.
</P>
<P>
   They've got the Stars Flu. Tightness in the offensive zone.
Congestion at the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff's playoff goatee, which rode so proud
and snide after Game 1, has turned cold and clammy.
</P>
<P>
   Let's see. The Stanley Cup Finals are not yet a week old, and
the Sabres have already played the they-cheat-on-face-offs card,
the they're-running-our-goaltender card and the always-popular
Stars-are-old-and-too-slow card.
</P>
<P>
   With a desperate Game 4 facing them tomorrow night, the Sabres
have an empty hand and maybe one option left:
</P>
<P>
   Go fish.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams that were once alleged to be so alike are
starting to show their differences. The Stars are confident,
focused, invigorated by the reassurance that the system _ the
almighty, seasonlong system _ still works.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres, on the other hand, were shaken by losing and by
being thoroughly squelched in Game 3 on their home ice.
</P>
<P>
   You heard the Sabres. After the 2-1 loss, Ruff said, ``I thought
we were pretty tight. We were squeezing the sticks ... They gave us
a darn good lesson there. They suffocated us.''
</P>
<P>
   They sounded frustrated, but more confounded than anything.
Which is odd, because if the Stanley Cup playoffs have taught us
anything over these past three seasons, it is that the momentum in
postseason hockey can change in a eye-blink or, better still, a
goaltender's heartbeat.
</P>
<P>
   One wrist shot. One errant skate. A goal by Craig Ludwig, of all
people.
</P>
<P>
   What happened yesterday, the Stars have proven conclusively, has
only vague bearing on what likely will happen today.
</P>
<P>
   So why the long snout on Team Buffalo?
</P>
<P>
   Stars Flu, it says here. And this dose may linger for, oh, three
or four months.
</P>
<P>
   The question posed for Ruff yesterday was what he planned to do
to get his offense kick-started.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff's rambling reply mentioned power plays, and then how the
Stars like to fall to the ice and block shots, and then how a
thicket of black-and-green trees seems to have sprouted up in front
of Ed Belfour, and finally, ``The key here is getting the shot
through somehow, to get it on the net and look for rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Stop the presses! Wake up Toe Blake!
</P>
<P>
   It is that simple. But the Stars have made it seem so hard.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres appeared stunned last Saturday night that they could
have been held to only a record-tying 12 shots on goal. Actually,
it's also only 16 shots over the past four periods.
</P>
<P>
   But this is what the Stars do. They want to snuff your
opportunities and sap your enthusiasm. They want to get inside your
40-goal scorer's head. They want to wilt your coach's moustache.
</P>
<P>
   Funny how impressions tend to flow. To a goodly share of the
Canadian and U.S. media at these finals, the Stars' Ken Hitchcock
was thought to be a whip-cracking, stubborn maniac of a coach who
ruled by the credo, ``Presidents' Trophy or bust.''
</P>
<P>
   But day by day, the same media has discovered that Hitchcock may
be more ``Captain Kangaroo'' than his haircut. He is affable and
intelligent, giving thoughtful answers to even the most inane
hockey query. What other coach in the NHL chases away his P.R. man
so that he can answer a few more questions?
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock could probably say anything at this point of the
playoffs and find it in headlines the next morning. But now he
holds the cards.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Hitch will ``turn loose'' the Mike Modano-Jere Lehtinen
line, and maybe he won't. Maybe Benoit Hogue will rejoin the
playoffs, and maybe he won't. Maybe Michael Peca should check the
Joe Nieuwendyk line, or maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, on the other hand, began the finals by bleating something
about Brian Skrudland's face-off habits. Then he whined about
officiating. Then he whined about the Stars' rough play.
</P>
<P>
   But after one loss at home, the former Sabres' captain sounds
like a whipped puppy. He talked yesterday about how ``worn down''
his players were.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. I thought that was supposed to be the Stars' fatal flaw.
</P>
<P>
   If I were a doctor _ Dr. Stanley, I presume _ I'd say he has the
Stars Flu.
</P>
<P>
   I'd advise the coach to take two aspirin. Have some more whine
and chicken wings.
</P>
<P>
   In a few days, it'll all be over.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
