<HEADER>
A3896 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-1STLD-W     06-13 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 VILLAGES YIELD EVIDENCE OF MASS KILLINGS BY SERBS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to rewrite 14th graf, beginning Nine other men ..., for
clarification; i.e., it is not certain whether two of the shot
uncles were killed. In 7th graf, inserts `26' for clarification. In
12th graf, beginning In Hallac and Ribar..., inserts new clause for
clarification. In 17th graf, changes `Just a mile' to `A few
miles.')  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLAC, Yugoslavia _ After weeks of unconfirmed reports from
terrified refugees, the first direct evidence that Serb forces
carried out mass killings in Kosovo _ and have tried to cover them
up _ emerged Sunday at this village, where freshly turned dirt lay
just feet from a bullet-pocked wall.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, Albanian refugees who fled the village reported
that Serb paramilitaries had killed 46 people during a two-day
rampage in mid-April here and in a nearby hamlet, called Ribar.
</P>
<P>
   The signs of recent digging here, along with 26 new graves in
the local cemetery at Ribar, may mean that a mass grave was
excavated and the bodies reburied. Two dozen burned houses in the
area also stand as evidence of some form of attack.
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Ward, an investigator with Human Rights Watch who has
been collecting witness accounts of the attacks in the area, said
the graves support accounts he has heard of the rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents one of the first direct confirmations of witness
statements describing the killings of civilians,'' he said. ``Now
we have the first evidence confirming that it has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Hallac said that in recent weeks local police
exhumed a mass grave holding 20 men, carried out autopsies on the
victims and then ordered local villagers to rebury the bodies in
individual graves in the local cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Ribar, the victims were exhumed from 26 individual
graves, examined and then reburied.
</P>
<P>
   Reburying bodies in individual graves and producing autopsies
giving an explanation for the killings could make it more difficult
to prove in court that people were executed instead of killed in
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers also said that in the days prior to the arrival of
NATO forces in Kosovo, Yugoslav officials transferred as many as
1,500 Albanian prisoners from the prison in the nearby town of
Lipljan to a Serb jail outside Kosovo. Ejup Pajazi, a 56-year-old
taxi driver released from the jail Saturday, said he was told the
prisoners were taken to a jail in the city of Nis in southern
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Pajazi's allegation could not be confirmed, but no large group
of prisoners from Lipljan has entered Macedonia in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Former prisoners released into Macedonia last week said they
were rounded up after NATO airstrikes began, accused of having ties
to the Kosovo Liberation Army and charged with ``terrorist''
activities. Severe beatings to force confessions were a daily
occurrence, the former prisoners said.
</P>
<P>
   In Hallac and Ribar, the evidence of killing was strikingly
different. In Hallac, a 10-by-30-foot patch of freshly turned earth
in an empty lot near the village center was by far the most
dramatic evidence; villagers said it once held the bodies of 20
people killed by Serb paramilitaries. Two men's shoes and what
appeared to be a torn shirt lay on the surface of the dark soil.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers, who gave accounts mirroring those given by refugees
last month, said the Hallac killings occurred on April 19th. A
dozen Serb paramilitaries shot dead 11 men in the vacant lot, they
said, including a 23-year-old father of two who was shot in the
face after he repeatedly asked to be released.
</P>
<P>
   Nine other men were killed in their homes, the villagers said.
Hafize Gashi, 19, gave a painstaking tour of the killing ground
around her home. Her father, she said, was killed in the garden;
one uncle was shot beside the well, another in front of his
adjacent home; and her 26-year-old cousin and a 70-year-old uncle
were killed inside her home. The paramilitaries then set the bodies
on fire, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the charred remains of the family's living room, she
pointed out what appeared to be a charred human knee joint lying on
the floor. ``We tried to gather all of the bones for burial,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitaries forced local gypsies to bury all 20 corpses,
villagers said. Police from Lipljan then arrived on May 2 and
ordered the graves exhumed. Blaming the killings on paramilitaries
they could not control, the police said the victims should be
buried properly. But they then barred the villagers from burying
all twenty victims together in the graveyard, the villagers said.
On Sunday, twenty freshly made graves could be seen in the
community cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles up the road in the village of Ribar, 26 freshly made
graves could be seen in the community cemetery. The victims there
included men, women, children and the elderly, according to the
grave markers. The village's oldest and youngest victims died
together, residents said, when paramilitaries shot a 7-year-old
girl and her 73-year-old grandfather as they ran across a field to
escape.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers' accounts of the attack, which they said occurred on
April 18th, a day before the Hallac attack, mirrored those given by
refugees who fled into Macedonia last month. Shemsije Vishesella, a
38-year-old widow still wearing a bandage from where a bullet
shattered her jaw, led two reporters on a tour of the gutted house
where her two sons and husband were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in the living room, seemingly in a daze, she described
how the family had been going through its morning routine when
shots rang out outside, signaling the arrival of the
paramilitaries. ``My husband said, `Don't be afraid,' '' she said.
``He said, `They are coming but don't be afraid.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitaries kicked the door in and hustled her husband
and 17- and 14-year-old sons outside. She was led outside and found
each of them lying face down on the ground. As she demonstrated
where each one lay that morning, she stroked the grass as if she
were stroking their hair.
</P>
<P>
   Ordered by the paramilitaries to leave, she hid behind a fence,
peered into the yard and was spotted. When the bullet hit her jaw,
she passed out. The paramilitaries then shot her husband and sons
dead, she said, as they lay beneath apple and cherry trees in the
family garden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
