<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK WOULD LIFT THE CUP TO HIS MOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Joe Nieuwendyk is just two victories away from
the waltz every player in the National Hockey League dreams of
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   He can almost taste it now, can see it happening in his dreams.
Spinning around the ice, the great silver cup held high, eyes
gleaming in triumph.
</P>
<P>
   God willing, he will lift hockey's holy grail to the heavens,
offering it up to the person whose face he sees whenever he closes
his eyes:
</P>
<P>
   His mother's.
</P>
<P>
   Every game night, even in the midst of the tumult and frenzy of
the Stanley Cup Finals, Nieuwendyk drags himself wearily off the
ice to his seat on the Stars' bench between shifts and sees her
face in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   She smiles, and the strength begins to pour back into his arms
and legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if she's there with me, and I'm sure she is,'' said
Nieuwendyk, who has led the Stars to a 2-1 lead over Buffalo in the
best-of-seven race for Lord Stanley's Cup. ``I can feel her
presence. I think of a her a lot, especially when I'm on the
bench.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been gone almost four years now, dead of cancer just
three months after doctors diagnosed the dreaded disease, but not a
day goes by that Nieuwendyk, who grew up only about a two-hour
drive from here in Whitby, Ontario, doesn't think about her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always there for me, supporting me in whatever I
did,'' he said on the morning after his two goals, including his
record-tying sixth game-winner of the playoffs, carried the Stars
to the 2-1 victory against the Sabres that puts Dallas back in
control of the series.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of 13 months, Nieuwendyk has gone from tragic
figure to budding hero of the Stanley Cup playoffs, a favorite for
the Conn Smythe Trophy, which goes to the postseason MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Who can forget watching San Jose's despicable Bryan Marchment
run Nieuwendyk, his leg held up off the ice and unable to slow his
momentum, into the boards at Reunion Arena in Game 1 of the
quarterfinals? The damage was immense: torn ACL and cartilage in
his right knee. End of playoffs, career hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   With their leading scorer and team MVP out, the Stars' bid to
reach the Finals would die on the ice at Detroit's Joe Louis Arena
in Game 6 of the Western Conference finals, leaving fans wondering,
``What if Joe had been there?''
</P>
<P>
   Stars officials, meanwhile, wondered if Nieuwendyk would even
play again and if so, would he be the player he had been before the
injury?
</P>
<P>
   Already playing with a detached ACL in his left knee since 1991,
Nieuwendyk, at 31, faced incredible adversity. He would have to
have surgery on both knees.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the daunting physical rehabilitation process that lay
ahead, Nieuwendyk was also psychologically shattered as he watched
his teammates struggle against the Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hurting so much inside, I couldn't even watch the
playoffs at first,'' he said. ``I wanted to be out there so badly
to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as low a moment in his life as he'd experienced since his
mother died. But he knew what she would expect of him.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nieuwendyk hadn't raised her son to be a quitter.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said there was no way Nieuwendyk could expect to be
ready by the beginning of the 1999 season. They didn't know Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forced to find out how hot it was in Dallas all summer,
that's for sure,'' said Nieuwendyk, remembering how he dragged
himself out of bed each morning to follow his rehab program. ``It
was a tough summer, I won't lie about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once our season ended last year against Detroit, it was
kind of like a new beginning for me. That was my focus all summer.
I didn't venture from it and as the season went on, I started to
feel better and better.''
</P>
<P>
   That's typical Nieuwendyk. He didn't exactly get into all the
gritty details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe downplayed that,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``Joe worked
hard in the gym but \Rstrength and conditioning coach\S Jimmy
McQueen put Joe through hell. It was painful for me to watch,
because when it was 100 degrees outside, Jimmy made Joe put a
harness on and haul him around in the parking lot on a tire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe hauled him all of August in Texas and all through
\Rtraining camp at\S Vail, up and down the hills. Nieuwendyk came
back 31/2 weeks early not because of the rehab work, but because of
the extra work he went through, which was really the football
mentality borrowed from the Cowboys, all of this harness work that
Joe was willing to do. Jimmy just pushed the hell out of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk, his mother's face always in front of him, simply
bowed his head and dug in, never asking for mercy. It was Hitchcock
who pleaded for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would go out there and say, `Look, it's 104 degrees, let's
calm this down a little.' It didn't matter if it was 6 or 7 o'clock
in the morning, Nieuwendyk had to do the stuff, and I think it made
him mentally tougher, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players would do their thing and there would be Joe, all
by himself, up and down and all over the place. He deserves a lot
of credit because he pushed the envelope big time, but he did it
the natural way. The machinery left after a while, and he just did
it the old-fashioned way, hauling tires with people sitting in them
and hauling guys hooked to harnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Nieuwendyk, who has taken his game to another level in the
playoffs as the Stars try to survive injuries to Mike Modano, Brett
Hull, Benoit Hogue and Grant Marshall, has hauled his team to the
cusp of a waltz with the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very fortunate when I first started my career to be on a
good Calgary team in the late '80s,'' said Nieuwendyk, who was an
integral part of the Flames' 1989 Stanley Cup champions. ``It
taught me the value of hard work. When you're just 22 and you have
the type of success our team had, you think it's going to happen
every year. When you do get back you want to take full advantage of
it and just play for your teammates every night and play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember winning the Cup and what it felt like, but now that
I know how hard it is to get here, I'm trying to absorb more this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He is 32 now. That first time, a decade ago, Nieuwendyk's mom
was alive and Bryan Marchment was merely a thug-in-training. Life
looked like it could be full of waltzes with the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Now a much wiser Nieuwendyk knows better. Maybe that's why this
one means so much to him.
</P>
<P>
   He wants this dance, wants it so bad he can taste it.
</P>
<P>
   That one glorious spin around the ice, the Cup, glistening in
the lights, lifted to the heavens, held high above his head while
the crowd roars.
</P>
<P>
   He's been saving this dance for a long time now, you see.
</P>
<P>
   For his mom.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
