<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ELIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIE BACK IN THE NBA FINALS WITH ANOTHER TEXAS TEAM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ In January, after the NBA lockout ended and teams
were scrambling to fill their rosters, the San Antonio Spurs' coach
and general manager, Gregg Popovich, looked at his club and saw a
hole the size of one of his marvelous 7-footers.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a talent gap, because in Tim Duncan and David
Robinson the Spurs had the best low-post tandem in the league.
Their point guard, Avery Johnson, was serviceable, and their
two-time All-Star small forward, Sean Elliott, was returning in
good health after two injury-marred seasons.
</P>
<P>
   What San Antonio needed was intangible. Notoriously nice and, by
NBA standards, almost saintly, the Spurs were Exhibit A for the
leaguewide notion that without a ruffian, a club could only go so
far.
</P>
<P>
   So in an effort to add some nastiness to his team's demeanor,
Popovich joined the crowded bidding war for Latrell Sprewell,
reportedly offering Elliott, Will Perdue and Vinny Del Negro. The
attempt proved fruitless, with Sprewell instead taking his fire and
grimace to the Knicks. So Popovich signed Mario Elie, a less
talented but equally hard free agent.
</P>
<P>
   A ninth-year veteran, Elie has not played spectacularly _ no one
expected him to _ but the 35-year-old shooting guard has been the
edgy, restless court tough that Popovich wanted. After going 5-5
with Elie playing in a reserve role early in the season, the Spurs
have gone 40-9 with him as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Elie has become the Spurs' Charles Oakley, and they
recognize the link between his arrival and their first trip to the
NBA finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the angriest guys I've ever met _ on the court,''
Johnson said. ``Off the court, he and I are good and we spend time
together working out in the summer. But on the court, he's got this
edge, this angriness about him. He's bitter about a lot of things
when he's out there.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Johnson added: ``He's always telling me that he doesn't touch
the ball enough, and I've got to remind him that he's not Tim or
Dave. So he stays mad all the time, and we kind of needed that
little edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Elie, a member of the Houston Rockets' championship teams in
1994 and 1995, did not waste time feeling out his new teammates or
trying to blend in.
</P>
<P>
   While the Spurs were on their way to a 6-8 start, he tore into
Robinson and Duncan for what he perceived to be their lack of
intensity and heart. Elie has since amended his views of the Spurs'
two big men, realizing that their placid ways on the court are an
extension of their personalities, not evidence of a lack of
passion.
</P>
<P>
   But Elie's misjudgment of Robinson and Duncan is understandable.
A New York City native, he was not accustomed to their
tranquillity. Having grown up five minutes from Madison Square
Garden, he was used to hustling, rushing, tension, to physical and
oral confrontation on the court. He played in the vicious 1994
finals series against the Knicks that led people to criticize the
brutish state of the post-Jordan NBA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my second time playing in the NBA finals in Madison
Square Garden,'' said Elie, obviously pleased to be returning home
in style again. ``But this time is a little different in that I'll
play a more integral part. My first year with Houston, I only
averaged 8 or 10 minutes a game. Now I have a bigger role as a
starter. And Jerry Seinfeld, Chris Rock, Puff Daddy and everybody
are all going to be at the game, so it's going to be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the starters in this series, which begins Wednesday, no
one comes close to matching Elie in finals experience. He is the
only starter on either team who has played for an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   His Spurs teammates Steve Kerr, acquired in a pre-season trade,
and Will Perdue won three championships apiece with the Chicago
Bulls, but neither is expected to play much of a role against the
Knicks, although Kerr has received more playing time recently.
</P>
<P>
   While Elie was a bit player in his last finals trip to the
Garden, he has since proved to be a clutch performer when the stage
is large.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he saved Houston from a second-round exit at the hands
of the Phoenix Suns by hitting a 3-pointer with 7.1 seconds left to
give the Rockets a 115-114 victory in Game 7. Then, in the finals
against the Orlando Magic, he nearly doubled his regular-season
scoring average with 16.3 points a game in Houston's four-game
sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Elie has been less heroic in these playoffs, making only 23.5
percent of his 3-point attempts (4 of 17) after leading the Spurs
at 37.4 percent during the regular season. He is averaging 6.4
points in the 12 playoff games _ 11 of them victories _ after
averaging 9.7 in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   But defensively, he has been strong, shutting down Portland's
Isaiah Rider in the Western Conference finals. Elie will guard
Allan Houston, with the understanding that slowing him down is
vital to San Antonio's success. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Allan Houston is a terrific talent and I'm looking forward to
the challenge,'' Elie said. ``I've played against Grant Hill and
Michael Jordan over the years, so this is just another challenge
that I relish. If I can just do my job on my guy, it gives my team
a chance to win a championship.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Popovich had in mind when he acquired Elie five
months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
