<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATHLETES-GROUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIANS SEEK VOICE IN CHANGING IOC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Athletes, like most other people, agree that the
International Olympic Committee needs changes, and they have
finally formed an organization to make themselves heard.
</P>
<P>
   For 2 1/2 days, 80 people with Olympic backgrounds met at the
Regal U.N. Plaza Hotel in New York to formulate an agenda to make
athletes heard. The group included 46 recent Olympic athletes from
more than a dozen nations, including 12 gold medalists.
</P>
<P>
   The discussions ended Sunday, and Mark Tewksbury, the Canadian
swimmer, 1992 Olympic gold medalist and co-founder of the athletes'
movement, said he was encouraged. When the recent illegal-payment
scandals involving IOC members erupted, Tewksbury quit three
Olympic-related positions in protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to return the Olympics to their old ideals,'' he said.
``We want to return the IOC to what it said it always wanted to be.
We plan to send a positive statement to them.'' He said they
planned to begin sending the message with the IOC meetings this
week in Seoul, South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The participants here included speed skater Johan Olaf Koss of
Norway, distance runner Zola Budd of South Africa, swimmer Dawn
Fraser of Australia, sprinter Grace Jackson of Jamaica and three
Americans: swimmer John Naber, triple jumper Willie Banks and the
skater Peter Carruthers.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes call their organization Olympic Advocates Together
Honorably. It is financed by Magna, a Canadian corporation that
supplies auto parts to manufacturers. The athletes and Magna say
they have no hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to get a piece of the pie,'' Naber said, ``just
to assure that the pie tastes as good as the recipe says it
should.''
</P>
<P>
   Koss added, ``We want to show the youth of the world there is
fair play and a higher standard for athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   And Jackson said: ``We need a communications link between
athletes and the IOC. I think this organization can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC already has an athletes advisory board that includes
seven men and women elected by fellow athletes at the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics and three elected by athletes at the 1998 Nagano Winter
Olympics. That board has proposed that the 10 elected athletes
become IOC members until the next athletes' election.
</P>
<P>
   Tewksbury said this was no attempt to grab power.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to take over management of international
sport,'' he said. ``The principles in the Olympic charter are good.
They have not been upheld.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
