<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT STRUGGLES WITH CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ The concern and talk is about Carlos Perez, and
whether the Dodgers lefty will be removed from the starting
rotation. Obviously, it's given the Dodgers fits.
</P>
<P>
   But right-hander Darren Dreifort isn't pitching much better
these days. It's just that the reason for his failures are much
easier to identify. The former No.1 pick, known for being erratic
around the plate, is having more trouble than ever before throwing
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort's undoing wasn't the seven hits in Sunday's 9-3 loss to
the Oakland Athletics. It was the six walks, plus a hit batter,
that spelled doom for Dreifort. Of the seven runs he allowed in
41/3 innings, only Miguel Tejada reached via hitting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept reminding him to keep his front side closed,'' said
Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley. ``It was flying open toward the end.
He was yanking some pitches away to right-handers.''
</P>
<P>
   It cost Dreifort (5-5) his place on the mound when he walked
three straight A's to set up the five-run fifth inning. Dreifort
opted not to speak to reporters after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort entered the day tied for fifth in the National League
in walks. He's now walked 46 in 671/3 innings, or 6.1 per nine
innings. Last season Dreifort walked 2.85 per nine innings and,
before this season, walked 3.59 per nine innings in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's frustrated probably more than anything because he knows
he's better than that,'' said Dodgers pitching coach Claude Osteen.
``Some of these younger guys are not far enough along to know
themselves when they know how to make corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort, he came to me (between innings), and he said the
pitches were doing something he didn't want them to do. He said,
`What am I doing?' The ball was cutting a way he didn't want it to
cut. We've got to recover from it and we have to (during) certain
facets of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson was forced to go to reliever Jamie
Arnold for 31/3 innings of relief. But Johnson said it wouldn't
keep him from using Arnold to start in Perez's place Wednesday if
such a decision is made.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth pushed back again: One thing that's hampered
Johnson's style is the lack of a left-handed hitter off the bench.
Outfielder Todd Hollandsworth was supposed to provide it, but he's
been injured most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Johnson said it'll be at least another week before
Hollandsworth can return to the lineup because of a torn muscle on
his right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he felt good the other day, but that's before he did
anything,'' Johnson said. ``It's a little different when you try to
throw and try to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long ordeal for Hollandsworth, who missed the first
16 games of the season with a strained right hamstring. He injured
his side swinging at a pitch in Cincinnati on May 28 and was
supposed to miss only a few days. He's missed the last nine games.
It also puts a strain on Johnson, who likes to use his bench to
rest the veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called matchups,'' Johnson said. ``It helps to have
matchups to strengthen the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing grand about it: Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros
averages 25 home runs a season and went three straight seasons with
at least 30 homers and 100 RBI. He's hit 10 homers this season and
Sunday had his streak of hitting a homer stopped at three games.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, one thing Karros is yet to do is hit a grand slam. He's hit
187 homers in his career, but none have come with the bases loaded.
Karros had an opportunity to change that Sunday but grounded out
with the bases loaded in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   This season Karros is 1 for 8 with the bases loaded; in his
career, he's 25 for 76 (.329).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
