   (NYT6) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- June 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SCENE-3,
6-13 -- An enormous column of Serbian civilians follow their army
and police out of western Kosovo on Sunday, moving slowly past a
convoy of Italian troops going the other way, toward Pec and
Prizren. Thus far, NATO is failing at its stated intention of
creating a climate of security in Kosovo where all the inhabitants
of this ravaged land can return to their homes and live peacefully.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- June 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SCENE-2,
6-13 -- Serb army soldiers in Pristina wait for vehicles to
withdraw from Kosovo on Sunday. An enormous column of Serbian
civilians followed their army and police out of western Kosovo,
moving slowly on the narrow roads past an enormous column of
Italian troops and armor moving the other way, toward Pec and
Prizren. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) PRIZREN, Yugoslavia -- June 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-SCENE-1,
6-13 -- Ethnic Albanians in Prizren wave an Albanian flag as they
celebrate the arrival of NATO troops on Sunday. In Prizren, the
main square was full of Albanians of all ages who had never left,
but hid in their apartments for nearly three months. As the Serbs
retreated east, they passed thousands of Albanians who lined the
road and shouted, ``NATO! NATO!'' and ``Thank you!'' at any passing
NATO military vehicle. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PRISTINA, Yugoslavia -- June 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RDP-1,
6-13 -- French officers negotiate with Russian troops that blocked
roads around the airport near Pristina on Sunday. The Russian
troops allowed Serbs to leave but turned NATO forces away in an
embarassing impasse for NATO peacekeeping efforts in Kosovo.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CEDAR RAPIDS, Iowa -- June 13, 1999 -- BUSH-IOWA-2, 6-12
-- Supporters in Cedar Rapids await the arrival of Gov. George W.
Bush on Saturday, the front-runner for the Republican nomination.
Setting the theme for his campaign upon arriving in Cedar Rapids,
Bush said that he would be at once an activist and a conservative
president -- a ``compassionate'' Republican who would advocate
using the nation's prosperity to help its downtrodden. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
