<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      06-13 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE KNICKS' MAGICAL RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, June 14:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks, a team that nobody thought would outlive
the first round of the NBA playoffs, are now in the championship
round, and their opponents, the heavily favored San Antonio Spurs,
have got to be wondering, who are these guys?
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what the Knicks' dazed and dazzled fans are
asking themselves, and the only sure answer is that they bear no
resemblance to the team they were two months ago, when their record
was 21-21. Necessity, in the form of critical injuries, has forced
them to use different combinations and play a more up-tempo style.
They have become quicker, more creative, less selfish with the
ball, and in so doing have defeated three playoff teams that were
supposed to beat them, including the formidable Indiana Pacers on
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Each game has produced a new hero _ Larry Johnson in Game 3,
Latrell Sprewell in Game 5, and, in Game 6, Allan Houston, whose
32-point effort on Friday created pandemonium in Madison Square
Garden. The Knicks may now have to go forward without Johnson, who
suffered a sprained knee, but this is a team that so far has
flourished in adversity.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have survived the demotion of their general manager
and rumors that their coach would be the next to go. They have
surmounted clubhouse bickering and the loss of their star center,
Patrick Ewing, who went down with a torn Achilles' tendon in the
second game against Indiana. Most of all they have survived
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-playoff Knicks always seemed to find ways to
self-destruct at the most inopportune moments, usually the fourth
quarter. The word comeback was not part of their emotional
vocabulary. This team finds ways to win.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Ewing hurt and helped the Knicks. It robbed them of
a rebounding force and another reliable jump shot, but it also
forced Jeff Van Gundy, the coach, to give more playing time to
Sprewell, whose explosive moves create chances for himself and
others, and to Marcus Camby, a rapidly maturing player about whom
Van Gundy can no longer have any doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Camby has been everywhere, running around like a mad stork _
rebounding, passing, dunking, blocking shots. Without him, without
Sprewell, without a resurgent Houston and without Johnson's
improbable run of three-point shots, Van Gundy and the Knicks would
be on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   This has been a magical post-season, mystifying even the Knicks.
``I feel I've been part of a story that is bigger than all of us,''
Johnson said the other day. The question now is, is that story
bigger than the San Antonio Spurs, a tall, strong, versatile team
that has not lost since May 11? Most experts say no. The Knicks
fans are thrilled that the question has come up at all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3926 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     06-13 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS AT THEIR `WORST'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Manager Davey Johnson said he was too mad to hold a
team meeting Saturday so he waited for Sunday morning to discuss
the many shortcomings of the Dodgers. The meeting took 15 minutes,
though if time permitted it could have lasted 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   So inspired were the Dodgers by the talk that they went out
and... you got it, lost again.
</P>
<P>
   The Oakland Athletics completed the three-game sweep of the
Dodgers with a 9-3 win at the Oakland Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``After (the meeting), you should play better,'' Dodgers catcher
Todd Hundley said. ``Right now, I can honestly say, this is the
worst it's been all year. We have to turn it back around. If we
keep going in this direction, it's going to be a long year, and
we're a better team than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (29-32) have lost three straight and six of seven,
were swept for the second time in less than two weeks and
nose-dived to three games under .500 for the first time, They're
also now tied for third place with Colorado and could be in fourth
place by the time they play Tuesday against Pittsburgh, which
happened to wax the Dodgers earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do other things better,'' Johnson said of the
meeting. ``Pitching has to tighten up, we can't make mistakes in
the field and we have to find more ways to manufacture runs.
Baseball is a game where, no matter what your ability, you have to
apply those abilities, apply those talents. We have to do a better
job of it. That's all there is to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between being good and bad is small. We all
have to be on the same page _ re-apply ourselves and do the things
we're capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were gung-ho for a few innings, scoring first when
Eric Young led off with an infield single and scored on Gary
Sheffield's groundout.
</P>
<P>
   The A's scored twice in the third, set up by walks, and the
warm, fuzzy feeling the meeting left was obliterated in the fifth
inning when walk-prone pitcher Darren Dreifort lost his command.
Dreifort, an enigma in that the movement of his pitches is near the
best in baseball, walked three straight batters before being
replaced in the fifth inning. Each of those runners scored,
culminating with an only-in-Dodgerland type of play.
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Jamie Arnold struck out Ryan Christenson on a ball in
the dirt with the bases loaded. The ball bounced hard off the
backstop and back to Hundley, who instead of running to touch home
for the force threw wildly to first. Two runs scored, the A's had
an 8-1 lead and Dodgers were looking bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I could get to home before the runner and I
wound up throwing the ball into right field,'' Hundley said.
``That, right there, is the first time it's happened with the bases
loaded, the third out. First time in my career I can remember
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, by that point the outcome could be pretty well
predicted, though it added a little insult to Dreifort's line. He
allowed seven runs on four hits in 41/3 innings. Dreifort (5-5)
walked six and lost his third straight.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, who entered the series with a major-league-low .235
batting average, battered Dodgers pitching. They hit .294 and
scored 25 runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a manager has a meeting, it should help guys relax a
little bit,'' Sheffield said. ``He lets you know he's with you, he
backs you. I took the meeting the meeting as a positive _ positive
at all of us. We all have to do the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the A's did all the non-stat-oriented things to
further humble the Dodgers. They took extra bases, worked counts
deep and moved runners over. And they had a pitcher, 23-year-old
Tim Hudson, who threw strikes and relied on his fielders.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson (2-0) won his second major-league start with ease. He
allowed two runs on seven hits and struck out eight, mostly with a
nasty forkball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's so much we ran into Hudson or we ran into
ourselves,'' said Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros, who went 3 for
4 with two doubles. ``Obviously, it's frustrating. We've got 100
games left and we're playing whether we want to or not. We're
playing those games regardless, so you get out of here and focus on
Tuesday's game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
