A3927 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-LLOYD-NYT &LR;      06-13 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LLOYD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN LLOYD, 51, AN ARCHEOLOGIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Lloyd, a British archeologist who unearthed relics yielding
new information about day-to-day living in classical times, died on
May 30 in Oxford, England. He was 51 and had worked with Oxford
University's Institute of Archeology for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   He had a brain tumor, said The Independent, which reported his
death on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fieldwork by Lloyd ``has given us new understanding for ordinary
life in towns and villages and farms throughout the ancient
world,'' Prof. Graeme Barker, head of Leicester University's School
of Archeological Studies, wrote last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Lloyd was field director of excavations at the
site of the old-time Greek and Roman city of Berenice in what is
now a suburb of Benghazi, a port on Libya's Mediterranean coast.
That work produced insights into many facets of life in Berenice,
which was given that name under the Greeks in the third century
B.C. and was acquired by the Romans in the first century B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lloyd and others sought information about the ancient
history of the Biferno River valley in Italy. That project included
squads of archeologists walking present-day farmers' fields in
search of bits of old pottery and other remnants of life in the
valley in classical times.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1981 article he reported that such ``field-walking
archeology'' by ``survey archeologists'' had revealed an
undreamed-of ``busy countryside'' of farms, residences and
communities in what are now nations all around the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Broughty Ferry, Scotland, Lloyd graduated from
Manchester University. He went on to be a lecturer successively at
Sheffield and Oxford universities from 1977 to 1988 and a fellow of
Wolfson College, Oxford, from 1988 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He married Vicky Doughty in 1976, and they had a son and a
daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990613.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-13 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3929 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIRED-TEACHERS-SPI &LR;      06-13 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIRED-TEACHERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RETIRING TEACHERS, CLASSROOMS HAVE CHANGED OVER 30 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DEBERA CARLTON HARRELL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Class of '99 is graduating after about 30 years,
facing a new millennium without chalk dust, school bells, upraised
hands and reverberating hallways.
</P>
<P>
   The grads will miss the toothless grin of a beginning reader,
the ``light-bulb'' glow on the face of a kid who finally ``gets''
long division, the troubled teen who discovers he's an artist, the
junior chemist whose experiment trips the smoke alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for hundreds of veteran public school teachers statewide,
it's time to retire. Although some admit to burnout, and one said a
``class from hell'' triggered her retirement, most are choosing to
leave on top, memories warm and legacies intact.
</P>
<P>
   Among the retiree Class of 1999 are many whose careers span
decades of cultural foment and change, from Vietnam to the
techno-revolution. Or, as one teacher joked, ``from `Leave It to
Beaver' to `Beavis and Butthead.'''
</P>
<P>
   From former Peace Corps volunteers to take-no-prisoners math
instructors, these retirees, most in their 50s, have survived
reductions-in-staff and recessions and adjusted to curriculum
shifts (phonics to math to state tests), new laws (special
education, education reform) and dramatic demographic changes.
</P>
<P>
   In response to such cultural trends as poverty, substance abuse,
fractured families and violence, they have become counselors,
social service workers and security officers as well as teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when teachers' salary debates and walkouts prompted
some to reconsider their professions, many veteran teachers say
they would make the same career choice today. Said respected
30-year Bellevue teacher Karen Gosch: ``I believe I had an
impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Retiring Garfield High School math teacher Jack Babani likes the
word ``impact'' so much he calculated it: 150 kids a year times 30
years of teaching means 4,500 kids whose lives intersected with
his. That doesn't count parents and teaching interns. For teachers
who also have coached sports, add a few thousand more kids.
</P>
<P>
   For most, those relationships were a matter of quality as well
as quantity.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Diane Kegin, who started teaching kindergarten when kids
merely ``drank milk and rested on a rug,'' is retiring after 37
years in the Hoquiam School District, where efforts to protect the
spotted owl produced timber layoffs and tough times for families.
</P>
<P>
   A former student, a Hispanic girl now in first grade, gave Kegin
a retirement present _ a crumpled piece of paper that said, ``I
want to hold onto your hand forever,'' written painstakingly in
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me cry,'' Kegin said.
</P>
<P>
   Kegin and others said one of the biggest changes over the
decades is that kids increasingly look to teachers to fill
emotional gaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had many kids, many times, that have asked me, `Can I go
home with you?''' Kegin said. ``They don't want to go home. ...
I've seen a lot more broken homes over the years. The stable family
is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Dean Hoff, a business education teacher at Kennewick High
School, agrees. Hoff, who survived a heart attack nine years ago,
will retire after 31 years. He said he believes more and more
students want to talk to teachers because ``communication at home
doesn't seem as good as it was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids need someone to talk to, and they turn to teachers _
someone who's kind, non-threatening, someone who will listen,''
Hoff said. ``My students, in a retirement tribute, signed things
like `thanks for being a great teacher and a great friend.' That's
how I like to be remembered.''
</P>
<P>
   Retiring teachers say believing in kids is critical _ and so are
high expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teachers feel very responsible for kids, to prepare them to
live and work in this world,'' said Gosch, who still receives
correspondence from former students living nearby and as far away
as Japan, Australia and Scandinavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teachers are givers and sensitive people who really care.
I feel like teaching was my mission in life, and I think I
succeeded,'' said Gosch, part of a teaching team at Clyde Hill
Elementary, which had some of the state's highest reading scores
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My expectations are high,'' she said. ``I think kids rise to
the expectations of their teachers and parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Tammie Ensign of Olympia, retiring after 25 years mostly in the
North Thurston School District, recalls ``an 8-year-old boy who
came to class all disheveled. His desk was always a mess, he never
got his work done and just really had a hard time with school.''
</P>
<P>
   When Ensign inquired, the boy said he was living in a trailer
with his mom and younger brother; he slept on the floor and was
responsible for getting everyone up in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ensign said she told the ``bright kid'' what she expected of
him, and pushed him to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reached the point where he did his work well ... he later
moved, but when he left, he gave me a big hug and a little note
that said, `Thank you and I'll miss you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fifth-grade teacher Sharon Held was hugged and saluted by
grateful students, parents and colleagues at a retirement party
last week. She became teary-eyed as 33 years _ the last 15 at
Bennett Elementary in Bellevue _ drew to a close.
</P>
<P>
   Held, a former Peace Corps volunteer in Uganda who entered
teaching out of ``a sense of service,'' recalls first meeting one
student when he was trying to escape down a tree after being caught
running on the school roof.
</P>
<P>
   Held was determined to show the self-described ``bad boy'' he
could become ``a productive, valued member of the class not by
misbehaving, but through positive behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Much individualized attention and many ``contracts'' later, the
boy settled down, discovered a talent for drawing, and began
helping classmates illustrate their books for a school publishing
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had leadership potential. He had things to contribute,''
Held said. ``One of the most important things a teacher can do is
to find out what each child's gift is and allow him or her to
showcase it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many retirees say kids in some ways are like they were 30 years
ago _ ``more interested in friends than school'' _ but their social
skills have plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers say kids are more rude and less respectful of adults
and peers; they do not look people in the eyes when they speak or
they pass in front of others without saying a word. They often
ignore instructions and yell at their parents.
</P>
<P>
   Many retiring teachers also believe attention spans are shorter
(they blame television and electronic games).
</P>
<P>
   Security, once a blank in school budgets, is a huge issue now.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, kids fought but they rolled around in the
grass and punched each other,'' Kennewick High's Hoff said. ``Now
you worry about two kids fighting, because one of them could bring
out a knife. Things are scarier.''
</P>
<P>
   But many retiring teachers think self-discipline and personal
responsibility are making ``much-needed comebacks,'' and they plead
for more parental involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Holden, a 31-year veteran and Newport High School science
teacher, has taught through Purple Haze and purple hair, but says
nothing compares to the Vietnam era for student unrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, society has changed,'' Holden said. ``I remember at
the Class of '70's graduation, parents and other adults booed a
student speaker off the stage in tears because he made some comment
about Vietnam. We haven't really had anything compared to that
since.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers also say that for all their hard work, some of the
mightiest lessons have come from students.
</P>
<P>
   Holden, who also is a football coach, recalls 16-year-old
student and football player Brad Bowers, who died from cancer in
1977:
</P>
<P>
   ``One day he was healthy, catching a touchdown pass, the next
day he was limping. A week later he had his leg amputated because
of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched this kid battle cancer for 18 months before he died.
He taught me about grace, about living, about faith. That kid had
the greatest impact on my life. Anytime anything seemed like a big
deal, I could always look back on that kid and I knew my deal was
not a big deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-13-99 2352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
