<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the additional
story for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Monday, June 14, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Veronica Villarreal at (206) 448-8342.
</P>
<P>
   BICYCLIST (Seattle) _ The sound of her jaw pounding into the
pavement sounded like a potato chip crunching underneath someone's
foot. Carrianne Pullar still remembers the morning rush-hour
traffic whizzing by as she and her mangled bicycle lay helpless on
the side of the road, her jaw shattered. It's an experience the
29-year-old Pullar has understandably tried to push out of her
mind. Yet this week _ three years after Pullar crashed while riding
her bicycle to work in West Seattle _ she is competing for the
Saturn of Bellevue, Wash., team against some of the world's top
cyclists in the HP LaserJet Women's Challenge in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   By Holly Cain. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
